<SLUG> BC-RUNNER-KAN </SLUG>
  
 80-year-old marathon runner still going strong  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATIE HOLLAR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As of Thursday, Ed Burnham had run 22,417
miles.
</P>
<P>
   That's just about 2,500 miles shy of running around the earth.
And he has seen a lot of the globe along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham has completed at least one marathon in every state. He
ran in Berlin the same year the wall came down. He raced past Big
Ben in London. He sweated through marathons in Cancun and Cozumel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not bad for an 80-year-old man,'' Burnham said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Burnham is one of a handful of older runners in Kansas
City. When races have an age division for 80 and over, he is
usually the only participant.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I do pretty well,'' he laughed. ``If it's 70 and over,
well, it depends.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend Burnham will run in two local races: the 10K KU
Alumni Jayhawk Jog today and the Kansas City Downtown Airport 8K
Tarmac Run on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to run in all local races, because they're usually for
charity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham did not start running until he was 60, when he retired
from his administrative position with the Veterans of Foreign Wars.
</P>
<P>
   At age 70 he completed his first marathon. He said he had been
running about once a month since. His next marathon will be
Quebec's Marathon des Deux Rives on Aug. 27 _ two days before his
81st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year on my 80th birthday I ran the Omaha marathon,'' he
said. ``That was kind of neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnham has had to clear some hurdles in his 20 years of
running. He has suffered a broken ankle and a broken elbow. He got
a stress fracture in his leg. His thyroid quit working properly.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Burnham recovered. With a cast, with pills or with
time, he was back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Good genes and a healthful lifestyle are what keep him going, he
said. And he plans to keep going for as long as he feels like it _
or when his marathon time tops seven hours.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he said, he'll just do half-marathons.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he has some time. Burnham completed his last marathon
in six hours, 26 minutes and 35 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Taylor, a local race announcer and the promoter for the
Tarmac 8K, said Burnham was ``a real champion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To run 100 marathons after you're 60 is incredible,'' Taylor
said. ``Just incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
