A3315 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-ENERGY-STOCKS-     08-05 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ENERGY-STOCKS-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GAS GIANT BETS HEAVILY ON A SURGE IN DEMAND
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 6)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Will natural gas prices stay high? Consumers hope not,
but the Anadarko Petroleum Corp., for one, is betting that they
will.
</P>
<P>
   Prices at the wellhead have leapt 80 percent this year, to more
than $4 per million British thermal units. Further, if colder
temperatures return after the unseasonably warm winters of the last
few years, supplies could be squeezed tighter, sending prices even
higher.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be just the start, argue executives at Anadarko,
one of the largest independent oil and gas producers. They and a
number of other producers and analysts say a fundamental shift in
the natural gas market has brought permanently higher prices. They
cite soaring demand from new electricity generation plants, after
years of weak overall consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Anadarko is making a huge bet on this thesis. Anadarko, based in
Houston, has just acquired Union Pacific Resources for almost $6
billion, gaining drilling rights in gas-rich western Canada and
other places. Last week it announced it would raise capital
spending this year to $1.5 billion, one-third more than earlier
projections.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were not impressed when the Union Pacific deal was
announced in April, but they have come around. Anadarko shares are
now up more than 40 percent for the year. At $49, they are trading
at about 12 times the $4 a share that Robert J. Allison Jr.,
Anadarko's chief executive, expects the company to earn over the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just isn't enough supply, or enough supply excess, to
get soft gas prices again,'' Allison said in an interview last
week. A severe winter will cause spot shortages, he predicts,
potentially causing prices to hit $7 early next year.
</P>
<P>
   William Featherston, an analyst at PaineWebber, says that a
group of 15 gas producers he tracks are expected to post a 75
percent gain in discretionary cash flow _ net income plus
depreciation and deferred taxes _ to $9 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even strong fundamentals are subject to the whimsy of
investors, whose appetite for technology stocks hurt valuations of
so-called old economy stocks in recent years. Lately, the shares of
some big exploration and production companies have moved almost
inversely with the Nasdaq index, rising as the index has fallen.
Even so, some analysts say they have much farther to go. ``The
stocks are reflecting $2.50 gas,'' said Featherston. ``It's a real
disconnect.''
</P>
<P>
   Often found in the same fields as oil, natural gas has far
different economics. By and large, it cannot be transported like
oil _ some is liquefied overseas and shipped to the United States,
but it is very expensive to do that _ so the United States gets
nearly all its gas from North America. It is shipped around the
country through pipelines, mostly from places like the Gulf of
Mexico, Canada, Texas and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, natural gas has little OPEC risk, and prices
are much more closely tied to pure supply-and-demand forces than to
political decisions made half a world away. But that also means
that the United States cannot browbeat foreign producers into
higher production when prices rise, as it has sometimes done with
oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil markets are global, but the gas market is continental,''
said Tom Robinson, a managing director at Cambridge Energy Research
Associates, a consulting and research firm in Cambridge, Mass.
``Producers tend to be full out into the market, and what that
means is that no reserves can be turned on when the market gets
tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Some developments could cause prices to fall. A recession, for
example, would check demand. Should oil prices drop, some
industrial users would switch to other fuels. If the industry were
to sharply boost exploration spending, supplies could rise, putting
pressure on prices. That has not happened yet, although there are
now 772 active gas rigs working in the United States, an increase
of more than 50 percent from a year earlier, according to Baker
Hughes Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But in the near term, prices could go higher simply because
there may not be enough gas in storage. Last year, winter demand
caused gas stocks to fall from three trillion cubic feet in
November to one trillion in April, and that was during one of the
warmest winters on record.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, gas stores are already 18 percent lower than
last year, and analysts forecast that stocks may not reach more
than 2.7 trillion cubic feet by November. Another warm winter could
be enough to leave inventories lean by early next year, but normal
winter temperatures could raise demand by 100 billion cubic feet or
more a month, cutting deeply into storage, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a rude awakening coming,'' he said, for homeowners in
the Northeast, where annual gas bills will average $200 higher.
</P>
<P>
   Supplies are tight now partly because demand, until recently,
was unusually soft, lulling the market into complacency. Warm
winters played a role, but there were other factors. The Asian
recession affected American industry's gas use. Low oil prices _
before OPEC moved last year to curtail production _ made other
fuels cheap alternatives. Oil and gas companies held back from new
investment in production in response to pressure from Wall Street
to use cash flow to pay off debt. Domestic gas production has
actually dropped slightly in the last few years, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   But now, demand is rising, oil prices are high, and mass layoffs
from the industry's shakeout two years ago have helped create a
labor shortage that has somewhat constrained drilling. Even more
important is the new demand created by utilities and independent
power producers scrambling to build plants to supply electricity to
regions running short of power. With coal and nuclear power out of
favor, almost all of the new electricity generation plants are
gas-fired.
</P>
<P>
   The National Petroleum Council, a group of industry officials
who advise the secretary of energy, expects annual demand in the
United States to rise to 29 trillion cubic feet over the next
decade, compared with 22 trillion this year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, imports from Canada, liquefied natural gas from overseas
and depletion of gas in storage have made up the gap between
domestic production and demand. But what about future demand?
Proven reserves in the United States are about 160 trillion cubic
feet, and those have started to fall. New technologies have allowed
producers to pump more gas out of existing properties, but by and
large the nation's gas fields are maturing, and it is getting
harder, and more expensive, to locate more gas.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives, including Allison of Anadarko, argue that
if federal officials allowed more drilling in places that are off
limits, including certain parts of Alaska and offshore locations in
most of the lower 48 states, reserves might eventually double.
Otherwise, he said, ``you can only squeeze the oil fields so far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
