u p BC-GORE-SPEECH-1STLD-WRI     08-05 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPEECH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SPENT PART OF VACATION WRITING SPEECH, ADVISERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for rewriting)  
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Democratic National Convention just a few days off,
Vice President Al Gore spent part of his beach vacation in North
Carolina writing his own speech accepting the presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told reporters on Thursday that he had spent several hours
a day writing the address.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been drafted to tell him he should show it to other
people sooner rather than later,'' said Martin Peretz, Gore's
onetime Harvard professor and longtime friend. ``And I dread saying
it because I dread his response.''
</P>
<P>
   Peretz, who is better known as the editor in chief of The New
Republic, declined to say who had drafted him for the job, though
he hinted it was Karenna Gore Schiff, Gore's oldest daughter and
one of his closest advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff did not say whether she had asked Peretz to prod her
father into involving the professionals, but said that her father
was hard at work on the address that he will deliver at the
convention, which begins Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   One night, Schiff said, the entire family was at the dinner
table until nearly 10 p.m., nibbling on the remains of her dad's
favorite Chinese dish, Szechwan beef, and ``listening to him talk
through some of the paragraphs he had written.''
</P>
<P>
   After returning to New York, Schiff said, she spoke with her
father on the phone on Thursday. ``He read me a few new paragraphs,
which I thought were the best yet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For a candidate to write a speech of this importance by himself
is virtually unheard of in presidential politics. George W. Bush,
the Republican nominee, put his speechwriters through a number of
drafts, but like most candidates did not do any writing himself.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, though, is a former newspaper reporter who by all accounts
wrote every word of his 1992 book, ``Earth in the Balance.'' The
eulogy he wrote for his father's funeral in 1998 was widely
considered the best speech he ever gave.
</P>
<P>
   And it is hardly out of character for Gore, who has been known
to totally rework the speeches written by his staff, to have taken
on the speechwriting duties.
</P>
<P>
   He was heavily involved in the writing of his addresses to the
1992 and 1996 Democratic conventions. He also often does things on
his own; this is the candidate, after all, who designed his own
``Gore 2000'' campaign logo.
</P>
<P>
   Because this speech is considered crucial for Gore's election
effort, it is not surprising, either, that there might be concern
about making sure the vice president hears from the professionals.
</P>
<P>
   But, even if the pros have not seen a draft of Gore's speech, he
has at least talked to them about it. Last Saturday, Bob Shrum and
Carter Eskew, his top consultants, met Gore in North Carolina to
discuss the address.
</P>
<P>
   While on vacation, Schiff not only critiqued her father's
efforts but also worked on the nominating speech she is to give.
``It feels like a really important toast at a wedding,'' she said,
``and I have to dig through my head for anecdotes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
