<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIBBY-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIBBY SIGNS CONTRACT EXTENSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC basketball coach Henry Bibby ended months of
negotiating Friday by signing a three-year contract extension that
is intended to keep him at the university through the 2004-2005
season.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is being added on to the existing two years of Bibby's
original contract. He is expected to be paid about $375,000 next
season and the extension should eventually push him over the
$600,000 mark, which would place him in the upper echelon of
Pacific-10 Conference coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm honored that USC and (athletic director) Mike Garrett have
given me the opportunity to continue building upon the success
we've had with this program,'' Bibby said. ``Each year we've gotten
better and better. This extension solidifies the direction in which
Trojan basketball is headed. It's an exciting future and I'm proud
that USC wants me to be part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   There might some debate over whether Bibby will actually be
around by the end of the contract. He spoke with University of
Memphis officials about its then-vacant job last winter and he has
previously been interested in the Clippers' coaching position.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby had agreed to a verbal extension with USC officials in
March, but negotiations broke down and there was virtually no
contact in April and May. The two sides agreed in May, however,
that a deal could be worked out over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby signed his new contract prior to fielding what should be
his strongest team in his four-plus seasons. The Trojans have been
ranked in several early top-25 polls.
</P>
<P>
   USC returns all five starters from last year's 16-14 team and
seven of their top eight players. In addition, USC signed prep
All-American shooting guard Desmon Farmer of Flint, Mich., along
with point guard Robert Hutchinson and shooting guard Gennaro
Busterna. Also, 7-foot-3 freshman center Luke Minor will be
eligible after redshirting last season.
</P>
<P>
   It's conceivable the Trojans could be chosen to finish among the
top three teams in the Pac-10 next year. And USC has gotten off to
a fast start in recruiting this summer, with commitments from twin
brother guards Errick and Derrick Craven of Bishop Montgomery in
Torrance.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby has led USC to three winning seasons and a pair of
postseason appearances (the 1997 NCAA Tournament and the 1999
National Invitation Tournament).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy with the progress of the Trojan men's basketball
program under Henry Bibby,'' Garrett said. ``This contract
extension is a reflection of that. Now, we're looking for continued
development in his program; all indications are that we should be
seeing such success in the coming years.''
</P>
<P>
   The university is also publicly committed to building an
on-campus arena and hopes to begin groundbreaking before the end of
the year, although it still is in the process of raising the
necessary funds.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Former USC assistant Paul Mokeski, who attended Crespi
High in Encino, has an Aug. 10 hearing in Wisconsin for misdemeanor
possession of cocaine. He could be sentenced to up to one year in
jail and fined $5,000 if convicted. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HOLT-HNS &LR;      08-05 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HOLT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros' Holt walks away from line drive to face
</P>
<P>
   By SCOTT KAISER
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Staying with the pattern of this disheartening season,
Astros pitcher Chris Holt had to leave Friday night's 7-6 victory
over Montreal after getting hit in the face by a line drive.
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros leading 5-4 in the fourth inning, Holt retired
the first two batters before Expos center fielder Peter Bergeron
lined a 1-0 pitch off Holt's left cheekbone.
</P>
<P>
   Holt tried to shield his face with his glove, but he took a
direct hit and crumpled to the ground. Blood was evident as he
remained on the grass for several minutes before gamely walking off
the field under his own power.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was scary,'' said Astros third baseman Chris Truby.
``I've seen it a couple of times (after the game) on TV, but it's
really scary out there. That's probably the scariest thing for a
pitcher and for the guys on the field. When you see his face, it's
something you just don't wish on anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt was taken to the hospital for X-rays, which surprisingly
revealed only a bruised left cheekbone. Astros officials said his
status is day-to-day, which means Holt may be able to make his next
scheduled start against the New York Mets on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of getting the swelling down and to where he can
get comfortable on the mound and throw again,'' manager Larry
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident brought back memories of July 15, 1998, when Astros
closer Billy Wagner was hit on the left side of his head by a ball
off the bat of Arizona's Kelly Stinnett. Wagner was briefly
hospitalized and spent nearly a month on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Said Dierker: ``I didn't see it happen like I did with Billy,
because I was blocked by one of the vertical bars in the dugout. So
I didn't know if it deflected off his body or glove. It wasn't as
scary to me until I got out there, but then it looked worse because
his face was so swollen up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, I knew it wasn't worse, because Billy was dazed
when I got out there, and Chris was coherent. You could tell by his
answers to (assistant athletic trainer) Rex's (Jones) questions and
by the fact that he was moving around and looked like he was antsy
to get up.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt's injury extended a brutal stretch physically for the
Astros. Earlier this week, catcher Mitch Meluskey (right biceps
tendinitis), pitcher Shane Reynolds (two degenerative disks in his
lower back) and second baseman Craig Biggio (two ligament tears in
his left knee) were sidelined, with Biggio lost for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Holt) doesn't look good,'' said Biggio as he hobbled out of
the Astros' locker room on crutches. ``He's lucky (it wasn't
worse).''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
