<HEADLINE>
SOME SURVIVED PHILLY FEST, SOME DIDN'T
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The delegates have taken their stuffed elephants
and ``Liberals Make Me Sick'' buttons, and gone home.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, and his running mate,
Dick Cheney, are coming off the high.
</P>
<P>
   And the drugstores are selling hangover remedies like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, there was lots of celebrating by the GOP when the
Republican National Convention wrapped up here. It was a love-fest
from start to finish, and it went off without a hitch. From Bo
Derek to Bob Dole, delegates and big donors alike got their money's
worth, and then some.
</P>
<P>
   The convention will be remembered for a lot of things, mostly
for the fact that Americans, and networks, admitted they like
``Survivor'' better. Why not? On that island, they were eating the
rats and voting each other outta there &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   But Philadelphia had its own tribal winners and losers.
</P>
<P>
   And here are a few:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WINNERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Dubya:  &LR; Could the coronation have been any grander? Could &LR; 
the feel-good have been any goodlier? &LR; The man from Midland put his
stamp all over it, and his masses ate it up. Dubya, they luvya.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --George Herbert Walker Bush:  &LR; Four years ago, Daddy didn't
merit the convention limelight. Now the party doormat has turned
hero. Babs is looking good, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --Condoleezza Rice:  &LR; Nitpickers say she's too polished. But
whooping it up over Steve Young or discussing foreign policy, two
words come to mind: class act.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --Abel Maldonado:  &LR; Santa Maria GOP assemblyman provided salsa,
delivering the most authentic speech of the convention  &UR; en &LR; 
 &UR; espanol. Que Viva! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Ralph Nader:  &LR; Green guy ends up with a floor pass, and sends
Republican security teams into environmental crisis. You go, boy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Laura Bush:  &LR; Under pressure to produce, Mom came through
with some down home cookin'.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Vicente Fernandez:  &LR; Awesome Mexican music idol does the
impossible: gets Republicans to sing mariachi music in unison.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- J.C. Watts:  &LR; What's up with this guy? If he got any more
face time, he'd have his own miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOSERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Bob Dole:  &LR; ``There's still time for a recount?'' Don't think
so, Bob.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Dick Cheney:  &LR; Electrifying? Charismatic? Uh, like a
marshmallow sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Newt Gingrich:  &LR; Former GOP icon spotted in the back parking
lot wearing a ``Got Satan?'' T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Bush brothers:  &LR; Neal, with that old savings scandal, and
marvelous Marvin, so _ are they orphans? And Jeb _ smart,
bilingual, tech-savvy, big gov, big state. Why the mere hand-waving
duty?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- GOP elected women:  &LR; Relegated to kitchen hostess duties, or
hidden in the wings. Christi Todd? Kay Bailey? Baby, are you out
there?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Jim Rogan, Tom Campbell, Rick Lazio:  &LR; Battling for their
lives in three of the most high-profile congressional races in the
country. But a speaking slot in Dubyafest? Nooo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- The GOP motto:  &LR; ``Renewing America's Purpose _ Together.''
Huh?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- The media:  &LR; Frozen out of big fund-raisers, isolated from
the delegates in third-rate hotels with no mini-bars. And that
never-ending nightmare: a no-conflict convention.
</P>
</TEXT>
