<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-BLUE-JAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FADING QUICKLY AS BLUE JAYS RALLY FOR WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Remember David Clyde?
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers took him with the No. 1 overall pick in the 1973
amateur draft, the only time in club history they've had the top
pick of the draft. He didn't quite work out, but, who knows, the
Rangers might have better luck next year.
</P>
<P>
   Did somebody say wild-card race? Take a closer look at the
standings. The Rangers are much closer to the worst record in the
American League, and the No. 1 draft pick, than they are to the
wild-card leader, and it seems to be getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers let a 5-3 lead slip away by allowing seven runs in
two innings and fell to the Toronto Blue Jays, 10-8, last night at
SkyDome. The loss was the Rangers fifth in their past six games and
not only are they 9 1/2 games behind the Oakland Athletics in the
wild-card race, but they are just six games ahead of the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays, owners of the worst record in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough,'' Rangers second baseman Luis Alicea
said. ``Today was a good example. We played hard, we were ahead in
the game, they took the lead, we tied it, then they came back and
won it.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrin Fletcher delivered the game-winning hit, a two-run double
with two out in the bottom of the eighth inning. The Blue Jays had
taken an 8-5 lead in the bottom of the seventh with five runs off
Matt Perisho and Francisco Cordero before the Rangers rallied with
three in the top of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But reliever Mike Venafro couldn't keep it tied. With two outs,
he gave up a single to Tony Batista and hit Jose Cruz before
Fletcher, after fouling off three consecutive 2-2 pitches, grounded
one down the third-base line.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates said before the season that with all the
Rangers' young players, they could end up being much better in the
second half than the first half. But he knows now that's not going
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that changed when \RRuben\S Mateo got hurt, \RGabe\S
Kapler got hurt, \RPudge\S Rodriguez got hurt and we traded
\RDavid\S Segui,'' Oates said. ``All of those factors have changed
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Oates is trying to win with a roster filled with young
players who have some talent, but make key mistakes. Right fielder
Ricky Ledee dropped a fly ball in the fifth last night that led to
two unearned runs. Perisho, leading 5-3, walked the leadoff hitter
in the seventh. Cordero kept trying to blow hitters away and ended
up throwing hittable pitches down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Oates knows it's going to be hard, and he said bluntly: ``I'm
resigned to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to make sure the veteran players understand they
were young players once, they were rookies and they made
mistakes,'' Oates said. ``The goal is to win as many games as we
can, but we've got to give them a chance to play. I'm not into
development at the major-league level, but we've got to be
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be difficult, not only for Oates, but for a team that
has played hard up to this point. The schedule keeps getting more
difficult with 32 of the next 55 on the road and an August schedule
against traditional powers New York, Boston and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   This could get ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't will the team to win,'' Oates said. ``I'm not that
powerful. All I can say is we'll give a good effort. We still have
to play one-third of the season. You hired out for 162 games. If
they don't play hard _ which I don't expect, because we've been
busting our tails _ then we can fix that too.''
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Rusty Greer said, ``I can't foresee the future but I
think there's going to be some ups and downs. It's up to the
veterans to go out and stabilize the club, take it upon ourselves
to lead the way. We're going to have to play hard and get some
breaks, but that doesn't mean we can't go out and play good
baseball and win some games.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise they could be searching for the next David Clyde. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
