<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3350 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-SINATRA-STATUE-2ND     08-05 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SINATRA-STATUE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-1070(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN FOR TIMES SQUARE SINATRA STATUE GETS UNDER SKIN OF SOME
PEOPLE
</HEADLINE>
  (CHANGES quote to paraphrase in 9th graf)   
 By DEAN E. MURPHY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Rev. Francis Patrick Duffy got a spot in Times
Square in 1936 for his heroics on the battlefield and the streets
of Hell's Kitchen. George M. Cohan followed in 1959 as a tribute to
one of show business' greatest song and dance men.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani says there is room for one more famous
bronze guy out there on the crossroads of the world. The mayor and
his office have taken a shine to Frank Sinatra, whose last big hit,
in 1980, was ``New York, New York.'' The late entertainer's
daughter, Nancy Sinatra, has found a sculptor and promises to come
up with the money. There is even talk of an interactive Sinatra,
who would croon on command.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy Sinatra is thrilled; this is her dream,'' said Charlotte
Cohen of the city's Department of Cultural Affairs, who has been
involved in the plans. ``Everyone would love to see it done
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hushed refrain playing around Times Square is not so
gushing or welcoming. Start spreading the news, it goes. Not Here,
Not Here.
</P>
<P>
   No one really wants to say so, at least not loudly enough to irk
Giuliani or offend the Sinatra family, but the plan to erect a
statue of Ol' Blue Eyes on a traffic island at 44th Street and
Broadway (across the street from the site off the old Paramount
Theater, where Sinatra made his first real splash in 1942) has
acquired some enemies.
</P>
<P>
   The local community board, along with some Times Square
developers, isn't crazy about the idea of a new tourist attraction
in a place where the sidewalks are already overwhelmed by crowds.
And the theater moguls say the square's 100-year-old theatrical
tradition would be shortchanged by showcasing a singer and film
actor who started in Hoboken, N.J., made a quick sensation at the
Paramount Theater and then followed fame and fortune west of the
Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone bristles at the thought of Giuliani as arbiter of
Broadway celebrity. The community board and other local groups have
written a letter to the mayor asking for a meeting. They hope, at
least, to get the statue moved to a less central location.
</P>
<P>
   `The real issue for a lot of us is, what is the association with
Broadway?'' said Michael Presser, executive director of Inside
Broadway, the theater industry's educational program with New York
City schools. ``We see an extremely popular artist and legend, a
man of great achievement, but we don't necessarily see someone who
has been closely associated with New York theater. We feel he is
due an honor, but we also question this particular spot in this
particular neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra fancied himself top of the heap in the city that doesn't
sleep, but if the grumbling around Times Square is to be believed,
New Yorkers would like less Las Vegas and Hollywood in their
traffic-island idols. Times Square may be the center of the
universe, but it is also a stronghold of Midtown provincialism: On
the Great White Way, Sinatra, real or cast, is regarded as
decidedly off-Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office won't hear of it. Indeed, Anthony Carbonetti,
Giuliani's chief of staff, says they have not heard of it.
</P>
<P>
   Any opposition to Sinatra?
</P>
<P>
   ``That hasn't come up,'' Carbonetti replied.
</P>
<P>
   Does Sinatra deserve to be front and center in Times Square?
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think so,'' he said. ``But I am an
Italian-American who grew up listening to Frank Sinatra, and my
father would disown me if I said anything to the contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Sinatra insurrection is being staged largely in
whispers and behind closed doors is not entirely surprising.
</P>
<P>
   At one level, it is downright embarrassing for naysayers to
confess their misgivings in public. It is not easy to explain
objections to a 10-foot monument to one of America's greatest pop
singers, regardless of his New York pedigree. Times Square is
already home to a pro-wrestling restaurant and the retailer Toys
``R'' Us plans to build a 60-foot-tall indoor Ferris wheel across
the street.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the problem of City Hall and a mayor who, as one
Times Square community leader put it, is easy to make cranky.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Sinatra went directly to Giuliani with the statue proposal
shortly after her father died in Los Angeles in May 1998, city
officials said. Carbonetti said she had apparently made the
suggestion years earlier, but was encouraged to come back when her
father was no longer living. Statues in New York, unlike street
names in Sinatra's desert haunt of Palm Springs, Calif., are the
exclusive domain of the departed.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani loved the idea and, as he is sometimes inclined to do,
gave the seal of approval without consulting particularly far and
wide.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra initiated a design competition last August, settling in
December on Neil Estern, an accomplished Brooklyn Heights sculptor.
</P>
<P>
   The Sinatra-Giuliani plan was cast in stone _ or more precisely,
bronze _ before most anyone around Times Square got wind of it.
Official notice to Times Square businesses came in January as a
fait accompli from the City Department of Transportation, which
owns the concrete swath of Broadway and Seventh Avenue that Sinatra
will share with the armed forces recruiting booth.
</P>
<P>
   A community meeting with city officials, and possibly Nancy
Sinatra, is in the making. The session was proposed in May by the
leaders of three of the area's most influential organizations:
Community Board 5, the Times Square Business Improvement District
and the Mayor's Midtown Citizens Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Giuliani, the three community groups stayed away
from questioning Sinatra's New York bona fides. Instead, they
raised fears that another attraction in Times Square, already the
human equivalent of an overrun ant hill, would lock up the last
piece of open space in the theater district.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, the recruiting booth island doubles as Dick
Clark's stage on New Year's Eve, and it is also used to present
Broadway on Broadway and numerous other public events. It amounts
to little more than a Gotham-sized slice of concrete pizza, but
it's all Times Square has got.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't necessarily think any statue would be appropriate for
Times Square because we probably have enough going on,'' said David
Diamond, executive director of the Stage Directors and
Choreographers Foundation, who heads the community board's
committee on Times Square. ``But I don't want to discount the
possibility.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Diamond's suggestion: Put Sinatra's statue in Hoboken and place
a plaque honoring him at 1501 Broadway, the former Paramount
Theater that is now a World Wrestling Federation restaurant. It was
there that thousands of screaming bobby-soxers _ 30,000 of them on
Oct. 12, 1944 _ turned Sinatra into solo music's greatest pop
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   And who should stand in for Sinatra on the recruiting booth
island?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be quoted on any name,'' Diamond said. ``I
don't want to leave anyone out and offend someone.''
</P>
<P>
   But aren't they are all dead anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``They all have estates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office says it has already solved the overcrowding
quandary by instructing Estern to come up with a design that would
allow Sinatra to be carted off for special occasions. The
Department of Transportation also has plans to restrict pedestrian
access to the island to keep fans from spilling into the street and
disrupting traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The city is still undecided about whether the statue should
sing, reserving judgment until the implications for traffic and
nearby office workers can be studied. Estern says no one has talked
to him about adapting his art into ``an elaborate juke box,'' as he
called it, but he is clearly not enamored with the suggestion.
Diamond and others who work in the area share his reluctance,
largely out of fear of overdosing on Sinatra's barreling baritone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to have a public debate, after all this is a
democracy,'' Presser said. ``This is a very public piece of land.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, director of the Percent for Art program in the Department
of Cultural Affairs, said the statue, as a privately financed
project, has not received the intense scrutiny required when public
money is expended. Nonetheless, she said, the statue must still be
reviewed by the City Art Commission for design approval and by the
Department of Transportation for traffic and safety considerations.
It is unclear, however, whether either agency will hold a public
hearing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if it is something the mayor wants, then I think there
will be a statue,'' said a Midtown developer unwilling to speak if
he were named. ``Is there support? There is support, I guess,
official support.''
</P>
<P>
   Estern, an avid fan of Sinatra who regards the singer as the
perfect fit for Times Square, also thinks the resilient showman
will prevail. Look no further than Sinatra's own ode to the city,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can make it there, I'm gonna make it anywhere,'' Estern
recited. ``It's up to you _ New York, New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
