<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNCR-CLOSINGS-LADN </SLUG>
 
EXPECTING DNC CRUNCH, CITY WILL CLOSE STREETS EARLY &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The crunch of the Democratic National Convention
will start to be felt Monday by downtown businesses and commuters,
with some surface streets and freeway ramps closing a week before
the big event.
</P>
<P>
   Bracing for potentially violent protests during the Aug. 14-17
convention, most of the jewelry district and many other downtown
businesses will close, while other merchants plan to hire extra
security and stagger work schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``No city department, be it police or what have you, can
guarantee it (safety),'' Peklar Pilavjian, owner of the 500-tenant
St. Vincent Jewelry Center, which plans to close during the
convention, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way business reacts is they just shut down. They say the
heck with it, it's not worth the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans plans to shut down three heavily traveled downtown
freeway ramps near Staples Center starting Monday, so crews can
begin cleanup work and graffiti removal.
</P>
<P>
   The city has already begun closing surface streets near Staples
as security fencing goes up around the arena's perimeter, which
means downtown commuters can expect two weeks of detours, delays
and distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think most people are prepared,'' said Jeff Baugh, who
has observed Los Angeles traffic for 14 years as a traffic reporter
for KFWB-AM (980).
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be. If I work in downtown Los Angeles, this
weekend I'd be sitting at the coffee table, and I'd have the Thomas
Guide in front of me. I might go to Kinko's and blow up (maps) and
make sure I knew that entire area just to avoid problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The ramps scheduled to close Monday are the Pico Boulevard
off-ramp and 11th Street on-ramp on the northbound Harbor Freeway;
and the Pico off-ramp on the westbound Santa Monica Freeway. About
120 detour signs will be posted between Los Angeles International
Airport and Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, small sections of Figueroa Street, Pico and Flower
Street nearest Staples will also be closed. By Friday, the area
bordered by Venice Boulevard, Union Avenue, Hope Street and Olympic
Boulevard will be subject to travel restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   While no additional freeway closings are expected during the
convention, Caltrans will keep a close eye on the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our traffic engineers are going to be monitoring everything so
they can help traffic get around as smoothly and efficiently as
possible,'' said Caltrans spokeswoman Margie Tiritilli. ``If
problems do develop they'll seek the best ways to work them out to
everyone's satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   During the convention itself, city officials urge downtown
commuters to take public transit. But all Metropolitan
Transportation Authority bus lines that currently pass near Staples
are already being diverted, so bus riders are advised to allow at
least an extra 15 minutes. The nearest Metro Rail station to
Staples is Pico, on the Blue Line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're encouraging ride sharing and public transit,'' said
Frank Martinez, the city's DNC coordinator. ``We're encouraging
working with your employer in terms of flexible hours. You might
want to come in a little early and leave a little early.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of companies have taken that advice a step further and
decided to shut down altogether during the convention, either
fearing violent protests or because they expect customers to avoid
downtown anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you get 10,000 or 20,000 people gathering around for
a demonstration, the potential is always there for it to go out of
control,'' Pilavjian said.
</P>
<P>
   The 275 retail tenants in his building each averages about
$1,000 in business a day, he said - meaning that during the
four-day convention, his tenants alone will lose more than $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   Many offices that aren't dependent on retail customers are
advising employees to work at home or take their vacation days.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist at the Los Angeles Economic
Development Corporation, said the 35 employees at the EDC are
planning to work at home at least Monday, if not longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll wait to see what happens,'' Kyser said. ``The problem is
it's almost like Y2K revisited. You have so many stories about
what's going to happen and I think everyone is being prudent. They
don't want to risk their employees and customers.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information about traffic restrictions - including
real-time traffic flows during the convention - or the convention
in general, see the city's Web site, www.lacity.org.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
