<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-HERNANDEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' HERNANDEZ UPSET OVER POSSIBLE SKEPTICS  

</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez said Friday that there are Yankees
coaches who doubted the severity of his injury when he was placed
on the disabled list last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some coaches mentioned behind people's back that maybe I
wasn't as hurt as I thought,'' Hernandez said, without prompting,
through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who appeared to be near tears, added that it hurt him
very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is because they didn't come to my face and say it
to me,'' he said. ``I don't play around with my work.''
</P>
<P>
   On the disabled list because of elbow and back trouble,
Hernandez was asked to whom he was referring: ``Don't ask,'' he
replied. ``I am a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, said he was
surprised by Hernandez's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that we don't do, and I can speak for the
staff, is that we never have doubts about when people are hurt,''
Stottlemyre said. ``We've always gone the extra mile to make sure
people are OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre added, ``I think that's something that's
self-inflicted. I'm sorry he feels that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, spoke with
Hernandez just before Friday night's game against Seattle and said
El Duque would not elaborate or offer more insight into his
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of feel powerless to deal with it,'' Cashman said,
``because I don't know anything about it. Normally you deal with
things straight up _ if you have a problem with someone, you speak
to them directly about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is scheduled to be activated Saturday to pitch against
the Mariners.
</P>
</TEXT>
