<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS     08-05 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REED'S STRONG START STOPS JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Randy Johnson is everything Rick Reed is not. Scraggly
curls dangle from Johnson's Arizona Diamondbacks cap and fastballs
sizzle from his left arm. The right-handed Reed closely crops what
little hair he has, and his fastballs have none of Johnson's zip.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night at Bank One Ballpark, there was another difference:
Johnson was battered and Reed was brilliant. With 7 2/3 innings of
numbing precision, Reed pitched the New York Mets to a 6-1 victory.
The Mets have won nine of their last 10 games, and have beaten
Johnson the last three times he has faced them.
</P>
<P>
   Reed (6-2) carried a three-hit shutout into the eighth inning,
and he had set down 11 hitters in a row when Kelly Stinnett singled
in the eighth. Two more singles gave the Diamondbacks a run and
knocked Reed from the game, but by then the Mets led comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has terrorized opposing teams for years, and he is at
the peak of his effectiveness. In 45 starts since last May 30, when
he beat the Mets at Shea Stadium, he has a 2.14 earned run average
against all other teams. But in three starts against the Mets,
including the opener of last year's first playoff round, Johnson
has a 6.75 ERA, and Arizona has lost all three games.
</P>
<P>
   Asked before the game why his team has had success against
Johnson, Mets manager Bobby Valentine gave a sportsmanlike answer.
``Our hits have fallen in, I guess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reason may be the Mets' aggressiveness as a team,
which runs counter to their usual approach. The Mets are among the
most patient teams in the league, letting pitchers work deep counts
and drawing the fourth-most walks in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   But when teams let Johnson get ahead in the count with his
fastball, they face the task of trying to hit his slider, which is
considered his best pitch. When the Mets beat Johnson in May, the
Diamondbacks' catcher, Damian Miller, said he was surprised at the
way the Mets swung early. But, Miller had to admit, that is how he
would approach Johnson, too. Friday night, the first four Mets who
put the ball in play did so on the first or second pitch they
faced. All it produced was a single, pop out and two ground outs.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases empty and two outs in the second, Johnson fell
behind Jay Payton, 2-0. The count evened at 2-2, Payton hit two
foul balls, then Johnson threw another ball. On the full-count
pitch, Johnson jammed Payton, breaking his bat as Payton looped a
double to shallow left.
</P>
<P>
   It was troublesome, because it brought up Joe McEwing, who has
become a nemesis of Johnson's. Reserve players like McEwing
sometimes succeed against Johnson; they fill in for starters who
take a well-timed day off against the dominating left-hander. Jeff
Reboluet filled this role with Baltimore, when Johnson pitched for
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   McEwing got his first career hit off Johnson, in 1998, and had
two doubles and a homer off him this May. With the pitcher on deck,
Johnson pitched carefully to McEwing, and fell behind, 3-0. His 3-1
pitch was a fastball down in the zone _ a good pitch, it seemed,
but McEwing drilled it to the gap in right-center for a run-scoring
double that put the Mets ahead, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets singled twice off Johnson in the third until Todd
Zeile, who is 0 for 10 in his career against Johnson, saw three
pitches and fanned on a slider to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fourth, the bottom of the Mets' order bedeviled
Johnson again. Benny Agbayani smoked a slider into the left-field
corner for a double. Payton swung at a first-pitch slider and drove
it to right field for a single, putting runners at the corners.
</P>
<P>
   McEwing stood in, and again Johnson suffered. His first two
pitches were balls, and McEwing drove the third to right field for
a sacrifice fly, putting the Mets ahead, 2-0. Payton took second on
a sacrifice and third on a wild pitch, and Mike Bordick walked.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Derek Bell, who looked utterly helpless while
striking out in his first two at-bats off Johnson. This was
Johnson's escape hatch, but he could not take it. He fell behind
Bell, and when the count evened at 2-2, he missed badly with a high
fastball to run the count full. Bell hung tough, fouling off three
pitches before bouncing a routine grounder to short that should
have ended the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Womack bobbled the ball, and by the time he recovered and
threw to first, Bell had crossed the bag and Payton had scored.
Johnson was clearly shaken _ he missed inside on four straight
pitches to Edgardo Alfonzo, bringing up Mike Piazza with the bases
loaded and inviting disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza has been lethal with the bases loaded, and this time was
no different. He fouled off two pitches with two strikes, then
lashed a two-run single to right that gave the Mets a 5-0 lead.
Johnson had thrown 89 pitches, and he would throw no more: Russ
Springer came in from the bullpen and the Diamondbacks finally got
out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   For Johnson, it was his shortest start since May 19, 1998, when
he lasted three innings in a start for the Mariners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
