<HEADER>
A3365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-WALTRIP-BRICKYARD-NYT     08-05 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALTRIP-BRICKYARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALTRIP SAVORS SURPRISING TRIP TO FRONT ROW FOR BRICKYARD 400 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE CALDWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Twenty-four delightful and exhausting hours
later, Darrell Waltrip said his right hand was killing him, adding
as he flexed his hand that he could deal with the pain that only
politicians on whistle-stop tours can really know.
</P>
<P>
   So many people were so happy for Waltrip after he made the front
row for Saturday's Brickyard 400 with a surprisingly speedy
qualifying run that they offered jubilant, hearty handshakes deep
into Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the handshakes were a little too hearty. The popular,
self-deprecating, high-voltage veteran said he was actually tired
when he showed up for work this morning, and he joked that he
thought his hand would fall off if one more person shook it.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in a way, he said he had not felt this invigorated in a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   When Waltrip's qualifying run was over Thursday afternoon, he
stood in front of the main grandstand at Indianapolis Motor
Speedway and did a crowd-pleasing reprise of the dance he borrowed
from Ickey Woods, the former Cincinnati Bengals running back, when
he won the Daytona 500 in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Now Waltrip, 53, midway through a discouraging final season on
the Nascar Winston Cup circuit, has a chance to start a race at the
front of the pack, not the back. This was how his ``Victory Tour''
was supposed to work.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip has not won a race in eight years, and has not finished
better than 22nd in any Winston Cup race this year, but he has
vowed to do the most with this chance to win, because this chance
might be his last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like they say, a blind hog should be able to find an acorn
every once in a while, and I thought this old blind hog would be
able to find an acorn or two,'' Waltrip said as he sat on a jack in
his garage this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we'd be great,'' he said, ``but I didn't think
we'd be as bad as we've been sometimes. But I don't think we'll go
back to the same place and make the same mistakes now.''
</P>
<P>
   By earning a starting place next to Ricky Rudd, the pole-sitter,
Waltrip has given the seventh Brickyard 400 some extra sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Mayfield, who was leading the July 23 race at Long Pond,
Pa., until he blew a tire midway through the last lap, slammed the
wall during practice this morning and sustained a concussion that
was serious enough to keep him out of the race. His place is to be
taken by Kyle Petty, who failed to qualify in his own car.
</P>
<P>
   The chase for the Winston Cup championship is on low boil. Dale
Jarrett has climbed over Dale Earnhardt into second place in the
Winston Cup standing and is just 53 points behind the leader, Bobby
Labonte. But Earnhardt, hungry for his eighth Winston Cup
championship, has sounded particularly eager to win this race.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt even found time to tease his nemesis Jeff Gordon, the
one-time wonderboy and two-time Brickyard 400 champion from nearby
Pittsboro, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon turned 29 Friday, and Earnhardt said, ``He's finally
become a man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows I'll get him back some time,'' Gordon said in
response.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip, who plans to join the Fox network next year as a racing
commentator, does not have the benefit of time.
</P>
<P>
   That made his 180.923-miles-an-hour qualifying run Thursday
electrifying. Rudd sounded somewhat disappointed that he took the
pole position away 24 minutes later. Waltrip has not sat on the
pole for a race since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that Darrell had one of the best runs he's
had in many, many years,'' Rudd said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The run was encouraging enough for Waltrip's young team. He said
he considers himself to be a teacher for his team, which includes
Larry Carter, a first-year crew chief. The lessons have mostly been
unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip has not qualified for three races this year and is 38th
in the points standing.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said Friday that one of his goals was simply to get
Waltrip through his final season without serious incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to win one for him now,'' Carter said. ``We've just
got to get everything right for him _ the way it should be. I think
we've made a lot of progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than worrying about merely making the race in the final
round of qualifying _ as Waltrip has had to do in all but three
races this year _ Carter and Waltrip used a two-hour practice this
morning to get ready for the race. That, Waltrip said, was a
luxury.
</P>
<P>
   But to those who have said he has stuck around too long,
becoming sort of a Willie Mays with horsepower, Waltrip offers a
tart reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to do what I do on Sundays,'' he said. ``And
it'd be very easy for me to say: `OK, I'm not competitive anymore.
I quit.'''
</P>
<P>
   He will be quitting soon enough. He has one more chance to win
one more race, which would be his 85th and would put him ahead of
Bobby Allison alone in third place among Winston Cup drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip said he loves this place, loves its rich history, loves
driving here. He will not guarantee victory, but he said he does
not plan to embarrass himself, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want to fall back to last place,'' he said,
smiling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
