<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-RUNNING-STAG-NYT &LR;      08-05 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-RUNNING-STAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNING STAG READY AFTER 35,000 MILES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ In search of fun and pots of gold,
three jolly Englishmen have traveled to France, Germany, Dubai and
Hong Kong, as well as Massachusetts, Kentucky and New York. They
fly, of course, but it is a horse that leads them to these locales.
His name is Running Stag, and he has logged more miles than many
heads of state, hitting new soil with ground-burning speed.
</P>
<P>
   He has clocked more than 35,000 miles in the past year alone
and, for the third time in that span, has made the journey from his
base in Epsom in England to the United States, this time to take on
the country's best older horses in the Whitney Handicap on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   According to his owner, Richard Cohen, and trainer, Philip
Mitchell, their 6-year-old colt gets terribly bored galloping on
the soft grass in his native land. In fact, in 19 races on turf, he
has won only once.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching for a way for Running Stag to find the winner's circle
as a 3-year-old, Mitchell put him in a maiden race on the dirt at
Lingfield, England. He won by seven lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the best dirt horse in Europe,'' Mitchell told Cohen,
which was akin to the trainer declaring himself the best cricket
player in New York _ turf racing dominates the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell had a plan. Just as Running Stag took flight on the
dirt, he and his horse were going to take to the air in search of
what he called ``pots of gold,'' or richer races on his preferred
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's reply was simple: Why not? ``I like having fun for
starters and was game to see a bit of the world,'' said Cohen, 64,
who is enjoying his first week of retirement from his international
furniture, carpet and electrical company.
</P>
<P>
   So Mitchell sent Running Stag and an assistant trainer, Roger
Teal, to Belmont Park for the 1998 Woodward Stakes. The invader
finished a surprising third to the marquee horses of that day, Skip
Away and Gentleman. By 1999, Running Stag had become a respected
foe in the older-horse handicap division with a loss by a nose to
Behrens _ one of his rivals on Sunday _ in the Massachusetts
Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   He followed that with victories in the Brooklyn at Belmont and
the Grade II Saratoga Breeders' Cup here. Overall, he has earned
over $1.5 million in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The cost and mechanics of shipping Running Stag back and forth
was a tiny investment, given the far bigger payoff of winning
bigger purses. How do they ship and for how much?
</P>
<P>
   ``We take the first six seats out of first class,'' said a
deadpan Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   For an $8,000 round-trip ticket, Teal walks Running Stag into a
cargo plane, stands and holds him during takeoffs and landings, and
then sits in a chair nearby. ``He drinks and eats and naps just
like any other international passenger,'' Teal said. ``It's really
remarkable how calm he is.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons for running in the United States. The
races in America set up better for Running Stag's front-running
style. In Europe, horses tend to lope during the early part of the
race to preserve themselves for a late dash. And the constant
pounding on dirt can take its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe, we have to do too much up front in races,''
Mitchell said. ``But to train over here all the time is too much.
We can gallop him through woods back home, work him on grass.
American racing is hard on a horse.''
</P>
<P>
   In 38 races, Running Stag has demonstrated that he is far from
fragile. On his last trip to the United States, in May, he ran
three races in two weeks _ winning an allowance race at Belmont and
capturing the Grade II Massachusetts Handicap the next week before
tiring in blistering June heat to finish sixth behind the Whitney's
morning-line favorite, Lemon Drop Kid, in the Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Odds-makers have made Running Stag a 6-1 outsider in the
$750,000 Grade I Whitney. Mitchell and Cohen hardly care. They were
sent off at 25-1 last December when Running Stag finished second in
the Hong Kong Cup. It was after that race, as well as a few pints,
that Running Stag's rider, Shane Sellers, urged them to try the
mile-and-one-eighth Whitney. ``He staggered up to me with a big
glass in his hand and said the race set up for us,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   So they're here trying to wring out the last of the big times in
their equine odyssey. Cohen had to miss the last jaunt to the
United States because he was having angioplasty surgery. ``They
told me it was important,'' he said with a wry smile. ``Both of us
are getting old. Running Stag will go to stud soon and I'll sit
back and watch his progeny run. At home, we all have wives and
children who'd like to see us more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
