<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-TAKEOVER-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANDARDS SET FOR BIDDERS TO TAKE OVER SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When executives of Inside Broadway, a nonprofit arts
education program, learned that the New York City Board of
Education planned to turn over some of the city's worst-performing
schools to private hands, they decided to take a chance.
</P>
<P>
   That was until Friday, when school officials mapped out the
requirements for prospective bidders. Applicants must have
experience in running schools with more than 450 students and
budgets of at least $1.5 million, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Broadway worked with 150 schools last year, producing
shows, distributing Broadway tickets to schools and taking actors
into classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think those are bad qualifications,'' said Paul Naish,
executive business manager of Inside Broadway. ``But the newspaper
ad didn't specify what experience we needed. I have never run a
school. I've run arts programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Naish was among about 100 vendors from across the city and the
nation _ including Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; Boston; and Providence,
R.I. _ who crammed into a hearing room at the Board of Education
headquarters in Brooklyn to learn of the requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But only a handful of vendors _ like Edison Schools, the largest
commercial school-management company in the United States, and its
competitors Victory Schools and Advantage Schools _ had the
experience to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the smaller vendors complained about the requirement
that bidders have experience in running schools with more than 450
students. But Judith A. Rizzo, the deputy chancellor for
instruction, was unapologetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what I'm looking for,'' Rizzo said. ``I want to know
that you can run a school the size of a school in the Chancellor's
District. I want to see if you can do the deal.'' The Chancellor's
District is the special school district that the Board of Education
established for struggling schools.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Schools Chancellor Harold Levy issued a request
for proposals to help the board convert the failing schools into
charter schools in the fall of 2001. The move would release the
schools from many of the state and local regulations that now
govern them. If the schools' conversions to charter status are
approved by the state Board of Regents, the schools' new managers
will be able to renegotiate some union contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The plan does not specify how many or which schools would be
turned over to private management. But officials said it was likely
to focus on about seven schools and could include as many as 20 in
its first year, depending on the number and quality of
applications.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 schools qualify for the program _ about 40 of which are
elementary and middle schools and the rest high schools. They are
on the state's list of ``schools under registration review''
because of their poor performance and are in the Chancellor's
District.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The requirements also call, among other things, for applicants
to do a significant amount of community outreach, and for parents
of 51 percent of the students in a school to vote for a charter
conversion, in a process that would take months.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education would pay the management company on a
per-student basis to operate a school. State law requires an
allocation of only about $6,630 a student, not including money for
federal benefits and other special programs.
</P>
<P>
   While Advantage Schools expressed concerns about the condition
of the buildings, it planned to bid to operate some of the schools.
It operates schools in Philadelphia, Washington, Phoenix, and
Newark, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
