<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Astros </SLUG>
 lede -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two Truby homers help Astros top Expos
</P>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took the Expos' best shot _ literally _ and delivered
a couple of their own Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Truby hit a pair of home runs, and the Astros offset the
loss of righthander Chris Holt with a 7-6 come-from-behind victory
before a crowd of 38,502 at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   Daryle Ward added a three-run homer as the Astros rallied from
4-0 and 6-5 deficits.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros ended a two-game losing streak with only their sixth
win in 27 one-run games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Berkman broke a 6-all deadlock with a single to left field
in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have as many guys out as we do, you have to depend on
some young men coming of age,'' said manager Larry Dierker of the
injury-ravaged Astros, who have seven players on the disabled list.
``Berkman has been doing it all year long, Ward was doing it early
and has been hitting well lately, and Truby kind of came out of
nowhere (Friday).''
</P>
<P>
   Despite four home runs in the game _ three by the Astros, who
set a club record for round-trippers at home in a season _ the
biggest blow came during the fourth inning when Holt took a line
drive off the left side of his face. X-rays were negative, and Holt
was diagnosed with a bruised left cheekbone.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won their season-high third straight game at home and
are 6-3 at Enron Field since July 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos started early Friday, sending nine batters to the
plate against Holt during a three-run first inning.
</P>
<P>
   After Lee Stevens' two-run single up the middle, a walk to Geoff
Blum and a single by Chris Widger loaded the bases. Tomas de la
Rosa hit a broken-bat grounder past the mound, and Astros rookie
shortstop Julio Lugo attempted to make a barehanded grab but
couldn't complete the play in time.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Vladimir Guerrero led off with a triple to the
center-field gap and scored when Lugo's relay throw sailed into the
Montreal dugout, extending the Expos' lead to 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   The lead didn't last long as the Astros erupted for five runs in
their half of the third.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Eusebio singled to lead off the inning, and Truby followed
with a two-run homer off Javier Vazquez. Two batters later, Bill
Spiers singled to left field, and Berkman later singled to center.
Ward, who started at first base, then hit a three-run homer off the
right-field foul pole to give the Astros a 5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always clutch to see the other guys getting the big
hits,'' said Ward, who hit an eye-level pitch for his 15th home run
of the season. ``It kind of filters down through the whole lineup
and makes you say, `I've got to step it up, too.' To see the rest
of the team hitting, you don't want to be the only one not doing
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Silence fell upon Enron Field with two outs in the fourth when
Peter Bergeron sent a 1-0 pitch back toward the mound and off the
left side of Holt's face. The 28-year-old pitcher lay face down on
the ground for a few minutes, blood visible, before walking off the
field on his own power.
</P>
<P>
   Holt allowed five runs and seven hits in 3 innings. Wayne
Franklin replaced him, allowing one run and four hits in 2 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos tied the game at 5 when Wilton Guerrero hit a two-out
single off Franklin in the fourth. Geoff Blum put the Expos ahead
6-5 with a home run to left field in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Houston rallied to tie the game in the sixth when Truby hit his
second homer of the game. The Astros have hit 83 home runs at home,
breaking the old mark of 82 set in 1998 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday, Truby had gone 81 at-bats since his first _ and
only _ homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been kind of scuffling a little bit. I feel like I
haven't been doing anything the last few weeks,'' Truby said.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took the lead for good in the seventh. Lugo tripled
on a fly ball to right field that Vladimir Guerrero misplayed at
the wall, and Berkman singled to left off reliever Steve Kline
(1-4).
</P>
<P>
   Montreal had runners at first and third with two outs in the
eighth before closer Octavio Dotel got out of the jam with a
strikeout of Vladimir Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's providing us with something important, nailing down wins
(in the late innings),'' Dierker said of Dotel. ``He was frustrated
as a starter when he would come out after six innings, and
sometimes we were ahead and sometimes we weren't. He wasn't getting
a lot of wins. Knowing how competitive he is, you can see how he
cherishes being in (there in) the ninth inning under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel pitched the final 1 innings for his fifth save and hasn't
allowed a run in 12 relief appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian-born Astros reliever Jason Green (1-0) picked up his
first major-league win. He held the Expos to two hits over 1
innings.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
