</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MILOSEVIC-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHALLENGING MR. MILOSEVIC
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 5: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic is running for another term as Yugoslavia's
president in an unfair election that he will most likely win by any
means necessary. Nevertheless, the opposition should run against
him. No one believes that Milosevic will leave office simply
because voters tell him to. But if the opposition can unite on a
single presidential candidate for the elections in late September,
it can at least revitalize its popular support and shake some of
the apathy that is paralyzing Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition will certainly run candidates in local elections.
Anti-Milosevic candidates won in more than 30 municipalities in
1996, although protesters had to occupy the streets for months in
order to get Milosevic to recognize the victories. These local
officials give the opposition control of some funds and broadcast
media, in addition to political stature and a base for organizing.
The posts are crucial to keep. The opposition should also run
candidates in the federal Parliament to reduce Milosevic's
near-total control.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has taken no chances with his own re-election.
Recently he has shut down many of the remaining independent media
in Serbia, and has been intimidating opposition politicians and
independent activists through violence and abuse of the courts. His
ubiquitous propaganda allows him to remain the most popular
politician in Serbia. But he is helped by a petty and ineffectual
opposition. Polls, however, show that if the opposition united
around a single candidate, that person could win. Even if there is
little chance the winner would be allowed to take office, this
would energize the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend there is a convention of the Serbian Renewal
Movement, whose leader, Vuk Draskovic, is the main obstacle to a
united opposition. Draskovic has in the past cut deals with
Milosevic and sabotaged opposition unity, acts that should
disqualify him as a candidate this time.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic has said that his party will not participate in the
elections if Milo Djukanovic, the president of Serbia's tiny sister
republic of Montenegro, stays out as well. But Djukanovic, who has
led his republic in a mutiny against the Yugoslav president, has a
better reason for boycotting. He is already under the constant
threat of attack from the Yugoslav army stationed in Montenegro _
an attack that Washington fears may come soon. The presidential
election will be staged with new rules that are part of a recent
constitutional coup by Milosevic, which greatly reduced
Montenegro's influence in the presidential election and over all.
</P>
<P>
   If the opposition does contest the election and Milosevic wins,
countries such as Russia, Greece and Italy should not use his
``victory'' as a pretext to improve their relations with Serbia.
They well know he keeps power through repression. Nor should
Milosevic look forward to a change in American policy if Gov.
George W. Bush becomes president. The Republican platform says
there should be no negotiations with indicted war criminals such as
Milosevic, and that Washington should seek their arrest, trial and
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Contesting Milosevic for the presidency requires opposition
unity. Democratic opposition parties were able to beat Vladimir
Meciar in Slovakia and Franjo Tudjman's party in Croatia only when
they overcame their internal squabbles. Milosevic is more
malignant, but that only makes unity even more necessary. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
