<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, August 5.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARAFAT-ARABS (Cairo, Egypt) _ On the face of it, Arab support
for the Palestinian position has never been so seamless. Or so it
would seem as the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, has
crisscrossed the Middle East to garner support from his
counterparts and build a defensive line for his position on a peace
deal with Israel. One after the other, Arab kings and presidents
have said they stand behind Arafat, no questions asked, as he holds
out for Palestinian sovereignty over Arab East Jerusalem and the
right of return for Palestinian refugees. But behind the
uncompromising public statements, more pragmatic approaches are
also being discussed seriously for the first time on those
thorniest of disputed issues. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-ARMS (Washington) _ U.S. intelligence assessments of
North Korean arms programs. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-U.N. (Shanghai) _ Taiwan is again pushing to join the
United Nations, arguing that the world body could be a good forum
in which Taiwan and China could settle their differences. By Craig
S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-SINATRA-STATUE (New York) _ The Rev. Francis Patrick Duffy
got a spot on Times Square in 1936 for his heroics on the
battlefield and the streets of Hell's Kitchen. George M. Cohan
followed in 1959 as a tribute to one of show business' greatest
song and dance men. Mayor Rudy Giuliani says there is room for one
more, Frank Sinatra, whose last big hit, in 1980, was ``New York,
New York.'' But the hushed refrain playing around Times Square is
not so gushing or welcoming. No one really wants to say so, at
least not loudly enough to irk Giuliani or offend the Sinatra
family, but the plan to erect a statue of Ol' Blue Eyes on a
traffic island at 44th Street and Broadway has acquired some
powerful enemies. The local community board, along with some Times
Square developers, isn't crazy about the idea. And theater moguls
say the square's theatrical tradition would be shortchanged by
showcasing a singer and film actor who started in Hoboken, made a
quick splash at the Paramount Theater and then followed fame and
fortune west of the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PHILIPPINES-CHARITY (New York) _ A tale of philanthropy: a
publishing executive has gained notoriety and popularity in the
Philippines by contributing vast sums of money _ in the millions,
perhaps _ to build hospitals and civic facilities. The problem,
Manhattan prosecutors say, is that she embezzled the money from her
company. By Katherine E. Finkelstein.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ORPHANED-BRANDS (Cincinnati) _ Todd Wichmann and Richard Owen
barreled into the Procter &AMP; Gamble headquarters last month and were
about to head upstairs when the security guard stopped them.
Waiting for permission to enter a place they had worked almost all
their adult lives felt ``bizarre-weird,'' Wichmann said as he
fiddled with his red visitor's badge. He and Owen had just quit
their jobs at P&AMP;G to form Redox Brands Inc., a company that would
specialize in buying once-famous laundry and cleaning brands that
giants like their former employer are discarding. By Kruti Trivedi.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo and graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   BARNEYS-QUESTROM (Undated) _ When troubled retailer J.C. Penney
announced last week that Allen L. Questrom would be its new chief
executive, Wall Street was euphoric. Investor enthusiasm stems in
large part from the work that Questrom did reviving ailing public
companies like Federated Department Stores and Macy's, which
Federated acquired under his leadership. But in the most recent
chapter of his career, as chairman and chief executive of Barney's
New York Inc., it is less clear that the veteran turnaround man has
spun straw into gold. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN _ (Philadelphia) _ Anthony Lewis writes about
Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BERKOW-COLUMN (Zion, Ill.) _ Sports of The Times: Adolph
Kiefer, an Olympic swimmer at the 1936 Berlin Games, remembers his
encounter with Adolph Hitler. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (Moved in ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANARCHY-REVIVED (Undated) _ Self-described anarchists are small
in number. But anarchism, broadly construed, is becoming
fashionable. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IRONY-RECONSIDERED (Undated) _ So is irony a bad thing or a good
thing? It depends, in part, on what you mean by irony, which has
become a critical term of nearly infinite elasticity. By Charles
McGrath
</P>
<P>
   REAL-LIFE-TV (Undated) _ Watching ``real life'' moments from the
television shows, ``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother,'' I felt an
all-too-familiar twinge. Plato described it as the contradictory
feelings of repulsion and fascination that arise when a dead body
is viewed by the living. Corpses must have caused an ancient form
of rubber necking. Now, television does it. I watch in gruesome
embarrassment. By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-NOVELIST (Undated) _ At 37, Moses Isegawa is a novelist
with an increasing international reputation. His first novel,
``Abyssinian Chronicles,'' was recently published in the United
States, having already been published in the Netherlands (where the
author now lives) and in Finland and Germany. The book is a coming
of age novel with a cast of evocative African characters and an
account of the political turbulence during the regime of Idi Amin,
the former Ugandan dictator. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BLACKLIST (Hollywood) _ The Writers Guild announced this
week that the writing credits on 14 films, released between 1951
and 1964, will be corrected to include the names of several
screenwriters blacklisted by Hollywood studios. The current credits
either omit a blacklisted writer's name or use a pseudonym. By
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
</TEXT>
