<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-GILL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOURCE: LAKERS CLOSE TO SIGNING KENDALL GILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ The Lakers might have at last found a taker
for their $2.25 million salary-cap exception, but it won't fill
their greatest need _ help in the frontcourt.
</P>
<P>
   As the Lakers continue their search for a rebounding big man,
they are closing in on a deal to bring New Jersey Nets swingman
Kendall Gill to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Gill has balked at a $4.4 million offer to re-sign with New
Jersey and is considering less lucrative deals, several New York
newspapers reported. On Friday, an NBA source told the Daily News
that Gill is indeed close to signing with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A time comes when you'll take less elsewhere if you have to.
That time has arrived,'' Gill told the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of the 6-foot-5 Gill, a natural shooting guard who
played small forward for the Nets, would seem to give the Lakers a
glut of guards. They return starters Kobe Bryant and Ron Harper and
reserve Derek Fisher and still hope to re-sign Brian Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   But Gill's presence would give the Lakers some flexibility. If
Glen Rice leaves, as expected _ either as a free agent or in a
sign-and-trade deal _ Gill could replace him; or Gill could start
at guard, with the 6-7 Bryant moving to small forward.
</P>
<P>
   Gill's presence also would allow the Lakers to reduce the aging
Harper's minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-year veteran, Gill played the last four-plus seasons with
the Nets, following stints with Seattle and Charlotte. He averaged
13.1 points, 3.7 rebounds and 2.8 assists last season and
registered 1.83 steals per game _ ninth in the NBA. He was the NBA
steals leader in 1998-99, with 2.68 per game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
