<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3393 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     08-05 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HOPE GOODWIN FOLLOWS IN LOPES' SPEEDY FOOTSTEPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We would claim poetic license and say the Dodger
Stadium basepaths once torn up by Davey Lopes lie abandoned and
overgrown with weeds, but that would be unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Unfair to the grounds crew, which works hard to keep that
historic dirt looking sharp. Oh, and mildly unfair to a generation
of Dodgers players.
</P>
<P>
   Young men have continued to run and play on those basepaths in
the two decades since Lopes packed up his churning spikes and moved
on to become a coach _ and now the manager of the Milwaukee
Brewers. A few of those young men could even steal a base.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, the L.A. franchise that employed the
National League's leading basestealers eight times in the 1960s
(Maury Wills) and 1970s (Lopes) has abandoned the art of the theft,
not unlike the rest of the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an afterthought,'' Lopes said Friday upon his return to
Dodger Stadium with the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin aims to return that lost art to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, the former Dodgers prospect reacquired Monday in the
trade of Todd Hollandsworth to the Colorado Rockies, is the long
overdue heir to Lopes' base-stealing crown.
</P>
<P>
   His story is a study in what has become of the running game in
the era where, as Goodwin says, ``Guys don't come up saying, `I
want to steal 100 bases,' they come up saying, `I want to hit 100
home runs.'''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, from an academic family, got an inkling he was fast
afoot in high school at Fresno Central, where he split time between
baseball and track. But he wasn't the fastest kid in the
schoolyard. He says he didn't realize how fast he was until college
at Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   One day a Bulldogs flanker, Andre Alexander, challenged the
baseball player to a race. A third man put up the prize money.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden we were lining up in the parking lot and
everybody was gathering around,'' Goodwin remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin won the race. Alexander went on to play two seasons in
the Canadian Football League and one in the World League.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin went on to sign with the Dodgers in 1989. You'd think
baseball would take a guy with his speed and immerse him in the
finer points of basestealing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, it wasn't until after he was waived by the
Dodgers and went to the Kansas City Royals in 1994 that he got some
meaningful lessons. And the lessons came not from a coach but from
a teammate, Vince Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman taught him how to take a lead and get a jump. He taught
him to use videotape to study the pickoff move of the next day's
pitcher. The following year, Goodwin stole a career-high 66 bases
in 88 attempts for the Royals, and over the past five years he has
been the major leagues' steals leader with 243.
</P>
<P>
   His ability to imitate Lopes' fast feats depends now on his
batting (only .208 outside hitter-friendly Coors Field at the time
the Rockies traded him) and his continuing education in the ways of
National League pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The story of how Goodwin played six professional seasons before
he was tutored in basestealing didn't surprise Lopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very few people that have the knowledge to teach a
player of that magnitude the art and science of basestealing,''
Lopes said before the Brewers and Dodgers opened a three-game
series Friday. ``Coaching the basestealers is usually handled by
the outfield coach, and he may not know that much about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing to a basestealing instructor on the Dodgers'
big-league staff is first-base coach John Shelby, who never stole
more than 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become less and less (a part of offenses) because teams
go for the long ball,'' Lopes said of the years since he led the
league with 77 in 1975 and 63 in 1976. ``The economics of the game
dictate that guys who are bigger and stronger get the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Managers are more content to anchor their baserunners and plan
on the three-run homer. And pitchers have gotten tougher on
basestealers, speeding up their deliveries with slide steps.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, 6-foot-1 and 175 pounds, realized early on that speed
would be his meal ticket. The Dodgers realized just before the
trading deadline that speed was something they missed.
</P>
<P>
   The new leadoff hitter and center fielder vows to do right by
those old basepaths, to be the kind of runner who Lopes says will
steal ``when even the least knowledgeable fan in the park knows
you're going to steal.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't trip over the weeds, Tom. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 0158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
