<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3394 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-OLY-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     08-05 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE LOST A TRUE HERO AND A BEAUTIFUL PERSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We lost a true hero and a beautiful person &QL; 
One of my heroes left us this week, and our world is a lesser place
because of it.
</P>
<P>
   You never saw her name in a box score. She never hit a home run
or scored a touchdown. She never won an Olympic medal or led her
team to a title.
</P>
<P>
   She never served an ace at Wimbledon or ripped off her shirt and
showed us her sports bra at the dramatic close of an international
soccer match. She didn't have Anna Kournikova's sexy ponytail _ at
least not when I knew her _ or dated famous NHL stars or appeared
on ESPN's ``Up Close.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she didn't have any hair at all.
</P>
<P>
   But she was one of the most beautiful people I've ever met.
</P>
<P>
   In her 12 short years, Kelly Davidson proved to those who knew
her that she was a champion at the most important game of all _
life.
</P>
<P>
   Her funeral was held yesterday in Austin after she succumbed to
a battle with cancer that lasted almost half of her young life.
</P>
<P>
   My Webster's defines ``succumbs'' as to ``yield to superior
strength or force ... to be brought to an end by the effect of
destructive or disruptive forces.'' That's the best way I can think
of to put it, because Kelly never surrendered, never gave up, never
quit fighting to simply live her life like any other child.
</P>
<P>
   You probably didn't know Kelly, not personally anyway, but you
likely saw her and didn't realize who she was. She was ``adopted''
by two-time Tour de France winner Lance Armstrong a couple of years
ago and has appeared on some of his TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Her sweet smile as she bicycled with Armstrong lit up the TV
screen.
</P>
<P>
   It was Kelly that Armstrong singled out for a special greeting
at the end of his victory in one of the stages of last year's Tour
de France. And when he made an appearance on ``Good Morning
America'' after the race, they'd arranged a special hookup with
Kelly at Cook Children's Medical Center. Armstrong, a cancer
survivor himself, saw to it that Kelly was presented with a new
bike.
</P>
<P>
   Lance and his wife, Kristin, visited Kelly to say goodbye a few
days before she died Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lance and Kelly met in a McDonald's in Austin 3 1/2 years ago,
naturally drawn to each other because they were the only two bald
people in the place. They laughed. They joked. They exchanged phone
numbers. A few days later, Kelly's mother, Jamie, was shocked when
she picked up the phone and Armstrong was on the other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to talk to that little girl,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   We were lucky that they allowed us an occasional peek into what
obviously became a close and beautiful friendship. It was a
mutually beneficial relationship. Kelly would personally help raise
more than $20,000 for the Lance Armstrong Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and I crossed paths a couple of weeks before Christmas
last December at the Fort Worth Ronald McDonald House, her home
away from home.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' Rusty Greer was there to dedicate the House's
Serenity Garden, and Kelly was one of three very sick children who
were on hand to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had an attitude that she was going to get the most out of
life, even if she was sick, and that was refreshing,'' Greer said
yesterday from Toronto, ``because it makes you realize how much
more there is to life than nine innings of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   She was pale, her cheeks were hollow and her eyes were sunken.
Pain and fatigue had beaten her down. None of that could keep her
inner strength and something else _ a sense of peace is the best
way I can think to describe it _ from shining through.
</P>
<P>
   The brightly colored lights on the Christmas tree only
emphasized the waxy whiteness of Kelly's skin and smooth, hairless
scalp, but when she smiled, it was like someone had suddenly turned
klieg lights on in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired,'' she confided at one point, ``but I'm always
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, she broke my heart.
</P>
<P>
   She captured it, too, for I have thought of her often since that
day. I would get occasional e-mail updates on Kelly from the nice
folks at the Ronald McDonald House, or see her TV commercials
again.
</P>
<P>
   We had talked about our dogs _ she had a new puppy named Andre _
and about her dreams.
</P>
<P>
   In her dreams she wasn't sick anymore. She could run like the
wind and never get tired. She could keep up with Lance on her bike.
In a few years she would turn 16 and get a new car for her
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A red Mustang convertible,'' she said, flashing that smile
again.
</P>
<P>
   It would have happened, too. You just know it would have,
somehow.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other, more important, plans afoot. Kelly won't be
here for another birthday, or another Christmas, or another Tour de
France and I won't kid you, that's hard for me to understand.
</P>
<P>
   She'd probably explain it all to me, if she could. She had that
way about her, an understanding of the way things worked, that
something special that's so easy to see, yet so hard to describe.
She just touched people's lives just by being herself.
</P>
<P>
   I count myself lucky that mine was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Now I find myself in need of a long walk. I want to feel a soft
breeze on my face while I think of a beautiful 16-year-old girl,
racing down the road in a red convertible, her long hair streaming
in the wind, a smile as big as Texas on her face.
</P>
<P>
   Fly fast, Kelly. Fly just as fast as you can. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 0208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
