<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SMITH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMMITT SMITH SHOWS THE JAPANESE THAT ABILITY MAKES YOU TALL IN
FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Emmitt Smith had to travel 6,420 miles to feel tall.
</P>
<P>
   It's a feeling the Cowboys' Pro Bowl running back doesn't get a
chance to experience often in the NFL, where the word ``big'' is
only used to describe his feats running the football.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese look at me and think I'm big,'' said Smith, whose
5-foot-9, 209-pound frame is considered ``small'' in the NFL.
``Then when they see some of the other players on these teams, they
look like giants to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who missed the Cowboys' preseason opener against
Pittsburgh with a sprained big toe, is likely to be held out of
tonight's American Bowl game against the Atlanta Falcons because of
the week-old injury. He remains a game-time decision for the 9 p.m.
CDT kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   The toe injury is not considered serious. Smith has been able to
run plays in practice since arriving here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was here in April \Rpromoting this game for the NFL\S,
I found that in some way the Japanese people are kind of surprised
that a guy of my stature can go out and do what I do,'' said Smith,
who is the NFL's leading active rusher (13,963) and third all-time
in league history behind Walter Payton (16,726) and Barry Sanders
(15,629).
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably gives them a little bit of hope that if he can do
it, maybe I can do it, too. Hopefully, that's what they get out of
it,'' Smith said. ``Because I don't necessarily believe that the
biggest guy always wins. David knocked Goliath down, and took his
head off.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, Smith spoke with some of the 30,000 people who play
American football in this country. He tried to inspire them with
his words, not just his size.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of size, Smith was handed what he termed a
``loaded question'' from KTVT/Channel 11 sports director Babe
Laufenberg, a former NFL quarterback, on the floor of the Tokyo
Dome:
</P>
<P>
   How does Emmitt Smith feel he would do in running the football
in the NFL behind an all-Japanese offensive line?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too well,'' Smith replied, quickly adding, ``Not
necessarily because of their size but maybe because of their skill
level in terms of the game itself. American players have been
playing football since they were 8 years old. Come on, be fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go through all the stages of the game,'' said
Smith, who began as a third-grader in pee wee football in Florida.
``I grew up playing the sport. A lot of Japanese haven't grown up
playing the sport, just as they haven't had the same coaching and
teaching that we've had.''
</P>
<P>
   American football was introduced to Japan in 1934. The high
school and college programs use NCAA rules, not NFL rules, as a
standard. But the NFL as a spectator sport has quickly grown in
popularity since the first American Bowl game here in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   No fewer than 11 Japanese players have played in NFL Europe,
including three who have been signed to 10-day contracts and will
participate in tonight's game. They include wide receiver Masaito
Itai and linebacker Masafumi Kawaguchi for the Cowboys and tight
end Nachi Abe for the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Smith plays is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys don't want to risk an injury with any of their key
players. But they want to establish a focus that will allow them to
take care of business on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be able to win on the road,'' quarterback Troy
Aikman said. ``It's a mind-set. We have to be more consistent as an
offensive team, because for us to be the team that we ultimately
hope to be, we have to execute and score points. That has been our
point of emphasis the past five months.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Warren will start at tailback for the Cowboys for a second
week in a row if Smith is held out. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
