<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH AIMING FOR THE SKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ New Texas Tech coach Mike Leach said yesterday
at the Red Raiders' media day that he would be disappointed if the
veteran offensive players aren't sharp when they join the freshmen
for the first full-squad workout today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do, I'm going to feel really good about it all,'' he
said. ``I thought we had an excellent spring and I've mentioned
before that I felt like they are the furthest along of any team
I've been a part of as far as picking up the package.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach said that includes last year's group at Oklahoma, where
Leach was the offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as knowing the system, \Rthe players at Tech\S have
picked \Rthe package\S up sooner and gone a little further with
it,'' Leach said. ``These players are more established in their
roles, knowing what they're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kliff Kingsbury, who completed 24 of 26 passes for
321 yards and three touchdowns in the spring game, said he wasn't
surprised the players took to the offense so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of veteran receivers and running backs,''
Kingsbury said. ``And everyone was so excited that we were going to
be throwing the ball around that everyone really got into it quick.
There's more excitement than nervousness heading into the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore running back Shaud Williams, who set a school freshman
rushing record with 320 yards on 21 carries against Colorado last
season, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to get going,'' Williams said. ``We've been
working out all summer and have high expectations _ like winning
the Big 12 championship and going 14-0. We put that pressure on
ourselves and want to live up to those expectations.''
\Nsubheds:Walk-on shines Freshman wide receiver Trey Haverty, an
invited walk-on, has shown signs that he might be the ``steal'' of
the incoming class.
</P>
<P>
   Haverty, who caught 68 passes for 914 yards as a high school
junior, broke an ankle in the only contact scrimmage of August at
Richardson Berkner last year. He returned to play in six games and
caught 36 passes for 683 yards. He also played basketball and ran
track, winning the District 6-5A 400-meter championship.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Naval and Air Force academies offered scholarships. He
said neither appealed to him, and his girlfriend's parents, both
Tech exes, urged him to explore walking on with the Red Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trey had his best practice in our fourth practice
\RThursday\S,'' Leach said. ``That's pretty good, considering we
had them pretty sore and broken down by then.''
</P>
<P>
   Haverty (6-foot, 188 pounds) said the ankle is holding up and he
has his 4.52 speed back. \Nsubheds:Injury outlook Mike Leach said
he expects the healthy return of four veterans who had surgery last
season _ including running back Ricky Williams (knee), offensive
guard Jason May (knee) and linebackers Jonathan Hawkins (shoulder)
and Rusty Bucy (knee). None participated in spring scrimmages. Only
Williams might not see full contact initially, but he said
yesterday that the knee is ``97 percent'' healed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other 3 percent is mental,'' he said. \Nsubheds:Promising
assistant New Tech defensive coordinator Greg McMackin and special
teams coordinator Manny Matsakis are among 21 top head-coaching
candidates, ``who should be on the list of every athletic director
looking for a savior,'' according to the August issue of ``American
Football Coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Leach, Southern Mississippi coach Jeff Bower and Clemson
offensive coordinator Rich Rodriguez were on the magazine's list
last year. Tech called Bower and talked to Leach and Rodriguez when
searching for a replacement for Spike Dykes, who retired.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma defensive coordinator Mike Stoops is the only other Big
12 coach on this year's list. \Nsubheds:Defense hopeful Greg
McMackin's 4-3 defense has created excitement among Red Raiders
defensive tackles, almost on the same level that Mike Leach's
offense stirred the receiving corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach McMackin is one of the best in the business,'' senior
veteran Kris Kocurek said. ``One of the first things he told us was
we're going to have two good defensive tackles, because them
getting upfield and penetrating to the ball is what makes our
defense. That got me excited right from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``His tackles are playmakers and that hasn't been the case since
I've been here. I've been holding up the linemen so the linebackers
can make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Kocurek, tackle Robert Wyatt and end Devon Lemons anchor a front
seven expected to be the strength of McMackin's defense.
</P>
<P>
   McMackin has previously been coordinator at Utah (1990-92), Navy
(1992-93), Miami (1993-95), the Seattle Seahawks (1995-98) and
Hawaii (1999).
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
