<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3398 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-INDIANS-LA     08-05 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-INDIANS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS HIT HARD ALL AROUND IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Angels were hit hard Friday night, but the blows
they sustained did not end with Jim Thome's game-winning homer in
the ninth inning of the Indians' 11-10 victory in front of 43,182
at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   After closer Troy Percival surrendered the two-run homer by
Thome, he landed on the disabled list with an inflamed elbow.
Percival, who had offseason shoulder surgery, will be examined more
thoroughly in the next couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the only bad news for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Seth Etherton, who gave up eight runs and 10
hits in 22/3 innings, will miss at least one start because of a
tired shoulder. Matt Wise likely will replace Etherton in the
rotation, although Ramon Ortiz remains a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bad day all around for the Angels, who rallied from a
9-5 deficit and took a 10-9 lead on Adam Kennedy's RBI single in
the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   In came Percival, who has come to know Jacobs Field as his
personal house of horrors. He began the season with a record of 0-3
with three blown saves and a 19.06 ERA here, but broke the string
with a save May 29.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, he began the ninth by getting Roberto Alomar on a liner
to center, then walked Manny Ramirez. Then on a 2-2 pitch, Thome
hit a 79-mph curveball into the right-center field seats to finish
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to bounce it,'' said Percival, who has nine blown
saves this season. ``I've got no feel for what I'm trying to do
right now. I can throw hard, that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival hit 98 mph on the radar gun Friday, but it isn't an
indication of how he's feeling. Percival said he hasn't felt right
all season, as he's compensated for his recovering shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been guarding my shoulder by throwing with a lot of
elbow,'' Percival said. ``It's not sound. I'm trying to do it, I'm
trying to be a hero, but it's hurting the team when I can't execute
my pitches. I've tried to make adjustments but right now I can't
make a quality pitch when I need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival said he didn't feel well at all the last time he
pitched, on July 30 against the White Sox. But even four days off
didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough look at the radar gun and hit 99 and come in here
and admit you're not right,'' Percival said. ``The last two years
have been a nightmare for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed reliever Juan Alvarez will be called up from
Triple-A Edmonton to replace Percival on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton's problem doesn't seem as serious as Percival's, but
it's still a blow to the team. He pitched in winter ball right up
to spring training and said he believes all the work has finally
caught up to him. He was checked out by the Indians' team doctor,
who suggested he needed to rest the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said everything was fine, it's just fatigue,'' Etherton
said. ``I've been through this before, but this is the extreme. I
can't throw my fastball over 85 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels hope they'll get help soon in the starting rotation
from Kent Mercker, who threw four innings (0 runs, 0 hits, 0 walks,
4 strikeouts, 52 pitches) in his rehab start Friday night for
Single-A Lake Elsinore. Mercker will make another start Wednesday
before joining the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret when you come to a window of opportunity,
you're looking for production, you're not looking for
development,'' Scioscia said. ``We're not looking for anything but
what guys need to give us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's loss was the Angels' ninth in 13 games, but they are
still only six games behind first-place Seattle in the AL West.
However, they've fallen five games behind Oakland in the wild-card
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standings are academic right now,'' Angels manager Mike
Scioscia said. ``I don't see anyone pulling away. This is probably
the toughest stretch of games we've played. We haven't played well
the last two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense continues to hit, as the Angels had four players
with two hits each Friday. The bullpen _ leading up to Percival _
was good. Mike Fyhrie, Mike Holtz and Shigetoshi Hasegawa combined
for 51/3 innings and allowed only one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``You score 10 runs in a game, at some point you think you have
a chance to hold it,'' Scioscia said. ``There are some things we
need to tighten up.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
