<HEADER>
A3399 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-BREWERS-L     08-05 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BREWERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS COME BACK FOR 2-1 WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ These are the games the Dodgers need to win _ have
to win, really _ if they are to turn this into a pennant run to
remember.
</P>
<P>
   Home against a less-than-overpowering foe. Already playing well.
Ace Kevin Brown on the mound and rolling.
</P>
<P>
   And then just as it appeared the Dodgers might stumble Friday,
blowing a dominating outing by Brown when the Brewers tied the game
1-1 in the eighth, they rallied with Eric Karros' run-scoring
single in the bottom of the inning for a 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Brown threw 72/3 impressive innings, tying his career-high with
12 strikeouts and looking a lot like a guy signed for $105 million.
</P>
<P>
   Only to leave without a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that matters is giving the team a chance to win,'' Brown
said. ``I did that. I'd like to have that one pitch back, but I can
handle it a lot better knowing we came back to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were riding Adrian Beltre's home run off rookie Paul
Rigdon for a 1-0 lead when Brown entered the eighth having struck
out the last five Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said Brown had felt a ``little
tweak'' in his right side when he batted in the seventh, and Brown
got into immediate trouble when catcher Raul Casanova opened the
eighth with a ground-rule double.
</P>
<P>
   Casanova advanced to third on pinch hitter Tyler Houston's
ground out to second. James Mouton ran for Casanova, and the
Dodgers brought the infield in.
</P>
<P>
   Brown got Ron Belliard to foul out to Karros at first, and
appeared to get out of trouble when he got two quick strikes on
Marquis Grissom.
</P>
<P>
   But Grissom worked the count full and then lined a run-scoring
single to left. Grissom had three of the six hits Brown allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson quickly came and got Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fetters relieved, just before catcher Todd Hundley threw
out Grissom trying to steal for the second time on the night.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who kept threatening early against Rigdon only to
strand six runners in the first four innings, went quickly after
reliever Juan Acevedo.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek opened with a single and took third when Gary
Sheffield grounded out. Shawn Green was intentionally walked to
bring up Karros.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, who had stranded two runners in the first when he struck
out chasing ball four, bounced a hard single up the middle just
beyond the bare-handed attempt of Acevedo and a diving Belliard at
second to score the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who said the pain in his side was probably just a cramp,
came away without the win, but the Dodgers had the kind of victory
they needed, staying 2{ games behind the Giants in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   Fetters finished the game with a perfect ninth, raising his
record to 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate for (Brown), but good for me,'' Fetters said.
``He pitched a great game. Kevin Brown is going to give you a
quality outing every time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have now won five of their last six at home, and
have won the first game of all five series since the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   Just the kinds of things that teams that want to be there down
the stretch have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't worry too much about the big picture right now,''
Brown said. ``Right now, it's about game by game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rigdon, acquired last week from the Indians in the trade for
closer Bob Wickman, was starting his second game for the Brewers.
He went seven innings, allowing the one run on five hits and three
walks.
</P>
<P>
   Acevedo took the loss, falling to 1-4. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
