<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-UNIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERIZON OFFERS NEW PLAN IN BID TO PREVENT STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Verizon Communications Friday proposed a five-year contract to
two unions that have threatened a walkout that would disrupt
technical and customer services to 25 million subscribers on the
East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon spokesman Steve Marcus declined to discuss details
Friday, but confirmed that a proposal that addresses pay and
benefits was submitted at the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   The Communications Workers of America and the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, which represent 85,000 telephone
workers, say they will strike if an ongoing contract dispute is not
resolved by midnight. The parties' two-year contract expires at
11:55 p.m. Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   A strike could disrupt the billing of calls and result in some
phone connection delays for Verizon customers. It would also affect
new installations.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon, which was created by the merger of GTE and Bell
Atlantic Corp., said it would disperse about 30,000 managers in the
event of a strike. The managers would monitor the network and
respond to serious repair calls, as well as line disruptions. The
company added that dial tone and basic telephone service would be
available.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus said the company is hoping to reach an agreement with the
unions. ``We have submitted a comprehensive contract proposal, and
we are expecting that the issues will be resolved before the
midnight deadline,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But union officials said a strike seemed inevitable. ``Major
issues have been left to the 11th hour, but there is not enough
time to work them out,'' said Steve Early, a chief organizer for
the CWA in New England.
</P>
<P>
   He said the proposal does not address job security, access to
new technical jobs, and a union plan that would permit labor
leaders to organize the telephone company's nonunion wireless
employees. Currently, 45 of the 3,500 technical and service workers
at Verizon Wireless belong to a union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the company to agree to remain neutral when people at
Verizon Wireless sign union cards and when those cards are
presented to a third party to be checked,'' Early added. ``Their
contract proposal does not address that or other contract language
that relates to job security. We're also against a five-year
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus described Verizon Communications as a separate entity,
and said any union concerns about labor matters within the wireless
division should be directed to officials at Verizon Wireless. He
said officials at the wireless unit are willing to talk with labor
leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
