   _ By ANDREW C. REVKIN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Chooses Evolution
</P>
<P>
   In a blow to creationists, Kansas voters rejected the state
school board's decision last year to remove evolution from the
school science curriculum, paving the way for that decision to be
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   In a Republican primary on Tuesday, voters defeated three
conservatives who supported the new science standards, in favor of
moderates who want evolution to be taught. That means evolution is
all but certain to be reinstated in the standards.
</P>
<P>
   Evolution is still a battleground in other states, however. And
some opponents of the theory of evolution said the Kansas defeat
would only stiffen their resolve.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PAM BELLUCK
</P>
<P>
   Liberia's President Blamed In a Diamond-Driven War
</P>
<P>
   International efforts to end the diamond-driven civil war in
Sierra Leone, where rebels have wrecked the country and mutilated
thousands of civilians, are being thwarted by the president of
neighboring Liberia, U.S. and British diplomats said at a United
Nations hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberian president, Charles Taylor, has taken command of the
rebels' fight against government troops and international
peacekeepers, the diplomats said, adding that Taylor meets
regularly for strategy sessions with rebel officers, while
personally profiting from trading arms, ammunition and food for
smuggled diamonds. The Liberian government denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BLAINE HARDEN
</P>
<P>
   Soldier Sentenced for Murder
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. military court in Germany sentenced a U.S. soldier to
life imprisonment without parole for the murder of an 11-year-old
Kosovo Albanian girl. Staff Sgt. Frank Ronghi, 36, pleaded guilty
to sodomizing and murdering Merita Shabiu while on peacekeeping
duty in the Balkans. Ronghi's sentence was the most severe one open
to a military court holding a trial in Germany, where the death
penalty does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROGER COHEN
</P>
<P>
   A New Kind of Publisher
</P>
<P>
   Staking out a place for itself in the world of electronic
publishing, Random House, a unit of Bertelsmann AG, created a new
imprint to publish exclusively digital books. The company said 20
new titles will be available beginning in January, either for
downloading via the Internet or in single paperback copies printed
as ordered by high-speed presses; none of the books will be
distributed to bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK
</P>
<P>
   German Silence Is Challenged
</P>
<P>
   A bombing that wounded nine immigrants, six of them Jews,
prompted Germany's foreign minister, Joschka Fischer, to suggest
that a silent majority of Germans may be abetting such crimes by
not speaking out against them.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants, particularly in the formerly communist east, find
themselves repeated targets for neo-Nazi rightist groups, and
Fischer was clearly taking aim at the apparent passivity of many
Germans in the face of racist crimes that have become commonplace.
It is time, he said, that the silent majority was ``roused.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROGER COHEN
</P>
<P>
   Bungled, but not Political
</P>
<P>
   One year before the 1996 presidential election, the Immigration
and Naturalization Service launched a program to naturalize 1
million immigrants. The timing raised eyebrows. Now a Justice
Department report has found that while the agency bungled the job,
and as many as 180,000 immigrants became citizens without proper
background checks, officials did not improperly meddle with the
program to beef up voter rolls by election day.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LIZETTE ALVAREZ
</P>
<P>
   A New Drug Front
</P>
<P>
   The nation's law enforcement community reported that it was
suddenly facing another potential front in its longstanding war on
drugs: a psychedelic drug nicknamed Ecstasy. It has gained wide
appeal among young  &QL; 
people, particularly those on the nightclub circuit, and in the
last 10 months, agents for the U.S. Customs Service have seized a
record 8 million doses at the nation's airports and other ports of
entry.
</P>
<P>
   Still, law enforcement officials seem to be at a loss over how
to combat it. _ By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ
</P>
<P>
   Questions on Brady Law
</P>
<P>
   A study in The Journal of the American Medical Association says
there is no evidence the 1994 Brady Law, which mandates background
checks of handgun buyers, has contributed to the recent sharp
decline in homicide.
</P>
<P>
   That is music to the ears of the National Rifle Association,
which argues that laws don't stop criminals from getting guns.
</P>
<P>
   But gun control advocates say the study is flawed, and even the
study's authors acknowledge that a major reason the Brady law may
not have been effective is its limited scope.
</P>
<P>
   _ By FOX BUTTERFIELD
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
