<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHAT ON EARTH WERE THEY THINKING? 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prince Albert is in a can.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody is going to let him out.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has got to be dying.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has been going his way. Everything has been going W.'s
way.
</P>
<P>
   One White House official tried to dismiss the Republican
convention, filled with black entertainers and sombrero-wearing
Latino singers onstage and well-fed white guys in the audience, as
``Showboat.''
</P>
<P>
   (Related footnote: In 1962, W.'s uncle Jonathan made the front
page of Variety when he considered reviving a black-face minstrel
show Off Broadway.)
</P>
<P>
   But no matter What Lies Beneath his contrived tableau of
inclusivity, W., in essence, has already had the Democratic
convention.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats want to respond in kind, they will have to
stick all their women and minorities in the audience and parade a
bunch of rich old white guys in half-moon glasses checking the
Nasdaq ticker onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, already coiled to the max, must head to the West Coast for
his big week with scenes of a Bush triumph buzzing in his head.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't look promising.
</P>
<P>
   If the vice president wants to step out of the president's
shadow, L.A. is not the place to do it. Indeed, it is impossible to
think of a worse city to showcase the Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is Bill's town, and Hillary's town.
</P>
<P>
   It is not Al's town, or Tipper's town. (Her relentless jamming
on the drums has not drowned out the memory of her campaign against
dirty rock and rap lyrics.)
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's a palindrome. AL-LA. But how can the Uptight Al Gore
try once more to set free the Real Al Gore if no one is paying any
mind?
</P>
<P>
   Every day brings news of another lavish tribute/fund-raiser
larded on for Bill and Hillary, with Whoopi, Barbra, Cher, Carly,
Harvey, Bette. Best of all is one for Hillary at Kenny Rogers'
ranch, starring Red Buttons.
</P>
<P>
   (Al baby, when your two weak points are a sex scandal and a
fund-raising scandal, do you guys really have to go to the capital
of sex to fund-raise? Not to mention the home of the Buddhist
temple and Monica Lewinsky's birthplace, Rodeo Drive.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, oblivious to such problems, is thrilled to get another
chance to hang with David Geffen. He thinks L.A.'s the most fitting
place for what he wistfully calls ``my farewell convention.''
</P>
<P>
   The president has even been invited to a fete Sunday for his
sanitized, idealized alter ego, Josiah Bartlet, president of the
luminous ``West Wing.'' (Where vixens never presume to linger over
pizzas in the Oval Office.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Al is trying to hustle the First Couple out of town
after the convention's first night, they're coming several days
early to rattle their tin cups, so they will actually spend more
time in L.A. than the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood players have struggled to transfer their affections to
Gore. But the most fickle town in the world remains steadfastly
loyal to the Entertainer in Chief. The boy from Hope gave the
glitteries all the respect and overnights in the Lincoln Bedroom
they yearned for; plus he's a bona fide groupie.
</P>
<P>
   We had a movie star who was a president and a president who
liked to cut loose with the Rat Pack. But Bill Clinton was the
first president to act as if he would actually rather be a movie
star. He didn't scorn Hollywood values. He aspired to them. He was
the sort of world leader who liked to take a break from a meeting
with Boris Yeltsin to spend quality time with Sharon Stone and
Cindy Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood, where focus groups also determine how the product is
pitched, has an uneasy sense that Gore is a supporting character,
not a leading man. He's bad box office. And we can only assume he
hasn't taken advantage of offers from worried directors like Steven
Spielberg to help him improve his ``I Walked With a Zombie''
speaking style.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles also makes Gore a juicy target for the Republicans.
The man who ``reinvents'' himself ``at every turn,'' according to
Bush, is going to the capital of reinvention to reinvent himself
yet again.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, W. extolled simple Midland values _ humility,
spirituality, a sense of community and an impatience with pretense.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will give his speech amid Hollywood values _ out-of-control
egos, blatant materialism, a dog-eat-dog ethos and a devotion to
pretense.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who hopes to win by excoriating louche Clinton values,
summed up the president this way: ``So many talents, so much charm,
such great skill. But in the end, to what end? So much promise, to
no great purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   What better way to describe Hollywood?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
