 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for Sunday,
August 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ They busted Robert Brennan in the
shower. It was a gambit right out of ``The Sopranos,'' collaring a
man when he is most vulnerable, soaping himself and singing ``Con
Te Partiro,'' and thinking he's a regular Andrea Boccelli. After he
was dried and dressed and escorted _ polite term _ to headquarters,
Brennan, once a very huge name in thoroughbred racing and
investment circles, was charged with criminal fraud. And none other
than Bill Parcells posted bail. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   LIPSYTE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Despite the moralizing monologues of
marketers and medievalists (Muggles all), arguing that the Harry
Potter books are Christian, anti-Christian, Freudian, Jungian,
traditional, New Age, their enormous success is obviously based on
Jock Culture. There are striking similarities between Quidditch in
the Harry Potter series and sports in the Chip Hilton books of 50
years ago. By Robert Lipsyte.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ It is not as if George W. Bush
needed to convince Bobby Valentine that he could manage the
country. Valentine is a registered Republican who last voted for
the other ticket in 1972, for George McGovern. No, Valentine made
it clear one day last week in his Shea Stadium office that he is a
W. man, all the way to November, the 1992 dismissal in Texas
notwithstanding. A look at the relationship between Mets manager
Bobby Valentine and the man who fired him as the Rangers manager,
George W. Bush. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DAY'S EVENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES-MARINERS (New York) _ Seattle at Yankees, 4:35 p.m.
By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-JIM-DANDY (Saratoga, N.Y.) _ The $400,000 Jim Dandy for
3-year-olds. By Joe Drape.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-REDSKINS-SNYDER (Ashburn, Va.) _ There are always stories
about Daniel Snyder, the Washington Redskins' owner. Some are true.
Some are tall tales. They swirl around him as if he were living an
Aesop fable. The moral of the stories is, well, mixed. He is a
savior, a braggart, a genius and the big bad wolf all wrapped up in
one. And he wants to win. Snyder, who took control of the Redskins
in the spring of 1999, is a poor loser, and because of that he
might be the best thing to happen to professional football in
years. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-MIAMI (Undated) _ After several years of struggling, the
Miami Hurricanes are moving back toward the top of college
football. It is as if the Miami program has been totally
re-created. Butch Davis, the straight-talking former Dallas Cowboys
assistant, is entering his sixth season as the Hurricanes' head
coach, and he has worked very hard to eliminate any resemblance to
the renegade Miami teams that won national titles and had players
who talked as well as they played. By Dave Caldwell.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ Lead item: The money is dwindling fast.
With one nine-player trade down and apparently none to go, many of
the alleged blockbuster deals are being committed to rumor. The
Great Free Agent Class of 2000 have almost all been signed, and the
Chicago Bulls are still wondering where everyone went. But Jerry
Krause can take heart. If Michael Jordan's old team does not pull
off a monster swap, survives yet another season of fan backlash and
saves its millions, the class of 2001 has much to offer. By Mike
Wise.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ Lead item: The quarterback soap operas
in San Francisco have been legendary, and while what happened
between Jeff Garcia and Steve Young may not make the top five, it
is still interesting. And around the league, both now and
historically, relationships between a starter and backup at
quarterback can often be tense. Other items include Ray Rhodes'
reappearance in Washington and players who dispel the players'
disturbing bad-boy image. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ Lead item: A challenger for the
American League West championship and the leader in the AL
wild-card division, the Oakland Athletics are in Chicago this
weekend playing the team with the league's best record, then come
to New York for a three-game series with the Yankees that will end
the most rigorous segment of their 2000 schedule. The Athletics
will have played 10 successive series, a total of 30 games, against
teams with winning records. Will they have lived to tell about it?
Other items: The return of Carl Everett to the Red Sox and the
deal-happy Yankees' ability to hold onto highly-rated prospect
Alfonso Soriano. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT-STORM (Undated) _ The sailor in `The Perfect Storm' got
a bad rap from the movie and the book. By Herb McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-LOBSTER (Undated) _ The lobster industry in Maine
hasn't been decimated like its counterpart in Long Island Sound,
but there are enough red flags about man-made contaminants up there
to cause profound unease and protest among state lobstermen and
community leaders. By Paul Molyneaux.
</P>
