<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ROCK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUMPING THE BIG TENT: THE ROCK DOESN'T KISS BABIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(Eds: Words in boldface should be set in italics.) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the evidence of flying headbutts, figure-four leglocks and
The People's Elbow, you might not see The Rock as a GOP kind of
guy. He is usually in black underwear, talking trash, wiggling
eyebrows as expressive as John Belushi's, in his role as the World
Wrestling Federation's hunkiest heel and its reigning champion.
</P>
<P>
   But there he was last week, not at a Wrestlemania or a
Smackdown, but at the Republican National Convention, which shared
two things with the WWF: The event was scripted and the outcome was
never in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The Rock was ``in the house,'' as he likes to say, to deliver
unto the conventioneers a voter registration message and to
introduce House Speaker Dennis Hastert, a former wrestling coach,
strictly an amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you smell what The Rock is cooking?'' he asked, a
trademark question (translation: ``If you know what I mean''),
which he first uttered at Wrestlemania XIV in 1998, sitting next to
Gennifer Flowers, who was interviewing him.
</P>
<P>
   See, The Rock  &UR; is &LR;  political. And politic. He  &UR; never &LR;  labeled
the convention crowd at First Union Center in Philadelphia a
``bunch of jabronis'' (that is to say, nobodies).
</P>
<P>
   ``Fourteen million eligible voters watch The Rock every single
week,'' he said with an oratorial fervor calculated to inspire
young Republicans and voters everywhere to perform their civic
duty. But were they watching? Do the GOP's demos mix with the WWF's
young male viewers? Only if they were hoping to see a steel-cage
death match pitting the tag team of George W. and Poppy Bush
against John McCain and Jesse ``The Governor'' Ventura, who
wrestled when The Rock was a mere pebble.
</P>
<P>
   Just who is The Rock?
</P>
<P>
   His real name is Dwayne Johnson, a 28-year-old, third-generation
wrestler, who is half Samoan and half African-American.
</P>
<P>
   The Rock, a thoroughly rotten character, is short for his former
nom de mat, Rocky Maivia, a nice guy who finished last _ like
Michael Dukakis. He speaks of himself almost entirely in the first
person. As in, ``The Rock says . . .''
</P>
<P>
   His autobiography, ``The Rock Says . . .'' (Regan Books), was on
the New York Times best-seller list for 20 weeks, falling six weeks
short of ``Have a Nice Day!'' by another another wrestler, Mick
Foley (a k a Mankind and Cactus Jack).
</P>
<P>
   In his 283-page memoir, he writes about why The Rock is The
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   His irresistible personality: ``The Rock is charismatic, funny,
smart . . . and completely over the top in terms of ego and
arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   His modest ego: ``With his sculpted physique, honey-brown
complexion, razor-trimmed sideburns and piercing gaze, The Rock
looks like a million bucks _ which is appropriate since that's
almost exactly what The People's Champion will earn for his
evening's labor.''
</P>
<P>
   His serendipitous character development: ``The quirks and
peculiarities evolved organically. I never said, `Hmmm, I need a
gimmick. I need an angle, I need . . . I need . . .  &UR; I need an
eyebrow &LR; ! And then _ I know! _ I'll take the most basic maneuver in
wrestling and turn it into the most electrifying move in wrestling,
and I'll call it  &UR; The People's Elbow &LR; ! Yeah, that's the plan!'''
</P>
<P>
   His ingenious mission statement: ``It's funny, I always like to
say now that The Rock is the kind of guy who won't kiss a baby and
he'll  &UR; throw &LR;  an old lady across the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, get out and vote! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
