<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FROM RACING TO HOUSE ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They busted him in the shower. It was a gambit right out of
``The Sopranos,'' collaring a man when he is most vulnerable,
soaping himself and singing ``Con Te Partiro,'' and thinking he's a
regular Andrea Boccelli.
</P>
<P>
   After he was dried and dressed and escorted _ polite term _ to
headquarters, Robert Brennan, once a very huge name in thoroughbred
racing and investment circles, was charged with criminal fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that in 1995 Brennan cashed in $500,000 in
gambling chips but did not turn the money over to a trustee, who
had been appointed after Brennan had declared bankruptcy a month
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan has denied the charge, and several friends of his,
including a former football coach by the name of Parcells, sprung
for the bail of $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   People are loyal to Bob Brennan, including Dennis Diaz, who in
1985 opted for a $2 million bonus to race the Kentucky Derby
champion he owned, Spend a Buck, in an arriviste event labeled the
Jersey Derby at the race track Brennan owned, Garden State Park,
rather than honor the tradition of the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Despite thumbing his long and handsome nose at the
establishment, Spend a Buck wound up earning $3,552,704, the
highest annual income ever in racing at that point, earned the
Eclipse Award as Horse of the Year, and then retired.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz was busy monitoring the stock market from his Florida home
Friday, but he found time to speak well of Brennan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no relationship other than in racing that year,'' Diaz
hastened to note. ``He was a heckuva nice guy, a very nice person,
candid and honest. I had no bad experience with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read a story about him on the Internet, and that's really
all I know, but I'm just sorry he's going through whatever he's
going through.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough after 15 years, but Diaz surely cannot forget the
buzz when Brennan came courting in his helicopter. There was an
exciting whiff of marginality to Brennan's penny-stock dealing,
more specific than the whispers that followed another charmer named
Jay Gatsby to his new digs in East Egg.
</P>
<P>
   Greed has been around for a long time, but there are moments
when it seems to be getting worse _ in the houses of cards of the
dot.com world, the manic faces of Wall Street traders, the feeding
frenzy of Manhattan apartment speculators, the scorched-earth zeal
of bankers, lawyers, realtors and developers who would squeeze
gauche little houses onto corners of suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Brennan was the spiritual godfather of those pests
who call us at home with stock offers. He made it sound almost
patriotic, proclaiming ``Come grow with us,'' as if he were some
kind of latter-day Franklin or Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, a federal judge in New York called Brennan ``a big
crook'' for his actions with First Jersey Securities, then a symbol
of opulence, now quite terminally defunct, along with the
aspirations and savings of his followers.
</P>
<P>
   This was the fellow who was going to transform racing, a sport
particularly open to new blood because all it takes is one good
year at the various gaming tables of life to buy a horse or even a
racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, like Diaz, knew he would never be accepted by the
crusty racing establishment, so he played on twisted populist urges
like a Trump of the Swampland. Talking about being one of nine
children, growing up in an apartment in Newark, he called racing
``an elitist sport,'' saying he wanted to make it ``clean, healthy
and wholesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Often he said, ``In this country we can still dream.''
</P>
<P>
   His dream was to land his noisy helicopter smack in the middle
of the 1985 Belmont, which he had scorned by leaving Spend a Buck
home. They waved him off, telling him to land on the fringe of the
complex, but later that day he proclaimed how much he was doing for
racing by subverting the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' he lectured, ``what we're doing is a great argument
for a race track run by the private sector, rather than a
quasi-governmental agency.''
</P>
<P>
   And he added, ``I don't believe in accepting mediocrity just
because it's always been accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounded good for a month or two, but eventually he went back
to his real life. This is the first time Brennan has been charged
with a crime, investigators being cautious about indictments in the
P.T. Barnum sucker-born-every-minute world of penny stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan is not the first sports official to run afoul of the
law. In recent years, Bruce McNall, the man who owned Wayne
Gretzky, so to speak, has gone away for improperly dealing in
valuable coins and John Spano, a temporary owner of the Islanders,
went to jail for being a wannabe millionaire. And one recalls the
campaign contribution problems of a certain George M. Steinbrenner
III, who ultimately required a pardon from President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Several executives in Salt Lake City are in big trouble for
greasing delegates of the International Olympic Committee. In
Australia, Olympic officials were funneling tickets to friends. In
soccer, South Africa recently lost a close election to Germany for
the right to hold the 2006 World Cup, when one delegate abstained,
extremely suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   Given his gall, Robert Brennan would have been right at home in
international sport. In calling for high bail, one assistant U.S.
attorney cited Brennan's expensive tastes, his trips by private
jets and helicopters, and allegations he has money hidden overseas.
There was even talk of a French girlfriend, which means he must be
guilty of something.
</P>
<P>
   Now Brennan is home in New Jersey, presumably tethered by his
high bail, courtesy of his friends, including the football coach.
Who wants Bill Parcells mad at him for skipping bail? For the
moment, Robert Brennan is back to taking showers without getting
busted, and that's progress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
