<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-MIAMI-NYT &LR;      08-05 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MIAMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MIAMI HURRICANES, AND PERHAPS THEIR SWAGGER, ARE BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE CALDWELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Miami Hurricanes are back. Tell them that at your own risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to go back to old times,'' Dan Morgan, a senior
middle linebacker, said, practically scowling.
</P>
<P>
   They like to think they walk with a swagger that is different
than the old Miami swagger. They have made it back near the top of
the college football polls by struggling, which the old Miami teams
never had to do during that run of four national titles during the
late 1980s and early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   These Hurricanes have overcome the transgressions of the old
Miami teams _ transgressions that cost the program 31 scholarships
and too much time _ and this Miami team does not seem eager to heap
new transgressions atop old transgressions. All these Hurricanes
want to do is to beat teams like Florida State and Virginia Tech
for the first time in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if the Miami program has been totally re-created. Butch
Davis, the straight-talking former Dallas Cowboys assistant, is
entering his sixth season as the Hurricanes' head coach, and he has
worked very hard to eliminate any resemblance to the renegade Miami
teams that won national titles and had players who talked as well
as they played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can go out and talk a good game,'' the senior wide
receiver Reggie Wayne said. ``We want to go out and play a good
game, too.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that the Hurricanes have abandoned
trash-talking. This Miami team _ which has a full complement of 85
players on scholarship, returns 14 starters and finds itself in
just about every preseason college football top 10 _ has amassed so
much talent that the players simply do not want to mess up a good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see us in a very positive light right now,'' Davis
said. ``Maybe this year, it's not based on the past. Maybe it's
because we have enough athletes to put ourselves in that
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The right tackle Joaquin Gonzalez, a junior, said this is the
first time in his collegiate career that the Hurricanes have felt
some pressure to accomplish something big. Gonzalez said Davis told
them to behave as if they had been there before, but the fact is,
Miami has not had a team of national-championship caliber for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Miami lost 31 scholarships because of NCAA sanctions in 1995.
The Hurricanes, down to 58 scholarship players, finished 5-6 in
1997, Davis' third year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an eye-opener,'' said Gonzalez, then a redshirt
freshman. ``We had been living off the Miami legend _ hiding behind
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis figured the best way to deal with that facade was to get
rid of it. He instituted rules, and lots of them. His players,
figuring the old way did not work, bought into it.
</P>
<P>
   Two key players missed a mandatory study hall before Miami's
1998 game against UCLA _ Davis suspended them. He hired a new
strength coach. He has supplemented the wide-open passing game that
made Miami famous in favor of a no-nonsense running attack.
</P>
<P>
   With such an emphasis, Davis has accumulated almost too much
backfield talent. The Hurricanes enter the season with four
excellent running backs: Clinton Portis, James Jackson, Jarrett
Payton (Walter Payton's son) and Najeh Davenport. Miami has so much
talent in the backfield that Davis said, jokingly, ``We're going to
run the wishbone.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Kelly, the quarterback who led the Hurricanes to a
stunning victory over Ohio State in the 1999 season opener, has
left the program to pursue a professional baseball career with the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays. But Davis was prepared there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly sustained knee and shoulder injuries late in the season,
giving Miami a chance to groom Ken Dorsey, a 6-foot-5-inch
sophomore. Dorsey completed nearly 62 percent of his passes and
finished with a better quarterback efficiency rating than Kelly.
Dorsey started the last three games of the season, all lopsided
victories for the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lessens some of the anxiety and some of the questions you
have with a new quarterback,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a heart like a lion,'' Santana Moss, a senior wide
receiver who could become a Heisman Trophy candidate, said of
Dorsey. ``But he's a young dude, too. We'll have our arms around
him like he's our little brother.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the way the Hurricanes got through the tough times. Many
of them decided to come to Miami because they had been Hurricanes'
fans in the old days.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, the linebacker, said, ``I wanted to be one of the people
who brought the program back to prominence.''
</P>
<P>
   The players quickly figured the only way to do that was to
listen to Davis, 48, who had been an assistant at Miami under Jimmy
Johnson from 1984 to 1988. Davis wants them to play with emotion,
but they knew showboating and taunting were out. Moss said they are
expected to be men first on the field, then players.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-6 season showed them that they needed to work harder in
the off-season. They were rewarded with a 9-3 season in 1998 in
which they ruined the national championship hopes of UCLA in the
final regular-season game. They whipped Ohio State in the 1999
season opener, then rebounded from tough losses to Penn State, East
Carolina and Florida State by winning seven of their last eight
games. The only loss in that stretch was to Virginia Tech, and they
think they learned something from that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it brought us together,'' the senior defensive back Al
Blades said. ``Now we know what the cost is. I think we work as
hard as any team in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the old Miami players felt that way, too, but the
Hurricanes never made a point of publicizing their work ethic. Now
Davis anchors his defense around a soft-spoken-yet-ferocious player
like Morgan, whom Davis said ``is easy to hold up as a role
model.''
</P>
<P>
   Even during the tougher times, Miami was able to sign most of
the top high school players from South Florida and many from
elsewhere in the state. But now Miami can sign national caliber
players from outside the state again. Davis can even be picky. He
said he does not need disciplined players as much as he needs
players with character.
</P>
<P>
   One freshman, D.J. Williams of De La Salle High in Concord,
Calif., could start right away at weakside linebacker at Miami.
Williams is the kind of player who might not have given Miami much
consideration early in Davis' tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they wanted to go through the perception that
the program was going to take a dip,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were around for the dip seem to be glad they stayed.
Blades said any school is subject to lean times. In some ways, the
tough times make the good times all that much more enjoyable, even
if these Hurricanes do not want these good times to be like the old
good times.
</P>
<P>
   ``There definitely have been some growing pains,'' Gonzalez
said, ``but you definitely have to go through some things to learn
about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne said, ``Talking, to me, is nothing if you lose.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
