<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-REDSKINS-2TAKES-N     08-05 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OWNER WITH ENEMIES, AND A PASSION TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHBURN, Va. _ There are always stories about Daniel Snyder, the
Washington Redskins' owner. Some are true. Some are tall tales.
They swirl around him as if he were living an Aesop fable. The
moral of the stories is, well, mixed. He is a savior, a braggart, a
genius and the big bad wolf all wrapped up in one.
</P>
<P>
   And he wants to win. Snyder, who took control of the Redskins in
the spring of 1999, is a poor loser, and because of that he might
be the best thing to happen to professional football in years.
</P>
<P>
   No owner since Oakland's Al Davis or Dallas' Jerry Jones has
shaken up professional football like the 35-year-old Snyder, who
plans to outwork and outspend his competitors. This off-season he
undertook the most aggressive free-agent spree ever, paying $40
million in signing bonuses to assemble what amounts to an all-star
team. Because of free-agent pickups like Deion Sanders and Bruce
Smith, both future Hall of Famers, many in the league believe the
Redskins are the Super Bowl favorites.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the National Football League has taken notice, not
only of Snyder's fat wallet, but also of his brashness, and some
say, his outright arrogance. Snyder may not be a renegade like
Davis, who sued his own league, and Jones, who sought to dismantle
the NFL's revenue-sharing system, but his aggressiveness is causing
the same kind of allergic reaction among his fellow owners. He
particularly irked some owners by being the first to charge fans
admission to training camp practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is true,'' Snyder said, ``I'm aggressive, I'm
entrepreneurial, I want to win. I want to win fast and now. All of
this is true, absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've run a lot of businesses and I've been very
rational,'' he said. ``And I've been in a lot of competitive
environments and this is just another competitive environment where
if you want to win you really need to be aggressive. If you're not,
you won't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellington Mara, the Giants' co-owner, who is in the Hall of
Fame, has said in the past that he is no fan of Jones, and during a
recent interview Mara made it clear he was not a member of the
Snyder fan club, either.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had met Snyder, a rival owner in the National
Football Conference East, Mara responded: ``Yes, we've met. I
wouldn't use the word charming with him, but he's been fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with a lot of what he has done, and I don't want
to get specific about what I don't like,'' said Mara, the first
owner to publicly criticize Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is entitled to do what he wants, because he paid $800
million for the team. A lot of us old fogies wish we had made as
much money as he has at that age. But I wonder if he is the type of
person who will only look out for himself, instead of the
well-being of the entire league.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thought Snyder was a younger version of Jones,
Mara joked, ``Please don't say that.'' Then with a serious tone,
Mara said: ``Let's hope he doesn't become an older Jerry Jones.
That would be unfortunate. But I think he's headed in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Mara's comments were typical of those from other team owners,
many of whom spoke only on condition of anonymity, and illustrate
Snyder's plight. While trying to make the Redskins winners again,
he must be aggressive, but in doing so, he is angering many of the
people with whom he must coexist, partly because he goes against
some NFL traditions, partly because he has rubbed some the wrong
way with his cockiness. Only Davis and Jones are referred to with
the same kind of venom by the NFL's elite.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder represents a new breed of NFL owner. As millionaires get
younger, and more begin to buy their way into professional
football, they will move with the kind of urgency that made them so
rich so quickly. Snyder earned his first million by the time he was
20, and by 31, he was the youngest chief executive of a company on
the New York Stock Exchange. He is president of Snyder
Communications, a direct-marketing firm, and before there is a
speck of gray in his hair, he may have a Super Bowl ring.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins were once a model team in the glory days of Joe
Gibbs, but they have made it to the playoffs only twice since their
last Super Bowl appearance in 1992. Wanting the Redskins to shed
their veil of mediocrity, Snyder has turned the team upside down,
moving with all the tenderness of a thunderstorm. He has fired some
two dozen employees, including General Manager Charley Casserly.
The team's contract negotiator, Joe Mendes, quit late last month,
citing thee need to take a break. From what, he did not say, but to
work for Snyder, or to compete against him, requires skin as thick
as concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to the stories, told throughout the league, by
owners, coaches, general managers and former and current Redskins
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Like the one about Snyder yelling himself hoarse in dressing
down coach Norv Turner in the trainer's room immediately after a
loss at Dallas last October. Turner came out of the meeting
ashen-faced. Snyder, who said that jobs were on the line, added,
``I'm going to get my voice fixed, and then I'm going to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   During one practice, Snyder is said to have called one of the
team's personnel men a ``dumb idiot'' in front of other members of
the organization after the man made a derogatory remark about a
player Snyder liked. Snyder denied the story.
</P>
<P>
   And this off-season Washington was interested in Seattle wide
receiver Joey Galloway, but the Seahawks froze out the Redskins and
traded Galloway to NFC East rival Dallas. Incensed, Snyder, with
only one year of league experience, called Mike Holmgren, the
Seattle coach and general manager and a 20-year NFL veteran, the
story goes, and chewed him out.
</P>
<P>
   Truth or fiction? Holmgren refused to give details of his
conversation with Snyder. Snyder said only that the two men
``kidded each other pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   During one of his first league meetings, Snyder met the Detroit
Lions' vice chairman, William Clay Ford Jr., son of the team's
owner, and made an obnoxious remark about Ford's family business,
the automobile industry.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said through a spokesman that he could not recall the
story. An owner who spoke on condition of anonymity said that he
was standing next to Ford and heard the conversation and that
Snyder did indeed say something that irritated Ford. Snyder called
the story ``total garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I have done,'' Snyder said, ``has been twisted into
great pretzels. I don't go into the locker room before gams ever.
I don't stand on the sideline like Jerry Jones. I don't watch film
with the coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories overshadow Snyder's contributions to his team. He
has unified a formerly divided front office and coaching staff. He
hired the talented Vinny Cerrato to replace Casserly. He increased
the number of blacks in the organization. He fixed a disgraceful
parking problem that caused fans to wait hours to get in and out of
the stadium he owns, FedEx Stadium, and he replaced substandard
practice fields.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, because of his sweat and more than $15 million out of
his pocket to finance the needed stadium changes, he has made
watching a Redskins game more enjoyable for fans, and the
organization more of a home for coaches and players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all he has made everyone accountable,'' said Bruce
Smith, a former Buffalo player, ``from the top to the bottom. As a
player you have to respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, his supporters say, has other positive attributes.
Because he grew up in a multicultural setting in suburban Maryland,
they say, he has an easier time relating to black team and league
officials, who often complain that some owners speak
condescendingly to them. One black league official said Snyder was
the first owner to ask him out for a beer.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder is invaluable in another way _ he has what players call
juice. Today's NFL has no dynasties. And fascinating characters
like Mike Ditka, Lawrence Taylor and Refrigerator Perry are gone.
Stars such as John Elway, Dan Marino and Steve Young have retired.
Now some of the greatest football debates are about the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder is giving the league personality, several owners
conceded, and a much-needed kick in the shin, by forcing everyone
else to work harder and to be more creative to keep up.
``Competition never hurt anybody,'' Mara said. ``The moves he is
making, yes, they hurt the league in a sense, but on the other
hand, it is good to shake things up every once in a while. The
worst thing is being comfortable, and he is disturbing our
comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder deserves credit for quickly building what looks to be a
championship-caliber team. In 1998, the season before Snyder took
over, the Redskins were 6-10. Last year they were 10-6 and won the
NFC East before losing in the second round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Then in April, Washington drafted Penn State linebacker LaVar
Arrington ($34 million contract) and Alabama offensive tackle Chris
Samuels ($30 million); both are having excellent training camps and
will be starters. Snyder signed veterans Mark Carrier (five years,
$15 million), Jeff George (four years, $18 million), Smith (four
years, $23 million) and Sanders (seven years, $56 million).
</P>
<P>
   Snyder and his staff quickly assembled not just talent, but also
depth. Nothing quite like it has been done before. It is true that
eventually the signings may seriously affect the team's salary cap,
just as the San Francisco 49ers' maneuverings in the 1990's have
hurt them now. One owner who has analyzed Washington's cap contends
that after next season, the Redskins will have to do major salary
restructuring and dump players to stay within the cap, now $62.2
million. Snyder denied this.
</P>
<P>
   But Snyder is not afraid to take chances. There are teams that
are perennially stuck near the bottom of the standing but rarely
make aggressive moves to break out of the funk.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Snyder can taint his positive efforts by going too far, the
same way Davis and Jones have before him. For example, Snyder, in
an attempt to market the Redskins brand beyond Washington, began
advertising in Baltimore, violating a gentleman's agreement not to
advertise in each other's market. David Modell, the Baltimore
Ravens' president, said the Ravens might retaliate with airplane
ads over the Redskins' training camp in Ashburn.
</P>
<P>
   No one should think Snyder is without supporters, however. He
said he had a good relationship with Commissioner Paul Tagliabue,
and just last week the Carolina owner, Jerry Richardson, visited
the Redskins' complex, observing the changes Snyder has made.
</P>
<P>
   So don't be surprised if several years from now, many teams are
charging fans to watch training camp practices. It is, after all, a
copycat league. ``Did you see that trophy case out there?'' Snyder
asked. ``My goal is to add as many trophies as I can. I plan on
being here a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
