<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3428 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-AUGUST-NEWS-REVIEW-NY     08-05 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUGUST-NEWS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACATIONERS, BEWARE THE DOLDRUMS OF AUGUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By KURT M. CAMPBELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's summertime and the living is easy, or at least it is
supposed to be. Every August, exhausted policy-makers, tired
traders and burnt-out journalists flee their high-powered jobs for
two weeks of R&AMP;R in the Hamptons, at Martha's Vineyard or on the
Maryland shore. Pity these poor power players; they're just looking
for a few days of sun and sand with the kids before returning to
the frenzy that will begin again the day after Labor Day. But if
the 1990s are any indication, August can be the cruelest month for
those who cherish international calm and stable currency markets.
</P>
<P>
   This year, in some ways, is worse than usual, if only because
the political conventions have put a major crimp in August
getaways, as they do every four years. But they cannot seriously be
considered in the same category as what has been happening in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the record for August crises in the last decade _ it
truly is a remarkable collection of calamities,'' said James
Steinberg, the recently departed deputy national security adviser
in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the mother of all August crises with Saddam's
invasion of Kuwait at the beginning of the decade in 1990,'' he
said, ``along with several other Iraqi provocations during
subsequent Augusts. There were also the embassy bombings in Africa,
various Balkan ordeals and the Atlanta Olympics terrorist bombing
in 1996.'' That last actually took place at the end of July, but
the reaction and investigation demanded attention well into August.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg's list covers various national security emergencies,
but it doesn't have to end there. Crises in the globalized
financial sector have also been striking with irritating regularity
in August, which was once synonymous with portfolio stability.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government defaulted on its debt in August 1998,
setting nerves on edge among money managers. The so-called
Committee to Save the World convened regularly by conference call
from vacation locales that summer, with Robert Rubin, who was then
the Treasury secretary, and Lawrence Summers, his deputy at the
time (and now his successor) holding the fate of the world in one
hand and a bonefishing rod and tennis racket, respectively, in the
other.
</P>
<P>
   But the picture is not all bleak. Advances in technology have
enabled crisis managers and journalists to communicate with
encryption or log on and file during even the most challenging
international crises. This can lead to unusual sightings on some of
the nation's beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a guy on a Hampton beach a few years ago who was
building a sand castle one minute with his daughter, and the next
was screaming at the top of his lungs into his cell phone that he
had to have the numbers on Nigerian debt immediately,'' said Dane
Neller, the CEO of the New York-based gourmet food chain, Dean &AMP;
Deluca. ``He used his daughter's little yellow shovel to transcribe
the financial figures in the sand, breaching the castle's moat in
the process.''
</P>
<P>
   James Adams, the very British former Washington correspondent
for the London Sunday Times, recalls a fellow becoming so engrossed
in an August article he was composing on a blanket on a beach in
Weekapaug, R.I., that he lost track of the advancing tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very messy business indeed,'' Adams said. Sand and
sea water are now more worrisome hazards to beach users with
technology than sharks or stinging jellyfish.
</P>
<P>
   However, sometimes a crisis demands more than simply phoning in.
For many power players in Washington and New York, the only thing
worse than a crisis in August that demands their attention is a
crisis in August that can somehow be managed or covered without
their direct participation. There is no greater shame for a true
insider than to arrive at a chic Martha's Vineyard dinner party
only to find that the competition has been urgently called back to
the city, while he or she is left to sunburn and stew about the
unfairness of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one key for any self-respecting crisis manager on
vacation is maintaining a flexible outlook that can be summed up in
two words: refundable tickets.
</P>
<P>
   One Washington spouse, asking not to be identified for fear of
jinxing this year's annual getaway, confided that ``during one
Middle East flare-up a few summers back, my husband insisted on
driving four hours back to the White House situation room for a
30-minute meeting at which most of the participants were wearing
either khakis or tennis togs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say,'' she added, ``we had a few Augusts back then
where we had a failure to recreate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
