<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Aug. 6:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-JEWS-IMMIGRATION (Berlin) _ Jewish immigration to Germany
is, surprisingly, rising steadily. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ The PRI, the party that has
ruled Mexico for all of the country's modern history, is quickly
imploding after its recent loss in presidential elections for the
first time. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   SOMALIA-REVIVE (Arta, Djibouti) _ Somalis here are optimistic
that they are closing in on the outlines of a government for their
country, which has been in a state of anarchy and warlordism since
a civil war in 1991. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-GAYS-RALLY (Montreal) _ Gay and lesbian Canadians rally
this weekend, but a prominent chef who has ``come out'' says he
will not attend, setting off a debate about tolerance both within
and outside the gay community in Montreal. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   BELARUS-ELECTION (Moscow) _ The tussle over the fairness of
elections in Belarus. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-U.N. (Beirut) _ The United Nations deploys peacekeepers
along the border with Israel for the first time. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   SLA-IN-ISRAEL (Kibbutz Kabri, Israel) _ How the remnants of the
Southern Lebanon Army, the proxy militia that helped Israel
maintain control over southern Lebanon, is faring now that they
have fled to Israel. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-LABOR-LAWS (Cheriton, Va.) _ Child migrant labor laws are
being tested in the fields of Virginia, Maryland and elsewhere in
the country where children of illegal migrants, mostly
14-year-olds, are put to work. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   GM-HUMMER (Detroit) _ Trying to capture the spirit of the times,
General Motors is introducing a whole new brand: the Hummer. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MARRIAGE-PENALTY (Edgartown, Mass.) _ Two days after
Republicans wound up their political convention with promises of
tax relief, President Clinton on Saturday vetoed a tax break for
married couples that is the cornerstone of the Republican effort,
saying it was too costly. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-CHEMO-PAYMENTS (Washington) _ In an effort to save
money for Medicare, the Clinton administration is planning to cut
payments for anti-cancer drugs used to treat hundreds of thousands
of elderly patients in doctors' offices. The move has provoked an
outcry from patients, doctors and members of Congress, who say the
cuts will make it far more difficult for Medicare beneficiaries to
obtain chemotherapy. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-MEDIA (Undated) _ The major networks may have complained
loudly about a dearth of breaking news and even cut back their
coverage this year of the Republican National Convention. But no
such griping was heard from the local electronic news media, whose
broadcasting needs convention officials tried to satisfy to a
degree unmatched by previous party gatherings. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ECON-ASSESS (Washington) _ The economic agenda presented to
the Republican National Convention and the nation on Thursday night
by Gov. George W. Bush stuck closely in many ways to Republican
orthodoxy. But there were twists. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-JESUS-DAY (Undated) _ Gov. Bush declared June 10th Jesus'
Day in Texas, kicking up a small storm of protest from various
non-Christian groups. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FRIENDS-MEDIA (Santa Barbara, Calif.) _ Why Gore's friends
are steamed at the news media. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-DINNER (Undated) _ A reporter's account of a private dinner
with Al Gore, unsupervised by aides, several weeks ago. By Melinda
Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-GAY-LEGISLATOR (Atlanta) _ Only reluctantly will Karla
Drenner acknowledge that after the election in November, she will
become the first openly gay state legislator in the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
