<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3435 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-GERMANY-JEWS-IMMIGRAT     08-05 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-JEWS-IMMIGRATION-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SOVIET JEWS FIND UNEASY PEACE IN GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Violetta Botwinikova is a new-wave Berliner, brisk and
chic, a 24-year-old entrepreneur, Moscow-born, Jewish _ and very
much at home in an adoptive land that changed history by producing
a killing machine for Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Her nails are sculptured ellipses _ Botwinikova is a beautician
with a sideline in the bistro business _ and her manner smooth as
her nail polish. ``I came to Germany in 1990 because my family
could stay here, simple as that,'' she said, poking a spoon into a
frothy cappuccino. ``I cannot live in Israel. I need a European
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   After a decade here, Botwinikova speaks German easily, the
Russian accent dancing lightly on sentences of hermetic Teutonic
perfection. She is proud to be a Jew, she says, and comfortable in
a Germany that has given her freedom and money. ``Israel is too
provincial,'' she mused, smiling. ``And there are too many Jews
there.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing number in Germany, too. With Europe generally
closed to legal immigration, the quiet influx into Germany of Jews
from the former Soviet Union constitutes one exception. The Central
Council of German Jews says it now has 85,000 members, up from
29,000 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   With a further 20,000 to 30,000 Jews known to be living here
without registering with the council _ Botwinikova is an example _
Germany's Jewish population has recently surpassed 100,000 for the
first time since Hitler dispersed and destroyed a prewar community
of over 500,000 Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal feeling is that the re-establishment of a Jewish
community is a kind of victory over the Nazis and what they tried
to do,'' said Manfred Becker, a senior Berlin city official dealing
with religious affairs. ``This is the point, even if such
immigration costs money. We feel a sense of moral obligation on the
German side.''
</P>
<P>
   But how far should these obligations go? It is clear that
ambivalence and hostility also exist over Jewish immigration in a
German population whose full range of feelings over the new
arrivals is unknown for the simple reason that they have never been
consulted.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a bomb exploded in Duesseldorf, injuring nine
immigrants, six of them former Soviet Jews. Nobody has claimed
responsibility; the police insist it is too early to say
anti-Semitism lay behind the attack. But the next day a makeshift
synagogue in Potsdam was daubed in ``Sieg Heil'' graffiti, and
politicians have expressed alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Violent anti-Semites are no more than a small fringe of German
society. But an awkward moment has clearly been reached in
German-Jewish relations. Jews are pouring in, at least 5,000 of
them a year, supported by annual state payments of tens of millions
of dollars, even as German impatience with Holocaust-induced
obligations is rising.
</P>
<P>
   With a recent agreement for a multibillion-dollar payment to
Nazi-era slave laborers and three major Jewish institutions under
construction in the new capital of Berlin, many Germans have a
feeling of ``enough already,'' in the words of Michael Blumenthal,
the director of the Berlin Jewish museum that will open next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have arrived at a very complex psychological situation that
is not always pleasant,'' Blumenthal said. ``What I sense among
many Germans is a feeling that we have done all this, and the Jews
should be grateful to us and not keep asking for more, not take
advantage of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Such feelings are rarely expressed publicly by Germans because
they are officially taboo. Martin Walser, a prominent writer, broke
that taboo in 1998 when he declared that he was tired of Auschwitz
being used as ``a moral cudgel'' or ``a tool of intimidation that
can be deployed at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   He was widely disavowed. But Paul Spiegel, the president of the
Central Council of German Jews, said he increasingly met fellow
Germans who warned him ``not to remind us every day of what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlin's Jewish population, which has doubled to over 12,000 in
the past decade, now receives more than $20 million a year from the
municipal budget for the upkeep of Jewish buildings and schools,
security and other matters. By contrast, the Turkish population of
170,000 receives virtually nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Jewish community, the German side must avoid the
impression that it holds the money purse closed,'' Becker said.
``But we are discreet about the sum we pay. We do not want it to be
a headline because we know it could cause resentment.''
</P>
<P>
   With Berlin's debts over $30 billion and many city programs
being cut, potential for resentment is high. Just how high is
unknown because, Becker continued, ``nobody dares take an opinion
poll in Berlin or Germany about Jewish immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``Suppose only 55 percent were in favor,'' he replied.
``Imagine the outcry. My personal estimate is 70 percent would
approve, but our society lacks the courage to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Boris Feldmann, a Jew who reached Berlin from Riga in 1991, and
who lost three grandparents to the Nazis in World War II, is not
too worried about what Germans may think of him. ``You should ask
me how I felt in Latvia as a Jew,'' he said. ``In a place where you
could lose your job if you went to synagogue.''
</P>
<P>
   In common with many of the Jews arriving in Germany from the
east, Feldmann is a little impatient with questions about German
anti-Semitism and the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed through the prism of Stalin's crimes, and against the
backdrop of Soviet anti-Semitism, Germany can seem like a land of
freedom with a terrible history, but perhaps no more terrible than
that of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I go on radio shows with Russian Jews in New York,''
said Feldmann, who publishes a successful range of Russian-language
newspapers in Germany. ``They ask me how I can live in Germany. But
the Holocaust is in the past. You cannot live endlessly thinking
the people on the street are related to that madness.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Feldmann was in the Soviet Army. He was stationed in
Kaliningrad and when the rise of the Solidarity union in Poland
threatened to sweep away the Communist government, he was
dispatched to the Polish border. A Soviet invasion seemed imminent,
and Feldmann would have fought, although he despised the idea.
</P>
<P>
   In this experience, he finds a lesson, for he believes many
ordinary Germans lived with similar dilemmas under Hitler. Not the
fanatics, not the SS, but the average German. And so he is inclined
to be understanding.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, are Alexander and Ljudmila Sumin, the Jewish owners of
a construction company who arrived in Berlin from Estonia in 1991.
When somebody scrawled ``Arbeit macht frei'' _ the words above the
gate to Auschwitz _ on their son's exercise book in school, they
told themselves there was good and bad in all countries and the bad
had predominated in Tallinn in the form of repeated hounding of
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Schoeps, an expert on German-Jewish affairs, noted that
Jewish veterans of the Soviet Army and veterans of the Wehrmacht
recently held a reunion in Berlin at which they contentedly pored
over wartime mementos. ``This may be hard to understand from an
American perspective, but these Soviet Jews feel liberated in
Germany,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Germany has reached out to people like Feldmann. Ever
since the last East German leader, Lothar de Maiziere, began
welcoming Soviet Jews in 1990, and former Chancellor Helmut Kohl
adopted a similar policy after unification, Jews have been received
here with a welcome almost as generous as that reserved for
``ethnic Germans'' _ people of German stock coming mainly from
Russia who have automatic right to German citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Once visa requests are approved, and 5,000 families a year now
receive such approval, Jewish immigrants receive work permits,
residence permits, full welfare benefits, including medical and
dental care, a place to live, free schooling for children and
German lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Synagogues are being built: New ones recently opened in Dortmund
and Kassel and one is under construction in Dresden. There is a
five-year waiting list among Jews in the former Soviet Union who
have applied to come to Germany, most of them simply seeking a
better economic future although they are officially described by
Germany as refugees.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years, the Jews are eligible for German passports.
No wonder, then, that there is a thriving trade in false Jewish
papers in Moscow, for these papers amount to an elusive passport to
a European Union otherwise accessible only to ``asylum seekers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the Jewish immigrants are privileged,'' said Barbara
John, the Berlin official who oversees the city's large immigrant
population. ``This should be seen as a form of reparation. Jews
were murdered and we feel better if we do this.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Germans plainly feel angry. Throughout Europe, the
arrival of immigrants causes more resentment than in the United
States partly because the newcomers are eligible for many social
benefits, giving some people the feeling that foreigners are taking
their tax money.
</P>
<P>
   But other factors are involved here. Many of the arriving Jews
have taken up residence in the former East Germany, where Jews were
almost unknown for most of the postwar years, official Communist
propaganda scarcely alluded to the Holocaust, the population was
told it had fought on the right side against Hitler's
``capitalist'' government, and the Communists regularly used
scapegoats to buttress their views.
</P>
<P>
   So it is natural enough that anti-Semitism has found fertile
ground in cities where unemployment is as high as 20 percent and
any handouts to foreigners are liable to be targeted in the
propaganda of neo-Nazi movements.
</P>
<P>
   Irina Knochenhauer, a Jew from St. Petersburg who works for the
Central Council of German Jews in the state of Brandenburg, near
Berlin, said, ``The Duesseldorf bomb was no surprise. There is a
lot of anti-Semitism here, open and subliminal. Many people in the
east still have no idea what a Jew is.'' Even in the west, regular
contact with Jews remains unusual for most Germans.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, she prayed in an improvised Potsdam synagogue _
plans to build a permanent one await approval and financing _
daubed with the words ``Sieg Heil'' and ``Juden.'' It was a painful
experience, proof to her that for Jews, in the end, Germany amounts
to a ``macabre choice.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 36, she has spent half her life in Russia and half her
life in Germany, after marrying an East German in 1983. But she
does not feel at home in Germany and is certain she will move on
once her teen-age daughter has finished school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I have done everything to try to make it work here,''
she said. ``And Germany has tried hard too. But it does not work.
This is a people that destroyed itself in 1933, killed itself, and
it cannot come back from this death. So they live on a superficial
level in which Jews are symbols of something, but not people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish repopulation of Germany is at an early stage. It is
too soon to say what German patriotism, if any, the children of the
new immigrants will feel. The gulf between the feelings of Feldmann
and the feelings of Knochenhauer is evidence enough of the complex,
diverse emotions involved. And a Germany still adjusting to
unification has not openly confronted its sentiments at this
improvised Jewish immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Karsten Voigt, a Social Democrat and Foreign Ministry official,
called the return of the Jews ``my party's and my generation's last
triumph over Hitler.'' But recent developments suggest it may be
premature to speak of victories. The ``normality'' so restlessly
sought by Germans in their relations with Jews remains elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Germans are committed to Jewish immigration and many
are uncomfortable,'' said Deidre Berger, the head of the American
Jewish Committee in Berlin. ``Some see a way to make good the past,
but some think there is a Jewish conspiracy to blackmail them and
the world has made Germany feel guilty long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
