   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Aug. 6, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   POL-CONVENTIONS-REVIEW (Philadelphia) _ George W. Bush went a
long way at the Republican convention toward casting himself and
his party in a favorable light. But the event was, for the most
part, dull. Bush produced what was in effect an anti-commercial _
Don't Watch This! _ for Al Gore's upcoming Democratic convention.
Gore is getting much advice about what he should do to get his
candidacy on track, but it's not going to matter much if no one's
watching. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SUITS-REVIEW (Undated) _ In a business culture that has
long fixated ambivalently on the image of computer wizards brewing
technological revolution in their garages, the backstory to two
digital copyright battles involving Napster and DVDs being waged in
federal courts on either coast has a familiar ring. They are either
tales of David vs. Goliath or of irresponsible hackers taking aim
at the establishment. Both cases have underscored the unprecedented
ability of individuals armed with digital technology to upset the
status quo. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   AUGUST-NEWS-REVIEW (Undated) _ It's August, and things are
supposed to be slow and easy for public officials, business people
and journalists. But if the 1990s are any indication, August can be
the cruelest month for those who cherish international calm and
stable markets. A look at major news events that took place in
August in recent years. By Kurt M. Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   THIRD-PARTIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at third-party movements
in the history of U.S. presidential elections. They have seldom
played significant roles, except as occasional issue raisers and
spoilers. In a sense, third parties have played a vital role in
America's political system by expanding it and maybe, in a peculiar
way, preserving it. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRIC-DEREG-REVIEW (Undated) _ Cheap, reliable electricity
was long taken for granted in the United States. Not anymore, at
least not in California. Four years ago, California decided to
deregulate its electric industry to promote competition, lower
prices and better service. This summer, power bills have doubled in
San Diego, blackouts have hit San Francisco, and the state has been
forced to cut off some big customers to protect the rest of its
power grid. The power supply is near collapse. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ROCK-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Republican National Convention
had two things in common with a World Wrestling Federation match:
the event was scripted and the outcome was never in doubt. The
champion known as The Rock was there to deliver unto the
conventioneers a voter registration message and to introduce House
Speaker Dennis Hastert, a former wrestling coach. By Richard
Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-DONORS-REVIEW (Philadelphia) _ It began in 1988 with Team
100, made up of $100,000 contributors, when the elder George Bush
invented the Republicans' first elite donor club. Last week the GOP
convention was overrun by a stampede of 600 Team 100 members, who
were invited to take out those checkbooks and give the party
$250,000, the entry fee to the Republican Regents, the party's
newest and most exclusive donor club. By Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   KILLER-KID-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Friends and acquaintances of
youths who kill often have heard boasts, plans for mayhem or seen
such warning signs as a fascination with guns. But they did nothing
to stop the crimes. The recently released testimony of teenagers
who knew one such killer, Michael Carneal of West Paducah, Ky.,
provide some insight.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   SPANGLISH-INTERNET-REVIEW (Undated) _ As Spanish speakers around
the world adopt computers and the Internet, they are importing
English technology-related words into their vocabulary. The
hybridization of Spanish and English into Spanglish is not new; it
has been accelerating for decades, irritating Spanish language
purists as well as Latin American nationalists who see the process
as more cultural infiltration from the United States. What's
different now is that authorities in much of the Latin world appear
to be throwing up their hands in the face of the latest English
invasion. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ARABS-REVIEW (Cairo) _ At the urging of the
Palestinians, a few Arab leaders like Egypt's President Hosni
Mubarak and Jordan's King Abdullah have renewed the perennial call
for a summit conference of Arab leaders, this time billed an
emergency meeting for Arabs to regroup after the failure at Camp
David and to counter the U.S. spin that the breakdown was due
solely to Arab recalcitrance. The chimera of a united Arab front
continues to shimmer on the horizon _ and, suddenly, not just for
the Arabs. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVAR-VENEZUELA-REVIEW (Caracas) _ Throughout South America,
no figure is more revered and quoted than Simon Bolivar, who freed
the region from Spanish rule nearly 200 years ago. But Bolivar said
many different and often contradictory things. That means that
modern leaders like Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez have a whole
menu of positions from which to choose when they seek to justify
their own actions. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-MUGABE-REVIEW (Harare) _ In the West, Zimbabwe's
President Robert Mugabe is seen as a bloody despot and race-monger
who fuels the violence that churns through the countryside. But in
much of Africa, he is viewed as a hero trying to redress historical
wrongs. To many Westerners, these two conflicting views seem
impossible to reconcile. How can Mugabe be praised for pursuing an
honorable cause if he kills innocents along the way? By Rachel
Swarns.
</P>
<P>
