<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   QB Rivalries in 49er-Land
</P>
<P>
   If there is anyone who understands the difficulty of following a
legend, it is the quarterback Steve Young. In the early 1990s,
Young and Joe Montana were in a heated battle for the starting job
in San Francisco. Montana was struggling to overcome injuries and
refused to be a backup. He eventually finished his career in Kansas
City, and just last week was inducted into the Hall of Fame. Young
went on to win a Super Bowl with the 49ers and will also someday be
inducted.
</P>
<P>
   But on his way out the door, Montana made it known that he and
Young were not exactly friends. ``Steve is on a big push for
himself,'' Montana said in a 1991 interview. ``And any time you
have a competition, there is always that certain amount of
animosity towards each other. I can say we only have a working
relationship. That's all it is. After that, he's on my team, but as
far as I'm concerned, he's part of the opposition. He wants what I
have, and I have to approach it that way. There is no other way to
deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Young vowed that if he was ever in a situation
where a younger player was behind him, he would not treat that
player the way Montana treated him.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, Young got the chance to make good on those
words, but if you believe the current 49ers quarterback, Jeff
Garcia, Young failed.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback soap operas in San Francisco have been
legendary, and while what happened between Garcia and Young may not
make the top five, it is still interesting. And around the league,
both now and historically, relationships between a starting
quarterback and his backup can often be tense.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said this week that he wishes Young, who retired during
the off-season, had been more supportive last year. Young was the
only returning quarterback, and behind him were Garcia and Steve
Stenstrom. When Young sustained a season-ending concussion in Week
3, Garcia became the starter. Garcia said that at that point,
Young's attitude became quite chilly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure not being in the role he was normally used to being
in, as far as being the starting quarterback and the guy everybody
else can count on, that really changed his mindset,'' Garcia said.
``In doing so, I didn't really feel there was a whole lot of
activity from him in helping us young guys. He was dealing with his
own thing, so he kept to himself in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia understands part of why Young was distant. It was a
difficult time for Young who, because of a series of concussions,
faced the end of his career. Those times are always the most
difficult, and they can wreck a player's emotions, turning someone
as classy and friendly as Young into more of a loner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than questioning during games, asking him what we could
do to hopefully have some success on the field, other than that, it
didn't seem like _ I don't know _ that's sort of a difficult area
to describe,'' Garcia said. ``I think everybody's going to approach
those situations the best way they know. If I'm in those shoes, I
approach it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked at his situation last year and realizing that it
got to the point he wasn't going to be back as a player,'' Garcia
said, ``I would have liked to have seen more of the coach come out
in him. Especially when dealing with new guys on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   So Young's personal soap opera had come full circle. He survived
Montana's jabs, only to act, according to Garcia, not exactly
personable years later when injuries were forcing him to
contemplate his mortality as a player.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's words caused a stir in 49ersville, and prompted a
meeting between Garcia and coach Steve Mariucci, who chastised
Garcia for chastising a team legend. After the meeting, Garcia was
complimentary of Young. That is called damage control.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Garcia should prepare for what could be a long
season. The 49ers are a wreck, the victims of manipulating the
salary cap for far too long. They have little talent and even less
depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll surprise some people,'' Garcia said. ``That's the
attitude I'm taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes Finds a Supporter
</P>
<P>
   When Ray Rhodes was fired as coach of the Green Bay Packers
after last season, one of the people who remained a big fan was the
Washington owner, Daniel Snyder. He brought Rhodes to the Redskins,
made him the defensive coordinator and thinks Rhodes will soon
become a head coach again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Ray to take advantage of what I think is a great
opportunity here,'' Snyder said. ``I think ultimately Ray will be
one of the great head coaches in football. I really believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes has been fired twice in the past 20 months, in Green Bay
and before that in Philadelphia. Yet there has never been a
question about his skills as a coordinator. He remains perhaps the
best defensive mind in the game. Now, Rhodes is trying to turn
around a defense that was ranked 30th last year and nearly mutinied
under Mike Nolan, now the defensive coordinator with the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things Rhodes did was change the scheme, which
asked linemen to hold up blockers, while the linebackers made the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This defense allows everyone _ not just the defensive line _
but everyone to be a little more free and allow our football skills
to take over,'' said Dan Wilkinson, a defensive lineman. ``It was
frustration across the board last year, because were asked to do
things that we didn't think made too much sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Better Role Models
</P>
<P>
   Professional football players have made a lot of off-field news
recently, much of it negative. They have been arrested on charges
of everything from driving while intoxicated to murder.
</P>
<P>
   But there are players in the game who do positive things. Tampa
Bay linebacker Derrick Brooks, for example, took 19 disadvantaged
teen-agers from the Tampa and Orlando Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs on a
12-day trip to South Africa as a reward for good grades.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis Colts' running back Edgerrin James donated $250,000
to his alma mater, the University of Miami. Philadelphia Eagles
quarterback Donovan McNabb is giving $100,000 to Syracuse
University, his alma mater, for a new locker room in the school's
football complex. In addition to his gift to Syracuse, McNabb is
also financing scholarships at his former high school and a
business loan program through his hometown church.
</P>
<P>
   And Tennessee's Eddie George, who recently signed one of the
largest contracts ever for a running back, took 20 credits this
spring at Ohio State University toward the completion of his
undergraduate degree.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
