YEAR AFTER SHOOTING, JEWISH CENTER RECOVERS ITS SMILE &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DANA BARTHOLOMEW 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   GRANADA HILLS, Calif. _ Counselors sport Day-glo hair. Kids
erupt with woodwind cheer. And parents drive out of the North
Valley Jewish Community Center assured their children are safe.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12 months since an gunman shot and injured five people
Aug. 10 at the center and killed a mail carrier in Chatsworth, the
center strives for normalcy.
</P>
<P>
   The only evidence of change are security guards who stand
sentinel at the padlocked iron gates. Otherwise, it's a normal day
at camp. No one talks about accused gunman and admitted racist
Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr. or his possible motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here aren't looking back,'' said Michelle Schipper,
director of the JCC in Granada Hills. ``We continue to move
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a triumph over evil - good will win. The
community has pulled together. We have won.''
</P>
<P>
   At the center, attendance is up, programs and memberships have
increased and laughter - as always - is in the air. An arts
curriculum has been added and the New Valley Symphony has made the
JCC its home.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from tightened security, the only obvious acknowledgment
of the tragedy that struck a year ago is a Unity Garden emerging on
the centers' front lawn.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings have prompted other changes, however.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying public momentum from the incident, Gov. Gray Davis
signed into law an assault weapons ban and gun control bills
requiring trigger locks for safety and added regulations at gun
shows and banning so-called Saturday night specials throughout the
state.
</P>
<P>
   A toll-free hotline for schools and day care centers was
established to advise how to beef up security. And an advisory
panel on hate crime was established that recommended further
legislation against hate groups.
</P>
<P>
   Though the number of hate-based crimes in Los Angeles has
increased, possibly because of better reporting, the Granada Hills
shootings has greatly increased awareness on the part of city
services, City Councilwoman Laura Chick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These terrible things can happen, anywhere, everywhere in our
city,'' Chick said. ``They have to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Flashback to Aug. 10, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On that day a stranger entered the center and wounded Isabelle
Shamoleth, the longtime receptionist; Mindy Finkelstein, a teen-age
counselor; James Zidell and Joshua Stepakoff, then 6; and
5-year-old Benjamin Kadish.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Santos Ileto, a Filipino-American postman, was gunned
down in Chatsworth during what appeared to be the same spree.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow, a neo-Nazi from Washington state, was charged with the
shootings and could face the death penalty if convicted during a
trial set for February 2001.
</P>
<P>
   According to authorities, Furrow admitted to targeting the JCC
as a ``wake-up call'' for Americans to start killing Jews, and said
he murdered Ileto because he was a federal employee who was not
white.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ileto's family has lectured on the pain of hate
crime and growing incidents of it toward the Asian community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to lose someone from a medical condition,''
said Ismael Ileto, 37, Joseph Ileto's older brother whose father
died of a heart attack just before the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another to lose one from a heinous crime, from a vicious
act of violence. We never experienced anything like this before, we
never even thought about ... us as a target.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, those injured at the Jewish Community Center
have largely recovered, Schipper said. Shamoleth, ``the backbone of
this place,'' returned to work the day she got out of the hospital.
Two out of the three injured children are back on the playground.
</P>
<P>
   Only Kadish, who was given a colostomy as a result of his
injuries, has gone to another camp. ``He's doing much, much
better,'' said his mother, Eleanor.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Weber, a social worker for the Jewish Family Service that
has helped many of the JCC families work through their trauma, said
most realize ``life can be controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   While there are no guarantees against random violence, she said,
there is comfort in added security and crime prevention.
Nonetheless, some children still experience bad dreams, disturbed
sleep and eating disorders.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, she said, ``you're not afraid of people shooting
you, of seeing blood on your teacher, of seeing your parents
terrified,'' she said. ``The difficulty is knowing you were singled
out because of your ethnicity and religion.''
</P>
<P>
   As a response to the shootings, the Los Angeles Police
Department has increased its presence at schools and community
centers. Its many divisions use video footage of its quick response
as training films, an LAPD spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish community leaders said that while security has been
beefed up in synagogues across Los Angeles, it is important to
reach out to other faiths in an effort to destroy the hate culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``When kids are shot, whether it's in a community center or a
drive-by shooting, your really discover the importance of life -
and the importance of family,'' said Michael Hirschfeld, executive
director of the Jewish Community Relations Committee. The committee
is a member of the Jewish Council Federation, which oversees the
JCC.
</P>
<P>
   Personal responsibility is also vital, said Rabbi Harold
Schulweis of Valley Beth Shalom in Encino. ``The emphasis needs to
be on godliness, rather than God,'' he said. ``God needs allies on
Earth - and that's our responsibility. And that's the lesson for
all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
