<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FREE-AGENT MARKET, IT'S WAIT TILL NEXT YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The money is dwindling fast. With one nine-player trade down and
apparently none to go, many of the alleged blockbuster deals are
being committed to rumor. Solid but unspectacular free agents like
Danny Fortson and Aaron Williams have been given presidential
suites by teams hoping to procure their services for minimal
charge.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the Great Free Agent Class of 2000 have almost
all been signed _ including Williams, who agreed to terms with the
Nets on Friday _ and the Chicago Bulls are still wondering where
everyone went and why they had to settle on Ron Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry Krause can take heart. If Michael Jordan's old team
does not pull off a monster swap, survives yet another season of
fan backlash and saves its millions, the class of 2001 has much to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber, Dikembe Mutombo, Michael Finley and Antonio Davis
will have opportunities to be free agents. Depending on whether
several players opt out of deals, there are also Anthony Mason,
Tyrone Hill, Corliss Williamson and Jerome Williams to add to the
Bulls' talent-challenged roster.
</P>
<P>
   If Washington buys out Rod Strickland over the last year of his
deal in 2001-2, he would be a free agent going into next season.
</P>
<P>
   Several players are still on the market this summer, but not all
may take the $2.25 million exception being offered by teams.
According to a Pacific Division executive, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, many player agents are telling general managers to
find more creative ways to sign their clients _ given that the
exception will most likely balloon to $4.5 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   With annual allowed increases, a contract beginning at that
number could turn into a multiyear, $30 million deal next season.
That means instead of Fortson or Williams, the exception could go
to a free agent next season like Shandon Anderson, Doug Christie or
Christian Laettner.
</P>
<P>
   Other possible 2001 free agents who could secure those kind of
deals include Shawn Bradley, Erick Strickland, Bryan Stith, Chris
Gatling, Clarence Weatherspoon, Anthony Carter, Aaron McKie, Malik
Rose or Grant Long.
</P>
<P>
   Players will actually be weighing their contract offers from
their current clubs against a midlevel exception, meaning it may be
harder for teams to hold on to their best role players.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Webber is going to reap the largest reward. For
everyone who decried the end of the $100 million deal, well, it's
back.
</P>
<P>
   The salary cap will most likely be $42 million to $44 million
next season. A player like Webber, the All-Star Kings forward, can
receive 30 percent of his team's salary cap based on his experience
level of seven to nine years.
</P>
<P>
   If the cap were $42 million, Webber could receive $12.6 million
his first season. With annual raises, a maximum deal would total
out to $120.9 million over six years if he stayed with Sacramento.
That is $6 million less than Kevin Garnett's record deal signed in
1997, the one that infuriated owners before the lockout in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Dust Settles
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill and Tracy McGrady smiled gleefully for the cameras
the other day, donning their new pinstriped Orlando Magic jerseys
and putting the focus back on the Magic four years after Shaq
migrated to Los Angeles and left the franchise reeling.
</P>
<P>
   Signing Hill, arguably the most accomplished all-around player
in the game, and McGrady, one of the NBA's rising stars, was a nice
coup, replete with all the attention deserving of the day.
</P>
<P>
   In Charlotte and Miami, they were also parading their new
players. Eddie Jones and Anthony Mason made Miami Coach Pat Riley
smile the same way acquiring Jamal Mashburn and P.J. Brown made
Charlotte Coach Paul Silas happy _ a nine-player deal both sides
deemed fair.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in San Antonio, the Spurs put the finishing touches
on acquiring Derek Anderson. Quietly, the 1999 NBA champions
reloaded. Among 29 teams searching to stay on top or improve, they
may end up as the real winners of the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Filling a huge hole at shooting guard with the best free agent
left on the market, they persuaded Anderson, 26, to play for $2.25
million next season. Anderson, who is 6-foot-5, averaged 16.9
points, 4.0 rebounds and 3.4 assists a game in 64 games for the
Clippers last season.
</P>
<P>
   He is a definite upgrade from Mario Elie, whom the Spurs will
now probably let go via free agency.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, San Antonio signed the one player they could not
lose, Tim Duncan, for three years and $33 million with a
fourth-year option. They also kept two other important pieces to
the puzzle, the aging Avery Johnson and the emerging Antonio
Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   In a whirlwind week, the Spurs inched closer to the Lakers and
Blazers. Persuading a young player like Anderson to play for an
instant contender rather than accept a sign-and-trade deal from the
Clippers to Denver was key.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Mark Bartelstein, agent for the Blazers forward Brian
Grant, was trying to portray his client's decision to turn down a
$90 million sign-and-trade deal that would have sent him to
Cleveland as noble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this speaks volumes about the man,'' Bartelstein said.
``It's incredibly unbelievable, in this day and age, for an athlete
to say so strongly, `It's not about the money.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Let's be clear on this: Grant did not turn down the money as
much as he turned down the notion of playing for the Cavaliers, who
wanted to break their ties with Shawn Kemp more than they wanted
Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Blazers find a team for him soon, Grant's decision to
opt out of a deal still worth more than $40 million may go down as
one of the biggest blunders of the off-season _ up there with the
Bulls' ending up with Ron Mercer and millions still to spend on
players who rejected them.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Bartelstein should be given the benefit of the doubt. A
long list of elite teams still have the midlevel exception left to
sign a player, a contract worth $2.25 million next year. If Grant
and his agent are truly unconcerned with the money, they will leap
at an opportunity to contend for a championship with another team.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West Retiring
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West is expected to quit Monday as team president of the
Lakers. Though he may remain as a team consultant, a four-decade
relationship between a player and a club will most likely come to
an end.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Kupchak, the general manager, will succeed West. And coach
Phil Jackson will most likely have more input on personnel
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Few American sports executives can claim the success of West,
just as few Hall of Famers can claim the playing success of West.
He won one championship as a player and six as an executive.
</P>
<P>
   When he was not lofting a half-court shot that found the net in
the finals or earning the moniker Mr. Clutch during his consummate
playing career, he was taking weighty risks in the front office _
risks that paid off miraculously.
</P>
<P>
   Clearing salary-cap room by unloading a multitude of players
during the summer of 1996, West gutted the Lakers in pursuit of
Shaquille O'Neal, even when it was unclear whether O'Neal would
return to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   He kept the Showtime Lakers purring and eventually rebuilt the
franchise with wunderkinds like Shaq and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   His health prevented West from attending games this past season.
Once the coolest of customers on the floor, his nerves can no
longer take the tension of a tight game.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to Rod Thorn and Hotrod Hundley, here's
hoping West Virginia's greatest ballplayer can find joy in the game
again, that Zeke from Cabin Creek makes the transition to
retirement more peacefully than fitfully. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
