u i BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-525(2     08-05 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-525(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO BROADEN SUPPORT, MEXICAN VICTOR NOW WOOS HIS OPPONENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The weeks after Mexico's presidential voting have
always been a time for hand-kissing, when supplicants of all
stripes use any opportunity to express rapturous, supine loyalty to
the latest president-elect.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox has turned the traditional rituals upside down,
using the weeks since his victory in July 2 balloting to visit his
vanquished rivals, one by one, to apologize for his slashing
attacks on them during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For Mexicans, there is plenty of charm in what is a display of
humility perhaps as stunning as Fox's election itself. In the month
since he won the election, Fox has outlined a hugely ambitious
program of reforms aimed at modernizing Mexico after a century of
one-party rule. If he wants, as promised, to bring change, he needs
to broaden support.
</P>
<P>
   In neither house of Congress does his center-right party enjoy a
majority. So even as he has been working to solidify the eclectic
left-right coalition that helped him to victory, he has been
mending fences with the forces he vanquished.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday evening he met Francisco Labastida, the defeated
governing party candidate, whom he ridiculed as an ``errand boy''
before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told Mr. Labastida of our intention to lodge an apology for
the harsh campaign,'' Fox said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   To foreign eyes, this might seem like simple good sportsmanship.
But in a country where presidents have enjoyed kinglike powers and
often acted with regal arrogance, Fox's magnanimous bearing has
seemed a remarkable shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our presidents have been as infallible as the pope,'' said
Jorge Chabat, a professor at the Center for Investigation and
Teaching in Mexico City. ``So it startles us to see Fox express his
apologies. He's inviting us to see that our rulers are made of
flesh and blood, and this is unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's behavior has broken with his predecessors' patterns in
other ways. Presidents-elect from the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party, which won every election from 1929 until Fox's
stunning upset, tended to keep their policy plans vague until they
took office. Their transition teams worked in secret. And in public
appearances, they maintained an aloof solemnity and spoke in opaque
terms that often left Mexicans puzzling over what the new ruler was
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, in contrast, has appointed a sprawling transition team,
with dozens of experts studying everything from tax rates to police
training to foreign policy, and their work is unfolding under the
glare of tumultuous media coverage. Fox has spoken bluntly in
interviews with television newscasters, radio hosts or newspaper
reporters virtually every day since his election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one thing _ I think he talks too much,'' said Hector
Aguilar Camin, a novelist who is host on a weekly political
round-table discussion on Televisa, the largest network. ``The risk
is that everybody is going to get tired of him. But it's great that
he's put his agenda out in the open, and I'd bet he has more
support now than when he won the election a month ago. He's
performed very skillfully.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fox does not take office until Dec. 1, but the next political
cycle will get under way with the first session of the new Congress
on Sept. 1. Fox's National Action Party will have 208 seats in the
500-member Chamber of Deputies. That means he will need to attract
43 votes to reach the 251-vote majority needed to pass legislation.
The former governing party will have 209 seats and the main leftist
party 53. In the 128-seat Senate, Fox's party will have 46 seats,
the PRI 60, the leftist party 15, and small parties the rest.
</P>
<P>
   It will take skillful negotiating to gain approval for even a
part of the new president's sweeping plans for remaking Mexico. He
hopes to open up both the electric power and petrochemical
industries to private investment, plans that infuriate powerful
unions. He wants to abolish several cabinet ministries, including
the attorney general's office, replacing that with a United
States-style Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   That would require several constitutional amendments, as would a
recent proposal to remove the prohibition on the re-election of
lawmakers and city mayors, a legacy of the 1917 revolution whose
war cry was ``Effective suffrage, no re-election!'' He has promised
to overhaul the educational system and to provide huge new credits
to small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Those and other promises will require hefty new tax revenues,
and when his economic advisers last month offered their first
suggestion for how to raise them, proposing to eliminate sales tax
exemptions for medicines and most groceries, there was an
outpouring of criticism on radio and television talk shows. Fox
quickly retreated, and Mexicans realized they had witnessed the
deft use of a U.S.-style political tactic, the trial balloon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is night and day from the way politics were handled in
the past,'' said Denise Dresser, a political scientist at the
Autonomous Technological Institute in Mexico City. ``Issues like
taxes were discussed behind closed doors by insiders and then
imposed on the public. Fox is showing a willingness to test citizen
reaction to initiatives and change them when there's resistance.
We're seeing the end of the imperial presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Fox still must persuade Mexicans to accept higher taxes, and
his evolving plans for fiscal reform are likely to be the focus of
the most intense debates of his first months in office.
</P>
<P>
   Rogelio Ramirez de la O, an influential Mexico City economic
consultant, argued in a recent report that Fox would face a
cash-flow squeeze far more severe than previously acknowledged
because President Ernesto Zedillo's economic advisers have
understated the financial burden they are leaving behind as a
legacy of a bank rescue from 1995 to 1997, which has so far cost
taxpayers $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate a period of hard learning for the new
government,'' Ramirez wrote. ``They will soon find out the need for
extra revenue is heavily underestimated.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fox's recent attempts to make peace with his adversaries
suggest that he understands the difficulties ahead. One of the
first came on July 26 when he visited Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the
defeated leftist candidate, to ``present our apologies,'' as Fox
put it later, for calling Cardenas ``a traitor to the fight for
democracy'' during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, at a ceremony in which an electoral tribunal
formally certified Fox's victory, he asked the magistrates to
forgive him for another harsh campaign utterance. In January, when
the tribunal had ruled against him in a campaign dispute, Fox had
called the tribunal's legal arguments ``the grunting of swine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had chalked up that insult to campaign passions,'' Jose Luis
de la Peza, the tribunal president, said on Thursday. ``Obviously
it was an act of considerable nobility for him to offer an
apology.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same speech to the tribunal, Fox also sought conciliation
with gay Mexicans, whom he had offended with several homophobic
campaign remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's build a free and generous Mexico where nobody is
persecuted for their political or religious beliefs, life styles or
sexual preferences,'' Fox said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
