<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. PEACEKEEPERS ARRIVE TO GUARD ISRAEL-LEBANON BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ U.N. peacekeeping troops finally began
spreading out in force along Lebanon's border with Israel on
Saturday, after weeks of haggling over just where the border is and
22 years after their presence was first authorized.
</P>
<P>
   Convoys of white-painted armored vehicles began snaking through
the stony hills of southern Lebanon, occupied until May 24 by the
Israeli army and its proxy local militia, shortly after 6 a.m.,
carrying about 700 U.N. troops.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, a smaller vanguard, in platoon strength of
about 30 soldiers each, had taken up six positions along the
border.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, the operation was proceeding smoothly, with the
most serious incident being a brush fire that had detonated three
land mines near a newly established position of Indian troops.
</P>
<P>
   But the troop movement was halted after nine hours because the
troop movements were slowed by land mines and by the reluctance of
a number of local landlords to rent out their land for new U.N.
positions, fearing they would not be compensated by the Lebanese
government, said U.N. officials.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, officials said, the troop movement, which is to
resume on Monday went smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah guerrillas, the effective force on the ground, quietly
turned over the fortified strongholds and observation posts they
had taken when the Israelis abruptly departed two months ago,
leaving the Christian-led militia called the South Lebanon Army to
flee in their wake.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, drawn from the regions predominately
Shiite Moslem population, had already pledged to cooperate with the
U.N. deployment and the expected sending of Lebanese army soldiers
and police to fill the security vacuum left when Israeli forces
left in May after a 22-year occupation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the guerrillas are not giving up their weapons, which they
will stash away in their homes and other hiding places,'' a
Hezbollah official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arms of the resistance will remain steadily within reach
in the equation, but they will be kept invisible,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The full deployment of troops from the Indian, Irish, Fijian,
Nepalese and Ghanaian battalions of the command formally known as
U.N. Interim force in Lebanon, or Unifil, is expected to take
several days to a week. The force is being expanded from a strength
of 4,600 to about 6,000 troops. Including a detachment of Ukrainian
soldiers sent to dig up the land mines scattered around the area.
</P>
<P>
   A Lebanese force of 500 soldiers and 500 security police is
supposed to follow the U.N. troops into the south some 24 hours
after the United Nations sets up its posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready for it now but we want to see where Unifil
deploys so our special force knows where to go,'' said Lebanese
Prime Minister Salim al-Hoss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
