<HEADER>
A3466 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CLINTON-MARRIAGE-PENA     08-05 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MARRIAGE-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT VETOES MARRIAGE-TAX CUT HE CALLS RECKLESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ Two days after Republicans wound up their
political convention with promises of tax relief, President Clinton
set up an election-year battle Saturday by vetoing as too costly a
tax break for married couples that is the cornerstone of the
Republican effort.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton accused the Republicans in his weekly radio address of
advancing a series of ``tax giveaways'' that abandon the fiscal
discipline that has helped produce the longest economic expansion
in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't retreat from this opportunity of a lifetime to keep
our economy strong and move our country forward,'' said Clinton,
who signed the veto this morning during a visit to Martha's
Vineyard for a weekend vacation and fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm vetoing legislation that represents the first
installation of a fiscally reckless tax strategy,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The veto, which Clinton had long threatened, sets the stage for
a renewed partisan fight over tax policy when Congress returns to
Washington after Labor Day. It is a fight that Republicans
especially view as defining the parties in both the presidential
and legislative elections.
</P>
<P>
   John Feehery, the spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
said Hastert planned to try to override the president's veto in the
first vote. He said the veto would put pressure on House Democrats,
who are competing for control of the chamber. Still, overriding it
would require a two-thirds vote in both the House and Senate;
neither passed the bill by such a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks coinciding with Clinton's radio address, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, the Republican presidential nominee, anticipated
the veto and rhetorically urged his opponent, Vice President Al
Gore, to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of tax code is it that penalizes marriage?'' said
Bush, speaking on a train platform in Pontiac, Mich., as he toured
the state. ``It's a bad tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet today _ and yet today _ President Clinton is going to
veto that bill. Vice President Gore, you need to tell your partner
not to veto the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, in their own weekly radio address, said Clinton was
turning his back on married couples and perpetuating the view that
the federal budget surplus belonged to the government instead of
the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that special and sacred moment when the bride and groom say
`I do,' they also unwittingly say `I do' to higher taxes,'' said
Rep. J.D. Hayworth of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Al Gore ``still peddle the shopworn slogan that
correcting this injustice is just a break for the rich,'' Hayworth
said. ``But Americans know better. We understand that two spouses
earning $25,000 each are not wealthy by any stretch of the
imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties have advanced plans to remedy the so-called
marriage penalty, a quirk in the tax code that forces many
two-income couples to pay more in taxes than they would as singles.
But the Republican plan is the broader one, giving an election-year
tax break to nearly all married couples, even those who do not pay
a marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a sticky one for Democrats, who are seeking to walk
the line between fiscal discipline and providing what is a
politically popular benefit. When the Senate backed the Republican
plan last month, providing $292 billion in tax breaks for married
couples over the next 10 years, seven Democrats broke with their
party.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is urging a more modest tax-relief package intended to
benefit people of low and middle incomes. He has given himself some
wiggle room, however. Last month, Clinton said he would agree to
the Republican tax reductions for married couples if Congress
backed his proposal for a Medicare prescription drug benefit.
Republicans, who have their own, less sweeping prescription drug
initiative, refused.
</P>
<P>
   The two approaches over how to spend the record federal budget
surplus mirror the turf staked out by the two presidential
candidates. Gore has advocated a more modest tax-relief package
than his Republican opponent. Gore has called Bush's plan risky.
Bush dismisses Gore's stance as government as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans took great pains at their convention in Philadelphia
this week to portray themselves as an inclusive party that reaches
out to people of all ethnic groups and income levels. But as
Clinton stumps on behalf of Gore, he knocks the Republicans for
favoring the wealthy and turning their backs on minorities. At a
Friday night fund-raiser for Hillary Rodham Clinton's New York
Senate campaign, he told a group of wealthy donors that Gore would
not leave anybody behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other guys are going to give you a bigger tax cut than we
are,'' Clinton told 200 guests at the seaside gathering on
Nantucket. But he said the country as a whole would be better off
under Gore's stewardship, helping rich and poor alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll give you lower interest rates and a better stock
market,'' the president said. ``You'll make more anyway. But I
think we ought to all go along for the ride.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton compared Republican plans to spend much of the projected
surplus to a foolhardy person spending sweepstakes money before the
check arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever get one of those letters from Ed McMahon and
Publishers Clearinghouse?'' Clinton asked in what has become one of
his biggest applause lines of late. ``Think about it: `You may have
won $10 million.' Now, if you went out the next day and spent the
$10 million, you should support their program. But otherwise, you
ought to stick with us.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The standoff over tax cuts is a repeat of past end-of-the-year
budget confrontations, which Clinton has shown himself quite adept
at maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, the Republicans profess to be relishing the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``House Democrats will have an opportunity to get rid of the
marriage penalty by overriding the veto,'' Feehery said. ``It's
going to be a tough fight. We're going to expose their real
proclivity for higher taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Hayworth called Clinton the ``de facto campaign
manager'' for Gore and said the president's veto would hurt his
favored candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the best efforts of the punditocracy to say that tax
breaks don't matter,'' Hayworth said, ``for Mr. Gore's electoral
health, Clinton the campaign manager ought to reconsider.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Democrats praised the president's action as fiscally
prudent. Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., called Clinton ``wise to
veto tax cuts that are not directed at the middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer added, ``He is right to be concerned that the huge cost of
the Republican tax cuts will bring us back to the days of
intractable deficits.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
