<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GEORGIA-GAY-LEGISLATO     08-05 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-GAY-LEGISLATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WOMAN WHO WILL CHANGE THE FACE OF POLITICS IN THE DEEP SOUTH  

</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Karla Drenner will change the face of Georgia
politics, though she would rather not talk about that. She will
talk about her two 4-year-old children and about her interest in
the environment and education. But only reluctantly will she
acknowledge that after the election in November, she will become
the first openly gay state legislator in the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   Drenner defeated the Democratic incumbent, June Hegstrom, in the
primary last month, and with no Republican or third-party
candidates on the ballot in November, her election from her
suburban Atlanta district to the Georgia House of Representatives
will be a formality.
</P>
<P>
   The only openly gay legislator in the entire South is Glen
Maxey, who has been representing Austin in the Texas House of
Representatives since 1991. When the Georgia General Assembly
convenes next year Drenner will be the first in the Deep South,
which is made up of Mississippi, Alabama, Louisiana, South Carolina
and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Drenner, who has a doctorate in public policy and 15 years of
experience as a consultant for several companies on environmental
health and safety, edged out her opponent by campaigning hard on
these issues in a district that is 60 percent black and has a small
openly gay minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they cared about was quality representation,'' Drenner
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sloan Wiesen, a spokesman for the Gay and Lesbian Victory
Fund in Washington, which helps gay candidates in campaigns for
political office, said: ``The Deep South is one of the areas where
we still have a long way to go. There still are some people who
would rule out voting for someone just based on their sexual
orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not illegal in Georgia to deny housing and employment
based on sexual orientation, and a law that would bar gay couples
from adopting children has been debated in the General Assembly but
never passed.
</P>
<P>
   These are issues that many gays in Georgia hope Drenner will
work to resolve. She accepts the attention uneasily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a candidate who is gay, not a gay candidate,'' she said.
``I didn't run to become the first openly gay person in the
Legislature. I ran because it was my dream, and I finally had
enough courage to actualize it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Drenner, 38, does not want her public service to be defined
by her sexual orientation, some say she may be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Woolard, who became an Atlanta councilwoman in 1997 and
the first openly gay person elected to public office in Georgia,
said of Drenner:
</P>
<P>
   ``She's going to have to create a balance for herself between
being the standard bearer for all gay people, and assuring her
constituents that she's not a single-issue candidate. For gay
elected officials, if you do anything on behalf of the gay
community, it suddenly becomes reflected as your entire agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   But gays say they hope that Drenner's visibility as a lesbian
will be an important step forward for gay rights in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Drenner said she was aware of the opportunity, and welcomed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can put a face on a stereotype, I think that in
and of itself creates change,'' she said. ``I think that my being
there will create change. Some of these people may have never met a
gay person before, and at least now they'll have the opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
