<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-GAY-RALLY-NYT &LR;      08-05 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-GAY-RALLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTREAL'S GAY CELEBRITY CHEF REFUSES ROLE IN GAY PRIDE PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ When Montreal's huge gay pride parade rolls through
downtown on Sunday, organizers expect more than 100 marching groups
and 500,000 people, either watching or walking.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the parade will march without the one Montreal resident
whose recent coming out caused the biggest media frenzy regarding
homosexuality that French Canada has seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find these pride parades ridiculous,'' said Daniel Pinard, a
celebrity television chef, whose congenial disposition masks a
cantankerous spirit. ``I have always hated parades, all these
people singing to the same tune.''
</P>
<P>
   Last New Year's Eve, Pinard said he decided, at age 57, to stop
smoking, to stop drinking, and to make public his homosexuality.
The decision by Pinard, a prominent member of Quebec's celebrity
star system, to speak publicly about being gay set off Quebec's
most publicized coming out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did 11 TV shows, 16 radio programs, and I got 4,000
letters,'' Pinard said recently over dinner, a gastronomic
excursion in which he never sipped wine or lit up a cigarette and
largely talked about what it is like to be gay in Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   When the day for his announcement arrived last March, Le Journal
de Montreal, a tabloid that reminds its readers daily that it is
``the number one French daily of America,'' used yellow ink to
highlight the headline on the cooking star's decision to talk of
his ``homosexualite.'' A soap opera star magazine ran his photo on
its cover, and upscale French newspapers devoted dozens of columns
and articles to digesting his decision.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, media attention mushroomed because a familiar
household figure for the last 25 years had decided to talk about
being gay. But in the largely laissez-faire society of modern
Quebec, interest seemed to grow because when Pinard came out, he
came against something: homophobic television comedy shows and
radio talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   While some people in the United States may believe that their
country has an exclusive franchise on radio and television shows
that many perceive as offensive, this city of commuters offers a
wide selection of radio talk show hosts pandering to the perceived
prejudices of their audiences, largely suburban white men trapped
behind steering wheels. In the late afternoons, off-color comedy
shows take over, pitching raunchy fare to teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   One television program, ``Piment Fort,'' or ``Hot Pepper,'' had
degenerated, Pinard said, into ``mean programming, where they make
fun of gay people, of short people, of ugly people, of fat
people.'' He added, ``They would insinuate that someone was gay,
knowing full well it would harm him. I was amazed that no one
protested.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinard, a silver-haired man who still burns with resentment over
the day half a century ago when a schoolmate taunted him with an
insulting French term for homosexual, decided to denounce ``Piment
Fort'' on an intellectual talk show, ``Les Francs-Tireurs,'' or
``The Snipers.''
</P>
<P>
   The response was overwhelmingly positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the letters I got, only 10 were opposed,'' said Pinard.
``I had police cars stop, and policemen get out to congratulate
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did his appearances lead to discussions of attitudes
toward gays, but the province started debating the subject of
bullying in general. One letter of thanks came from a 10-year-old
boy who said he was lampooned at school because he stuttered.
Another came from the mother of a short boy whose schoolmates threw
derogatory nicknames at him picked up from ``Piment Fort.''
</P>
<P>
   People involved with producing the show have taken a low
profile, refusing to speak with most journalists. On Wednesday,
Jean Bissonnette, the producer, said in a brief interview: ``We
don't have any comments to offer. We don't want to feed what we
call the Pinard affair. He has his own cause to push.''
</P>
<P>
   Normand Brathwaite, the show's host, boasted last spring to
Journal de Montreal, ``I back up what I say.''
</P>
<P>
   While Canadian television's celebrity chef may have scored
points for tolerance, his outspokenness began to antagonize other
gay people after he started last month to serve as spokesman for
Gai Ecoute, this city's leading gay telephone hot line and social
service referral service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only ones who have attacked me, were the gay press,''
Pinard said over a plate of quail at his favorite St. Catherine's
Street restaurant, Le Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's thriving gay press wondered why Pinard should be
considered a gay spokesman when he called Montreal's gay community
a ``ghetto,'' and said that, if there were a pill to become a
heterosexual, he would take it in 30 seconds. On talk shows, he
routinely says he wants to be known for what he does in his
kitchen, not in his bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want people to watch me, and think, `There's a gay
who cooks,''' Pinard said, explaining in part why it took him 40
years to come out. ``I prefer for them to think, `Here is a guy
makes food, and who has some funny mannerisms.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting the gay label as his overriding identity, he said:
``Ambiguity is the zest of life. I hate it when they categorize you
in a little category.''
</P>
<P>
   These views, gay leaders and journalists contend, are
insensitive to gay people in Quebec who have banded together for
mutual support. Even though Montreal is considered a tolerant place
by tourists, recent surveys indicate that about two-thirds of
Montreal gays have not revealed their sexual orientation to their
co-workers and that a similar portion have seriously considered
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really expressed a lot of disdain for the gay community,
and that created a chill,'' said Yves Lafontaine, editor of Fugue,
a gay magazine. ``He can have his own opinions, but not as
spokesman for Gai Ecoute.''
</P>
<P>
   So at the gay pride march on Sunday, when the large Gai Ecoute
group rolls down the parade route, Mayor Pierre Bourque of Montreal
will be riding atop the lead limousine. The mayor, a heterosexual,
will be filling in for Gai Ecoute's spokesman, the man who set the
city talking this year about homosexuality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
