<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A's Can Thank Their GM For Their Success
</P>
<P>
   No, Jason Giambi said, he was not responsible for his team's
acquisition of his brother, Jeremy, earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy approached me about it,'' Giambi, Oakland's most
productive hitter, said recently, referring to the team's general
manager, Billy Beane. ``He said: `We want to get your brother. What
do you think?' I'm like, `Oh yeah, that'd be awesome.' So he went
out and did it. It wasn't any of my doing. It was all Billy Beane's
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics are basically all Billy Beane's doing. A
challenger for the American League West championship and the leader
in the AL wild-card division, the Athletics are in Chicago this
weekend playing the team with the league's best record, then come
to New York for a three-game series with the Yankees that will end
the most rigorous segment of their 2000 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics will have played 10 successive series, a total of
30 games, against teams with winning records, and they will have
lived to tell about it. They began Saturday's schedule with a 15-10
record in those games, having increased their wild-card lead from
one and a half to three and a half games and sliced their distance
from Seattle from three games to one.
</P>
<P>
   Their position is somewhat remarkable considering that, in this
age of payroll disparity, they have one of the five smallest
payrolls in the major leagues. Among the lowest-paid players on
that payroll are Mark Mulder and Barry Zito, rookie starting
pitchers who epitomize the idea that the Athletics are ``all Billy
Beane's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulder and Zito, neither of whom began the season with Oakland,
are pitching in only their second seasons professionally. Mulder
turned 23 on Saturday; Zito is 22. Both left-handers, they will
start in the series against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had a covey of position players who were already
here or would be here in the next year or two,'' Beane said,
explaining the presence of the young pitchers. ``When we went into
the Mulder and Zito drafts, we tried to find the most polished
pitchers so they could be part of this. We passed on some pitchers
who maybe had a higher upside but might not be ready as quickly. We
needed to get pitching prospects here quickly to mesh with the good
young position players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics made Mulder the second player chosen in the 1998
draft; Zito was the ninth the next year. Mulder became a member of
the Oakland rotation April 18 and responded with a 5-2 record in
his first 13 starts. He has since slumped, going 1-5 in his next
seven starts.
</P>
<P>
   Zito is a more recent addition, pitching his first major league
game July 22 and gaining a 1-0 record and 2.37 earned run average
in three starts.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation has another young pitcher, slightly more
experienced than Mulder and Zito. Tim Hudson, 25, is the team's No.
1 starter in his fourth professional season, second in the majors.
He is scheduled to pitch against the White Sox on Sunday with his
12-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   The young position players Beane referred to are abundant,
whether or not Jason Giambi, at 29 with a .325 average, 27 home
runs and 95 runs batted in, qualifies. Shortstop Miguel Tejada is
24, third baseman Eric Chavez is 22, catcher Ramon Hernandez is 24,
left fielder Ben Grieve is 24 and center fielder Terrence Long is
24.
</P>
<P>
   Beane himself is young, 38, a former major league outfielder,
whose wisdom was well ahead of his playing talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sort of retired as a player on spot,'' Sandy Alderson
recalled, ``when he found out the advance scouting position was
open. He applied for the job and did a great job in that
capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson was the Athletics' general manager when Beane played
for them in 1989, the last season of his decidedly unspectacular
career. Starting in the Mets' organization, Beane produced a .219
average in 148 games and 301 at-bats over six seasons. He has
already accomplished more as a general manager, which he became in
October 1997, after Alderson groomed him for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a tremendous amount of enthusiasm for the game, an
excitement for the game that translated into a great deal of energy
and tremendous work ethic,'' said Alderson, now the top baseball
operations executive in the commissioner's office. ``He just ate
and slept the game. Beyond the enthusiasm, he's as intelligent as
anyone I've ever met in the game. He grasped concepts and really
was receptive to new ideas and different approaches to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   One approach that Beane has learned well is how to construct a
team with a payroll less than a third of the Yankees' pay sheet.
The Athletics have not won anything yet, but the real test for
Beane will come if they do reach the playoffs for a couple of
seasons and the good young players remain good.
</P>
<P>
   Those players will also accrue major league service time and
will reach the point in their careers when they can become free
agents. But the owners, not Beane, will determine the type of
contracts the players are offered.
</P>
<P>
   Beane, meanwhile, will continue searching for good young players
and making judicious trades, such as the two deals he made with the
Mets last July that brought Long to the Athletics to play center
field and Jason Isringhausen to be their closer.
</P>
<P>
   Isringhausen was not a closer in the Mets' system, but Beane saw
the potential long distance. The 27-year-old right-hander has
adapted well to this role, gaining 25 saves in 30 chances this
season. Except for a four-game stretch early in May, during which
he squandered three save chances, Isringhausen has been steadily
effective. His success has served as another example of Beane's
ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any doubt when I left that he would do an
exceptional job,'' Alderson said of Beane. ``That's one of the
reasons I felt comfortable leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Everett's Tantrum Costly
</P>
<P>
   The 10-game suspension Carl Everett earned with his temper
tantrum has ended, and none too soon for the Boston Red Sox.
Without their No. 1 power hitter and run producer, the Red Sox won
five and lost five.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, no one knows what Everett might have done in those
games (hitting, not erupting), but during his absence, the Red Sox
averaged 3.8 runs a game compared with 5.4 in the 10 games before
his suspension. Had they been able to score five or six runs a game
in four of the five games they lost, the Red Sox would have won the
games.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, they fell an additional two and one-half games behind
the Yankees without Everett.
</P>
<P>
   The Deal(s) With Surhoff
</P>
<P>
   Just about everyone the Yankees talked to in the weeks leading
to the nonwaiver trading deadline wanted shortstop Alfonso Soriano.
If they could have divided their top minor league prospect into
several parts, the Yankees could have had any number of outfielders
and pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Expos wanted Soriano for Rondell White. The
Baltimore Orioles wanted Soriano for B.J. Surhoff. The San Diego
Padres wanted Soriano for Surhoff. Whoa. How many teams does
Surhoff play for?
</P>
<P>
   Right now only one, the Atlanta Braves, though the Mets would
like to have acquired him for their outfield. But first story
first.
</P>
<P>
   How could the Padres have had Surhoff and traded him to the
Yankees for Soriano? By engineering a three-team deal that would
have also included the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the Orioles would have sent Surhoff to San Diego
for outfielder Eric Owens, catcher Carlo Hernandez and Jeremy
Owens, a minor league outfielder. The Padres then would have
packaged Surhoff with the starting pitcher Matt Clement and the
reliever Donne Wall and shipped the package to the Yankees for
Soriano and several other minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   The germ of the three-way deal was the Yankees' attempt to get
Clement for their starting rotation. But the teams couldn't agree
on appropriate payment so Kevin Towers, the Padres' general
manager, asked Brian Cashman, his Yankees counterpart, if there was
another player he could get elsewhere to justify the package of
players the Padres wanted. Surhoff, Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the Padres and the Orioles progressed to the point
where Towers thought they could make a deal. But then Syd Thrift,
the Orioles vice president for baseball operations, asked Towers
this critical question: Are you getting Soriano in this deal?
</P>
<P>
   Why do you have to know, Towers replied. Because, Thrift said.
</P>
<P>
   Because if the Orioles gave the Padres Surhoff and he then went
to the Yankees for the player the Orioles had wanted for Surhoff in
direct talks with the Yankees, Thrift's standing with his employer,
Peter Angelos, would not be worth a broken bat.
</P>
<P>
   So Towers felt obliged to admit that yes, he would be getting
Soriano. End of three-way transaction.
</P>
<P>
   But the collapse of those talks prompted the Orioles to renew
their effort to send Surhoff to the Yankees for Soriano. But the
Yankees refused to change the stance they had held since the
winter: They would not swap Soriano for Surhoff.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets wanted Surhoff, but when rumors cropped up last winter
that he might be traded to the Mets, Surhoff, wanting to stay in
Baltimore, placed the Mets on his no-trade list. The Braves weren't
on it, so the Orioles traded him to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Soriano, meanwhile, remains in the Yankees' organization. There
had been much talk about the Yankees' willingness to trade him to
the Expos for White, but that possibility turned out to be all talk
and no intention. The Yankees kept dangling Soriano because they
wanted to keep Montreal interested while they searched elsewhere
for an outfielder they would rather have had. Surhoff was their No.
1 choice, but it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
