<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SOCCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FROM WORST TO FIRST  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Aug. 6:
</P>
<P>
   While most New York fans have been focusing on the pennant runs
of the Yankees and the Mets, those who have ventured to Giants
Stadium this spring and summer have been treated to an even more
stirring drama. That is where the MetroStars, the area's entry in
Major League Soccer, have pulled off one of the most heartening
turnarounds in recent local sports history. The MetroStars have
gone from league laughingstock to a dominant power. Going into this
season's final stretch, the team holds a commanding lead in its
Eastern Division.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars' odyssey from worst to first may not yet be the
talk of the office water cooler. This is, after all, a game still
capable of driving traditional American fans to despair with
limited scoring and the occasional 0-0 tie. But the MetroStars have
averaged 17,674 fans a game this season, the second-highest number
in the five-year-old league.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer at Giants Stadium is a festival of diversity, with
bilingual public announcements and an intermingling of suburban
soccer families, European expats wearing Manchester United or Inter
Milan jerseys, and members of the Colombian diaspora who come to
cheer on their compatriot, Adolfo (El Tren) Valencia, the team's
leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the MetroStars may be better known in Germany than they
are locally, thanks to the acquisition of the legendary German
defender Lothar Matthaeus. The 39-year-old player has been injured
much of the season, but his arrival in New York this spring put the
league on the map, not to mention on German TV.
</P>
<P>
   Matthaeus is more the exception than the rule. Unlike the former
Cosmos of the deceased North American Soccer League, the MetroStars
rely on a core of talented young American players like Mark Chung,
Petter Villegas, Clint Mathis and Mike Petke.
</P>
<P>
   For those fans who need a crosstown rivalry to get the blood
boiling, help may be on the way. MetroStars' investors, John Kluge
and Stuart Subotnick, have exercised their option for an expansion
team in the 2002 season. Both Queens and Long Island are among the
sites being considered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
