<HEADER>
A3511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NC-HOTEL-REAL-2TAKES-     08-05 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-HOTEL-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEAR ASHEVILLE, N.C., A 1900-STYLE INN RISES AT BILTMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LYN RIDDLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ A hundred years ago, shortly after George W.
Vanderbilt built a 250-room French Renaissance country estate
outside this western North Carolina city in the Blue Ridge
Mountains, he carefully sketched out plans for a 50-room inn on the
property.
</P>
<P>
   His list began with $3,200 for 449 doors and windows. It ended
with a total: $17,509.29, excluding wallpaper, plumbing, heating
and electrical work.
</P>
<P>
   Today, on a hill on what remains of Vanderbilt's estate, some
two miles from the country home he called Biltmore House, a
213-room inn is taking shape. The Biltmore Co., led by Vanderbilt's
great-grandson William A.V. Cecil Jr., will spend $31 million on an
inn designed with the intent of giving guests a glimpse of what it
was like to stay on the lavish estate about 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 900,000 people visited Biltmore House and its
outbuildings, including a conservatory and a winery. As a tourist
destination, Biltmore now employs about 1,100 people, and it served
as a location for several movies, including ``Richie Rich'' and
``Being There.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard T. Pressley, the chief financial officer and executive
vice president of Biltmore Co., said that market research showed
that 60 percent of the visitors to Biltmore House stay in local
motels, and most stay in midpriced chains with room rates of about
$100 a night. Most visitors are between 35 and 54 years old, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked at this project for 20 years,'' Pressley said.
Once convinced it was sound financially, company officials spent 18
months interviewing architects and contractors. They selected
Thompson, Ventulett &AMP; Stainback Associates of Atlanta as its
architect, along with Design Workshop of Aspen, Colo., landscape
architect; Hughes Design Associates of McLean, Va., interior
designer; and W.G. Yates &AMP; Sons Construction Co. of Philadelphia,
Miss.
</P>
<P>
   The designers took some of their cues from the work of the
distinguished team that designed Biltmore House before the turn of
the century. Richard Morris Hunt, architect for the center part of
the Fifth Avenue facade of the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New
York, designed the house. Frederick Law Olmsted, who designed New
York's Central Park with Calvert Vaux, created the landscape plan.
</P>
<P>
   In designing the hotel, to be called the Inn on Biltmore Estate,
``the intent was partially to create a building that didn't compete
with the house but gave guests a sense of staying at the house,''
said Scott Sickeler, the project's lead architect. ``What caught me
by surprise was Olmsted and the influence he had over the estate,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   The designers sought to give guests the same sort of experience
when driving up to the inn that visitors get on the three-mile
approach road to the house, a road that meanders through five
different North Carolina landscapes. The house is not visible until
visitors get right up to it. In a similar manner, guests will be
given only small glimpses of the inn as they wind their way up the
hillside.
</P>
<P>
   Landscaping, influenced by Olmsted's work, has already been done
to allow a year's growth before the inn's opening, scheduled for
March 1.
</P>
<P>
   The inn faces Mount Pisgah and Mount Pisgah National Forest.
``It is 270 degrees of uninterrupted wilderness,'' Sickeler said.
Other views are of Biltmore House itself, framed by woodlands and
mountains, and of downtown Asheville, several miles in the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Biltmore Co. decided to manage the inn itself, rather than
contract with a national chain, because corporate officials wanted
direct control over quality, Pressley said. The company hired as
general manager Michael Chaffin, who previously managed the Stephen
F. Austin Hotel in Austin, Texas, and the Omni hotel, also in
Austin. Biltmore's hospitality division is managed by Thomas B.
Ruff, a senior vice president of the company who previously worked
with Marriott Hotels and Resorts and Hyatt Hotels Corp. Chaffin and
Ruff say their goal is to create an inn that will win top ratings
from guidebooks like those from AAA and Mobil.
</P>
<P>
   In-season room rates will range from $160 to $195 a night. Nine
suites will be available, ranging from $900 to $2,000 a night. The
$2,000 suite has 1,400 square feet with a sitting room and one
bedroom with an optional second bedroom. Discount packages will be
available, but prices have not been set, Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   The inn can accommodate small corporate functions, but not
conventions. Its largest meeting room will be the 1,800-square-foot
Vanderbilt Room, and it will also have two smaller meeting rooms
and two banquet rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The lobby will have a large fireplace that mimics the huge
fireplaces of Biltmore House. Vanderbilt was a book collector, and
so the inn will have a library, an unusual feature for a hotel. The
restaurant will be called simply the Restaurant at the Inn on
Biltmore Estate. Guests will also be able to eat in the more casual
restaurant at the estate's winery, just down the hill. Admission to
Biltmore House _ $32 for adults _ will not be included in the room
rates, and the inn will have a gatehouse, meant to keep out the
merely curious.
</P>
<P>
   The company has incorporated some of the signature features of
Biltmore House in the inn's design. Limestone, used on the exterior
of the house, will cover the lobby floor. The roof will be slate,
and oak for the library came from trees on the property, as did the
black walnut floors for the private dining room.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The inn will compete with two other venerable Asheville hotels,
the 510-room Grove Park Inn, which is now building a $27 million
40,000-square-foot spa, and the 36-room Richmond Hill Inn. The area
also has a number of upscale B &AMP; B's as well.
</P>
<P>
   The company will begin taking reservations for the inn in
October, and group events scheduled after April 15, 2001, are
already being booked.
</P>
<P>
   The Vanderbilt connection with the Asheville area began when
George W. Vanderbilt, a grandson of the steamboat and railroad
industrialist Cornelius Vanderbilt, visited the North Carolina
mountains in the late 1880s. The area was known for its healing
mineral springs and fresh mountain air. In 1888, Vanderbilt decided
it was the place for his country home. He began buying land,
eventually assembling an estate of 125,000 acres, and commissioned
designs for the house and its landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   The house took six years to build. It covers four acres and
included many amenities unusual for its time: elevators, electric
lights and telephones. The first major event held there took place
on Christmas Eve in 1895, when Vanderbilt, then a 33-year-old
bachelor, entertained dozens of guests who had arrived in five
train cars from New York and Newport, R.I. Through the years,
Vanderbilt and his wife, Edith, entertained many celebrities at
Biltmore, including Henry James, Edith Wharton and John Singer
Sargent.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt died in 1914 during an emergency appendectomy in
Washington, and his widow returned to the estate, where the
couple's only child, Cornelia, grew up. Over the years, Edith
Vanderbilt donated and sold off much of the estate. Some 87,000
acres were deeded to the federal government for what is now Pisgah
National Forest. Another chunk became Biltmore Village, a
commercial area now just outside the Biltmore House gate.
</P>
<P>
   But the house and 8,000 acres have remained in the family
through four generations. It was opened to the public in 1930 at
the request of Asheville city officials who hoped it would bolster
an economy reeling from the Depression. It closed during World War
II and was reopened in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   By 1959, Biltmore House was losing $250,000 a year. William A.V.
Cecil, a grandson of Vanderbilt and then a New York banker,
returned to the family business shortly thereafter and began a
turnaround that many people told him could not be achieved. The
house was placed on the national Register of Historic Places in
1963, and almost a decade later, Biltmore made a profit: $16.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best money I've ever made,'' Cecil, now chairman of
Biltmore Co. and the father of the current chief executive, is
reported to have said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
