u i BC-MALAYSIA-ANWAR-TRIAL-     08-05 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-ANWAR-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSION GROWS IN MALAYSIA AS JUDGE DELAYS ANWAR VERDICT 
 
</HEADLINE>
  By MARK LANDLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Friday was to have been a day of
reckoning for the leader of Malaysia's reform movement, Anwar
Ibrahim. Given the furies that have swirled around Anwar for the
last two years, it could have been a day of reckoning for his
country as well.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, the judge in his trial on sodomy charges
unexpectedly delayed the verdict. Now, a tense air of expectancy
has descended on this city. From office suites to roadside food
stalls, people are debating why the judge did not hand down his
ruling as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy theories abound. Some say Malaysia's prime minister,
Mahathir Mohamad, feared that a guilty verdict would draw thousands
of protesters into the streets in a noisy repeat of the battles
that raged after Anwar was convicted of corruption last year.
Others contend that the judge is wrestling with his conscience, and
may stun the country by acquitting Anwar, a former deputy prime
minister and Mahathir protege, of sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   To the 500 Anwar supporters who turned out on Friday in front of
the High Court brandishing portraits of the ousted deputy prime
minister, chanting ``Reformasi'' and scuffling with the police, it
was evidence of a government with something to fear from its
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps they did not want a show of support for Anwar,'' said
Chandra Muzaffar, deputy president of the pro-reform National
Justice Party, which was formed, with Anwar as its standard-bearer,
after his first conviction. ``If you look at all the factors, the
regime is not as strong as people think they are.''
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of the sodomy charge, Anwar could be sentenced to
20 years in jail. He is already serving six years for corruption,
and is barred from politics for five years after his release.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir's coalition won an unassailable two-thirds majority in
the elections. The 74-year-old prime minister, Asia's
longest-serving leader, has spent much of the last year
consolidating his power by going after new rivals, like Malaysia's
increasingly popular Islamic Party.
</P>
<P>
   While few people here say they believe Anwar is guilty of
sodomizing his wife's chauffeur, as he is charged, his trial no
longer provides a rallying cry for most Malaysians, who have moved
on to other concerns, like getting the most out of Malaysia's newly
energized economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anwar has not been as much in the public imagination over the
last year,'' said K.S. Jomo, a professor of economics at the
University of Malaya. ``But it's not as if Anwar's reduced
visibility has helped Mahathir. A great number of people now
believe this was basically a personal vendetta.''
</P>
<P>
   Together Anwar and Mahathir had turned Malaysia into an economic
star of Asia. But Anwar soon emerged as a threat to the prime
minister, who ruthlessly turned on him. In September 1998, Anwar
was abruptly dismissed, and a few weeks later, dozens of police
officers and army troops burst into his house to arrest him. He was
charged with sexual misconduct and abusing his power by interfering
in a police investigation of his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's trial has raised troubling questions about Malaysia's
once-respected judicial system. The prosecution flailed wildly in
its attempt to prove that he had engaged in ``carnal intercourse
against the order of nature.'' After first alleging that Anwar had
sodomized the chauffeur, Azizan Abu Bakar, ``one night in the month
of May 1994,'' the prosecutors shifted the date to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   When Anwar's lawyers noted that the building in which the act
allegedly took place had been under construction at the time, the
prosecution switched the date again, to 1993. Malaysian law allows
prosecutors to amend charges during a trial. Under
cross-examination, Azizan said the police had ordered him to change
the date.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, 52, strenuously denied the charges, saying he was the
victim of a conspiracy orchestrated by Mahathir. His lawyers
presented alibis for almost all the days of the three-month period
in 1993, during which the sexual misconduct was supposed to have
taken place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time around, the evidence was very flimsy,'' said Anwar's
wife, Wan Azizah Wan Ismail. ``The feeling one had in the courtroom
was like, `Is this for real?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
