<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DIXIE-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIXIE UNION TO GET TEST IN HASKELL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEANPORT, N.J. _ The disappointment of Dixie Union's
fifth-place finish in the 1999 Breeders' Cup Juvenile was still
with the trainer Richard Mandella when he made his way to the barn
at Gulfstream Park the morning after the race. But even more bad
news awaited Mandella: Dixie Union had just run the worst race of
his career after having won the Hollywood Juvenile Championship,
the Best Pal and the Norfolk, and had also sustained a chipped knee
that would require surgery.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of going back to California, he went straight to
Kentucky for the operation, Mandella said.
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Union, the son of Dixieland Band, made a swift recovery,
and by early spring Mandella was debating whether to hustle him
onto the Triple Crown trail. A streak of bad weather and bad
racetracks made that decision for him. So instead of heading to the
classics, Dixie Union made his first start as a 3-year-old the day
after the Kentucky Derby, far from Churchill Downs, winning a
six-and-one-half-furlong allowance at Hollywood Park in California.
</P>
<P>
   In his next two starts, Dixie Union finished second twice, as
the favorite in both the Lazaro Barrera Memorial at seven furlongs
and the mile-and-a-sixteenth Affirmed Handicap on July 1, showing
improvement each time. On Sunday, he tries to join the fray for the
second season as he faces eight others, including the Belmont
winner Commendable, the favored More Than Ready and the Triple
Crown veterans Captain Steve and Impeachment in the $1 million
Haskell Invitational at Monmouth Park. It is a Grade I race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a couple of sprints and a route race,'' Mandella
said. ``Right now, he's a very good sprinter we hope will get one
and one-eighth miles. He's not quite back to where he was, but I am
optimistic he will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Union was listed at 6-1 behind the 5-2 favorite More Than
Ready, who ticked off five straight victories as a 2-year-old and
has been consistent this year, if victorious only once. Captain
Steve, winner of the Grade I Swaps in his last start, was made the
3-1 second choice in the field of nine, while the entry of
Commendable and Impeachment was 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Also entered in the Haskell are Thistyranthasclass, the winner
of four straight at Monmouth; Mercaldo; Kiss A Native; and the Ohio
Derby winner, Milwaukee Brew, who has won four straight races.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bunch of real nice horses in here,'' said Kevin
Attard, who will saddle Milwaukee Brew for his father, Tino. ``If
the track plays fair, it should be to our advantage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
