<P>
   GOP CONVENTION FOLLOW-UP
</P>
<P>
   CVN-BUSH _ PHILADELPHIA _ George Bush's convention took great
strides in rewriting the GOP story from the party of status quo to
the party of reform, from the party of protecting wealth to the
party of providing help, from the party of narrow interests to the
party of inclusion. But even as the party's only openly gay
congressional representative was addressing Bush's convention,
Bush's platform committee was voting not to soften anti-gay
language in the platform. This dichotomy has been evident
throughout the campaign, and the question remains: Which is the
real George W. Bush, and which is the real GOP? (Montgomery, Dayton
Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CVN-REAL-GOP _ PHILADELPHIA _ George Bush's convention took
pains to portray the Republican Party as one in transition from the
party of narrow interests to the party of inclusion. But even as
the party's only openly gay congressional representative was
addressing Bush's convention, Bush's platform committee was voting
not to soften anti-gay language in the platform. Amid other such
discrepancies, the question remains: which is the real George W.
Bush, which is the real GOP. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GORE _ WASHINGTON _ Now that the Republican National
Convention is history, Vice President Al Gore needs to counter its
effects in two main ways: deliver an acceptance speech in Los
Angeles that counters the style and substance of George W. Bush's,
and choose a running mate who compares well with Dick Cheney.
(Shepard, Cox News Service) MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   VOTER _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Sen. John McCain may have caused Gov.
George W. Bush plenty of headaches in the bitterly contested
Republican presidential primary, but, if Ohio is any indication, he
may have done Bush and all Republican candidates a big favor. The
sparks flying off McCain's Straight Talk Express generated a wave
of interest among voters, particularly Republican voters, that
hasn't been seen in a primary in many years. According to newly
released statewide voter registration figures compiled by the Ohio
secretary of state's office, that wave almost doubled the ranks of
the state's registered Republicans. Democratic registration also
grew, but the registered Republican increase more than doubled the
Democratic gain. (McCall, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
