<HEADER>
A3530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-LOBSTER-1100     08-05 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-LOBSTER-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS FOR DUMP SPUR MAINE LOBSTERMEN TO PROTEST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Maine)  By PAUL MOLYNEAUX   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York and Connecticut lobstermen are not alone in fearing
that their precious resource is being threatened by man-made
contaminants. Maine, the nation's largest lobster source, has not
suffered the alarming die-off that decimated the Long Island Sound
lobster fishery this spring, but Maine fishermen, environmentalists
and town officials have seen enough red flags to voice their
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Maine's Department of Transportation announced plans
to dump dredge spoils contaminated with lead, mercury, PCBs and
petroleum derivatives, into the prime lobster grounds of Penobscot
Bay. The proposed disposal site, five miles from Vinalhaven, Maine,
an island about 50 miles northeast of Portland, lies within an area
where 19 million pounds of lobster were caught last year _ nearly
40 percent of the state landings. When Penobscot Bay lobstermen and
community leaders heard about the dumping proposal, they came out
in force to protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a scientist,'' said Vinalhaven's town manager, Sue
Lessard, looking at the transportation department's plan. ``But I'm
intelligent enough to know this is not a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the causes of the Long Island Sound disaster remain
uncertain _ last week, New York area lobstermen blamed pesticide
spraying _ some scientists believe contaminated dredge spoils
played a role. Consequently, Maine fishermen have asked regulators
to find new approaches to dump dredge material.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's transportation department did not expect any opposition
when it applied for its dredge material disposal permit _ part of a
port redevelopment project at Mack Point, in upper Penobscot Bay.
At an April hearing on the application, Paul Pottle, the
department's project manager, told the public that the permit
called for dumping 121,000 cubic yards of dredge material and that
the contaminated material would be left at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Lessard, armed with facts, caught Pottle off guard when she took
issue with his statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obtained copies of the permits being applied for,'' Lessard
told Pottle, ``and I'm a little confused as to what I've heard.''
Lessard said the application asked to dispose 375,000 cubic yards
of material at the Rockland, Maine, site, at least 50,000 cubic
yards of it contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   Lessard also pointed out that federal rules required the
Rockland site to be monitored every 10 years and that it had not
been monitored since 1989. She, and many others, said that they did
not object to the Mack Point port project, only the proposed
disposal of the dredge spoils. They called for a review of the
Rockland site before any future dumping.
</P>
<P>
   The Mack Point project, high on Gov. Angus King's list of
priorities, has ``a lot of political will behind it,'' Lessard
said. ``If it's a state mission to build this port, we want it
handled responsibly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Vinalhaven, where 75 percent of the year-round residents
depend on the lobster industry for their livelihood, it comes as no
surprise that a furor over the disposal of dredge spoils spread in
coastal areas and led to another meeting in late April. State and
federal officials addressed the concerns of Vinalhaven and other
Maine fishing communities.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Boutilier of the Army Corps of Engineers' New England
office said that the disposal site off Vinalhaven was scheduled for
review this year. ``We'll be seeking input from fishermen on how
best to conduct the site evaluation in order to address their
concerns,'' he said, but he added that the results might not affect
the Mack Point project.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Jones, owner of the Vinalhaven Lobster Co., suggested that
a review of the Rockland site should lead to the end of dumping.
``We don't want another Long Island Sound,'' he said. ``We need to
close the Rockland site permanently.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine's commissioner of the Department of Marine Resources,
George Lapointe, urged fishermen and community leaders to work with
the state to find solutions to Mack Point and future dredge
disposal issues. ``Let's get the facts on the table,'' Lapointe
said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that ``dumping had occurred at the Rockland disposal
site since the '50s, concomitant with the largest increase in
lobster landings in Maine history.'' Lobster landings have
increased from 22 million to 53 million pounds in the last 50
years.
</P>
<P>
   With the dredge material from Mack Point and several harbor
maintenance projects scheduled to go to the Rockland disposal site,
Maine's transportation commissioner, John Melrose, asked fishermen
to consider the economic repercussions of closing the area's only
ocean disposal site.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that's left me sort of unsettled is that much of the
discussion has been focused on the lobster resource,'' Melrose
said. ``You need to consider what will happen to other projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocean dumping of contaminated dredge spoils has become a
nationwide problem, and Melrose acknowledged that ``the long-term
prospects for doing business as usual are not good.'' But for the
short term, he expressed worries that if the Rockland dump closed,
the rising cost of dredge spoil disposal might shut down marine
activity in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The transportation department estimates that each ship entering
a Maine port generates $40,000 to $74,000 for local communities. In
addition, the Mack Point port would link shipping with rail service
to northern Maine, Montreal and maritime Canada, providing goods to
those areas and export opportunities for the region's forest
products.
</P>
<P>
   Leroy Bridges, president of the Downeast Lobstermen's
Association, countered that Maine's $70 million lobster industry
also contributes to the state's economy and the tourist industry.
``People don't come to Maine to see ships unloading,'' he said.
``They come to eat lobster, and see us catching them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance Stewart, a University of Connecticut marine biologist who
has studied the effects of dredge spoil disposal on lobsters for
decades, believes the lobsters in Long Island Sound succumbed to a
number of stresses, including pesticide spraying and rising water
temperature. ``Although dredge spoils may be having some impact,
they are not at the top of my list as far as the cause of the
die-off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bayer, executive director of the University of
Maine-affiliated Lobster Institute, agrees that anything that will
kill an insect will kill a lobster, but he remains cautious. ``We
still worry about dredge spoils,'' he said. Many Long Island Sound
lobstermen had lost boats and homes, Bayer said, as a result of the
economic repercussions of the crisis. ``Is it worth the risk?'' he
asked.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a resolution of conflicting interests, Bridges, Lessard
and representatives from several advocacy groups met with state
officials on June 13. The meeting resulted in some progress, but
the situation remains tentative.
</P>
<P>
   ``MDOT agreed to consider reducing the total volume on its
application to, 75,000 cubic yards, and find an upland disposal
site for the contaminated material,'' said Ben Neal of the Island
Institute in Rockland. ``I think it's good that people are talking,
but the jury is still out on what level of commitment MDOT has.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's department of transportation ``agreed to reduce the
volume on the application to 75,000 cubic yards for this round, and
find an upland disposal site for the contaminated material,''
Lessard said. She said she believed the department ``is cognizant
of our concerns and is trying to compromise.'' She added, however,
that nothing had yet been put in writing.
</P>
<P>
   The transportation department's Melrose is hopeful that
affordable ways can be found to use contaminated material, possibly
in the construction at Mack Point. But dredge material will
continue to be generated by other projects, and Melrose wants to
avoid future conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, his department, the Army Corps of Engineers and
Maine agencies have set to work with various individuals and groups
to create a long-range plan balancing environmental and economic
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Lessard and Bridges have faith in the negotiations. But economic
realities continue to drive the Mack Point project, and
contaminated dredge material could still legally be dumped in
waters off Vinalhaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important we don't go down that road,'' Lessard said.
``There's way too much at stake.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
