<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3533 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-DINNER-NYT &LR;      08-05 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DINNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALONE WITH GORE, ALMOST UNRESTRAINED
</HEADLINE>
   (With GORE-MEDIA-FRIENDS) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore's Hank Williams imitation is certainly surprising, and
he did it at dinner, by request _ with his mouth full of food,
actually. ``Have you ever seen a robin cry,'' he twanged, ``when
leaves begin to fall.'' Then, on a roll, he sang a few lines of
Garth Brooks' ``I've Got Friends in Low Places.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there is no sense that a recent on-the-record dinner with
a reporter can be considered an occasion to glimpse the ``private''
Al Gore, he was the good company his friends swear that he is,
laughing over some of his favorite stupid country lyrics, making
fun of himself for pandering to Roman Catholics, even gossiping a
little.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that the dinner took place at all, unsupervised by
aides, in Gore's hotel suite on the road in New York several weeks
ago, says that he is not always as cautious as he is generally
considered.
</P>
<P>
   He began by saying grace over the herb chicken and roasted
vegetables and remarked that he had always been puzzled by the idea
that a person cannot believe fervently in both God and science. ``I
never saw the slightest inconsistency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking unselfconsciously of his own faith, he said, ``The
separation of church and state is a very healthy principle I would
die for, but this insistence on separating belief from our daily
life is at the root of many of our problems.''
</P>
<P>
   He expressed interest in Garry Wills' new book, ``Papal Sin:
Structure of Deceit,'' and because it is critical of the Catholic
Church, said, laughing, ``I guess I won't be able to praise his
work any more with any degree of political safety.''
</P>
<P>
   And he mocked himself, too, in describing his stubborn efforts
to proselytize the astronomer Carl Sagan, saying: ``My great
challenge was to convert Carl Sagan. I moved him from atheist to
agnostic. But I think he was just playing word games with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3535 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-VOTER0806-COX     08-05 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTER0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain's run boosts ranks of Ohio GOP
 &HT;    By Ken McCall
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Arizona Sen. John McCain caused Texas Gov. George
W. Bush plenty of headaches in the bitterly contested Republican
presidential primaries, but, if Ohio is any indication, the GOP
maverick may have done Bush and all Republican candidates a big
favor.
</P>
<P>
   The sparks flying off McCain's Straight Talk Express ignited a
firestorm of voter interest that almost doubled the ranks of Ohio's
registered Republicans, according to newly released voter
registration figures compiled by the Ohio Secretary of State.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the March 7 primary, Republican registration shot
up by more than three-quarters of a million voters, from 844,293 to
1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The increase is more than twice the jump Democrats saw.
Democratic registration, prodded by an already-decided, but
still-smoldering contest between Vice President Al Gore and former
Sen. Bill Bradley, grew by 327,270 to reach 1.27 million.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the largest Republican gains were in counties that have
historically been GOP strongholds, indicating the ``new''
Republicans were likely old Republicans or GOP-leaning independents
who hadn't voted in a recent primary.
</P>
<P>
   The figures also indicate that cross-over voting _ Democrats
switching parties to vote in the Republican primary _ was not
widespread in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the total number of voters who voted in the
Democratic primary in 1998, but switched to the Republican primary
this year was 74,458 or just under 10 percent of the total
Republican registration gain. Those party-switchers amounted to
only 2.4 percent of the primary turnout and less than 1 percent of
the state's registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   Some political observers say the results give Republicans an
edge going into November because they have more voters motivated
early and that primary voters tend to turn out for general
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Others are more cautious, even skeptical, of the apparent
Republican gain because of the way Ohio handles party affiliation.
In Ohio, a voter must have voted in one of the last two statewide
party primaries to be considered a member of that party. Anyone who
didn't vote in either the 2000 or 1998 primaries is classified in
Ohio as non-partisan, regardless of past political affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the March primary, those non-partisans still total
4.4 million or 60 percent of the state's registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ohio Republican Party Chairman Robert Bennett, who is happy
with his party's voter surge, said the non-partisan majority
muddies the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget the largest group is still the non-declared,'' he
said. ``Ohio is still a competitive, two-party state.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, several analysts said, Ohio Republican leaders
have reason to be optimistic about the November election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good news for the Republicans,'' said John Green, a
political scientist at the University of Akron. ``A substantial
group of voters have now revealed themselves as having an interest
in the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there is widespread agreement that most of the 516,790
Ohioans who cast ballots for McCain in March were likely already
Republicans or leaning that way, Green said the Republican gain
gives the party an ``organizational edge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you can send these people mail,'' he said. ``You can call
them on the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Adams, Wright State University political science
professor, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were a Republican looking at this you would say this is
a great opportunity,'' Adams said. ``We've got a bunch of people
here who, for whatever reason, came into the party. They made that
first tentative step at least. They're registered as Republicans
and they're ready to vote and how do we keep the McCain Republicans
voting for Bush in the fall?''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, on the other hand, downplay the significance of the
post-primary voter totals.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers mean absolutely nothing,'' said Ohio Democratic
Party Chairman David Leland. ``They're interesting, but all they
say is that the Republicans had a more interesting primary than we
did and were able to turn out more people.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County Democratic Party Chairman Dennis Lieberman
also is ``not concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore had sewn up the Democratic presidential nomination before
the Ohio primary, he pointed out, while McCain was still giving
Bush a good run for his money. And locally, Lieberman said, the
Democrats had no interesting primaries to drive voter turnout,
while the Republicans had a primary contest in the 42nd Ohio House
District between Washington Twp. Trustee Joyce Young and Kettering
Vice Mayor John White, who won the election. ``That increased
participation and voter turnout,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County Republican Party Chairman Jeff Jacobson agreed
that much of the registration increase was ``naturally affiliated
Republicans,'' but said a big primary turnout can have a ``ripple
effect'' in the general election, especially in local races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people who show up are more willing to support
their ticket, because they feel like, having voted in the primary,
they made some commitment to it,'' Jacobson said. ``I would suggest
we are not going to have trouble holding the vast majority of
McCain people because they are Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   That remains to be seen. Green, for one, said the Republicans
may have a harder time than they admit keeping McCain voters in the
fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the surveys we've had are accurate, they're a different
kind of Republican,'' Green said. ``They're more
independent-leaning, maybe a little more liberal, and certainly
more reform-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   The voters who were attracted by McCain's reform agenda will be
``hard to keep,'' Green said. ``It can be done, but the mainstream
Republican Party isn't their cup of tea. That's why they weren't
voting in primaries until McCain came along.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright State's Adams agreed that there's ``no guarantee'' the
McCain voters will turn out for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Adams said the Republicans can do is ``get McCain in
here'' campaigning for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said he expects McCain to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've invited him in and he's been very gracious,'' the state
Republican chairman said. ``John McCain's always been very popular
in Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   Leland said the Democratic Party won't do anything special to
woo the McCain voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in wooing over the 5 million voters who may be
participating in this election,'' he said. ``What we need to do is
talk about the issues we've been talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said Leland is on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have an awful lot of folks who are not declared and
are kind of up for grabs,'' he said, ``which is why traditionally
Ohio has been a bellwether state in presidential elections. It has
that really large undeclared category.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
