<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3546 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ARCTIC-FLIGHT0806-COX     08-05 1884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCTIC-FLIGHT0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flying to the land of the midnight sun and back
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Even in summer, you just don't swim in
the Arctic Ocean. It's always cold, so you approach it delicately,
respectfully, with one eye on the ice floes dotting the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-morning on July 3, Bud Barton, John Keys and Walt Pierce
carefully picked their way over the rocks and pebbles on the shore
by Tuktoyaktuk, Northwest Territories, untied a shoe, stripped off
a sock and dipped a big toe in the shallows.
</P>
<P>
   It was freezing. Goose bumps popped up on their arms as they
quickly dried off their toes and put their socks and shoes back on.
Then they stood looking out over the Arctic Ocean, dull blue-gray
beneath an overcast sky and more than 100 miles within the Arctic
Circle, and it struck them: They'd done it.
</P>
<P>
   What began two years ago as a vague, but determined, idea to fly
to the Arctic Circle culminated that July morning when three men in
jeans and windbreakers, all of them on the golden side of 50, stood
on the shore of the Arctic Ocean, looking out toward the North Pole
and, across the water, Russia. It was a view none of them had seen
before and they'd flown thousands of miles from Green River, Utah,
to see it.
</P>
<P>
   The flight was Jim Hurst's idea. Hurst, 78, of Green River, flew
as a bush pilot for 25 years in the western United States and 20
years in Canada. He retired from flying because of his health, but
as anyone who has ever flown an airplane knows, pilots never really
leave flying. Visions of the wild blue yonder always hover just
behind their eyelids, fresh and potent in the memory.
</P>
<P>
   Hurst wanted to fly to Canada again and reacquaint himself with
the places he knows, visit old friends, soar over vast stretches of
wilderness. Two years ago he began talking about the flight with
Keys, 58, retired from 35 years with the U.S. Bureau of Land
Management and an active Moab pilot. Keys was intrigued and kept
the possibility of an Arctic Circle flight in the back of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, in 1999, Hurst began pursuing plans for the Canada
trip in earnest. He got Keys to commit to the journey _ ``because
it sounded interesting,'' Keys said _ and met Barton, 76, who is
retired from the oil and gas industry, at Green River's Melon Days
last summer. Barton knew of Hurst because of his bush pilot fame,
and invited Hurst to his house for a cool drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we sat on my front porch and watched the river, and Jim
told me he was getting together a trip to the Arctic Circle and
would I be interested,'' Barton explained. ``I told him I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Barton signed on, he asked Pierce, 73, his longtime friend
who lives in Houston, to join the crew as his passenger and the
trip mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   If the crew was unconventional _ Hurst was the only long-time
pilot, Keys got his pilot's license when he was 51 and Barton when
he was 57 _ their planning wasn't. It was thorough.
</P>
<P>
   They ordered maps and flight plans from Aero Training Products
in Vancouver, British Columbia, downloaded information from the
Airplane Owners and Pilots Association Web site, learned Canadian
flight regulations, applied for radio licenses and charted out
several route possibilities. Between September last year and June
this year they compiled tools and polar survival gear, including
tarps, fishing equipment, a bear gun, pots and other essentials.
</P>
<P>
   By June they were ready to take off and planned to leave Green
River on July 1, allotting themselves two weeks for the journey in
case weather detained them or put them off course. July 1, however,
is a Canadian holiday, so the crew decided to leave June 28.
</P>
<P>
   They took off early that morning, Barton flying his 1959 Cessna
182 and Keys his 1965 Cessna 182. The morning was cloudless and
cool as Keys flew from the Moab airfield to Green River to meet up
with Hurst, his passenger, and Barton and Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Taking off from Green River, they headed for Pocatello, Idaho,
and a fuel stop, usually flying within sight of each other and
maintaining radio contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the nice things about this trip,'' Keys said,
``because on long trips you're in the plane for hours on end, so it
was nice to have people to talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first day, the flying was easy because the terrain
was familiar: Barton has logged hundreds of hours flying in the
area, especially to Logan, Utah, to bring his daughter home for
weekend visits, and Keys not only spent 35 years with the BLM, but
is a referee for college football games in the Big Sky conference
and usually flies to games.
</P>
<P>
   From Pocatello they flew to Kalispell, Mont., to refuel and
headed over the border into British Columbia. They stopped for the
night in Kamloops.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, over dinner, Hurst began to feel sick. By the end
of the night, his condition was serious enough that his friends
took him to the hospital, where doctors said Hurst shouldn't travel
farther north and should go home.
</P>
<P>
   The four men spent the next day deciding what they should do.
Hurst had no choice but to go home, but he insisted that the three
other men continue north and reach their goal of flying into the
Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wrenching decision, but finally they agreed because
they had become just as committed as Hurst to the goal.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of social workers in Kamloops, they found a flight
home for Hurst and continued on, missing his companionship and
knowledge of the area.
</P>
<P>
   On June 30 they continued north, aborting plans to stop in
Prince George because of bad weather. Instead, they turned back and
stopped for fuel in Williams Lake, British Columbia, staying that
night at the Stork's Nest Inn in Smithers, where storks roost in
the chimneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the best parts of the trip was how good the
flight service stations were and how friendly people were to us,''
Keys said. ``We never had a single problem landing and getting
fuel, and the people at those stations were always really
helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   They averaged about five flight hours per day, departing
mid-morning and arriving at that day's destination with enough time
to explore the town and meet people. In Whitehorse, Yukon
Territory, where they stayed July 1, Barton and Pierce went to the
Museum of Transportation, which featured a display about bush
pilots, while Keys walked around town.
</P>
<P>
   On the flight north they generally followed the Alaska Highway,
soaring over mountains thickly carpeted with trees, over rivers and
lakes and, when they were low enough, beaver dams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I was expecting in the way of topography,''
Barton said, ``but there were trees everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they had been flying under cloud cover most of the time
since flying into Canada, on July 2 they had their first, and only,
experience with truly sketchy weather when, after stopping for fuel
in Dawson City, Yukon Territory, they flew into a storm that got so
serious _ their visibility was reduced to zero _ they had to fly up
through the clouds, which would make coming down tricky.
</P>
<P>
   However, Keys said, the flight service personnel in Inuvik,
Northwest Territories, found a hole in the cloud cover for them and
guided them down, and, once they were on the ground, recommended a
fishing lodge where they could have a good meal.
</P>
<P>
   One of the flight service personnel and his wife met the three
men for drinks the next night.
</P>
<P>
   Once they reached Inuvik they officially were within the Arctic
Circle, though it hardly seemed like it because there was no snow
on the ground and looked, in many ways, like Minnesota: flat, green
and covered with thousands of ponds and lakes. They saw pingos,
permafrost formations that are mounds of mud that continually
freeze and thaw, as well as arctic birds and the midnight sun.
</P>
<P>
   They decided they wanted to fly over the Arctic Ocean and stick
a toe in, so the next morning, they flew northwest from Inuvik and
soared half a mile from the coast out over the Arctic Ocean before
landing in Tuktoyaktuk. Barton, Keys and Pierce each got a
certificate for sticking their toes in the Arctic Ocean and a
friendly local gave Keys the tip of a musk ox horn as he walked
back from the shore.
</P>
<P>
   They had flown about 2,500 miles, taking less time than they'd
expected because Hurst wasn't along to introduce them to his
friends and show them the sights, but they were satisfied from
having reached their goal. Now they just had to get home.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Inuvik, another friendly local referred Keys to a
resident artist who carved for him an Eskimo in a canoe harpooning
a whale, which became his prized souvenir of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I just met this man in the grocery store who referred me
to this local artist,'' Keys said. ``Everyone we met was just so
friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   After staying in Inuvik July 3, they began heading south. On
July 4 they stopped for fuel in Norman Wells, Northwest
Territories, and stayed for the night in Fort Simpson, a town on
the Mackenzie River that is the Dene tribe's headquarters and that
Pope John Paul II visited in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Every time they landed on that leg of the journey they breathed
a small sigh of relief because between Inuvik and Fort Simpson
there was nothing underneath them but wilderness, ``so you're
listening to every rattle of the engine, thinking, `Come on, baby.'
''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is amazing we didn't have any mechanical problems at
all, because if we had we'd probably still be up there,'' Keys
said. ``But everything went really well.''
</P>
<P>
   The following day they made it to Fort McMurray, a mining town
famous for its oil sand and, Barton said, was one of the most
modern towns they visited. Much of the time, he said, they were
landing on gravel runways in sparsely populated areas, ``but you
could tell Fort McMurray has mining money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On July 6 they continued south, stopping for fuel in Lethbridge,
Alberta, and marvelling over the sea of cattle feed lots that
stretched to the horizon, Barton said.
</P>
<P>
   They'd been flying under clouds most of the trip, but the
weather began to clear as they got close to the border, Keys said,
and as they flew into Montana they were under blue skies again.
They stayed in Great Falls that night and the next day, after
stopping for fuel in Cody, Wyo., they flew back into Green River.
</P>
<P>
   They were glad to be home, proud of reaching their goal of
flying above the Arctic Circle, but experienced a little of the
letdown that commonly follows the end of a big trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get home you think, `Why? Why did I do this?' ''
Barton explained. ``At first it's a relief to be home, but then
it's almost like a letdown. You think, `What am I going to see new
tomorrow?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this was just so we'd have bragging rights,'' Keys said
with a laugh. ``To me, it is an accomplishment to have flown up
there, to see the midnight sun, and to do it safely.''
</P>
<P>
   Keys said he will return to the Arctic Circle, but next time
he'll go with his wife, Dell, who also is a pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm 76 years old,'' Barton said. ``This probably was my
last hurrah. It was pretty good, though. I can say I dipped my toe
in the Arctic Ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
