<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3547 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CHEAP-TRAVEL0806-COX     08-05 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEAP-TRAVEL0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hotel, motel, B&AMP;B: The difference is service
 &HT;    By Ray Marcano
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ I've received several e-mails recently about bed
and breakfasts and whether they hold any advantages over hotels and
motels. The quick, easy answer is: It depends on your taste, and to
some degree, your budget. What are the differences?
</P>
<P>
   _ Hotel: I use this term to describe a full-service hotel that
provides a vast array of amenities. The bellhop handles your
luggage, the concierge sets up dinner reservations, housekeeping is
available 24 hours a day, you can swim in the hotel pool and then
work out in the hotel exercise room. And you can expect to pay for
those conveniences. You'll most likely pay to park, which has
always infuriated me (You're already paying to stay at the hotel
and you have to pay extra for your car?). You're expected to tip
almost everyone who performs a service. If a bellhop takes your bag
out of your car to the front desk, that's a tip; if someone else
takes your bags to your room, that's another tip; if you have a few
hours between check-out and your flight, and store your bags at the
hotel, the person who writes your claim check expects a tip and the
person who gets them out of the room expects one, too. You'll get
room service, which means $10 eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Try this rule of thumb: If staying at a hotel, add 50 percent to
the room rate. That's what you can expect to pay for incidentals
and food if you eat at the hotel restaurants. For many travelers,
this is the only way they'll travel. Budget travelers, though, are
often surprised when they decide to treat themselves to a night at
a nice hotel and find the costs are more than they wanted to spend.
</P>
<P>
   _ Motels: They run the gamut from one-story, no-frills
accommodations in which you get a room and not much else, to
all-suites motels with a nice array of perks. The downside: If you
need extra pillows or towels, forget it because housekeeping closes
at night. If you have the midnight munchies you'll have to drive
somewhere to eat. Pool? Maybe, but it'll be outside. Personal
assistance? Beyond the front-desk person there is none. And, most
motels are away from downtowns. But there are clear advantages, and
the biggest one is price. While you can't find a good hotel for $69
to $79 a night, you can find a first-rate motel for that. Parking
is free and some of the chains offer free breakfast. That's why
budget-conscious travelers often choose this route
</P>
<P>
   _ Bed and breakfasts: They're neither hotel nor motel. You're
staying in someone's home. You get a room, some with private baths,
some without. You get breakfast, though you should always ask what
breakfast consists of. And you get something hotels and motels
can't offer _ an attentive host. Any good B&AMP;B understands the need
for a gracious host who will stay up at night and tell tales of the
area, talk about family and want to know something about their
guest. Staying at a good B&AMP;B is like staying at a cousin's house _
relaxed, friendly, charming. The cost of a night at a B&AMP;B generally
falls somewhere between a good motel and hotel, and may not even
have the amenities of a motel. Some B&AMP;Bs have no televisions or
radios, and the owners don't allow guests to come in after a
certain time (don't want to disturb the others, you know.) So B&AMP;Bs
are for a certain kind of vacation traveler who likes a more homey
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   How do you know a B&AMP;B is a good one? In many cases, you don't.
There is no independent rating system, so you don't know if a B&AMP;B
is a one-, two-, three- or four-star. So do extensive homework.
</P>
<P>
   Web site: www.ohiobba.com lists dozens of B&AMP;Bs. www.bbonline.com
has hundreds of B&AMP;Bs throughout the country. Both sites provide a
nice overview of the property and rates. Always call to make sure
the information is current.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER IS ENDING
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, summer is almost over _ at least in travel
terms. Labor Day, the last long summer weekend, is just around the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking of taking a trip and waiting for those great
last-minute Internet specials, beware. Many of those ``specials''
notices are already warning travelers that discount fares aren't
good the weekend of Sept. 1-3. In addition, you'll likely find
specials at hotels and car rental agencies skimpy as well.
</P>
<P>
   So what to do? If you don't need to travel that weekend, go a
week before or after. You'll probably have a longer list of
specials to choose from. You could always, of course, just pony up
the additional money.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
