<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3548 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CITY-CAMPFIRE-KIDS080     08-05 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITY-CAMPFIRE-KIDS0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Fire is Alive
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In all three rooms of a tiny vacant apartment at
a housing project, 20 young boys and girls are hard at work on math
and reading problems, scrawling on worksheets they've flattened
across floors, tables, chairs, even the bannister leading upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   When their work is done, the kids know the real fun will begin:
a chance to make necklaces, keychains and bracelets from the bead
kits that Camp Fire program director Leslie Barr has brought for
today's session.
</P>
<P>
   A steady stream of children affectionately besiege Barr and her
volunteer assistant, 18-year-old Sujata Bhat, turning in their
finished work or asking for help with a problem. Meanwhile,
toddlers from the neighborhood tumble through the door, wanting to
be part of the fun as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can see, we have tons of kids, and we need tons of
volunteers,'' Barr says. ``There is nothing for the kids in this
neighborhood to do. No parks, no recreation. This is it.''
</P>
<P>
   For baby boomers who remember the Camp Fire TV ads of their
youth _ little girls gathered round a campfire roasting wienies,
singing Indian songs and making earnest pledges _ this urban scene
seems a total disconnect.
</P>
<P>
   But today's Camp Fire Boys and Girls (boys were added in 1975)
are more likely to gather in a housing project than at a
campground, and more likely to learn the skills of surviving in the
urban jungle than in the great outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Youth development still is the goal of the 65-year-old Camp Fire
Council of the Greater Dayton Area, but its organizers want the
public, and especially its 600 local alumni of former leaders, to
know that its target audience has changed. In the past three to
four years, Camp Fire has begun to reach out to disadvantaged
children who need to be helped where they live, play, go to school
and worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to build on our past, and at the same time find a way
to serve the needs of under-served children today,'' said Linda
Blocher, executive director of the local Camp Fire council. ``But
the problem is, very few people even know about us.''
</P>
<P>
   With a full- and part-time staff of 16, a budget of just
$200,000 and a core of volunteers from senior centers, high schools
and the University of Dayton, the local council sponsors a variety
of programs aimed at promoting self-reliance and social
responsibility among disadvantaged kids ages 4 through 16.
</P>
<P>
   The outreach includes weekly after-school programs for children
ages 7 to 12, where they can find safety, games, field trips and
tutors to help with their homework; life skills classes for
previously homeless children and their parents; volunteer service
projects for children in kindergarten through sixth grade; a young
entrepreneur program in which adolescents start their own business
and sell their own products; self-reliance classes that include how
to survive as a latchkey child, resist peer pressure and avoid
alcohol and drugs; as well as classes in baby sitting and
kindergarten preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Jones, 8, says she never misses the weekly Camp Fire
program at her housing project in Lebanon. ``I like the games, and
we learn things,'' she said. ``We learned how to set the table, and
like last week, we were learning about bullies and stuff . . . You
just walk away from them. You don't talk to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Wells, the volunteer who heads the after-school program in
Lebanon, says the kids from the surrounding housing project know
each other so well they treat each other like siblings, which
includes a lot of infighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a `no put-down zone.' What does that mean?'' Wells
asked the eight kids putting together puzzles and playing board
games in the neighborhood center.
</P>
<P>
   ``No putting down people,'' answered Jason Romin, 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``No calling people names,'' added his brother Justin, 11.
</P>
<P>
   As the children play together peacefully, it's hard to imagine
that, earlier that morning, several parents had complained to Wells
that the same kids had been fighting at a neighborhood basketball
court. ``Right now they're having fun. They're learning to work
together _ cooperating,'' Wells said. ``It's just a matter of
getting them to follow through 24 hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Phillips, the youth program coordinator for Dayton Urban
Ministries, credits Camp Fire volunteer Mary Yaney with turning
around the ministries' after-school enrichment program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children's behaviors really have changed since (Camp Fire)
has been involved with the ministries, especially their attitude
toward music and different arts and crafts,'' Phillips said. ``When
I first came here two years ago, nobody wanted to do arts. They
didn't want to do anything. Now they can't wait to see Mary, and
they get all excited because she always has some interesting
activities for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The ministries' Camp Fire group last year won a first place in
arts and crafts at the Ohio State Fair, as well as the grand prize
in the fair's nature theme for its collection of leaves and
wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Fire has developed programs to meet the needs of children
of nearly all ages, including a Young Entrepreneurs program that
introduces kids ages 9 to 13 to the business world by having them
design, market and sell their own products.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the local Camp Fire council launched a biannual
newsletter to try to reach more of the 600 or so alumni in the
Greater Dayton area. Council leaders are hoping that the pleasant
memories of camping, after-school club meetings and role modeling
that they experienced will inspire them to join the organization in
its new mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need their support,'' said Janet Davis, head of the
organization's alumni committee. ``We have to re-educate them in
how we can help the inner-city child. . . . We don't want everybody
to dig into their pockets, but we would like their enthusiasm. We
want to rekindle the spirit that was there.''
</P>
<P>
   If alumni need any anyone to fan their enthusiasm, all they have
to do is talk to 18-year-old Bhat, who has volunteered her time to
the Camp Fire program at a Dayton housing project for the past
three years. The kids know and like her so well now they greet her
instantly with hugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's given me a whole new perspective about the way people
live in other parts of the city that I wasn't aware of at all,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, she plans to major in public policy and sociology
when she enters the University of Chicago this fall. ``It's really
given me a whole new direction in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
