<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shades of retro cool: Sunglasses take inspiration from '60s,
'70s
 &HT;    By Ginger McFarland
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shades of Jackie O. sunning herself on the
Mediterranean or dodging the paparazzi revisit us now that
large-lens sunglasses are back in vogue. Brands such as Gucci,
Prada and Armani have reached back into the eyewear archives and
reinterpreted these retro frames to make them look new again.
</P>
<P>
   ``With time, all styles repeat themselves,'' says Drew Meirow,
owner of Planet Eyewear in Atlanta. Meirow noted the most popular
styles are aviators, semi-rimless frames and large rectangle
frames.
</P>
<P>
   Menelik, 32, promotions and marketing director of downtown
nightclub Karma, is rarely seen not wearing one of his dozen pairs
of shades. This trendsetter has been sporting large lenses since
the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shades are part of my personality. I feel naked without
them,'' he said. ``It's easy to throw on a pair of retro lenses and
make a statement without having to wear an entire '70s outfit.''
</P>
<P>
   Menelik, a former fashion design student, added: ``There is a
resurgence of the retro vibe in the music industry, which is
closely tied to fashion now. People want to feel like they are
attached to that ('70s) time period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They reminded me of something old school,'' says Sean Bailey,
24, of Atlanta. He can be spotted wearing his large orange lenses
by Incognito in Little Five Points or clubbing it downtown, or
anywhere he wants to look cool. `` The teacher/artist ``throws 'em
on'' with casual clothing when it's sunny.
</P>
<P>
   Shop around and you'll find that there's a large-lens style
ideally suited to your face size and shape. Bigger may be better,
but no accessory should overwhelm your outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
