<HEADLINE>
IN SEX CRIMES, PROSECUTIONS CAN DEPEND ON A GAME OF CHANCE IN
HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT 8 and graphic are being sent to NYT
photo/graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One woman was attacked last spring in Central Park by
two strangers who beat and sexually abused her until she broke free
and ran to safety on Manhattan's West Side. The attackers were
convicted of aggravated sexual abuse and are serving long prison
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman was attacked last summer by a man who dragged her
under the Coney Island Boardwalk, where, according to her grand
jury testimony, he punched her and raped her and told her that ``he
was going to put me 6 feet under.'' This assailant, a serial sex
offender, secured a lenient plea bargain for attempted assault. He
will be eligible for a parole hearing in January.
</P>
<P>
   The drastically different outcomes of these similar cases were
the result of what prosecutors, physicians and victims' advocates
describe as a game of chance inside emergency rooms at New York
City hospitals. The first woman received a thorough examination
that documented evidence of the attack. The second woman did not.
</P>
<P>
   Years after forensic exams became a standard part of treatment
for victims of sex crimes, the level of competence in administering
the exams varies widely. Some victims get meticulous treatment.
Many do not. This uneven quality of care, experts say, can mean an
uneven quality of evidence with which to prosecute some of
society's most malevolent criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a crap shoot,'' said John Albert, a director at
Safe Horizon, an organization that assists crime victims in the
five boroughs. ``Depending on which hospital treats you, you can
either get care that is excellent, or you can get care that is
delinquent.''
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Gov. George Pataki plans to sign into law the Sexual
Assault Reform Act, which includes a provision directing the
Department of Health to develop more rape treatment programs like
the one at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center, which treated the
victim of the Central Park attack.
</P>
<P>
   This treatment model, known as a sexual assault examiner
program, provides every victim with immediate care, a private
examination area and a nurse or a doctor with special training in
forensic exams. It also encourages examiners to serve as witnesses
before grand juries and in trials, giving prosecutors leverage when
negotiating plea agreements with defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of these programs exist in the 73 hospitals with
emergency rooms in New York City, handling a small fraction of the
2,000 to 2,800 rapes reported in the city each year. Nationally,
about 300 of these centers are in service, treating as few as 2
percent of sex crime patients in the country each year, though
experts say the programs have been expanding each year since their
inception in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The precise plans for expanding the programs in New York, and
for paying for them, have not yet been made, state health officials
say. But Pataki and victims' advocates say the act gives New York a
chance to create a network of sophisticated treatment centers
throughout the city, bringing a measure of parity to the care and
attention that victims of sex crimes receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, emergency rooms too often lack the forensic
expertise to collect the evidence needed to convict sexual
predators,'' Pataki said. ``The advocates have been advocating, and
we think they are right, that we need to have three of these
special centers in each borough. Through the state Department of
Health, we are going to work with them to make that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, state health law has required emergency rooms to
examine survivors of sex crimes with rape kits _ a box of equipment
and sampling envelopes that standardizes the collection of evidence
_ approved by the state. But these exams are sometimes undermined,
experts say, by tensions between the medical needs in emergency
departments and the legal needs of the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The potential problems are many. Prosecutors and victims'
advocates tell of patients who have been subjected to long waits in
public seating areas, of untrained examiners botching the exams and
of physicians who have turned over evidence to the police but have
refused to cooperate further. ``I've had nightmare examples,'' said
Linda Fairstein, chief of the Manhattan sex crimes bureau.
</P>
<P>
   To offset these problems, sexual assault examiner programs rely
on cadres of nurses, midwives and doctors who are trained in
finding, handling and documenting forensic evidence. The examiners
then volunteer to be on call, reporting to emergency rooms to
perform the exams whenever a victim arrives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our examiners are only allowed to treat rape patients on their
days off,'' said Karen Reichert, the program's coordinator. ``The
idea is that when you are examining a rape patient, you have no
other duties and no other priorities, so all of your attention goes
to the victim.''
</P>
<P>
   The programs also provide victims with trained advocates who
stay with patients throughout each hospital visit and provide
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals and their representatives say that many emergency
departments without specially trained, on-call examiners can still
provide effective treatment, and that the overwhelming number of
patients receive competent exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are incredibly compassionate and they really want to
treat people in the right and appropriate ways,'' said Mary
Johnson, spokeswoman for Greater New York Hospital Association,
which represents 100 area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But the Boardwalk case, which was cited when state regulators
fined Coney Island Hospital $46,000 last month, illustrates that
when a hospital is unprepared, or protocols are not followed, the
quality of care can sink by a baffling degree.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Health's investigation found that the hospital
made the woman wait three hours for the exam and then lost her
underwear and vaginal swabs. It also found the hospital bungled two
tests for sexually transmitted diseases, did not ensure she
received a full birth-control prescription and failed to provide
complete care from social workers.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said that if the evidence had not been lost it
might have been used to secure a rape conviction against Anthony
Jones, a serial sex offender who attacked the woman the day after
his release from prison. Instead, prosecutors dropped a rape count
in exchange for Jones' guilty plea to the comparatively minor
offense. He was sentenced to two to four years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The handling of the Boardwalk case stands in sharp contrast to
the treatment of the woman attacked in Central Park, who released
her medical records to The New York Times on the condition that her
name and the names of her attackers not be published.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the victim arrived at the hospital at 8:05 a.m.
and was immediately led to a private examining room, where a
physician performed an initial assessment within 10 minutes. A
social worker arrived within 25 minutes. The examiner, Dr. Lorraine
Giordano, was at the victim's side by 9 a.m., having been paged to
work from home.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the emergency departments in almost all hospitals, the
rape treatment center at St. Luke's-Roosevelt is equipped with a
video camera with a magnifying lens called a colposcope, as well as
a Wood's lamp, which illuminates a victim with a purplish-blue
glow, allowing examiners to find drops or smudges of an attacker's
body fluids that can be swabbed and analyzed for DNA. These two
pieces of specialized equipment let examiners search victims for
evidence that can prove an attack occurred and, in some cases, they
can link a suspect to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   In the Central Park case, the assault was cut short when the
victim's dog bit one of the attackers, allowing her to escape. The
attackers left behind no DNA. But with the colposcope, Giordano was
able to find and photograph genital abrasions that were consistent
with sexual abuse, supporting the prosecutor's charge.
</P>
<P>
   One law enforcement authority said that after one of the
defendants was confronted with the contents of the medical file _
which included images detailing the injuries _ he pleaded guilty to
the maximum charge and accepted a 15-year prison sentence. Until
that point, he had denied any sexual abuse had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   How often sex crime victims receive this level of treatment is
not clear; prosecutors and hospitals say statistics have not been
compiled in New York. Dr. Linda Ledray, of Minneapolis, who has
studied the programs for the federal Department of Justice, said a
study in the Midwest found that prosecutors introduced 48 percent
more evidence in cases in which victims were treated in examiner
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The study's contention supports local prosecutors' anecdotes
about high quality evidence gathered from the examiners' work.
``The injuries these examiners identify can turn cases from a
he-said-she-said case into cases of rape,'' said Marjory Fisher,
chief of the special victims bureau in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, prosecutors complain only that the programs do not
handle enough of the caseload. In Brooklyn, for example, the only
forensic examiner program is at Long Island College Hospital in
Cobble Hill. It treated 66 of 823 rape cases in the borough last
year. ``The program is great,'' said Julie Schwartz, deputy chief
of the Brooklyn sex crimes bureau. ``We just can't get as many
cases into it as we would like.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sexual Assault Reform Act requires the state to start
additional programs during 2001 and to develop standards for
supervising them. John Signor, a spokesman for the Department of
Health, said the department was working with hospitals to determine
which emergency rooms would become part of the proposed network.
</P>
<P>
   Many issues remain unresolved, including finding a formula for
underwriting the training and logistics required to develop new
programs, and addressing the concerns of ambulance services about
tying up crews on longer drives if they are required to bring all
sex crime victims to the designated centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really trying to figure out how to do this,'' said
Harriet Lessel, executive director of the New York City Alliance
Against Sexual Assault, which lobbied for the passage of the act
and is now assisting the Department of Health. ``All hospitals
cannot start or maintain these programs. They are very complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, hospital representatives and state health officials
say that some hospitals have expressed a willingness to take part.
State health officials and the governor would not discuss estimates
of the cost, but Pataki said he expected that the administration
would provide some of the money to expand the centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex predators are very often serial predators, and if we can
catch them and stop them after the first attack, we can prevent
them from having more victims,'' the governor said. ``You can't put
a price on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
