u p BC-BUSH-SPEECH-CLINTON-N     08-05 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SPEECH-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE ACCUSES BUSH OF STEALING CLINTON'S ORATORY
</HEADLINE>
  By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ White House aides grumbled Saturday that Gov.
George W. Bush's acceptance speech at the Republican National
Convention had been presidential _ too presidential, actually, as
they accused Bush of stealing not only President Clinton's ideas,
but his words as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a tone of pique colored with a tinge of glee, the aides said
they had come up with nine examples from Bush's convention speech
and other recent speeches that Clinton had uttered first. The list
may be significant chiefly because it shows the Clinton camp's
discomfort at Bush's infiltration of the president's rhetorical
territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters should be wary of someone who tries to portray others'
ideas as their own,'' said the White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart added: ``There's a fine line between flattery and
plagiarism. If he hasn't crossed it, he's deep in no man's land.''
</P>
<P>
   The list included these examples:
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicare does more than meet the needs of the elderly; it
reflects the values of our society,'' Bush told cheering delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicare is more than just a program; it reflects our
values,'' Clinton had said in 1997, remarks recalled this week by
White House aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will use these good times for great goals,'' Bush said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us take our long look ahead and set great goals for our
nation,'' Clinton said during his State of the Union address in
January.
</P>
<P>
   The similar language may be coincidental, but it fits into a
deliberate strategy on the part of the Bush campaign to blur some
of the traditional differences between the parties. The convention
itself reflected that approach as Republicans highlighted a
racially diverse cast and studiously steered clear of divisive
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Clinton himself has made the appropriation of others'
ideas a hallmark of his administration, regularly seizing
Republican initiatives that he deems worthy. But that was forgotten
Saturday as some aides to Clinton groused about Bush's
``Clintonian'' text.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart pointed out that Bush, during a June 30 campaign stop,
had said, ``How a country handles its moment of prosperity and
opportunity is just as stern a test of our vision, our judgment,
and our character as how we handle adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton utters quite similar words on a regular basis. ``How a
country deals with its prosperity is at least as big a test of its
judgment and its character as how a country deals with adversity,''
Clinton said on June 24 during a speech in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Bush campaign, Ray Sullivan, criticized as
``silly and beneath the dignity of the White House'' the claim of
political plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that taxpayer-funded White House aides are spending
so much time on Governor Bush's speech shows how desperate and
political the Clinton-Gore team really is,'' he said. ``The truth
is that both Bill Clinton and Al Gore have made careers of
reinventing themselves and claiming credit for other people's
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, the communications director for the Bush campaign,
said, ``Let me assure the president, with all due respect, he is
not our model for speechmaking, fund raising, or conduct in
office.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although there were a few dead ringers, some supposed
similarities discovered by White House aides did not appear all
that similar.
</P>
<P>
   In his convention speech, Bush recalled an artist friend from El
Paso, Tom Lea, who lives on a mountainside. ``It's the sunrise
side, not the sunset side,'' Bush said. ``It is the side to see the
day that is coming, not to see the day that has gone. Americans
live on the sunrise side of the mountain. The night is passing, and
we're ready for the day to come.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Clinton spoke of mountains, as well. ``We should be
filled with awe and joy at what lies over the horizon,'' he said,
declaring that the country stands ``on the mountaintop of a new
millennium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
