u p BC-GOP-MODERATION-NYT &LR;      08-05 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MODERATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: THIS TIME, A CANDIDATE PROJECTS HIS OWN IMAGE OF
MODERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The meeting of the National Black Republican
Leadership Caucus should have ranked high on the A-list of
happenings at the new Party of Inclusion's convention. The featured
politician was Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey, a moderate from
the political center, where Gov. George W. Bush of Texas supposedly
wants to herd the Grand Old Elephants.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the joint would be jammed, upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   But fewer than 30 black Republicans _ and not many others _
gathered in the basement auditorium of the African-American Museum
here on Tuesday to listen to Whitman. The telegenic tax cutter and
supporter of abortion rights tried hard to rally the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry she's not our vice-presidential candidate,'' said
Doris Oliveira, a black delegate from Tuskegee, Ala. ``But we would
have lost the South. They were going to walk out of the convention
if Bush had chosen someone who supports a woman's right to choose.
Our party's gotten so conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush lavishly embraced the rhetoric and style of
moderate Northeastern Republicans, few of those moderates made it
to center stage. At the convention four years ago the region's
Republican governors were leading men and women, helping in the
fruitless task of softening the harsh image of the party's nominee,
Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the candidate softened himself. It has been widely
noted that Bush kept the party's conservative elements out of the
glare of the convention, but he kept moderates largely out of sight
as well. His own language and tone did the job the moderates did
for Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman was a co-chairwoman for Dole's convention, along with
none other than Bush. Gov. George Pataki of New York gave a speech
nominating Jack Kemp as vice president, and Gov. John G. Rowland of
Connecticut also spoke. Susan Molinari of Staten Island, N.Y., then
a rising Republican in the House of Representatives, gave the
keynote address. This year, only Pataki had a prominent role, but
it was to read a scripted tribute to the three living Republican
former presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The showcasing of moderate governors that year was a bit of a
head fake. Dole had little intention of shaping the party in their
image. Bush managed to hit moderate chords, even as he reassured
many conservatives that he was their man, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone said to me today, `Governor Bush sounded like a George
Pataki last night with the moderate message he was pushing out,'''
Daniel Stewart, the mayor of Plattsburgh, N.Y., and a convention
delegate, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   With the theme of ``Leave No Child Behind,'' and people of all
races turning the convention stage into Bush's Neighborhood, and
lines like ``We Shall Overcome'' in his speech, Bush left moderates
feeling as if he had unleashed the party's inner Connecticut
Yankee. It was easier for them to swallow conservative platform
planks and his stands against gun control and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, New York state's first openly gay mayor, disagrees with
Bush on abortion and is upset with antigay language in the party's
platform. But in Bush he hears the tenor of the Republican Party he
knew growing up in New England and living in New York.
</P>
<P>
   He was buoyed by the appearance of the party's first openly gay
convention speaker, even if he spoke about international trade.
Sure, some Texas delegates held a silent prayer protest while he
spoke, but other Texans applauded. And a New York delegate waving a
gay pride flag on the convention floor drew a thumbs up sign from
another delegate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just see it as progress,'' Stewart said, ``slow progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The pro-choice moderates expressed delight with the convention,
even if most were sidelined. Unlike the 1996 convention, ``there
aren't the hard edges,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, among the losers in the vice-presidential sweepstakes to
the far more conservative Dick Cheney, said Bush replaced ``the
angry face of our party'' symbolized by strident congressional
Republicans, with the ``positive, problem-solving wing of the
party'' dominated by Republican governors.
</P>
<P>
   By prompting a blend of compassion and conservatism, said
William Kristol, editor of the conservative Weekly Standard, ``Bush
has balanced his own ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless of course it's another head fake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
