<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PLANS TOUR OF KEY STATES BEFORE CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES DAO with KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the days leading to the Democratic National
Convention, Vice President Al Gore plans to tour several important
battleground states, from Georgia to Pennsylvania to Michigan,
hammering at the emerging themes of his campaign, and emphasizing
that the presidential election will be about substance versus flash
and new ideas against old, his aides said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president will focus on a different issue each day,
including welfare, Social Security, health care and the economy,
seeking to draw sharp differences in style and policy with his
Republican rival, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tour will offer a striking contrast to the Bush
campaign's approach of image rather than issues, photo-ops rather
than substance,'' Gore's press secretary, Chris Lehane, said. ``It
will contrast Al Gore's agenda for working families with the Bush
agenda to benefit the privileged few and special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Going the Distance Tour,'' as the Gore campaign has dubbed
it, will begin on Tuesday in Nashville, Tenn., when the vice
president will appear for the first time with his running mate. It
will end on Tuesday, Aug. 15, in Michigan, when Gore stands
shoulder-to-shoulder with President Clinton for a symbolic passing
of the party's leadership torch.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will arrive at the convention in Los Angeles the next day,
and will accept the party's nomination on the night of Thursday,
Aug. 17. Clinton is scheduled to address the convention on Monday
night and then leave the next day, effectively clearing the stage
for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has previewed many of the themes he plans to
emphasize during his tour in speeches over the past two days. The
tour is also intended to highlight Gore's biography, and in remarks
on Saturday before the National Association of Police Organizations
in Washington, he talked extensively about his time as an Army
reporter in Vietnam and as a police reporter for The Nashville
Tennessean newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot and gained a tremendous respect for what law
enforcement officers do every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the group that he would push for ``common sense'' laws
to keep firearms out of the hands of children and criminals. He
noted that in Congress, he had supported bills banning so-called
cop-killer bullets and plastic guns. In doing that, he drew an
implicit contrast with Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney, who voted
against both bills while a congressman from Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``First time somebody shows me a deer in a Kevlar vest, I'll
reconsider that opinion,'' Gore said of the cop-killer bullet bill.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president touted the administration's efforts to help
police departments hire 100,000 new officers, and said he would
push for money to hire 50,000 more. He also said he would fight to
allow officers to carry their weapons while off-duty and for a
constitutional amendment guaranteeing victims the right to be heard
at criminal proceedings involving their attackers.
</P>
<P>
   The police group, which endorsed the Clinton-Gore ticket in
1996, has not decided whom to support this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney kept up their attacks on the Democrats on
Saturday as they continued a three-day trip, mostly by train,
through pivotal states in the Midwest. They started Saturday
morning in Pontiac, Mich., and made stops for rallies along the way
to Kalamazoo. Large, enthusiastic crowds greeted them, chanting
``No more Gore! No more Gore!''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney vowed to grant them that wish and made frequent
reference, in Bush's words, to the ``squandered opportunity'' of
the last eight years of prosperity. Bush pointedly laid the blame
not just on Clinton but on ``the Clinton-Gore administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also tied Gore to the president's veto of a bill to
eliminate the so-called marriage penalty tax, saying at a rally in
Durand, Mich., that Gore ``stands on the side of big government,''
not on the side of working families.  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &QL;
<P>
   After announcing his vice presidential pick in Nashville on
Tuesday, Gore will travel on Wednesday with his running mate to
Carthage, Tenn., Gore's home town. They will hold a town hall
meeting at the Carthage elementary school with about 150 Tennessee
residents, many of whom will reminisce about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   From there, they will travel to the home state of the vice
presidential candidate. Speculation is narrowing to three
Democratic senators _ John Kerry of Massachusetts, John Edwards of
North Carolina and Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gore and his running mate will go to Atlanta for a
meeting with Southern governors and a discussion on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, it is on to the Philadelphia suburbs for an event
with working women. On Saturday, they will travel to western
Pennsylvania and the girlhood home of the late Rachel Carson, the
environmental advocate and author of ``Silent Spring,'' a book that
Gore says strongly influenced him.
</P>
<P>
   Next Sunday, Gore plans to discuss children's health care at
University Hospital in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Aug. 14, the day the Democratic convention opens,
Gore will be in Independence, Mo., home of Harry S. Truman, where
he will discuss issues involving senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, will
speak at the convention. Gore will meet Clinton on Tuesday at an
as-yet-undesignated spot in Michigan, a crucial swing state, where
they will showcase the nation's economic expansion and try to
highlight Gore's role in the prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Gore will fly to Los Angeles, where his running
mate will be nominated. Thursday night, Gore gives his acceptance
speech and flies out that night to the Midwest, where he will begin
a four-day boat trip across the Great Lakes and down the
Mississippi River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
