<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-SERIAL-KILLER-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CLEARED BY DNA TESTS LED POLICE TO MURDER SUSPECT
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An investigator credited DNA science Saturday with
helping the police solve the murders of six women in Brooklyn. Not
only did it ultimately link a homeless man to the crimes, he said,
but it also cleared another homeless man in the case _ a man who
then befriended a detective and helped find the murder suspect.
</P>
<P>
   More than a week ago, the homeless man who was cleared by DNA
tests led detectives from the Brooklyn North Homicide Task Force to
focus on a 5-foot-3-inch panhandler, Vincent Johnson, 31, the
investigator said. And after DNA from Johnson came back with a
match Thursday night, the other man also helped the police track
the suspect down, spotting him Friday on a Brooklyn street wearing
a bright orange shirt. The man called the police and followed
Johnson until they arrived and arrested him, the investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, detectives were still questioning Johnson,
and police officials said he would be charged in the strangulation
killings in the Williamsburg and Bedford-Stuyvesant sections of
Brooklyn. The police said Johnson, a drug abuser who sometimes
spent time at the Glenwood hotel on Broadway in Williamsburg,
stalked and strangled the six women, leaving their bound bodies
where he killed them.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the victims were found on rooftops in Williamsburg and
one in a vacant lot there. Two others were found in apartments in
Bedford-Stuyvesant and one in a utility room under the Williamsburg
Bridge, where Johnson once lived on a cot. Most of the women had
been arrested in the past on prostitution or drug charges, police
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The police came across the homeless man who helped them during
the course of the investigation when detectives took DNA samples
from 25 to 30 suspects, officials said. The samples failed to match
the DNA that the killer had left behind, said one investigator
familiar with the tests. Among those cleared was a man who the
police had been told hung out with prostitutes in the area and had
argued with one of them, an investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   But after the test showed he was not the killer, he ended up
befriending a detective working on the case, Steven Feely, and told
him about another homeless man with whom he often smoked crack, a
man who talked frequently about tying up women and having sex with
them, the investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   The homeless man who aided the police said in an interview
Saturday that he had known Johnson for about three months and
frequently smoked crack with him. ``He'd point out girls all the
time and say, `I want that girl,''' said the homeless man, who is
42 and asked that his name not be used. ``He'd gesture with his
hands, and say how we could take them up the hill, tie the girls'
arms behind their backs, duct tape their mouths so they wouldn't
scream'' and have sex with them. ``He told me, `You could leave if
you don't want to do that.' And I thought to myself, `You are a
sick, sick maniac.'''
</P>
<P>
   The man, who is from Brooklyn and recently served a prison term
for a drug offense, said that he once talked with Johnson about how
there were a lot of police officers in an area near Marcy Avenue,
where two of the bodies were found. He said Johnson told him he had
had sex with one of the dead women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great, I've done a good job,'' he said of his help to
the police. The police said that when they brought Johnson in for
questioning last week, he refused to provide a DNA sample and said
he did not know any of the slain women, the investigator said. But
one of the detectives who brought him in remembered that he had
spat on the street outside. The detective warned him, as they went
into the station house, that he should not spit inside, and Johnson
explained that he had tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   But detectives were able to take a saliva sample from where
Johnson spat, and by Thursday night, the results showed that his
DNA matched DNA found on four of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Johnson used to hang around a methadone clinic
on the Lower East Side of Manhattan where two of the dead women had
sought treatment and a single room occupancy hotel on West 92nd
Street in Manhattan. A security guard there who would not give her
name said Johnson's mother lived at the hotel until she died seven
years ago from cancer. The guard said Johnson visited infrequently,
usually to get money.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The most recent victim was Patricia Sullivan, 48, who was found
strangled with her sneaker laces on June 22 in a vacant lot on
Marcy Avenue. Four months earlier, in February, firefighters
responding to a rubbish fire in a large utility storage room
underneath the Williamsburg Bridge approach ramp found the
decomposed body of a woman. Detectives believe it was Laura G.
Nusser, 43.
</P>
<P>
   They later learned that Johnson had once lived in the room on a
cot and that Nusser was last seen with him in the area. She had
been strangled with an electrical cord. The police are unsure when
she was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The first victim was Vivian Caraballo, 26, whose body was found
on Aug. 26, 1999, in the elevator room on the roof of 237 S. Second
St. in Williamsburg. She had been strangled with a piece of cloth.
Less than a month later, on Sept. 16, the body of Joanna Feliciano,
35, was found on the roof of 171 S. Fourth St.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Tucker, 21, was found dead inside her apartment on Park
Avenue in Bedford-Stuyvesant on Sept. 25, 1999. She had been
strangled with the drawstring from her pants. Katrina Niles, 34,
was found on Oct. 4, 1999, in her Marcy Avenue apartment. She had
been strangled with electrical cord and her throat was slashed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
