u a BC-SERIAL-KILLER-NEIGHBO     08-05 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-NEIGHBORHOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARREST IN BROOKLYN SLAYINGS CALMS NEIGHBORHOODS
</HEADLINE>
  (With DNA-SERIAL-KILLER)  
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many residents of a small section of northern
Brooklyn expressed relief Saturday after word spread that the
police had arrested a suspect in six strangulation and slashing
murders that occurred over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy they got him; I feel more safe now,'' said Stephanie
Robles, 16, who was walking with her mother, Maria Martinez, 54, on
South Eighth Street.
</P>
<P>
   When a possible connection between the first four murders _ all
brutal strangulations _ was reported last October, it stirred fears
around the blocks where the crimes occurred in Williamsburg and in
nearby Bedford-Stuyvesant.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said that many black and Hispanic women in the two
neighborhoods stopped walking alone at night.
</P>
<P>
   Marrin Rodriguez, a volunteer at El Puente, a civic group in
Williamsburg, said neighborhood leaders tried to calm fears after
the slayings. ``It was not like he was going to kill 20 people
without being caught,'' Rodriguez said. ``But they were scared.
After all, he was beating women, choking them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said the idea that the earlier victims had been
involved in risky lifestyles _ drugs or prostitution _ did not help
allay concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in the neighborhoods said they did not fear the
presence of a serial killer because they did not fit the profile of
those four victims, who were believed to have been prostitutes. ``I
never felt threatened,'' because the first victims were all
prostitutes, said Jeannie Bartel, who has lived in the area for
decades. ``It was like it was something that happened to another
neighborhood. It was almost like TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Madison Rink, 33, who is white, echoed Bartel's lack of fear,
but gave another reason. ``In some strange way there's a sense of
relief because I knew there was a certain demographic of the women
being targeted,'' who were all black or Hispanic, she said. ``And
with that sense of relief, there is guilt for those feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   But to many others, the suspected serial killer had grown to
mythical proportions as a predator of the night from whom no one
was safe.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Cruz, 22, who lives on South Third Street, between the
sites of two of the slayings, said she feared that the killer would
``just keep killing all the people.''
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety that began to grow last October increased in
February, and again in June, when the bodies of two more women were
found.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, neighbors _ to varying degrees _ said they were
relieved that the police had arrested Vincent Johnson, the man they
called the serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   The police say that the suspect's killing field stretched from
South Second Street in Williamsburg to Bedford-Stuyvesant's Marcy
Houses.
</P>
<P>
   The two neighborhoods where the killings occurred, separated
from each other by the Brooklyn-Queens Expressway, have been the
sites of considerable improvements in recent years, residents said,
but while parks and streets are cleaner, they remain havens for
drug dealing and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   The improvements added to the shock that accompanied the news of
the killings, residents said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel safer now. It was like he could kill anybody he wanted
to kill,'' said Paula Lopez, who lives in a building on
Williamsburg's South Third Street, near where two of the victims
were found strangled on rooftops. But, she added, echoing many
others, ``I still don't feel completely safe. There's too much
drugs, too many drug dealers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
