<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SHARED-LISTINGS-REAL-     08-05 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARED-LISTINGS-REAL-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE BROKERS DOT-COMMED INTO COOPERATING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly three decades ago, real estate agents across
the United States began to make life easier for home buyers by
sharing listings. Buyers visited just one broker, who could tell
them about everything on the market, even properties represented by
other brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The holdout was Manhattan, where real estate was handled the
old-fashioned way: Brokers jealously guarded their listings to
avoid having to split their commissions with rival brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Manhattan saw the light. The borough's three largest
brokerage firms _ Corcoran Group, Douglas Elliman and Halstead
Property Co. _ announced they were creating a database that would
place their combined listings on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers, brokerage-firm executives and academics say the
companies are acknowledging sweeping changes in technology,
consumer demands and financial realities.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan brokers had contended that the complex nature of the
co-op market _ having to deal with board approvals and
sensibilities toward privacy _ justified keeping listings private.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manhattan was always considered special and different, and
just because it worked somewhere else did not mean it would work
here,'' Sharon Baum, a top broker at Corcoran, said while taking a
break from shuttling clients around in her Rolls-Royce with ``SOLD
1'' license plates. ``To know how to deal with the boards, to know
people on the boards and how to get your clients in _ it was a real
art.''
</P>
<P>
   But Baum and other brokers admitted that agents citywide were
less concerned about giving sellers the greatest possible exposure
than they were about representing both sellers and buyers and not
having to split commissions with other agents.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Durkin, the new chief operating officer at Corcoran, said
that ``technology has clearly upstaged the helmet-haired,
blue-blooded, Kelly-bag-swinging real estate agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Patton, the executive director of the Real Estate
Institute at New York University, said that these days buyers
expected to be able to go to one place for all listings. And, he
said, several Internet companies _ like mlx.com and nyrealty.com _
entered the market to provide such a compilation.
</P>
<P>
   Patton, a former president of the Real Estate Board of New York,
said the brokerage firms responded by considering buying the online
companies. They also began placing listings on their own Web sites.
But their sites did not get as many hits as the more comprehensive
sites, which companies like Goldman Sachs began to explore
investing in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest fear was that some third-party with deep pockets
was going to come in, collect all of our listings and take our
business away,'' Durkin said.
</P>
<P>
   And smaller brokerage firms had long pushed for sharing so they
could offer clients the thousands of listings from the big
brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   The ice began to melt. About nine months ago, senior executives
at Douglas Elliman and Corcoran began discussing the creation of a
multiple listing service like those in other places across the
nation. Halstead joined the discussions in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The joint database is seen as a way to share the cost of
upgrading technology and to virtually eliminate the unit at each
company that compiles other firms' listings, a system called
co-broking, where brokerage companies can choose to disclose
information. The firms also hope that the database will eventually
be the best place to go for home listings, perhaps allowing them to
cut newspaper classified ads.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the announcement last week, the firms said that they were
inviting each brokerage firm in New York to participate. The
brokers in the system will have to post almost all their listings
to the shared database within 24 hours or face fines (amounts have
not been determined). The only exception will be homes of sellers
who request that the listing not be made available to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   One real estate industry official involved in the negotiations
said it ``took a lot of courage,'' because the firms were upsetting
some of their own brokers and because the firms knew that a joint
multiple listing Web site would ``cannibalize'' their own dot-com
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The firms are near a deal with California's homeseekers.com,
which put the first multiple listing service online, to create the
New York City system. They hope to have it running by Jan. 1. So
far, 30 brokerage firms, including William B. May Co. and Bellmark
Realty, have signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the online listing services in the city are girding
for competition. One, nyrealty.com, is about to change its name to
cityrealty.com and launch a site that will allow transactions
online. Daniel Levy, president of nyrealty.com, said, ``Everyone is
realizing that the Internet is affecting the real estate business,
just like it is impacting every other form of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice Mason, a prominent independent broker in Manhattan, said
the shared listings could have a pleasant side effect: collegial
brokers. She recalled when ``people would meet a client across the
street _ they would be afraid to meet them in the doorway _ because
other brokers would see them and think they had a new listing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
