<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE06-1STLD-COX     08-05 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE06-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE'S STRATEGY: FIGHT THE ``RUSTED WAYS'' OF OLD GUARD
 &HT;    Eds: Updates beginning in graf 6 with plans for Gore, Clinton
travel in Midwest; other editing throughout.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that the Republican National Convention is
history, Vice President Al Gore needs to counter its effects in two
main ways: Deliver an acceptance speech at the Democratic
convention that counters the style and substance of George W.
Bush's, and choose a running mate who compares well with Dick
Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the campaign will try to reinforce Gore's
contention that Bush, the son of former President Bush, and Cheney,
who served as defense secretary in the elder Bush's cabinet,
represent ``the old guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his first campaign appearance after the GOP convention
ended, vowed to fight ``the rusted ways of the old guard.'' He told
3,400 union firefighters in Chicago on Friday that he would battle
``the big interests'' and ``powerful forces lined up against''
working families.
</P>
<P>
   And campaign spokesman Chris Lehane said Gore's choice as
running mate will be someone who ``represents the future and not
the old guard like Bush's choice'' of Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reversing Bush's lead in the polls _ 19 percent
in the bipartisan Voter.com-Battleground survey taken immediately
after the convention _ Gore must step out of the shadow of Bill
Clinton, who is spoken of by the Bush-Cheney campaign as if he were
Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The most symbolic act of separation will take place Aug. 15 in
Michigan, where the two will hold a joint rally one day after
Clinton addresses the Democratic National Convention in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the handing of the baton,'' Lehane said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign announced the event as part of a seven-day ``Going
the Distance'' tour that will take Gore from his family home in
Carthage, Tenn., to Los Angeles to accept his party's presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   From Carthage, Gore will travel to Atlanta, a state that has
become more competitive for him now that there is a Senate race
featuring a popular former Democratic governor, Zell Miller, to
fill the term of Paul Coverdell, who died last month of a cerebral
hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also will visit the fiercely contested Midwestern states of
Pennsylvania, Ohio, Missouri and Michigan, highlighting favorite
issues _ welfare reform, targeted tax cuts, the environment, health
care and retirement security _ before arriving in Los Angeles on
Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Gore strategists see the Aug. 17 acceptance speech as the time
that the vice president becomes his own person, politically.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Friday he would offer ``a new vision for the future''
in his acceptance speech, which he says he is writing himself.
``I'll be talking about the new heights America can reach if we
stay on the right track and make the right choices today,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been in public office for nearly a quarter of a
century, Gore wants to use his acceptance speech in much the way
that Bush did his _ to introduce himself to American voters who are
just beginning to pay attention to the presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the American people know him particularly
well,'' said Gore media adviser Bob Shrum.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the firefighters that he wants the American people
``to know me for who I am.'' And in an interview with CNN, he said,
``I'm running on who I am. I'm running as my own man.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is scheduled to disclose his choice of a running mate
Tuesday in Nashville. The two will then campaign together nonstop
en route to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Gore family and his most senior advisers know whom the
vice president regards as the best candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation on the six people Gore listed last week as top
candidates has centered mostly on Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts,
who appeals to younger generations and is popular with the liberal
wing of the party.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has tried to add drama to the vice presidential
selection process by floating the idea of a ``wild card''
possibility, someone who has not been mentioned often in press
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's mention of a ``wild card'' caused considerable attention
to fall on former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Gore's lone
challenger for the Democratic presidential nomination this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Rendell, general chairman of the Democratic National
Committee and a former mayor of Philadelphia, spent much of the
week of the GOP convention in his home town promoting Bradley. Gore
strategists in Nashville spoke glowingly of the amicable meeting
Gore and Bradley had in Wisconsin last month, when Bradley
announced his endorsement of his former rival. And Bradley is a
native of Missouri, one of the key states the ticket will be
visiting on its way to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   The other names listed by Gore include Sens. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut, Evan Bayh of Indiana and John Edwards of North
Carolina. But Bayh and Edwards, both first-term senators, may be
seen as lacking the experience needed to step into the presidency
if necessary. Choosing Lieberman, whose state has a Republican
governor, would cost the Democrats one seat in a closely fought
battle for control of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri Gov. Jeanne
Shaheen of New Hampshire round out the list, but both have insisted
they do not want the job.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
