u a BC-NY-NILE-OUTBREAK-NYT     08-05 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NILE-OUTBREAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATEN ISLAND BECOMES CENTER OF THE WEST NILE VIRUS BATTLE
</HEADLINE>
     c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Concern about the outbreak of West Nile virus has now
shifted to Staten Island, where the first human case of the disease
in the country this year has been reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Nile problem is primarily a Staten Island problem,''
the borough president, Guy Molinari, said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 31 infected birds found in New York City, 26 were on
Staten Island, said John Gadd, a New York City Health Department
spokesman. Of three pools found to have infected mosquitoes, one
was in Central Park, and two were in Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of May, Staten Island University Hospital has
treated 13 patients with symptoms that could have come from the
virus, but only one case, an elderly man's, was confirmed, said
Brian Morris, a hospital spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Staten Island man, 78, was the first person in the United
States to contract the virus this season. The man, whose name was
not released, has returned home from the hospital. At his sickest,
the man had a temperature of 104.7, a stiff neck and mental
confusion, Morris said. City and state officials began spraying
areas in and around the city with the pesticide malathion last
month when two dead crows on Staten Island were found to be
infected with the virus. ``Right now we are the epicenter of the
virus, and we expect it to accelerate in the next three to four
weeks. It is peak season now,'' Molinari said. ``In the second half
of the summer, we can expect incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem, he said, is that Staten Island has many wetlands,
creeks and tributaries, which are not easily reached by spraying
carried out from the road.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile virus, which is transmitted to humans by mosquitoes,
can cause flu-like symptoms and, at its most dangerous stages,
encephalitis, a potentially fatal brain inflammation. It has spread
into New York state and Massachusetts in birds that have been
bitten by infected mosquitoes. Children, people with weakened
immune systems and the elderly are most susceptible to the disease,
though not everyone in those categories who is bitten by an
infected mosquito will develop symptoms, according to the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3599 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CHILD-LABOR-LAWS-ART-     08-05 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-LABOR-LAWS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHERITON, Va.: much money. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His journey to the United States was grueling. After Herman was
smuggled into Arizona, the smugglers stuffed him, his brother and
30 others into the back of a truck that carried them to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took 48 hours, and we didn't have anything to eat,'' said
Herman, who owes the smugglers $1,850. ``It was very hot. There was
no water. Some people fainted. We were very weak when we got
here.''
</P>
<P>
   For a recent 60-hour week, he received a $240 check. That
translates to $4 an hour, but his managers said he received the
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security and other deductions were taken out, his boss
said, but many farm workers wonder if their bosses pocket the
deductions.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, poverty drives the two largest groups of child farm
workers _ those like Herman who come from other countries and those
like Jose Arispe, born in Texas but compelled to work because his
father makes less than $10,000 a year doing farm work. On average,
the adult farm worker earns less than $7,500 a year, partly because
many find work for only eight months a year. Their incomes are cut
back further because federal laws do not require that farm workers
receive time-and-a-half pay when they work more than 40 hours a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Farm workers' advocates say growers are happy to hire these
youngsters. But many farmers say they prefer not to hire young
workers but are forced to because of a labor shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farmers' view is that workers under age 18 lack maturity
and are not particularly productive workers, and they do things
that are foolish and dangerous, so you prefer not to have them
around the farm,'' said Bryan Little of the American Farm Bureau
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   When the Fair Labor Standards Act was enacted in 1938, it set
more lenient standards for children doing farm work than
nonagricultural work, largely because farm work was seen as
wholesome and family-oriented. Agriculture has changed immensely
since then with the advent of huge corporate farms and of a network
of more than a million seasonal and migrant workers, many of them
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Children's advocacy groups say the laws need to be changed.
``Farm-working juveniles have second-class status _ they enjoy
fewer rights than their nonfarm-working peers, and they are
exploited while the government looks the other way,'' the Human
Rights Watch report said.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser, of the Labor Department, said the government was
increasing its investigations into improper use of child farm
workers. Last year it cited 46 farms for violations involving 102
minors. There are 1.9 million farms in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The government is spending more for day care centers for young
migrant children, and for migrant teen-agers, it is financing
special programs, including summer schools, to keep them from
dropping out. But all this may not be enough to keep Jose Arispe in
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not doing well in school,'' said Jose's mother,
Elizabeth. ``He wants to quit school. But I don't think that's a
good idea. But he said he needs to work and contribute money to the
family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0180 </DOCNO>
