<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 08/05/00. Database in
Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 213-237-4577
or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make individual
purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Aug. 5, 2000 -- NY-STORE-CAFE-2 -- ABC
Carpet and Home Warehouse Outlet in the Bronx has a flagship store on
Fifth Avenue in Manhattan. Customer after customer notes that it is
nothing like a typical factory outlet. The goods are artfully
displayed, there is no dust, and salespeople are willing to serve.
Employees carrying an Oriental carpet off the floor to prepare it for
shipment. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Aug. 5, 2000 -- NY-STORE-CAFE-1 -- ABC
Carpet and Home Warehouse Outlet in the Bronx has a flagship store on
Fifth Avenue in Manhattan. Customer after customer notes that it is
nothing like a typical factory outlet. The goods are artfully
displayed, there is no dust, and salespeople are willing to serve.
The cafe at the ABC warehouse looks like a model room, but the family
waiting for lunch are real people. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Aug. 5, 2000 -- NY-RAPE-FORENSICS --
Forensic exams have become a standard part of treatment for victims
of sex crimes. Some victims get meticulous treatment, while many do
not. This uneven quality of care, experts say, can mean an uneven
quality of evidence with which to prosecute some of society's most
malevolent criminals. Dr. Lorraine Giordano, a sexual assault
examiner at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center, found medical
evidence that helped lead to the convictions of two men in a Central
Park attack last spring. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Aug. 5, 2000 -- PERFECT-STORM -- Portrayed
by Sebastian Junger in his phenomenal best-seller "The Perfect Storm"
as a strange introvert with a fondness for the bottle, Ray Leonard
has now been skewered both in print and by Hollywood. As this
official photograph taken from a Coast Guard helicopter shows, heavy
waves battered Leonard and his vessel in 1991, and "The Perfect
Storm" battered his image. (U.S. Coast Guard/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 5, 2000 -- OBIT-DENHOF-2 -- Miki
Denhoff, one of the first women to be the art director of a magazine
died on Wednesday at her home in East Hampton, N.Y. She was 88. Ms.
Denhoff with her boss and collaborator, Alexander Liberman, the
executive art director of Conde Nast. Ms. Denhof "designed in an
intellectual way," a former colleague said. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Aug. 5, 2000 -- OBIT-DENHOF-1 -- Miki
Denhoff, one of the first women to be the art director of a magazine
died on Wednesday at her home in East Hampton, N.Y. She was 88. An
example of Ms. Denhof's work, the April 1964 cover of Glamour
Magazine. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 5, 2000 -- ECSTASY-SCOPE -- Ecstasy,
a euphoria-producing psychedelic known to chemists as MDMA, has been
around since 1912, when it was introduced in Europe as a potential
appetite suppressant. Seizures of the little white pills Ecstacy have
occurred so often in recent months that it is beginning to feel as if
law enforcement officials are doing little else besides cracking down
on the drug. Club goers at IVY, an Upper West Side dance club in
Manhattan. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ASHBURN, VA. -- Aug. 5, 2000 -- FBN-REDSKINS-SNYDER --
Daniel Snyder, who took control of the Redskins in the spring of
1999, is a poor loser, and because of that he might be the best thing
to happen to professional football in years. Snyder has not hesitated
to spend his money to improve the Redskins on the field. A flurry of
off-season signings has heightened expectations. (Justin Lane/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PHILIDELPHIA -- Aug. 5, 2000 -- GOP-MEDIA -- In the
absence of real news, or even real debate, what dominated American
news pages and airwaves last week was the sound of one party
clapping. Elizabeth Dole was one of many Republican luminaries made
available to local news outlets during the party's convention last
week. Dole, Aided by Charles Clark, a G.O.P. official, performed a
sound check for her convention speech. (Chang W. Lee/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ARTA, Djibouti -- Aug. 5, 2000 -- SOMALIA-REVIVE --
For two months, Somalis gathered in Arta, Djibouti, have debated how
to invent a government. They have a new charter and are set to elect
a president they hope will one day replace the nine-year chaos of
warring clans. So far, they have agreed on a national charter -
something like a transitional constitution - and within the next week
expect to elect a three-year, 225-member national assembly. (Tyler
Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
