<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      08-05 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND CHENEY TRAVEL BY TRAIN TO RALLY SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ They sounded a cry for lower tax codes in Pontiac,
Mich., and rallied people in Durand with the promise that President
Clinton was on the way out. A crowd of several thousand people in
East Lansing got a pledge that the military would be strengthened.
A smattering of people in Holly and Fenton got only waves and
smiles as the train rattled by.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second straight day on the rails for Gov. George W.
Bush and his running mate, Dick Cheney _ the second straight day of
trying to turn the momentum from a convention into a mandate from
Americans. And it took the Republican duo across much of the
breadth of southern Michigan, where they spent about seven
stop-and-go hours before abandoning the ground for the sky and
flying here Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish you could travel with us and see the great spirit of
America,'' Bush told the people at the East Lansing rally. ``It
lies in the heartlands of our country. It lies along the tracks
that we've been on with people from all walks of life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pledge is that if you give us the opportunity to lead this
nation, not only will we work on a positive agenda for what is
right for our country,'' Bush added. ``Our pledge is that if you
give us your trust, we will honor it.''
</P>
<P>
   As with much of the oratory that they used at the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia, Bush and Cheney were offering
indictments, both implicit and explicit, of President Clinton, and
they were attaching Vice President Gore to whatever disappointments
Americans had felt about Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The large, enthusiastic crowds mostly gobbled it up. They toted
signs with messages like ``I'd rather be Bushed than Gored.'' They
chanted: ``No more Gore! No more Gore!''
</P>
<P>
   At several stops, a few people protesting Bush's support for
capital punishment or opposition to abortion sought to thrust their
own voices and placards into the picture, but they were well
outnumbered.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's train trip through Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan and
Illinois, which he was scheduled to visit on Sunday, represented a
bid to win swing states that had voted Democratic in the last two
presidential elections, and Bush made a point at several stops
Saturday to mention that his campaign was open to independents and
Democrats, and to beckon them aboard.
</P>
<P>
   He also articulated some bedrock conservative philosophies and
proposals, summoning particular passion for the subject of lowering
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, at the Durand stop, said the train trip showed that he
and Bush were going to ``carry this fight from border to border and
coast to coast, because it's extraordinarily important that we have
a change in Washington.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
