<P>
   GOP CONVENTION FOLLOW-UP
</P>
<P>
   CVN-REAL-GOP _ PHILADELPHIA _ George Bush's convention took
pains to portray the Republican Party as one in transition from the
party of narrow interests to the party of inclusion. But even as
the party's only openly gay congressional representative was
addressing Bush's convention, Bush's platform committee was voting
not to soften anti-gay language in the platform. Amid other such
discrepancies, the question remains: which is the real George W.
Bush, which is the real GOP. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GORE _ WASHINGTON _ Now that the Republican National
Convention is history, Vice President Al Gore needs to counter its
effects in two main ways: deliver an acceptance speech in Los
Angeles that counters the style and substance of George W. Bush's,
and choose a running mate who compares well with Dick Cheney.
(Shepard, Cox News Service) MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MIDWEST _ Newly nominated Bush attacks Clinton's veto of
relief for marriage tax penalty as he begins a whistlestop tour
through the Midwest. (Heath, Austin American-Statesman) 18-20.VOTER
_ DAYTON, Ohio _ Sen. John McCain may have caused Gov. George W.
Bush plenty of headaches in the bitterly contested Republican
presidential primary, but, if Ohio is any indication, he may have
done Bush and all Republican candidates a big favor. The sparks
flying off McCain's Straight Talk Express generated a wave of
interest among voters, particularly Republican voters, that hasn't
been seen in a primary in many years. According to newly released
statewide voter registration figures compiled by the Ohio secretary
of state's office, that wave almost doubled the ranks of the
state's registered Republicans. Democratic registration also grew,
but the registered Republican increase more than doubled the
Democratic gain. (McCall, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   NETWORTH -TALLAHASSEE _ The average Florida legislator is now _
for the first time _ a millionaire, and last year earned $118,000
in outside income. The average senator was worth $1.9 million, and
the average House member $781,000 at the end of last year,
according to an analysis by The Palm Beach Post of annual financial
disclosure statements. The figures represent a 10 percent increase
for the average House member and a 12 percent gain for the typical
senator. ( Date, Palm Beach Post) 20. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-VISITORS _ Two years after the fatal shooting of two
U.S. Capitol police officers, designs are being completed for a
$265 million Capitol Visitors Center that will boost security and
allow police to better manage the flow of visitors. The center will
be the first planned addition to the Capitol building since 1959,
but you won't be able to see it from ground level. The 500,000
square foot center will be built underground, between the Capitol
and the U.S. Supreme Court building. (O'Dell, Cox News Service).
15.
</P>
<P>
   GA-SENATERACE _ Now that the field of candidates is set, here's
the curtain raiser for the 2000 U.S. Senate race. Who are the
candidates, and what are their chances. (Pruitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   FARMS-DROUGHT _ Since the start of the spring planting season,
an Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer and photographer have
followed a South Georgia farm family's fight for survival. They
come closer to losing that fight with each dry day. (Head, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DACHAS _ MOSCOW _ Summertime in Russia is synonymous with
one thing: dachas, the countryside homes where Russians get away
from everyday life, relax and spend quality time with family and
friends. Dacha culture has existed since Czarist times, and it has
spawned a rich cultural tradition. In Soviet times, these plots
helped people survive amid shortages of food, and the land remained
the only private property allowed. My Russian friends Slava and
Lucy, like millions of Russians, treat their dacha as their castle.
They spent five years building their home and now slave every
weekend in their garden all for the joy of eating the ruby-red
tomatoes grown on their land. (Coker, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTO.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN EDs: The earliest version of the story that MOVED on Wed.,
Aug. 2, on the NYT Wire has a large portion of the story missing.
Please, use versions that MOVED later.
</P>
