<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TANK0806-COX     08-05 2153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANK0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Over night success story was too good to be true
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Almost overnight, sports agent William
``Tank'' Black leaped from having one major client to more than 35.
Suddenly the once-broke former assistant football coach from South
Carolina was buying a brick mansion, leasing a private jet at
$3,000 per hour and giving expensive gifts to an exotic dancer who
was not his wife.
</P>
<P>
   To get there, NFL running back Fred Taylor of Belle Glade now
sadly concludes, ``Tank did his crooked thing.''
</P>
<P>
   What players such as Taylor saw too late was that Black was
taking his clients for a ride _ a ride into what federal
investigators say is the biggest agent fraud scandal they've seen
in the history of professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   Black, 43, is expected to appear in Detroit this week to answer
federal charges he laundered $1.1 million for a drug ring. He is in
the custody of federal marshals at an undisclosed location, a
spokeswoman for the U.S. Attorney's Office in Detroit said. If
convicted, he could receive up to life in prison and a $4 million
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Black's is a sprawling case that fills stacks of files in
federal courthouses from Gainesville to Tampa to central Michigan.
He and more than half a dozen associates have been indicted on
federal criminal and civil charges they conspired to defraud former
clients _ including Taylor and the NBA's Vince Carter _ by
mishandling $15 million of their money since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   One way Black lured clients was to give them money improperly
while they were still in college, many of them at the University of
Florida, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   There was a cautionary tale written on those dollars, if the
players had been able to see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy cheats to get you, he will cheat you when he gets
you,'' said Trace Armstrong, the Miami Dolphins' defensive end and
former Gator who is president of the NFL Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   When players hired Black as an agent to negotiate their
professional contracts, he did more than take an agent's cut of 3
or 4 percent. He persuaded clients to let him pay their bills and
invest their millions for returns he claimed were higher than the
stock market, 20 percent or better. Never mind that the companies
included an unproven start-up, in which he was a director, that
sold black-history board games; a company that made car-title
loans; and a mysterious offshore firm in the Cayman Islands. Most
of the players had little experience handling money. Some, like
Tampa Bay receiver and UF receiver Jacquez Green, had never had a
checking account.
</P>
<P>
   Black's lawyers say he was a victim himself, of shady investment
advisers, and that he did not knowingly do business with drug
dealers. He even refunded the players' money in some cases _ at
least the principal investment, if not the profits he promised
them.
</P>
<P>
   But at least $10 million is still missing, investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are still adding up what Black's clients lost, but
Green is reportedly out of $500,000; Detroit Lions receiver Germane
Crowell lost a similar amount; Carter some $300,000. Taylor appears
to be the biggest vbelieve they would receive.
</P>
<P>
   HINDSIGHT IS 20/20
</P>
<P>
   Taylor wanted to believe Black. Until last fall, the
Jacksonville Jaguars running back from the University of Florida
stood by his agent.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, he realized he could not get access to his own $3.6
million signing bonus and the head-spinning investment returns it
was supposed to be making. All he heard were excuses.
</P>
<P>
   With former teammate Ike Hilliard, now with the New York Giants,
Taylor has hired a Miami attorney to try to get his money back in a
civil lawsuit against Black. He has hired Drew Rosenhaus as his new
agent, and can only advise other young players to be more careful
than he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be careful and do a couple of background checks,'' Taylor
said, standing outside the cafeteria of a hotel in Jacksonville,
where the Jaguars have begun training camp. ``Start out with a
group of three to five (prospective agents). Dissect them one by
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Black sold himself as a former college player and coach who knew
what black athletes have to go through. He had been a short and
stocky receiver at Carson-Newman and assistant coach at the
University of South Carolina. In 1990, he formed his own management
company, Professional Marketing Inc., in Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   For years, his only prominent client was a South Carolina
receiver, Sterling Sharpe, who played for the Green Bay Packers.
But in 1996, Black began a push to become a super-agent.
</P>
<P>
   Within three years, his rise was eye-popping: He represented an
unprecedented five first-round picks in the 1999 NFL draft and more
than 35 clients overall. The names included New England Patriots
running back Terry Allen and Carolina Panthers receiver Rae
Carruth, who was later charged with arranging the murder of his
wife. He even branched into the NBA, luring emerging Toronto
superstar Carter, who grew up in Daytona Beach and whose mother
thought Black seemed sincerely interested in her son.
</P>
<P>
   PAYMENTS TO PLAYERS
</P>
<P>
   To build his business, Black handed out money to prospective
clients through a network of ``runners,'' or field assistants,
prosecutors say. He allegedly tried, unsuccessfully, to pay an
assistant coach at Louisiana State University to influence a
defensive tackle prospect there. But the most lucrative pickings
were at talent-laden UF in Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   While still at the University of Florida, Taylor received an
unspecified amount of cash from, or allowed expenses to be paid by,
a runner named Alfred Twitty who was employed by Black, according
to an indictment filed by the U.S. Attorney's office in
Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal began to come to light late in the 1998 season when
campus police received a tip that a Gator player, Tim Beauchamp,
was getting money from another agent. Beauchamp said he only wanted
what teammate Johnny Rutledge, was getting from Tank Black _ $500
to $600 per month. Another linebacker, Jevon Kearse, reportedly
drove a $133,000 Mercedes Black had bought him before the team's
1999 Orange Bowl game, though Kearse actually accepted title to the
car days after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Twitty, charged in Gainesville as part of the fraud conspiracy,
said he was paid $2,500 per month but now cannot afford his own
lawyer. According to an application he filed requesting a federal
public defender, he is now unemployed and, though single, has a
baby on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Rutledge and Kearse dropped Black as their agent when news of
the gifts became public. Florida coach Steve Spurrier said the
players were no longer welcome on campus, though neither the
athletes nor the school were otherwise punished. There was no
evidence the university had knowledge of the payments,
investigators concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Other former Florida players were not so lucky _ Taylor,
receiver Hilliard and receiver Reidel Anthony, found themselves and
their money caught up in the unfolding case. Hilliard also took
money in college before signing with Black, federal investigators
allege.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, those players got tied up with that guy,''
Spurrier said. ``They didn't know what kind of person he was. I
didn't know anything about him. And a year or two later, all the
money is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, the NFLPA president, said he has spoken to Florida
players this summer to remind them of the dangers that agents pose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should affect the players just from reading about it,''
Spurrier said. ``They know the rules. You can't take money. Not
from agents, not from boosters. They know the rules, what it takes
to stay eligible.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State coach Bobby Bowden said the Black case is
disheartening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scares you to death,'' said Bowden. ``You can talk to the
kids about this, but they're the ones who have to make the
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   POWER OF PERSUASION
</P>
<P>
   For Anthony, a 1998 first-round pick of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers
from UF and the son of South Bay Mayor Clarence Anthony, agent
worries only added to a miserable 1999 season in which he was hurt
for most of the year and dropped several passes. Trying to put it
behind him heading into the 2000 season has been a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard,'' Anthony said. ``You try to put it in the
back of your mind, but it still lingers.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of anxiety, Anthony and his father were able to
retrieve nearly $900,000 from Black in August 1999, but never saw
the profits the money was supposed to generate, according to
transcripts from a fraud caled in Tampa by the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know who to trust and how things are going to
happen,'' Anthony said, between workouts recently at Bucs training
camp. ``You have a lot of money and people are after it. They'll
grab it. I got caught in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony was not mentioned among the payments to still-eligible
UF players that federal investigators uncovered, and his father
tried to keep an eye on his financial dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Black could be persuasive when he urged clients to let him
invest their money, Clarence Anthony told SEC investigators.
</P>
<P>
   A typical sales pitch from Black went like this, Clarence
Anthony said: ``I have this product, BAOA, which is an
African-American board game that is going to blow up and going to
be a big company, and you guys should look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Black sat on the board of BAOA Inc., a San Diego company that
sold a game called Black Americans of Achievement. The game was
endorsed by the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who said later he was unaware
of Black's financial dealings but liked what he knew about the
agent.
</P>
<P>
   The company agreed to give the players free BAOA stock in
exchange for promotional services, but Black sold them the shares
for 50 cents to $1 apiece _ when the stock was trading from 4 cents
to 28 cents per share _ and charged them commissions as well, the
SEC says.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Black's then-clients, including NFL running back Natrone
Means, became suspicious, and Black later refunded the principal
investment to more than a dozen players, though the SEC concluded
he cost the players $240,000 in foregone interest.
</P>
<P>
   Black steered clients into new investments, including a company
called Cash 4 Titles. The company made loans in exchange for car
titles and promised a stratospheric return of 36 percent annually.
Black told players they would receive a 20 percent return but
arranged to keep the other 16 percent for himself, the SEC alleges
_ plus a $30,000 annual commission.
</P>
<P>
   But an increasing amount of the clients' money was heading to
offshore companies in the Cayman Islands. In the end, SEC officials
said it amounted to a classic pyramid scheme, in which money from
new investors was used to pay old investors. Taylor and Hilliard's
lawsuit names Cash 4 Titles directors Michael Gause and Richard
Homa among other defendants, though they were not indicted in the
federal criminal or civil cases against Black. They could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM LINE
</P>
<P>
   Black claimed he was duped, too.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Anthony told SEC investigators he asked Black about it:
``He said, 'You know, I put money in this thing, too. I was tricked
like everybody else. You know, Clarence, I thought these guys were
legitimate I'm just as _ been bilked out of money just like you
guys.' And my response was, 'But these guys trusted you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He went on to say, 'Yes, I know. But, you know, the fact of
the matter is it was _ the money is gone.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Then came the stunning news of drug charges, which arose from a
completely separate investigation in Detroit. Federal investigators
there were looking into a drug ring that brought cocaine into the
United States _ and allegedly laundered $1.1 million of its cash
proceeds through a South Carolina corporation set up by Black and
attorney James A. Franklin. One of Black's employees, Linda Wilson,
allegedly knew members of the ring, though Black's attorney says he
was unaware what business they were really in.
</P>
<P>
   An indictment unsealed in July charged Black and Wilson helped
fugitive Dean Parker, a member of the ring, obtain false
identification to flee the country, on a plane from Columbia, S.C.,
to Jamaica. For a 25 percent fee, fictitious companies set up by
Black, Wilson and Franklin in 1998 provided the drug ring with
``the appearance of legitimate sources of income,'' said U.S.
Attorney Saul Green in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fake companies was called Taylor Development Ltd. in
the Cayman Islands _ from Fred Taylor's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of lessons to be learned,'' Armstrong said.
``One of them is that good agents don't need to cheat. A lot of
players are learning the hard way that it will catch up to them
sooner or later.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
