<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who's not a millionaire?
 &HT;    By S.V. Date
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ The average Florida legislator is now _ for the
first time _ a millionaire, and last year earned $118,000 in
outside income.
</P>
<P>
   The average senator was worth $1.9 million, and the average
House member $781,000 at the end of last year, according to an
analysis by The Palm Beach Post of annual financial disclosure
statements. The figures represent a 10 percent increase for the
average House member and a 12 percent gain for the typical senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty shocking,'' said Rep. Bob Henriquez, D-Tampa,
and who, with a $22,332 net worth, is one of the legislature's
poorest members. ``As poor as I am, a million dollars is a lot of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the lawmakers are millionaires; only 43. But enough of
those have such great wealth as to pull up the average of all 160
members into the seven-figure range for the first time, with an
average net worth of $1,045,445. Last year's average net worth was
$952,502.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also made considerable outside incomes last year,
according to the disclosure statements: An average $105,501 in the
House and $152,965 in the Senate, on top of the $27,900 annual
legislative salary.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the per capita income in Florida last year was
about $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wealthy lawmakers, however, said the mere fact of their fortunes
doesn't detract from their ability to empathize with considerably
poorer constituents. ``I've been a janitor, a waiter,'' said Rep.
Allan Bense, R-Lynn Haven, who has $7.3 million in assets and last
year earned $2.6 million through his golf course and construction
businesses. ``I've worked my way through high school, worked my way
through college, through graduate school . . . I've been on the
bottom. I understand what it's like on the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the legislature's overall wealth, however, are sharp
distinctions along gender and racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   The average male legislator is worth $1.14 million, the average
female, $766,000. The typical white lawmaker has a net worth of
$1.27 million; the average black, $230,000, and the average
Cuban-American lawmaker, $191,000.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-1 ratio between white and minority legislators' financial
conditions reflects but greatly exaggerates the differences in
society as a whole, lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a tendency to elect people they're most
comfortable with,'' said Sen. Daryl Jones, D-Miami and chairman of
the black caucus. ``Republicans tend to be wealthier people, and
they tend to elect wealthier people. And Democrats tend to elect
people they're most comfortable with, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida lawmakers, like all other elected officials in the
state, are required to disclose their assets, liabilities and
incomes each July 1, although a number of legislators this year
missed that deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators are required to disclose all sources of income above
$1,000 or, in the alternative, file a copy of their tax return,
including all forms that disclose income sources, such as the W2.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to do so, though, brings no penalty, said Ethics
Commission spokeswoman Helen Jones, unless someone files a sworn
ethics complaint and the commission subsequently finds the lawmaker
guilty of the infraction and levies a fine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
