<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRIC-REVOLUTION-ECONOMIST-625&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MICROPOWER': ELECTRICITY PRODUCED, LITERALLY, IN YOUR BACKYARD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 325-word trim; 1,075 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 750-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It could be every bit as dramatic as the revolution that hit the
world's telecommunications industry in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And it is occurring in an unexpected business; but one in which
can be seen the same forces of innovation, competition and choice
that transformed yesterday's sleepy telephone monopolies into
today's high-tech predators.
</P>
<P>
   That business is electricity generation.
</P>
<P>
   Stifle your yawns. Power is every bit as big a business as
telecoms. America's $220 billion electricity market is larger than
those for cellular and long-distance telephony combined.
</P>
<P>
   And it is seeing a lot of consolidation: only this week two huge
utilities, FPL of Florida and Entergy of Louisiana, announced a $27
billion merger to form America's biggest electricity company.
</P>
<P>
   The analogy with telecoms goes further. All over the world,
generators have invested huge sums in power stations and
transmission grids, which many incumbents argue make them
``natural'' monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, just as the phone companies that used to make the same
argument have found, their legacy may serve only to turn them into
easy targets. Although power grids, like all networks, may be
natural monopolies, the generation of what they carry is clearly
not.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of competition in telecoms led to furious investment
and innovation, helping to give rise to the digital economy.
Centralized control gave way to such anarchic technologies as the
mobile phone and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A similar shift is starting in electricity, thanks to market
liberalization, environmentalism and technological advance. The
entrenched monopolies that run large, dirty power plants are facing
new competition from rivals with smaller and cleaner technologies
at their command.
</P>
<P>
   The result will be lower prices for consumers, and more capacity
to satisfy the world's ever-growing demand for electricity _ some
of it, ironically, caused by the spread of the Internet. And it
could soon mean power produced, quite literally, in your own
backyard.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to this revolution lies in ``micropower,'' the
generation of electricity by small-scale fuel cells and gas
turbines.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is not exactly new: most of it is, indeed, over a
century old. But, thanks in good part to a huge inflow of venture
capital into the business, it has in the past few years moved far
closer to commercial reality.
</P>
<P>
   One telling sign: such huge multinationals as America's GE and
Europe's ABB are fizzing with excitement about micropower.
Micropower offers substantial advantages over old-fashioned power
stations, in terms of efficiency, reliability, environmental
friendliness and, increasingly, price.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the transmission losses suffered while distributing
centrally-generated electricity over long distances were more than
outweighed by the economies of scale of large power stations. But
the efficiency of the new technologies has undermined this
calculation.
</P>
<P>
   Local power generation makes it easier to use the surplus heat
that even the most efficient generators release. Micropower allows
users to declare independence from electricity grids that _ as even
users in California have found this summer _ are becoming less
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   And the fuels involved (hydrogen or natural gas) come low on
environmentalists' hate-lists, certainly when compared with the
coal or nuclear energy of a typical power station.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of micropower may be even greater in poor
countries. Many of these have grids that make California's seem a
paragon of reliability, which is why so many of their customers
already run their own, mostly diesel-powered, generators.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel cells and microturbines may now allow some countries to
skip the giant-power-station stage of energy generation altogether
_ rather as many countries are sensibly jumping over wired
telephony and straight to wireless.
</P>
<P>
   If the world is ever to realize the full potential of
micropower, however, three big obstacles must be overcome: in
taxation, in standards and in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (325-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 625) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Micropower can be seriously slowed down by the distorted
taxation and subsidy of energy. Many big coal-fired power stations
are escaping ``carbon'' taxes on their emissions; even worse, a lot
receive fat subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   In parts of Europe, these come directly from taxpayers; in
America, they come through waivers that exempt many established
power stations from environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Tax codes may also discriminate directly against micropower.
Fuel cells, for example, attract unfavorable depreciation rates.
All such perverse incentives need to be removed if micropower is to
be given a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The second snag is a lack of uniform technical standards. One
attraction of micropower is that it can allow generator-owners to
become producers as well as consumers _ selling surplus electricity
back to the grid when they do not need it.
</P>
<P>
   That requires clever electronic control systems, which now
exist. But it also requires agreed standards. Yet few countries
have national codes governing interconnections to their power
grids.
</P>
<P>
   So manufacturers and owners of micropower units have to deal
with myriad, sometimes contradictory, rules whenever they want to
negotiate the right to buy and sell power. And that makes it all
too easy for established incumbents to thwart newcomers by citing
bogus safety concerns, imposing lengthy approval processes or
demanding outrageous fees.
</P>
<P>
   Governments should push efforts to harmonize standards and also
act more vigorously against such anti-competitive practices.
</P>
<P>
   The third obstacle is a regulatory mess that may hold up proper
competition in electricity. America has done most to liberalize:
about half its states have thrown open their power markets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the lack of coordination over interstate trading of
electricity, the absence of a single regulatory authority and the
requirement to have reserve capacity for peak demand have all led
to uncertainties that have deterred new entrants.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,075) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Promising technologies will be delayed unless such muddles are
dealt with _ and the results enforced. Enforcement is an even
bigger problem in Europe, where, thanks mainly to lobbying by
Electricite de France, the French have failed to implement EU
directives on energy liberalization.
</P>
<P>
   Even if these obstructions were cleared away, traditional power
stations would not disappear. Their capital costs are sunk and
their marginal running costs are not high. But once the idea of
micropower really catches on, few new big power stations are likely
to be built.
</P>
<P>
   In a few decades' time, the notion of a micropower unit in every
home and office may even have come to fruition. The whole conceit
that electricity is generated far away from where it is consumed
may then come to seem as quaint as the idea that every phone has to
have a wire attached.
</P>
<P>
   Let the electricity revolution roll. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
