<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-DOT.BOMBS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET CRUNCH CROSSES THE PUDDLE, LEAVES EUROBIZ IN A MUDDLE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 750-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Recent events have not been encouraging for Europe's crop of
once optimistic Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   They include such spectacular collapses as that of boo.com, a
spendthrift electronic sports-goods retailer that met impressive
standards of corporate extravagance while blithely losing a bundle.
</P>
<P>
   This week clickmango, an online health-care business, became the
latest of a string of such dot.com casualties. Clickmango's weekly
sales had reached the glorious heights of Pounds2,000 ($3,000), a
small fraction of the Pounds25,000 ($37,500) it was spending every
week to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing unusual in this, surely? After all, businesses, even
Internet businesses, fail all the time. America has, as ever,
blazed the trail; as its list of dead dot.coms lengthens, so do the
shadows over the best-known of them all, Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months hundreds of European fledglings are
likely to suffer the same fate as boo.com and clickmango. Hundreds
more will merge into larger entities with a better chance of
survival.
</P>
<P>
   The process of consolidation will have profound effects, some
beneficial but some harmful, on all European companies, not just
online ones.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the benefits first. Because of the swing of the funding
cycle, many European Internet start-ups are running out of cash at
the same moment.
</P>
<P>
   Until April this year, almost anybody in Europe could raise
funds for an Internet venture. But, after wobbles on America's
high-tech stock markets that month, investors, mostly professional
venture capitalists, took fright and funding abruptly dried up.
</P>
<P>
   Only the best business ideas now get any start-up money. Only
the best executed win the second and later rounds of funding that
are needed before any company can think of floating itself on a
stock market that is suddenly much less accommodating.
</P>
<P>
   During the coming shakeout, lots of poorly conceived companies
that should, by rights, not have been funded at all will disappear.
Others that have more to offer will be snapped up by rivals in a
flurry of paper mergers (cash, not shares, being today's precious
resource).
</P>
<P>
   One result is that genuinely pan-European Internet companies are
likely to emerge sooner than even the most ambitious start-ups had
expected.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, especially in the market for business services
(or B2B), big gains for Europe's economies should thereby be
unlocked. And pan-European Internet companies will be better placed
to fight off the challenge from American firms seeking to exploit
their strength and first-mover advantage at home by spreading
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional firms may also get in on the act. Europe's big
companies have been typically slow to take to the ``new economy,''
and even slower to invest in Internet efforts of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the speed with which Europe's Internet companies have
reached their consolidation phase, these slowpokes now have an
unexpected second chance to establish an online presence, at
much-reduced prices. There can be a benefit from watching others
make mistakes: call it second-mover advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet two dangers in particular lie ahead. The first is that
Europe's imported American-style venture capitalism, which
encouraged so many Internet start-ups to launch, might be thrown
over almost as soon as it has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to forget that America's investing infrastructure
took nearly three decades to develop from its Silicon Valley roots.
Over the past two years, Europe has seen a remarkable burst of
activity, but venture-capital firms have not had sufficient time to
foster the dense networks of contacts and knowledge that they need.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that a flurry of failures could send European
venture investors back to their old ways, favoring management
buyouts over start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   A second risk relates to Europe's entrepreneurial culture. From
Stockholm to Lisbon, a whole generation of motivated, excited
managers have poured their energies into starting Internet
companies.
</P>
<P>
   That has shaken up the executive floors more widely, as
traditional firms have struggled to hold on to the best talent and,
in many cases, have watched their market worth exceeded by cheeky
new entrants.
</P>
<P>
   With many of those new entrants now facing failure or
consolidation, there is a danger that the continent's businesses
may assume that, after all, nothing needs to change. That would be
a shame: an overly protected, over-regulated Europe has long needed
more, not fewer, risk-takers.
</P>
<P>
   How many failed entrepreneurs get a second chance will be an
important test of whether European business has really ``got'' the
new economy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
