<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FARMS-DROUGHT0806-COX     08-05 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARMS-DROUGHT0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `I ain't going to quit now,' vows weary worker
 &HT;    By John Head
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDERSON CITY, Ga. _ Johnny B. Rushing has been a full-time
farmworker for almost half a century. Each of those years, it
seems, can be read in his hands. They have been lined, gnarled and
strengthened by his labor in the fields of Worth County.
</P>
<P>
   It is the only livelihood Rushing has ever known, and 43 years
of it has been spent as a hired hand for one family. He works for
Jerald Carter, whose father first hired Rushing in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised up on a farm,'' says Rushing, 62. ``My daddy used
to farm. My granddaddy used to farm. I've just enjoyed being around
farming from when it was a mule to a tractor the way it is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't going to quit now,'' Rushing adds with a smile. ``Not
unless something bad happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But something bad is happening to farmers like Jerald Carter and
the people who work for them. Georgia's worst drought on record is
threatening their jobs and way of life. Since the start of the
spring planting season, an Atlanta Journal-Constitution
photographer and a staff writer have followed the Carter family
farm's fight for survival in this South Georgia community _ a fight
that comes closer to being a lost cause with each dry day.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many farm jobs hang in the balance because of
the drought. The closest thing to a count of farmworkers from the
state Department of Labor is a 1998 figure of 41,531 in
agriculture, forestry and fishing who were enrolled in the state's
unemployment insurance program. But that, no doubt, is well short
of the number of people who make their living raising crops and
livestock on more than 30,000 farms in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Focus on a single farm like Jerald Carter's, however, and it's
not the numbers that matter; it's what's at stake for people. Three
men _ Rushing, Jack McCullough and Jeff Mathews _ work for Carter.
They all have a lot to lose if the drought drives Carter out of
business. But Rushing has the most to lose because he's been
working at Carter Farms since he was a young man.
</P>
<P>
   A HARD LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Johnny B. Rushing (''I don't know what the `B' stands for;
that's just my name'') knows how hard the farming life can be. He
spoke about it on a late July evening, relaxing in a rocking chair
on the front porch of the Carter Farms office after another 12-hour
workday.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up on Ten-Horse Farm, in a house that held an extended
family of 19, including cousins and his seven brothers and sisters.
By the time he was 13, Rushing says, he was ``plowing a mule like a
man, because there was so many of us, and I had to do what I could
to help support them.'' He was 14 when he quit school and went to
work full time on the farm beside his father.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 19, Rushing went to work for Jerald Carter's father.
He has worked on the family's farms since then.
</P>
<P>
   Such longtime ties between farmworkers and their employers may
occur less frequently than they once did, but they endure because
of the nature of farming, says Doug Bachtel, a rural sociologist at
the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agriculture continues to be a family business in Georgia, and
(the relationship between farmworkers and employers) stays over
generations,'' Bachtel says. ``If you have a good worker, then you
stick with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Rushing was the only one from the large brood at
Ten-Horse Farm who stuck with farming as an adult. ``They just
didn't like it,'' he says of the others. ``They didn't like it when
they was kids. Hated to go out there and pick cotton. Hated to go
out there and feed the mules and water them.''
</P>
<P>
   His three brothers all finished high school and wound up in New
York. One recently retired from the New York police force, where he
worked undercover.
</P>
<P>
   None of Rushing's four sons had an interest in farming, and he
didn't push them toward it. He wanted them to get the education he
missed out on, then make their own decision about what to do with
their lives. One chose a career in the Army, one manages grocery
stores in Tallahassee; another, also in Tallahassee, manages a
fast-food restaurant; the fourth runs a car wash in Sylvester, the
Worth County seat where Rushing raised his family.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing says he doesn't regret his own decision to stay with
farm work. He says he ``can't complain'' about a salary of $300 a
week, plus a year-end bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get by,'' he says. ``You don't save much. You don't have
too much left over to spend. But I raised all my children, and I've
been getting by.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rushing, a big man with an easy smile, talks about the
future of farming in positives, despite the drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to get a little rain, some of it,'' he says.
``It's looking pretty good right now.''
</P>
<P>
   `JUST TIRED OF IT'
</P>
<P>
   But Jerald Carter sounds less optimistic about his chances than
at any time since he began putting seeds in the ground early in the
year. After a day spent working balky irrigation equipment, he sits
in one of the rockers on his office porch and executes what some
call ``the South Georgia salute'' _ a wave of his hand to shoo
gnats from his face. He could as easily be swatting the litany of
drought-related problems he's reciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean to be pessimistic, but I'm about to get enough of
it,'' he says. ``This is the third year in a row (of drought), and
I am just tired of it. You'd think directly this thing would break
and go away and we'd be back to near to a normal situation, but,
man, we've been near about the whole summer without any rain.''
</P>
<P>
   As July drew to a close amid the forecast of more hot, dry
weather, Carter was running out of water for irrigation. A well
driller was due to come by soon to look for a new source of water.
</P>
<P>
   One field of cotton _ the first he planted this year _ is pretty
much ruined, Carter says. He's just hoping he can collect on the
crop insurance. He continues to invest in the rest of his cotton
and peanuts _ spraying for pests, irrigating, plowing _ to keep the
crops going. And he prays that the weather forecasters will be
proved wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the cotton, it's fixing to be over with. It's fixing to
bloom out at the top, and it'll be over with,'' Carter says sadly.
``The peanuts have probably got a few more days. But we've got to
have a significant amount of rainfall for the peanuts to turn
around. . . . We need three or four days of rain. We need probably
two or three inches over a week's period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if Carter is able to bring his crops in, his worries
won't end. The prices they bring will determine if he makes a
profit. Right now, the market isn't good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commodity prices are just horrible,'' he says. ``I've got
some corn that's about ready to gather. I called the grain elevator
_ the man that buys corn here in the county _ yesterday morning,
and he told me that it looked like the market would go to where he
was going to pay $1.70 to $1.75 a bushel for it. My gosh! You can't
even think about breaking even at that price. You need $2.75 to
$2.80 just to break even. You really need $3 for it. We've watered
it. We've put a lot into it.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's going to happen if the rain doesn't fall and commodity
prices don't go up?
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to happen?'' he repeats. ``Are we all going to
dry up and go away? What's going to happen to us? I really don't
know. I'm so discouraged with it that I don't know what to do. I've
got so much invested in it that I can't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bachtel of UGA says the drought is forcing farmers to decide
whether they can stick with it. When the decision is to give up
farming, he says, it sends ripples through the rural economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's devastating,'' Bachtel says. ``It's devastating not only
for the farmer and his workers. It really affects the community. If
that guy goes out of business, there really isn't anything else for
the people who work for him.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days after Jerald Carter contemplates a worst-case
scenario, Johnny B. Rushing is asked the same question: What will
happen if things don't turn around?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll collect my Social Security,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Then he adds: ``But I expect I'll keep working for Mr. Carter. I
expect he'll find something for me to do. He always has.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
