<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3626 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-LAKE-WOBEGORE?-MINN-E     08-05 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKE-WOBEGORE?-MINN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKE WOBEGORE: CAN DEMOCRATS STILL COUNT ON MINNESOTA?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors...and MINNESOTA)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 725-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The Democratic Party's campaign planners rarely
lose sleep over Minnesota. The state's voters have chosen Democrats
in all but three presidential elections since 1948, and in all the
six most recent ones.
</P>
<P>
   But this land of fishermen and Scandinavian crypto-socialists is
no longer a bastion of the Democratic Farmer-Labor Party (as the
Minnesota branch still insists on calling itself).
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls put Al Gore and George W. Bush neck-and-neck there.
If Gore loses Minnesota, he loses the election. That is not because
of electoral-college votes: the state has only ten. But weakness
there would point to general weaknesses elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Political power in Minnesota, as in America as a whole, has
shifted to the suburbs, where Minnesotans are increasingly building
new homes. And, like suburbanites elsewhere, these people are
disdainful of party politics, and less loyal to any one party
label.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that nearly a decade of unparalleled prosperity and
a lack of any one defining issue have unmasked Minnesotans for what
they have always been: cautious, pragmatic and (gasp) centrist.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's voters strongly backed Michael Dukakis in 1988. In
1992 they plumped for Bill Clinton, though Ross Perot, for the
Reform Party, got 24 percent of the vote. In 1996 they backed
Clinton again.
</P>
<P>
   But recently Minnesotans have become more mercurial. In 1998,
young people and political fence-sitters raced to the polls to
elect as governor Jesse Ventura, the Reform Party's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's election, many think, was an ``up yours'' vote: a
rebellion for its own sake. But it also exposed fissures in the
state's once formidable Democratic apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   Party operators had endorsed Mike Freeman, another Farmer-Labor
stalwart, as their candidate for governor. At one time, that would
have been enough; but the primary was won by Hubert Humphrey III,
scion of a favorite Minnesotan son.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you knock out the two votes for Clinton and the
election of ultra-liberal Paul Wellstone to the Senate in 1990, the
Democrats have ``had as bad a decade as one can remember,'' says
Chris Gilbert, a political scientist at Gustavus Adolphus College,
in Saint Peter.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying reason is the ever-growing number of independent
voters. Worse for Gore, the poll that put him in a dead heat with
Bush also found independents more likely to vote Republican than
Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minnesota is no longer simply a kind of knee-jerk liberal
state,'' argues Stuart Rothenberg, the editor of a Washington
newsletter. ``It's just a bizarre state.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign is scrambling to cope with this. Gore has
visited Minnesota three times in the past five months to curry
favor with Ventura. He has made no secret of the fact that he needs
the support of the young, disaffected voters who supported the
governor, and who could hold the key to several Midwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   But in his quest for independents Gore may be snubbing those who
could labor for him in the autumn. When he last visited the state,
in late June, he courted the Democratic faithful only as an
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake,'' he told a group of diners in a local cafe,
``Minnesota is crucial to this election, and Minnesota will be won
or lost in your hearts.'' Democrats felt disinclined to believe
him, seeing that, the next moment, he was being chummy with
Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Once the campaign proper begins, after the conventions,
Minnesotans may start inspecting the two candidates' specific
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released on July 3 showed that 59 percent of them support
Gore's plans to use the federal surplus to shore up Social
Security, and only 31 percent support Bush's plans to let people
invest part of their Social Security taxes in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   And those Minnesotans who say that Social Security is the most
important issue (the old, who vote) favor Gore over Bush by 49
percent to 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore presses that issue, and finds others that appeal, he may
persuade Minnesotans to remember their native liberals: Hubert
Humphrey, Walter Mondale and Eugene McCarthy, who helped to foster
among many Minnesotans their once-deep belief that government was
more benevolent than meddlesome.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the privacy of the polling booth, Minnesotans may
decide to vote as they have nearly always done. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
