<HEADER>
A3629 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-EC     08-05 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIRKS, QUIPS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 375-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; SPOT-ON OBSERVATION OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing is part convention, part circus, part
flea-market.'' (Republican Senator Ben Nighthorse Campbell of
Colorado, Washington Post, July 31) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CREME DE LA CREME: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The best seats at the convention were allotted to the Regents, a
new club of donors who have given more than a quarter of a million
dollars apiece to the Republican Party this year. They also had the
best hotel rooms and, for the really favored few, a fly-fishing
trip with the speaker of the House of Representatives, Dennis
Hastert. (New York Times, July 30) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNFORTUNATE SLOGAN OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole's ``Strength through compassion,'' inviting
comparison with Hitler's ``Strength through joy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CV OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a librarian, I'm a schoolteacher, I'm a mother, I'm a
wife. And I'm a west Texan.'' (Laura Bush, consort of the
candidate, CBS Evening News, July 31) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YESTERDAY'S MAN (1): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who he used to be. He can't block the gangway.''
(Republican delegate, frustrated by the knot of reporters around
Newt Gingrich) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YESTERDAY'S MAN (2): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still time for a recount.'' (Bob Dole responds to his
standing ovation) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HUNK OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Little beads of sweat built up across his forehead as he
helped dig up weeds by the lake. Even working with a shovel by a
filthy lake, he looked adorable. Yum.'' (The Philadelphia Daily
News on George Prescott Bush (son of Jeb), July 31) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUBTLETY OF THE WEEK (1): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know. Do any of you guys know?'' (Protester,
asked to explain why she and her friends had dressed up as goats on
a very hot day) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUBTLETY OF THE WEEK (2): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Its, like, goats will eat anything. So, you see, it's a
metaphor for politics.'' (Second protester, explaining it all) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEADLINE STEALER Al Gore will announce his choice of
vice-president on Tuesday Aug. 8, the week before the Democratic
convention opens in Los Angeles. &QL;
</P>
