<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GA-SENATERACE0806-COX     08-05 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SENATERACE0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate duel like a blast from the past
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From Washington, a U.S. Senate seat beckoned Zell
Miller as the fulfillment of a long-time dream. Republicans,
casting about for a candidate, settled on one of their leaders,
Mack Mattingly.
</P>
<P>
   That was 20 years ago, the first time Miller and Mattingly
coveted the same seat in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   They never faced each other then. A primary loss by Miller kept
them apart, and Mattingly went on to defeat Democratic legend
Herman Talmadge for the seat.
</P>
<P>
   But the matchup that never happened two decades ago is finally
unfolding as Georgians prepare to select a successor for the late
U.S. Sen. Paul Coverdell in a Nov. 7 special election.
</P>
<P>
   Eight other candidates have signed up for the accelerated
three-month campaign. But most aren't expected to be more than
window dressing for the race.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Miller, 68, appointed by Gov. Roy Barnes as an
interim replacement, is the favorite, after 16 years as lieutenant
governor and eight years as governor. Mattingly, 69, who hasn't
been on the ballot in 14 years and hasn't won a race since his
upset Senate victory in 1980, will have to reaquaint himself with
voters in a state enlarged by 1.7 million new residents since he
left office.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Miller has set the tone.
</P>
<P>
   The popular former governor immediately embraced the legacy of
Coverdell, with whom he served in the Georgia Senate, and promised
to eschew partisanship in Washington in order to represent all
``7.5 million Georgians.'' He even broke ranks with Democrats and
President Clinton, a close personal friend, by saying he'll support
Republican efforts to repeal the marriage tax penalty and the
estate tax, even over a presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's position on the tax issues has taken ``two of the most
salient issues in the state'' out of play for Republicans, said
Emory University political scientist Merle Black.
</P>
<P>
   And Miller's commanding popularity _ he left office with an 85
percent approval rating and a recent poll for the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee says he leads Mattingly 61 percent to
21 percent _ means ``it'd take a political earthquake here'' to
beat him, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Miller fails to make it through the crowded field of
challengers without a runoff, a situation political experts believe
is unlikely, he becomes more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are hoping for a runoff, but they aren't about to
make the race a referendum on Miller. Party leaders, won't even
talk about the newly appointed senator's possible liabilities _ the
corporate boards he has served on since leaving office, his
consulting for the Philip Morris company or his divisive attempts
to remove the Confederate battle emblem from the state flag.
</P>
<P>
   What Republicans will try to exploit is Miller's ties to
President Clinton to lump him with liberal national Democrats. As
governor, Miller moved up Georgia's primary to give Clinton the
needed boost to win the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either you're a part of the Al Gore, Tom Daschle, Teddy
Kennedy team or the George Bush, John McCain, Paul Coverdell
team,'' said GOP Chairman Chuck Clay. ``You can't be a Paul
Coverdell Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   With his decision to skip the Democratic convention in Los
Angeles this month, Miller is trying to innoculate himself in
advance for those charges. ``These folks who think I'm going to go
up there and vote the party line or be Bill Clinton's lap dog don't
know Zell Miller,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   But even more often than Republicans invoke Clinton's image,
they'll use Coverdell's name in reverence. They have to establish
Mattingly as the rightful heir to the Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Already they have begun the gambit. The head of Coverdell's
campaign committee delivered Mattingly's qualifying papers and
declared he's the one that Coverdell would want in his chair. The
Coverdell campaign could give the funds remaining in the late
senator's account _ more than $537,000, according to the 1999
year-end report _ to the state GOP to spend on the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   But getting the message out is going to require much more money.
Political analysts say it will take massive TV advertising to pump
up Mattingly's name ID across the state. And national Republicans
have said that there will be little outside money directed to
Georgia if the race isn't competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly told some reporters that he, like wealthy airline
executive Lewis Jordan, who flirted with a run for the office,
could have pumped much of his own resources into the race. ``But I
think it's better to have the money coming from the people of the
state,'' Mattingly said.
</P>
<P>
   The former IBM salesman is known for his ability to drum up
campaign cash. But Miller has used his business ties, accumulating
$5 million in campaign pledges in the week he has been in office.
</P>
<P>
   Ayres, Mattingly's pollster, acknowledges the challenge. ``It's
obviously going to be an uphill climb. Governor Miller was a fine
governor, but this is a different race.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
