u s BC-MINORBALL0806-COX     08-05 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORBALL0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Betemit tearing through New York-Penn League
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wilson Betemit is trying to make up for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   The Dominican shortstop is hitting over .300 for Jamestown in
the New York-Penn League after missing spring training and all of
April and May in a dispute with the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Betemit, signed by Atlanta when he was too young, filed suit in
an attempt to be declared a free agent. But he and the Braves
reached a settlement in June.
</P>
<P>
   Now 18, Betemit reported to Jamestown in time for opening day in
the short-season Class A league. He was so happy about playing
again that he did flips _ a la Ozzie Smith _ as he took the field
before games.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing injury, the organization put an end to that
crowd-pleasing routine. But Betemit's play still is exciting fans.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting .320 last season while making the all-star team in
the rookie Appalachian League, Betemit raised his average to .338
with Jamestown.
</P>
<P>
   With Betemit and second baseman Greg Donato, the Jammers have
two of the top hitters in the New York-Penn League. Donato, 19, was
hitting .351 and led the league with seven homers and 31 RBIs.
Originally a third baseman, Donato was a 12th-round draft pick in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   RICHMOND
</P>
<P>
   The R-Braves have the worst record in the International League,
but manager Randy Ingle still is nearing the 500 milestone in
career victories. Ingle, 42, went into the year with a
regular-season record of 455-442. This is his ninth season, the
second in AAA. . . . Chipper Jones and Dale Murphy headline
Richmond's all-time team. Jones was a shortstop for the R-Braves
and Murphy a catcher. Other familiar names include Dusty Baker,
Glenn Hubbard, Brett Butler, Darrell Evans and Ralph Garr. Tommie
Aaron, Hank's late brother, made the team as a player and a
manager. The team also included Paul Runge, now manager at
Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   GREENVILLE
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Mike Moore hit three homers in a 10-2 victory over
Carolina. Moore, who went into the game with just six homers, drove
in four runs. A former first-round draft choice of Los Angeles,
Moore was signed by the G-Braves after being released by Southern
League rival Huntsville. . . . Second baseman Marcus Giles stole 20
bases for the first time in his career. The Class AA all-star had a
.284 average, with 13 homers and 45 RBIs. . . . Right-hander Zach
Franchiseur, a former University of Georgia pitcher from Conyers,
moved into the starting rotation. Jason Flach switched to the
bullpen.MYRTLE BEACH
</P>
<P>
   The Pelicans edged Potomac 3-2 in 17 innings _ the longest game
in the Class A Carolina League this season. From the eighth into
the 17th inning, Pelican pitchers Tim Spooneybarger, Chris Chavez
and Michael Gray retired 27 consecutive batters. Catcher Steve
Torrealba singled home the winning run. Left-hander Jung Bong, just
called up from Macon, pitched the first six innings. He struck out
seven and walked none.MACON
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Matt Butler improved to 11-4 as he and two
relievers combined to two-hit Cape Fear 8-0 in the Class A South
Atlantic League. Butler allowed one hit and five walks in seven
innings. He struck out seven as he lowered his ERA to 3.00.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
