r a BC-MEXICO-LOST-LEFT-ECON     08-05 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-LOST-LEFT-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FUTURE OF MEXICO'S LEFTISTS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 750-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For much of the past decade, the left-of-center
Party of the Democratic Revolution (PRD) could claim to be the main
opposition to Mexico's long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party (PRI).
</P>
<P>
   So the triumph of Vicente Fox, the candidate of the
center-right, in last month's presidential election has thrown not
just the PRI into disarray, but the left too.
</P>
<P>
   The election was a crushing defeat for the PRD. Not only did
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, its candidate, gain fewer voters than in his
two previous presidential campaigns, but the party lost more than
half its congressional seats.
</P>
<P>
   When the new Congress assembles, it will have only 52 seats in
the 500-member lower house. And though the PRD's Andres Manuel
Lopez Obrador was elected as mayor of Mexico City, he won by a
narrower than expected margin.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Mexico City, the PRD governs just four other smallish
states, in alliance with other parties.
</P>
<P>
   Defeat has sparked recriminations. At a tumultuous meeting of
the PRD's national council last month, some members blamed the
mirthless Cardenas for his leaden campaigning; he was no match for
the charismatic Fox.
</P>
<P>
   But Cardenas in turn pointed the finger at the party's various
internal squabbles. He has a point. The PRD was born out of the
first, and almost successful, presidential campaign by Cardenas,
then a dissident PRI leader, in 1988. That campaign drew support
from a host of small left-wing parties and social organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cardenas's great strength was the diversity of his movement,
but on turning it into a party, that diversity became a defect,''
says Marco Rascon, a former PRD congressman.
</P>
<P>
   The PRD's diverse constituent groups became factions within the
party, vying for posts. Amalia Garcia, the party's chairwoman, and
herself the leader of one faction, complained during the national
council meeting that she had to spend 85 percent of her time
dealing with internal disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The council meeting ended with a vague agreement to work with
the new government, which is due to take office on Dec. 1. But that
masks a deep division on ideology: some believe the PRD should move
further left; others, towards the center.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the left should do well in a country where poverty is
widespread, and the gap between rich and poor is wide. But the
PRD's mixture of PRI-style nationalism and Marxism is useless now
that the Mexican economy is so closely integrated with that of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, argues Ricardo Pascoe, formerly a close aide
to Cardenas, so too is a wishy-washy ``third wayism'' borrowed from
more developed, and less unequal, countries. That policy debate may
be resolved, or excerbated, by a leadership struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas will gradually fade away _ though his sons, one of whom
is a state senator, may in time replace him.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the most influential voices are likely to be those of
two of the PRD's state governors: Lopez Obrador is, or was, a fiery
leftist; Ricardo Monreal, governor of Zacatecas, is a pragmatist
who in the past urged the party to support Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The PRD's best hope may lie, first, in offering effective local
government, especially in Mexico City. But it could also start to
gain support in the trade unions and farmers' organizations now
that the PRI has lost its huge power of central-government
patronage.
</P>
<P>
   The PRD will not, at least at first, face much competition from
the more extreme left: strikers who kept the National University in
Mexico City closed for ten months recently have run out of steam,
and the Zapatist guerrillas in the south are waiting to see how
Fox's government deals with them.
</P>
<P>
   But the underlying challenge for the PRD is to place itself once
again at the center of a broad movement, of the kind Rascon speaks
of.
</P>
<P>
   In the PRD's heyday, Rascon himself was better known as
Superbarrio: dressed in the mask and cape of a Mexican wrestler, he
campaigned for better housing for the poor in Mexico City, as a
leader of an Assembly of Neighborhood Associations which backed
Cardenas's 1988 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rascon looks respectable, with a mobile phone and a pager
hitched to his ample waist, minding the fish restaurant he opened a
month ago in one of the capital's gentrifying neighborhoods. Maybe
one of the PRD's problems is that Mexico is changing in ways that
the left has not foreseen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
