<HEADER>
A3637 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-INTERNET-PAYMENTS-ECO     08-05 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PAYMENTS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWFANGLED E-COMMERCE, OLD-FASHIONED CREDIT CARDS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 600-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ For all the growth of e-commerce, it has lagged
behind in one significant respect: payments. Almost all goods and
services bought on the Internet are paid for by old-fashioned
credit- or charge-cards. Yet for many sorts of transactions,
plastic is inappropriate or unusable.
</P>
<P>
   Most attempts to launch rival online payment-systems have been
false starts. But over the past few months, three big American
banks have been having another try.
</P>
<P>
   They are promoting new services aimed at filling one of the most
glaring gaps left by credit cards: settling person-to-person (P2P)
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, such payments are made in cash, or, failing
that, by checks and wire transfers. But these cannot meet the
demand on the Internet for immediate settlement of transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers and buyers in many online auctions, for instance, are
often individuals, rather than businesses. X.com, by some measures
the most successful online personal payment system, says 2.7
million people have signed up for its PayPal system, which lets
users transfer money by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Many are undoubtedly drawn by the $5 the company offers just for
trying the service, but PayPal is also the cheapest payment method
available. Its popularity has spawned a number of imitators.
</P>
<P>
   It has also forced banks to pay more attention to personal
payments, says James Van Dyke, an analyst with Jupiter
Communications, a research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo, one of the biggest Internet banks, is tackling the
threat head on. In March, it took an equity stake in Billpoint, a
payments service offered by eBay, an online auction site.
</P>
<P>
   Other banks have started to offer online remittances. In March,
Chicago's Bank One launched eMoneyMail, which _ as its name
suggests _ allows customers to e-mail money to each other from
their credit cards or bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup will soon launch a similar service in cooperation with
America Online, the biggest Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   So far, personal payments have been a niche market, but banks
have an incentive to make their initiatives work: they can easily
accommodate person-to-business transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Not only would this make e-commerce easier for the 12 million
American households without credit cards; it would also be
attractive to many credit-card holders, 41 percent of whom are
hesitant to divulge their card details online, according to a
Jupiter survey.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, such systems do not always offer shoppers the
protection that credit cards routinely provide against fraud
(though this week PayPal said it would start reimbursing victims of
some frauds).
</P>
<P>
   With credit cards, merchants bear most of the risk. Avivah
Litan, an analyst with GartnerGroup, a consultancy, says online
businesses encounter credit-card fraud 12 times more often than
offline merchants. As a result, credit-card firms charge about
two-thirds more in transaction fees than they do for sales where
the card is physically present.
</P>
<P>
   Credit cards also usually set a minimum transaction size. This
has impeded the development of ``micropayments,'' where consumers
might, for example, pay a fraction of a cent to download a file.
</P>
<P>
   As yet, the volumes handled by personal services barely
register, when compared with older systems. Bank One, for example,
has managed to process just 15,000 eMoneyMail transactions in five
months of operation.
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Dieringer, eMoneyMail's general manager, believes
volumes will grow as Bank One promotes the system and ties it more
closely to customers' accounts. He is probably right that other
banks will follow suit, and that P2P will grow into more than just
a cute way to buy Beanie babies. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
