<P>
   SCI is also trying to trim its costs by cutting down on
expensive salesmen, and pitching its prepaid funeral plans directly
to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The company has long had ``affinity'' relationships with
organizations representing its target market, such as a British
charity for the old, Age Concern. Now it is extending these to
America's big companies, which are starting to offer SCI's
discounted funeral packages to their employees.
</P>
<P>
   And SCI's new Web site, dignitymemorial.com, allows visitors to
find their nearest funeral home. Eventually, the company hopes that
globe-trotting consumers will be able to buy a standard plan over
the Web that can be delivered at any of its 3,800 funeral homes
worldwide _ which are in the process of being branded as part of
SCI's network.
</P>
<P>
   Chiarelli reckons that the companies' focus on improving
internal operations and greater customer convenience, along with
their steady market share, may lure back investors.
</P>
<P>
   Although SCI's second-quarter profit figures, being released on
Aug. 8, will be lower than expected, it has already reduced its
debt to a year-end target of $3.6 billion-3.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite a resurrection, perhaps, but still less a cause for
mourning. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3642 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-PALL-FUNERAL-BIZ-ECON     08-05 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALL-FUNERAL-BIZ-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEATH INDUSTRY STRUGGLES TO STAY ALIVE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 575-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Barring a sudden outbreak of immortality, one would
expect undertaking to be a nice, steady business. Not so, according
to Fran Bernstein, an analyst with Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The past 18 months have been rather gruelling for America's
funeral industry. The top three U.S.-quoted companies, which
control roughly a fifth of the country's $30 billion market, have
seen their share prices collapse since the start of 1999. And a
fourth, Loewen, is now in the final throes of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Too much debt and too few deaths are largely to blame.
Historically, funeral firms' profits growth has been fuelled by
consolidation, with large firms buying up small, mom-and-pop
funeral parlors across America and overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The top companies, such as Service Corporation International
(SCI) and Stewart Enterprises, spent almost $9.3 billion on
acquisitions in the 1990s, according to Joseph Chiarelli, a
``post-life'' industry analyst at J.P. Morgan. But competition led
to consolidators paying hefty premiums for their purchases,
plunging many into debt.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse for a high-fixed-cost business, the number of deaths
in America has flattened out since 1998 to roughly 2.3 million a
year, after a steady rise of 1 percent a year for most of the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   With investors deserting the business, acquisitions are no
longer an option. Companies are instead selling peripheral assets.
</P>
<P>
   In July, SCI announced the sale of its French and American
insurance businesses, netting the firm $275 million in badly needed
cash. It has also sold its operations in Northern Ireland,
consisting largely of Protestant funeral homes in what have become
predominantly Catholic areas.
</P>
<P>
   The firms also have to grapple with a funeral market that is
changing fast. As Bill Rowe, head of Stewart Enterprises, points
out, today's customers expect something more personal than black
crepe and tasteful wreaths for the $5,000 they are paying out.
</P>
<P>
   So as well as catering to a growing demand for cremation,
Stewart offers a catalogue of less conventional arrangements, such
as New Orleans jazz funerals and ``permanent'' memorial Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   SCI too has expanded its products to include post-funeral
services such as legal assistance, bereavement counselling and
family archiving.
</P>
<P>
   SCI is also trying to trim its costs by cutting down on
expensive salesmen, and pitching its prepaid funeral plans directly
to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The company has long had ``affinity'' relationships with
organizations representing its target market, such as a British
charity for the old, Age Concern. Now it is extending these to
America's big companies, which are starting to offer SCI's
discounted funeral packages to their employees.
</P>
<P>
   And SCI's new Web site, dignitymemorial.com, allows visitors to
find their nearest funeral home. Eventually, the company hopes that
globe-trotting consumers will be able to buy a standard plan over
the Web that can be delivered at any of its 3,800 funeral homes
worldwide _ which are in the process of being branded as part of
SCI's network.
</P>
<P>
   Chiarelli reckons that the companies' focus on improving
internal operations and greater customer convenience, along with
their steady market share, may lure back investors.
</P>
<P>
   Although SCI's second-quarter profit figures, being released on
Aug. 8, will be lower than expected, it has already reduced its
debt to a year-end target of $3.6 billion-3.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite a resurrection, perhaps, but still less a cause for
mourning. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
