<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3643 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-US-EMBASSY-JERUSALEM?     08-05 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-EMBASSY-JERUSALEM?-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN EMBASSY IN JERUSALEM HITS A SNAG  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 575-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   EAST JERUSALEM _ Praising Ehud Barak for his courage at Camp
David _ and implicitly criticizing Yasser Arafat for showing less _
U.S. President Bill Clinton has raised the controversial matter of
moving America's embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   He has always wanted to do this, he said, but has held back
because of the damage it might do the peace process. Now, ``in the
light of what has happened,'' he would be reviewing the situation,
and would come to a decision before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Congress passed a law to move the embassy to Jerusalem,
which was supposed to come into effect in May 1999, the original
deadline for a Palestinian-Israeli final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Because the deadline was lost, and negotiations continued,
Clinton has had to invoke America's ``critical national security
interests'' three times in the past 18 months to delay the move.
</P>
<P>
   If he now decides to let Congress have its way, America would
join Costa Rica and El Salvador in recognizing Jerusalem as
Israel's capital, a step no other country has yet taken.
</P>
<P>
   International law defines Israel as an ``occupying power'' in
East Jerusalem and as the de facto power in West Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Quite apart from what it would do to America's efforts to serve
as honest broker in the search for peace in the Middle East, moving
the American embassy to Jerusalem would spill out a cascade of
subsidiary issues.
</P>
<P>
   One of these is the fact that the 3.2 hectares (8 acres) of land
in West Jerusalem designated for the embassy may not be Israel's to
lease. Before 1948, the area was home to some of the city's richest
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   After Congress's 1995 ruling, a Palestinian historian, Walid
Khalidi, did a little spadework. He found that most of the land
designated for the embassy site had belonged to 19 Palestinian
families. The descendants and heirs of these families now ``number
hundreds,'' says Khalidi, including at least 90 who are American
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing these Americans have already said they will
take their government to court if it builds an embassy on ``stolen
land.''
</P>
<P>
   That awkwardness would lead to others, one of them being the
question of restitution for Palestinian-owned properties throughout
the pre-1948 Mandate for Palestine, including West Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   According to Palestinian studies, Palestinian families hold the
deeds to some 40 percent of all properties in West Jerusalem;
another 36 percent belong to the Islamic Religious Trust, the
Christian churches and the British government.
</P>
<P>
   The private properties are the patrimony of the 90,000
Palestinians who fled from, or were driven out of, the Jerusalem
area during the 1948 war. Today these refugees and their
descendants number nearly 200,000 people. Many of them live in East
Jerusalem and the West Bank, some almost within sight of their
former homes.
</P>
<P>
   Individual claims for some form of restitution are going to be
put on the table, says Salim Tamari, a Palestinian sociologist who
has recently written a book about Palestinian property in West
Jerusalem (``Jerusalem 1948: The Arab Neighborhoods and Their Fate
in the War,'' published by the Institute of Jerusalem Studies).
</P>
<P>
   This is not because the Palestinians like to dwell on past
grievances, says Tamari, but because ``their homes have been taken
over by people who at the same time are claiming Jewish properties
in East Jerusalem. It won't wash.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
