<HEADER>
A3649 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-UNIFIL-LEBANON-ECONOM     08-05 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIFIL-LEBANON-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. FENCE-MENDERS IN LEBANON  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 450-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MARKABA, LEBANON _ On the pine-scented slopes along the
Lebanese-Israeli border, a platoon of United Nations peacekeepers
at last arrives to start the job they were first given 22 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five Ghanaian soldiers stake out a patch of soil
belonging to Lebanon, but repeatedly encroached upon by the Israeli
army. Having helped define the border, they must now prevent
incidents along it.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a twitchy Israeli foot-patrol that watches the
sightseers, and forbids cross-border sales of ice cream, while the
Ghanaians look on unconcerned. At the first sign of trouble, an
Israeli soldier says, the peacekeepers will turn tail and run.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, UNIFIL, as the U.N.'s acronym division has dubbed the
force, is famous for holding its ground. It came to southern
Lebanon in 1978 to ``confirm'' Israel's withdrawal and to help the
Lebanese government restore its authority.
</P>
<P>
   But the Israelis stayed put and battled Lebanese guerrillas.
UNIFIL, with no mandate to evict them, could only sit by and wait
for them to leave _ for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the force provided what humanitarian assistance
it could to local villagers and meticulously recorded each blow to
the peace it had hoped to keep.
</P>
<P>
   To date, 82 UNIFIL soldiers have been killed in the cross-fire.
For the most part, however, the job is mundane: inspecting car
trunks and patrolling empty hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   UNIFIL's Indian contingent, for example, keeps 30 men on
permanent alert at each of its three checkpoints, all for the sake
of the two or three occasions a month when someone tries to take a
gun through or drive past without stopping.
</P>
<P>
   They call one of the valleys in their zone ``Hezbollah highway''
after the guerrillas who are said to sneak through it, but none of
them has seen one.
</P>
<P>
   Their engineering division spends its time building football
playing fields, mending roads and righting cars that have turned
turtle.
</P>
<P>
   Locals love them for their free clinics, their expert vet, and
for the vague sense they convey that the world has not abandoned
south Lebanon. But there is little UNIFIL can do without the
cooperation of the Lebanese and Israeli governments.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, the Israelis mounted a full-scale invasion of Lebanon
under UNIFIL's nose. In 1996, Israeli shelling killed over 100
Lebanese civilians sheltering at a UNIFIL base in the village of
Qana.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the Lebanese government has been impeding UNIFIL's work,
refusing to allow its troops to patrol the border with Israel until
niggling territorial disputes have been settled.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the Ghanaian platoon arrived at Markaba, Lebanon
called off the redeployment, only to relent again a day later. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
