<HEADER>
A3651 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-FLOP-DOT.COMS-ECONOMI     08-05 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOP-DOT.COMS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUMORS OF DOT.COMS' DEMISE ARE GREATLY EXAGGERATED  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 450-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not the beginning of the end, more the end of the
beginning _ or perhaps only the beginning of the end of the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of dot.com burnouts and layoffs, the numbers
from America suggest that worse is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem with Internet companies (aside from huge losses
and dwindling supplies of cash at many of them) is not that there
have been too many failures but that there have been too few.
</P>
<P>
   Even in good times, some 40 percent of all new businesses fail
within their first five years of operation, according to Census
Bureau figures. In America as a whole, more than 70,000 companies
went bust during 1998, almost half as many as were started that
year.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the drumbeat of Internet failures is still
incredibly faint.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least 3,000 dot.com start-ups backed by American
venture-capital firms, according to VentureOne, a consultancy. Some
50,000 firms in America get some or all of their revenues from the
Internet, according to the University of Texas at Austin's Center
for Research on Electronic Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows quite how many of these have gone bankrupt, but the
available lists are shockingly short. The Industry Standard's
``dot.com flop tracker'' lists only 21 as of July 18.
Dotcomfailures.com lists a mere 20.
</P>
<P>
   Layoffs tell the same thin story. The University of Texas
research team calculates that 2.5 million Americans are employed in
the dot.com economy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet total American dot.com layoffs from December to July
amounted to only 6,800 in 118 companies, according to a study by
Challenger, Gray and Christmas, a recruitment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast this with a single announcement this week by Bank of
America, which plans to shed 10,000 workers over the next year
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Every year more than 1 million Americans lose their jobs, or
about 1 percent of the total employed. If dot.coms were simply to
meet this unexceptional norm, much less exceed it, as the headlines
would suggest they are, they would have to be making 25,000 layoffs
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Even accounting for considerable under-reporting, the Internet
industry broadly defined (including both risky start-ups and
larger, more established firms) is still running well below the
usual rate.
</P>
<P>
   All of which suggests two things. First, that the number of
layoffs and failures will rise dramatically, if for no other reason
than to reach the norms in other businesses. And, second, that this
is no bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   After all the dot.com mania of the past couple of years,
business as usual _ with all the failures that implies _ ought to
be welcomed, not feared. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
