<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACKING BUSH ON BASEBALL, THAT COULD BE THE TICKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
Attacking Bush on baseball, that could be the ticket 
The phone was ringing early Friday morning. The name that popped up
on the handy caller ID read: A. Gore.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But it couldn't be ``that'' ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me introduce myself,'' said the familiar voice. ``I'm your
vice president. And I'm running for president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I heard about all that. How can I help you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for my call is I have an important speech coming up
this month out in LA. This requires doing extensive research on my
opponent. I needed to check some facts with an independent
journalist, so ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``With a what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``An independent journalist. That's you, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I know of. I'm a sportswriter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, but as a sportswriter you spent, like, five years
reporting on a baseball team that was owned by my opponent,
correct?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, owned in part by ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``But he had the title of managing general partner, so he called
all the ownership shots. He's the guy who traded Sammy Sosa,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No ... that was Tom Grieve, the general manager at the time.
And the manager, Bobby Valentine, also had a large hand in it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But who was in charge? Who had the final sign-off on that
trade of Sammy Sosa?''
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, I guess you're right. But what the heck does any of
this have to do with being a candidate for president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You call yourself a sportswriter? And you still don't
understand? Can we go off the record?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure. What's your point here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is top secret. But our party platform, and our campaign
slogan coming out of the national convention this month will be:
`Does This Country Need Another Harold Baines?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, this is pure genius. That's how we win in
November. We beat him on his baseball record. All that nasty stuff
I'm been saying about Texas since he became governor _ it's nothing
but a smoke screen. But baseball is something all of America
understands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now hold it. He was actually a good owner, I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you, some kind of Republican? This was the worst
trade in the history of baseball. He gave up Sammy Sosa and Wilson
Alvarez for a lifeless bum in Harold Baines. Any man who has that
on his record is not qualified to be president of the United
States. And the American people will agree with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Big Al. C'mon. It was 11 years ago. 1989. That was the
first season of ownership for those guys. He was trying to be the
right kind of professional sports owner. He had people in place who
knew baseball. He was delegating authority. He was doing it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, sure ... just try to sell that to Sam Donaldson. I
watched their convention last night. I heard my opponent up there,
taking his shots at me. He crowed about the buck stopping here.
Well, I've got news for the man. In a couple of weeks, his buck is
gonna stop on Sammy Sosa. `Now is the time' _ that's what he kept
saying in his speech. But the time is coming, and real soon, when
he'll have to explain Harold Baines, and a lot of other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of stuff?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't run a baseball team, you can't run this country.
That's my platform. And the American people will agree with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, Big Al, he had five pretty good baseball years here,
everything considered. He took over a franchise that had totally
bottomed out, and ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``You must have been covering too much Cowboys in those days.
The early '90s, Jimmy started winning Super Bowls, and you let my
opponent slide over there in Arlington. That's it, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then what was the Rangers' record from '89 to '93, meaning on
his watch?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Offhand, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do. Try 414 wins, 396 losses. In five years, the team was 18
games over .500. Pitiful. If he's elected, his economic program
will have about the same kind of growth. How close did the Rangers
ever come to first place in that time? Got the answer right here.
Eight games. Not even close to being a contender. His baseball team
was a boring loser. Come November, the American people won't accept
that from a president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the team became economically feasible in the early '90s,
and that helped in some later success on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop protecting this guy. When the money started coming in,
what did he do to improve the club? Did he sign free agents?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, he did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, but let me give you those names. How about the immortal
Manny Lee. Did Gary Pettis thrill you? Or Dickie Thon? What about
bringing back Tom Henke when Henke was already washed up? Like I've
been saying all along, your guy doesn't know what to do with a
surplus budget. And this proves it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't agree with you. I don't think politics and baseball
are an accurate mix.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are so wrong. Just wait 'til my speech in LA when I remind
the American people that my opponent allowed Rafael Palmeiro to
walk in free agency, then he was thrilled about signing Will Clark
to replace him. When I hit him over the head with that one, I may
even carry Texas. Or at least Tarrant County.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to admit it, but that Raffy stuff is, well, damaging.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My man, you ain't heard nothing yet. I gotta go now. Bill is
holding on the hotline. But remember what I told you _ baseball is
bigger than politics, and this country can't afford another Harold
Baines.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
