<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-SURGERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD HAS SURGERY TO RELIEVE ABSCESS CAUSED BY RARE INFECTION
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former President Gerald Ford underwent successful
surgery in a Philadelphia hospital Saturday to relieve swelling in
his tongue from a rare bacterial infection, his doctors reported.
</P>
<P>
   The infection was unrelated to the stroke that caused Ford to be
admitted last Wednesday to Hahnemann University Hospital in
Philadelphia during the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the 87-year-old former president was on a path to
full recovery from both the stroke and the abscess in his tongue
and was resting comfortably at the hospital. A biopsy showed no
sign of a tumor causing the pain and swelling in his tongue, the
hospital reported. Doctors diagnosed the condition as a case of a
bacterial infection known as actinomycosis, a common oral bacillus
that rarely attacks the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   The abscess was drained, easing the swelling considerably,
doctors reported. Ford received a general anesthetic for the
25-minute surgical procedure and, after 30 minutes of recovery,
returned to his room where he was reported awake and alert as he
was greeted by his wife, Betty, and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's now, I think, completely recovered from his small
stroke,'' said Dr. Robert J. Schwartzman, the hospital's chief
neurologist, who said Ford's blood-thinning drugs were receiving a
final adjustment. ``As soon as that is accomplished he should be
ready to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   The pocket of infection deep within the tongue was described as
an exceedingly rare condition with so little casebook precedents
that the doctors declined to speculate on how the tongue became
infected. The doctors and Ford's spokesman, Calvin McDowell,
unofficially referred to it as ``the president's syndrome'' in
discussing it at a news conference at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``There simply aren't enough cases for us to draw conclusions in
the medical literature,'' said Dr. Richard Hayden, chairman of the
hospital's department of otolaryngology, who performed the surgical
procedure on the former president.
</P>
<P>
   ``His comfort level is markedly improved and his speech has come
back,'' Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   After being saluted at the convention Tuesday night, Ford later
went to the hospital and told doctors he was suffering acute facial
pain. He was told he probably had a bad sinus infection and was
given some antibiotics and released.
</P>
<P>
   But after a sleepless night, Ford returned to the hospital about
9 a.m. Wednesday, once more walking in on his own. The symptoms
were worse, he told doctors, and besides pain included dizziness,
numbness and an inability to speak without slurring words.
</P>
<P>
   Tests indicated that he had suffered at least one mild stroke in
the rear portion of the brain that controls basic functions like
balance, speech and swallowing, doctors reported.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was admitted to the neurological intensive care unit and,
within a day's treatment that included blood-thinning drugs,
doctors reported he was doing much better and could expect a full
recovery from the stroke. He was making such good progress that
hospital officials permitted Gov. George W. Bush to visit him for
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With Ford neurologically stable, the doctors decided to treat
the tongue abscess Saturday morning. As part of the treatment
following the surgery, Ford, who is allergic to penicillin, began
taking the antibiotics Clindamycin and Levofloxacin. Hayden
predicted a full recovery in the next several weeks with Ford to be
treated on an outpatient basis after he returns home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in great spirits,'' McDowell said. ``Everyone is very
excited. Ford is calling it a `beautiful day and beautiful news.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
