<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLASTATE-PREVIEW0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QB Weinke 'Noles' statesman
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chris Weinke knows he is not the average college
quarterback. The reminders are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was filling out a form for a physical the other day, and
another player was standing next to me,'' said the
</P>
<P>
   Florida State senior. ``I was born in 1972. He was born in
1982.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke, who spent six years in pro baseball's minor leagues
before returning to college football in 1997, turned 28 on July 31.
A week ago, he skipped the 10-year reunion of his high school
senior class in Minneapolis. Probably just as well, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Chris, what are you doing these days?'' Weinke asked,
mocking a potential question. ``Uh, I'm still in college.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of self-deprecating humor has served Weinke well
during his successful reign as college football's elder statesman.
He is 21-1 as a starting quarterback. But when the subject turns to
Florida State's effort to defend its 1999 national championship,
the joking stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people out there who think we aren't hungry, that
we're going to be complacent,'' said Weinke, who led the Seminoles
to a 12-0 season in 1999, capped by a 46-29 win over Virginia Tech
in the Sugar Bowl. ``That is the biggest mistake they could make.
We are working harder now than we did a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke is seeing to that, and the work began with himself. After
making the decision to return for his senior season, the 6-foot-5
Weinke threw himself into a stringent workout program to add muscle
and quickness. Last season, when he was returning from a November
1998 neck injury that nearly ended his career, Weinke bulked up to
245 pounds in an effort to protect himself.
</P>
<P>
   The pro scouts, who projected Weinke no higher than a
third-round pick in the 2000 NFL draft, told him he needed to get
quicker. He has, by slimming down to 229 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really had to tell me that I needed to get quicker; it
was obvious,'' said Weinke, who threw for 3,103 yards and 25
touchdowns last season. ``But last year, I was just worried about
taking a hit and surviving. Now, I'm doing everything I can to be
the best I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's in the best shape of his life, Weinke is demanding
the same of his teammates. He is in the weight room three days a
week because he thinks it is important for the younger players to
see him there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be a leader, you can talk all you want,'' he
said. ``Until you lead by example, nobody is going to respect you.
I learned that in baseball, where there were guys who could talk
and guys who could play.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, he led nightly throwing sessions in Tallahassee
that drew as many as 60 Florida State players. Coaches are not
allowed at such informal workouts, but Weinke stepped in to run the
show.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance isn't mandatory, but . . . ``If a guy shows up and
he's been gone for a couple of weeks, he knows he's going to get
his butt chewed out,'' Weinke said. ``I don't have any problem
calling a guy out in front of everybody if he's not coming to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bowden, set to begin his 25th season as the Seminoles'
coach, loves to hear it. Florida State has handled success well, in
posting 13 consecutive seasons of 10 wins or more. A player like
Weinke just makes his job easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not trade that guy for any other quarterback in
America,'' said Bowden, who has 304 career victories. There may be
some who are more talented, but there is not a better leader
anywhere. He is the perfect quarterback for our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss of All-America receiver Peter Warrick, Weinke
said, this Florida State offense actually has a chance to be better
than the explosive unit of a year ago that averaged 37.5 points per
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete was a special player but this offense can be better
because now we can spread the ball around to eight or nine
different receivers,'' he said. ``I was guilty of looking to Pete a
lot, because if I could get it to him, he could always make a big
play. But we've got a lot of guys on this team that nobody's really
heard about. And they are pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles have just one way to improve on the first 12-0
season in Florida State history, he said. With an early game
against BYU, on Aug. 26 in Jacksonville, the 2000 team potentially
could go 13-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I came back,'' Weinke said. ``I've got one national
championship, but I guess I'm greedy. I want another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
