u s BC-MINOR-BALL0806-COX     08-05 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-BALL0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This is the version on the 0806 budget.
 &HT;    Gimmicks key to moving the turnstiles
 &HT;    By Jeff Ostrowski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER _ It's a sweltering afternoon at the home of the Jupiter
Hammerheads, and Pat Hathaway and his 8-year-old son Andrew sit in
the stands and cheer.
</P>
<P>
   Hathaway brings his son to the ballpark about once a month. He's
lured by the Hammerheads' affordable tickets _ $4 to $5 each _ and
by minor league baseball's laid-back atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Although the team's alumni include Major League stars such as
Vladimir Guerrero, Hathaway isn't here for the quality of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the minors there are a lot more errors than in the majors,
so that makes it exciting,'' Hathaway says.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Florida State League. It's Class A baseball, near
the entry level to the professional game. The typical player has a
couple of years of minor league experience and makes about $1,200 a
month, plus meal money.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball might be a little rough, but many fans pay scant
attention to the games. They're more interested in giveaways such
as Pokemon trinkets and promotions such as sky-diving Elvis
impersonators.
</P>
<P>
   Fans such as Hathaway _ unlike big league fans _ typically don't
care whether a minor league club is in first place or last.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sellout crowds are as rare as profitable teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida State League's average attendance is 1,000, giving
the 14-team league one of the lowest attendance totals in minor
league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   If crowds are sparse, profitable seasons are scarcer. The median
loss for the 14 teams in the Florida State League in 1999 was
$216,077.
</P>
<P>
   The teams blame a variety of factors, including hot and rainy
weather, Florida's notoriously fickle sports fans and a plethora of
competing entertainment choices that vie for fans' time and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tough draw,'' acknowledges Mike Veeck, a co-owner
of the Florida State League's Fort Myers Miracle and three other
minor league clubs throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Miracle are one of only two independently owned teams in the
14-team league. The Hammerheads, St. Lucie Mets and Vero Beach
Dodgers are owned by their big league parents, and all three lose
money.
</P>
<P>
   Veeck says his team is profitable.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12 years the Montreal Expos have owned the Hammerheads,
the former West Palm Beach Expos have turned a profit for only one
season, and then just $10,000. In the team's other 11 seasons, the
Hammerheads have lost as much as $190,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, Dodgers and Miracle wouldn't reveal their loss or
profit.
</P>
<P>
   The Hammerheads' losses are narrowing, says Rob Rabenecker,
general manager of Jupiter's Roger Dean Stadium, thanks largely to
the team's $30 million home that opened in 1998. The 7,000-seat
park was designed by HOK, the architectural firm responsible for
well-received stadiums such as Camden Yards in Baltimore and Jacobs
Field in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   At the team's former home, West Palm Beach Municipal Stadium, an
outfield that wouldn't drain canceled games even on days when it
didn't rain.
</P>
<P>
   The Hammerheads' attendance shot to 90,000 in 1998, the team's
first season in Jupiter, up from 65,000 in 1997, the last season in
West Palm Beach. The team's net loss narrowed to $161,222 in 1998
from $186,263 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Hammerheads lost $54,177; Rabenecker expects the
club to turn a profit this year.
</P>
<P>
   If the Hammerheads become profitable, the black ink won't flow
from a winning record. Rather, Rabenecker says, profit will come
because the team pays attention to the cleanliness of its park, the
quality of its concessions and the attractiveness of its
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Minor league teams don't control the players they receive from
major league parents. Therefore, gimmicks are key to moving the
turnstiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Hammerheads gave out Pokemon coins during a game last month,
and the team has handed out backpacks. An Independence Day
fireworks show was a big draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just open the gates, we're going to get 250 or 300
people,'' Rabenecker says.
</P>
<P>
   While minor league baseball is known for bizarre promotions, the
Hammerheads' gimmicks are of the vanilla variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play it pretty straight-up,'' Rabenecker says. ``We're
trying to position ourselves as family entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because racier promotions proved distasteful, Rabenecker
says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, for instance, the West Palm Beach Expos brought in
Morganna, the busty groupie who gained fame by doddering onto
fields to kiss star players during games.
</P>
<P>
   Rabenecker was disturbed by the ruckus Morganna caused during
her one-game visit. He saw one father and son at the game; the
father held a copy of Playboy magazine for Morganna to sign.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the Expos hired Captain Dynamite, whose act consisted
of taking his Coffin of Doom to the pitcher's mound, dousing it
with kerosene and setting off a deafening explosion. As a side
effect, the pitcher's mound caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd went nuts,'' Rabenecker recalls. ``But I'm standing
there with the groundskeeper, and his eyes were bugging out.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the type of promotions Mike Veeck loves. He's the son
of the late Chicago White Sox owner Bill Veeck, a promotions wizard
who as owner of the St. Louis Browns had the 3-foot-7 Eddie Gaedel
pinch hit to draw a walk. (He did.)
</P>
<P>
   Baseball promoters consider the younger Veeck a pioneer of minor
league baseball marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Among Veeck's brainstorms: ``Field of Screams,'' a promotion in
Fort Myers that involved showing all-night horror movies on the
field after the game. He's also had mimes re-create close plays and
gave away inflatable bats sponsored by Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like double-entendres,'' Veeck says.
</P>
<P>
   The Vero Beach Dodgers haven't dared to be quite so risque, but
the team did hire guys to dress up in sequined Elvis outfits, jump
out of a plane and land on the field at Holman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the team sponsored a ``Dog Days of Summer''
promotion. Canines who paid for their owners received free tickets,
and the concession stands doled out doggie biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Vero's Dodgers might play on the same grass where Jackie
Robinson and Sandy Koufax once took the field during spring
training, but what really keeps the fans coming back isn't
tradition, says Dodgers General Manager Grant Griesser. It's
fireworks, sky-diving Elvises and seat cushion giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough sell,'' Griesser says. ``You can't just open the
gates and say, `Hey, we've got a baseball game.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Lucie Mets have a similar strategy, says Mets General
Manager Paul Taglieri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we're 20 games out of first place, we still have to
try to put on a show,'' Taglieri says. ``Our competition is the
movie theater, the roller skating rink across the street, going out
to dinner, the mall.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
