<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS AIM TO AVERT WALKOUT AT VERIZON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiations continued into the night Saturday as Verizon
Communications sought to head off a strike by thousands of service
representatives and technicians who threatened to walk off their
jobs at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the company's refusal to yield to labor officials'
demands to unionize employees in its wireless division, some 85,000
workers planned to strike shortly after the 11:55 p.m. Saturday
expiration of a two-year contract with Verizon Communications,
formerly Bell Atlantic. Of those workers, about 15,000 live in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to be terribly optimistic at the same time,'' said
Eric Rabe, a Verizon spokesman, during a late afternoon conference
call, ``but we're committed to doing everything we can to reach a
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The walkout would affect 25 million customers from Maine to
Virginia who are seeking installation or repairs of telephone lines
or who wish to add services. However, Verizon spokesman Steve
Marcus said the network would continue to function and customers
can still make and receive telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made some contingency plans, and we will have managers
fill in, about 30,000 managers, for some of these jobs,'' said
Marcus. ``We will, obviously, do everything we can to service
customers, but there will likely be some delays. The emphasis will
be on making repairs and keeping people connected to the network
rather than installing new services.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the company and the Communications Workers of
America, which represents 72,000 Verizon workers on the East Coast,
and the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, which
represents 13,000 employees, began June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations stalled over the unions' demands for contract
language that would guarantee job security in a changing
telecommunications market. At the top of this job security list: a
request for an agreement to guarantee voluntary card check
arrangements as well as expedited elections at Verizon Wireless,
the company's fast-growing wireless unit.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 42 of the wireless unit's 3,500 workers are
unionized. CWA organizers contend technical and service workers at
Verizon Wireless receive lower benefits, work longer hours, and, in
some cases, earn less pay than their union counterparts in other
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The walkout, the second by the CWA in two years, marks the
continuation of a life-and-death battle for both sides. Experts say
Verizon may be reluctant to yield on the issue of unionization,
particularly since many of its competitors are not unionized. At
the same time, the two unions must break into the growing wireless
telecommunications sector or face certain membership decline in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, to be unionized was not a competitive
disadvantage (for telephone companies),'' said Jeffrey Kagan, a
telecommunications analyst in Atlanta. ``But it is now. They face
competitors who are not unionized. Instead, every employee of every
successful telecom and tech company in this new economy is treated
like an owner, and they act like owners. They don't work to rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Bernard, director of the Harvard Trade Union Program,
likened the dispute to past labor disputes that have arisen over
double-breasting in the construction industry, which occurs when a
contractor creates a nonunion ``sister'' entity that hires only
nonunion workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the telecommunications industry's future,'' Bernard
said. ``But the fact that these firms are set up as a nonunion
sector is particularly galling to the unions, since they had
reached an agreement with Bell Atlantic that had called for
neutrality (in union organizing).''
</P>
<P>
   CWA said prior to its merger with Bell Atlantic Corp., Nynex
Mobile had agreed to a card check agreement and had recognized both
unions as bargaining representatives for sales and technicians in
Boston and New York. That was in 1992 and 1993, respectively. The
unions maintain that in 1995, after Bell Atlantic took over Nynex
Mobile, it declined to negotiate with either union.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews last week, Marcus said the company was willing to
discuss the matter but felt ``that it is really an issue for
Verizon Wireless, our subsidiary. Verizon Wireless is a separate
company and it is responsible for its own labor relations.''
</P>
<P>
   The unions have made some headway in a handful of wireless
units. At AT&AMP;T Wireless, they have won the right to institute a
voluntary card check procedure. Additionally, CWA has organized
some 5,000 wireless workers at SBC Communications, which owns
CellularOne. SBC's wireless units have a total payroll of 14,000
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Under such an agreement, the union can either declare itself the
sole bargaining agent for a group of workers after securing a
majority of union card signatures, or it gains the right to hold an
election within 10 days, with certification by the American
Arbitration Association. The organizing technique has, at many
unions, replaced the use of standard elections, which are often
challenged by employers.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon, fearful that union work rules and contracts will stymie
growth and prevent it from lowering prices when necessary, has
refused to budge on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
