<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-REAL-GOP0806-COX     08-05 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-REAL-GOP0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    While party shows unusual diversity, platform unaltered
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The more inclusive Republican Party that George W.
Bush led out of Philadelphia on Friday stands for a no-exceptions
ban on abortion and limiting sex education to teaching about
abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   While an openly gay GOP congressman addressed the convention for
the first time, speaking about trade, not gay rights, delegates
defeated efforts to rid the party platform of its calls for bans on
gay marriage and gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans congratulated themselves last week for their new
interest in diversity and a willingness to listen to dissenting
points of view. ``We commit to resolve our differences with
civility, trust and mutual respect,'' reads the introduction to the
platform section on ``Renewing Family and Community.''
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP remains committed to conservative social policies
that do not always square with the friendlier image that emanated
from Philadelphia. And the tension inherent in Bush's compassionate
conservatism might lead some voters to wonder which is the real
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the policy was geared to the conservative element in our
party,'' said Susan Cullman of the Republican Pro-Choice Coalition.
``All the public face was geared to the moderates in the rest of
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, a consultant to the Bush campaign and former
Christian Coalition executive, had a different take. ``We remain a
conservative party,'' Reed said, ``but this is a party that is
lowering the barrier to entry and opening the door wide to
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Tensions within the Republican and Democratic parties are, of
course, nothing new. The two modern parties succeed by knitting
together disparate groups.
</P>
<P>
   The platform is just one element in this delicate balancing act:
How does a party broaden its appeal without turning off its core
support?
</P>
<P>
   Yet this year, mindful of defeats in two presidential elections,
the Bush campaign has made a special point of playing up a
compassionate side of its conservative message.
</P>
<P>
   The early reviews are promising for Republicans. Polls of likely
voters taken throughout the week showed Bush increasing his lead
over Vice President Al Gore, even among women and independent
voters. These socially moderate voters, who backed Bill Clinton in
1992 and 1996, are widely thought to be keys to the outcome of the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats already have begun to try to exploit what they see
as discrepancies between GOP rhetoric and sub- stance.
</P>
<P>
   On abortion, Republicans tried to round off the edges of their
position by encouraging adoption (though only for heterosexual
couples) and giving assurances they oppose ``punitive action
against women who have an abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the platform unambiguously calls for outlawing all
abortions and appointing federal judges who oppose abortion rights.
Bush favors keeping abortion legal in limited cases and opposes any
litmus tests for judicial appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Republican abortion rights supporters hoped in vain that they
would win changes in the platform language. ``I have since 1976
been hoping we'd come to a point where this wouldn't be an issue,
but I've decided we're never going to reach that point,'' said Jo
Ann Davidson, the speaker of the Ohio House of Representatives and
a member of the platform committee.
</P>
<P>
   Cullman, the leader of the GOP's abortion rights advocates, said
she continues to believe that most Republicans do not feel as
strongly about abortion as the delegates to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complete ban on abortion and the litmus test on judges are
outrageous,'' Cullman said. ``And I didn't hear Governor Bush
remind us that he doesn't have a litmus test.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor, she said, is that a group of undecided voters
who watched Bush's speech under the gaze of Republican pollster
Frank Luntz generally liked what they heard, except for the
speech's segment on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the same proclamation of support for the ``life of the
unborn'' and an end to so-called partial birth abortions drew the
heartiest applause of the night inside the convention hall in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, former presidential candidate Gary Bauer, who
repeatedly attacked Bush for his silence on abortion during the GOP
primary campaign, lavished praise on his former opponent. ``In his
speech, the governor addressed the pro-life message compellingly
and definitively,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Concerning sex education, Sen. Bill Frist (R-Tenn.), a surgeon
and co-chairman of the platform committee, failed to make the
platform more moderate.
</P>
<P>
   As approved by the convention, the platform reads, ``We renew
our call for replacing `family planning' programs for teens with
increased funding for abstinence education, which teaches
abstinence until marriage as the responsible and expected standard
of behavior. . . . We oppose school-based clinics that provide
referrals, counseling and related services for contraception and
abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Frist sought to omit the references to family planning and
contraception. His committee would not go along.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was wrong,'' said Carolyn Meadows, a delegate from Georgia.
``We have things in our platform that define us from the
Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Cullman, addressing the same topic, said, ``The idea of throwing
out funding for family planning and replacing it with abstinence
only is like having your head in the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights was one area in which the Bush campaign would have
preferred less explicit anti-gay language. Again, the social
conservatives on the platform committee carried the day.
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. Jim Kolbe (R-Ariz.), who is gay, addressed the
convention, some Texas delegates bowed their heads in prayer, a
silent protest against his presence at the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe seized on the awkward moment to explain that his speech
and the protest were evidence of a new inclusiveness in the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
