u a BC-PILOT-SHORTAGE-NYT &LR;      08-05 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOT-SHORTAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED CANCELS 156 FLIGHTS AS PILOT SHORTAGE DISRUPTS THE AIRLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A shortage of pilots forced United Airlines to cancel 16 percent
of its flights at O'Hare International Airport in Chicago Saturday,
creating a wave of delays across the country that inconvenienced
thousands of passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellations, involving 156 flights, created one of the
more serious disruptions in service since April, when United's
contract with its 10,000 pilots expired and many refused to fly
overtime in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's difficulties were particularly surprising because
United had already reduced its schedule of flights by more than 2
percent to ensure that it would have enough pilots.
</P>
<P>
   A United spokesman, Chris Brathwaite, blamed much of the problem
on the weather. Heavy rains and thunderstorms over the last week
had caused delays across the country, Brathwaite said, forcing many
pilots to use up the hours they are legally allowed to be on the
job and leading to Saturday's crew shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a domino effect,'' he said. ``We are doing as
much as we have control over to make sure that people get the kind
of service that they expect.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Associations could not be
reached Saturday, but in the past, the union has said that it is
not involved in any concerted job action, which would be illegal
under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Individual pilots have said in interviews that there is an
unspoken agreement among many of their peers not to volunteer for
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare is United's biggest hub, so the disruption there rippled
through the system.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Carter, a psychologist and textbook editor in Pagosa
Springs, Colo., was trying to fly to Washington, D.C., to escape
the wildfires in her state.
</P>
<P>
   Carter got as far as Chicago only to find that her flight to
Washington had been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm plenty frustrated,'' she said, standing at the end of a
long customer service line. ``I may just go get a hotel because I'm
tired and hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Although United pared its schedule by 4,800 flights between May
and August, and it has taken nearly 2,000 more flights out of the
September schedule, there may be additional reductions, Brathwaite
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that there would probably be more delays Sunday. He
recommended that passengers call ahead, check United's Web site,
and ``exercise patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Full planes and severe thunderstorms have strained the country's
air traffic control system, leading to record numbers of delays
this summer. But United, the world's largest carrier, has been hurt
far worse than others. Its flights arrived on time only 57 percent
of the time in May, the last month for which statistics are
available, and it has had a record number of cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its pilots, United is negotiating a new contract
with its mechanics, baggage handlers and gate agents, who are
represented by the International Association of Machinists. The
machinists and the pilots took deep wage cuts in 1994 in exchange
for a majority of the stock in UAL Corp., United's parent.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the airline was struggling, but it has since
recorded several years of record profits. Both unions said their
members were promised generous contracts when the old ones expired.
They accused UAL management of going back on its word.
</P>
<P>
   United executives have said they are committed to reaching an
``industry-leading'' contract with the pilots and the machinists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
