<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS HAVE THEMSELVES IN BETTER FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; While it could take years to figure out which trade turns out
to be the best one made before the trading deadline, it's fairly
simple to decide Cincinnati's decision to trade lefty Denny Neagle
to the Yankees at the All-Star break was the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, like the Reds about now couldn't use a veteran left-handed
starter with playoff experience and nasty stuff?
</P>
<P>
   Reds general manager Jim Bowden was criticized for giving up on
the season too early because Cincinnati had fallen 10 games behind
front-running St. Louis in the National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   But there was half a season left and Mark McGwire's knee was
acting up. Now, the Reds have closed the gap to five games, McGwire
might not play for another month, if at all this season, and the
Cardinals are sputtering terribly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if today was Sept. 1, we'd still feel good about our
position,'' said Reds right-hander Pete Harnisch. ``So I think
we're in a decent spot now. Everybody feels pretty good for the
first time all year. I think things are a little upbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' recent hot streak has also quelled rumors about
manager Jack McKeon's job being on the line.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears even shortstop Barry Larkin, who nixed a deal
with the Mets and then signed a three-year extension with the Reds
during a wacky weekend two weeks ago, is managing to coexist with
McKeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think earlier in the season, when we dropped 10 games
behind, one of the reasons for that was we weren't focusing on what
we had to do,'' Larkin said. ``We were more concerned about where
we were in the standings behind the Cardinals. We let a lot of
games get away from us because we may have been scoreboard-watching
a little too much. A lot of the talk in the clubhouse was about the
Cardinals as opposed to the teams we were playing in that
particular series. We talked about that. We're refocused.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Schilling's impact: Not only does the acquisition of
right-hander Curt Schilling give Arizona the best one-two punch in
baseball in the starting rotation, but it also puts the
Diamondbacks in a wonderful position should they meet Atlanta in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling shut out the Braves 2-0 Wednesday in his home debut,
marking the fourth straight time he's beaten Greg Maddux. He's also
6-2 with a 2.54 ERA in his last eight starts against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Home and away: Colorado manager Buddy Bell got the chance
to chat with former Rockies manager Don Baylor, now managing the
Chicago Cubs, at Wrigley Field during the week. Among the topics of
conversation was how well the Rockies hit at home. &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; . And how
horrid they are away.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Jeff Cirillo is a perfect example. He came into
the season batting .309 at home and .306 on the road in his career,
and he's hitting .421 at home and .202 on the road this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most frustrating thing about managing there,''
Baylor said. ``You're on the mountain top when you're at home.
Everybody's hitting, but it's so draining when you leave that
place. Then when you go on the road, it's like, 'Where's my hits?
Where's my runs?' &UR;  &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies are hitting .233 and averaging 3.47 runs on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy's not the only guy who was frustrated by it,'' Baylor
said. ``I was in Atlanta last year. Their pitching staff didn't
want any part of Coors Field. They were all nervous. (Pitching
coach) Leo (Mazzone) was double-rocking over there in the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Courting Kendall: Pittsburgh continues to try to sign
catcher Jason Kendall to a long-term deal as the club gets ready to
enter a new stadium next season, but discussions aren't going well.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates signed John Vander Wal and Mike Benjamin to two-year
contracts this week, but general manager Cam Bonifay remains
frustrated about Kendall's situation. Kendall is under contract
next season, but he recently rejected a six-year, $60 million offer
because $23 million of it was deferred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
