<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3669 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-INDY0806-C     08-05 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-INDY0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Labonte's move wins Brickyard
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Brickyard 400 is considered one of the most
prestigious Winston Cup races of the season. Darrell Waltrip
referred to Indianapolis Motor Speedway as the ``holy land'' this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, stock-car racing on the world's most famous track
is sometimes dull. Kyle Petty said there has never been a ``good
race'' in the seven-year existence of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte won the Brickyard 400 on Saturday. The one
tantalizing moment of driving in the entire 160-lap race, which
turned out to be a one-on-one duel between Labonte and Rusty
Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a thrill,'' Labonte said. ``We've been close a
couple of times (in the past). The car was flawless. We only
adjusted air pressure all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace had the strongest car in the field _ leading 110 total
laps _ until the No. 2 Ford became difficult to steer late in the
race. With 15 laps remaining, Wallace's car went up five inches
higher than normal in the fourth turn, allowing Labonte to make a
bid to pass inside.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a drag race down the front stretch, with
Labonte's right front bumper making contact with the left rear end
of Wallace's car. By the first turn of lap 147, Labonte had cleared
Wallace, essentially clinching his first Brickyard victory.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last of nine lead changes at IMS, which has narrow
lanes and is known for being extremely tough for stock cars to pass
each other. There was relatively little side-by-side racing, with
the field scattered over the 2.5-mile track for most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard to pass here,'' Labonte said. ``I wasn't sure
(passing Wallace) was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip, the biggest story of the weekend by qualifying for the
No. 2 start position, dropped to seventh by the completion of the
first lap. Ricky Rudd, the pole sitter, finished 21st.
</P>
<P>
   The most exciting moments happened after the race. Labonte
pumped his fist excitedly for the fans during the cool-down lap.
When he steered the No. 18 Pontiac down pit road, he braked in
front of his bother's pit box.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Labonte sat out the race with dizziness and missed his
first Winston Cup start since 1979. The elder Labonte watched from
the pit box during the race, and saw replacement driver Todd Bodine
steer the No. 5 Chevrolet to a respectable 15th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup points leader Bobby Labonte increased his advantage
from 53 points to 87 in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
