<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-W     08-05 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO LOS ANGELES VIA NASHVILLE, TO PICK UP VOTES AND A RUNNING MATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change dateline, add fund-raisers in Hamptons) 
By JAMES DAO with KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTHAMPTON, N.Y. _ In the days leading to the Democratic
convention, Vice President Al Gore plans to tour several important
battleground states, from Georgia to Pennsylvania to Michigan,
hammering at the emerging themes of his campaign: that the
presidential election will be about substance versus flash and new
ideas against old, his aides said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In separate appearances with Southern Democratic governors,
President Clinton and his soon-to-be-announced running mate, Gore
will focus on a different issue each day, including welfare, Social
Security, health care and the economy, seeking to draw sharp
differences in style and policy with his Republican rival, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tour will offer a striking contrast to the Bush
campaign's approach of image rather than issues, photo-ops rather
than substance,'' Gore's press secretary, Chris Lehane, said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Going the Distance Tour,'' as the Gore campaign has dubbed
it, will begin on Tuesday in Nashville, when the vice president
will appear for the first time with his running mate. It will end
on Tuesday, Aug. 15, in Michigan when Gore stands
shoulder-to-shoulder with Clinton for a symbolic passing of the
party's leadership torch.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will arrive at the convention in Los Angeles the next day,
and will accept the party's nomination the night of Thursday, Aug.
17. Clinton is scheduled to address the convention on Monday night
and then leave the next day, effectively clearing the stage for
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has previewed many of the themes he plans to
emphasize during his tour in speeches over the past two days. The
tour is also intended to highlight Gore's biography, and Saturday
in remarks before the National Association of Police Organizations
in Washington, he talked extensively about his time as an Army
reporter in Vietnam and as a police reporter for The Nashville
Tennessean newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the group that he would push for ``common sense'' laws
to keep guns out of the hands of children and criminals. He noted
that in Congress, he had supported bills banning so-called
cop-killer bullets and plastic guns. In doing that, he drew an
implicit contrast with Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney, who voted
against both bills while a congressman from Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president heralded the administration's efforts to help
police departments hire 100,000 new officers, and said he would
push for money to hire 50,000 more. He also said he would fight to
allow officers to carry their weapons while off-duty and for a
constitutional amendment guaranteeing victims the right to be heard
at criminal proceedings involving their attackers.
</P>
<P>
   The police group, which endorsed the Clinton-Gore ticket in
1996, has not decided whom to support this year. But in introducing
Gore Saturday, the group's president, Thomas J. Scotto, warmly
praised Gore, saying the group has had a relationship with the
White House that ``is probably the envy of all other law
enforcement groups and politicians throughout this country.''
</P>
<P>
   From Washington, Gore flew here to spend the weekend on Long
Island attending three fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   Gore continued to hold any vice-presidential decision close to
the vest. When he landed Saturday afternoon at Suffolk County
Airport, reporters asked him if he was close to making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm about two and a half days away from it now,'' he said,
stating the obvious, since he has imposed a deadline on himself for
an announcement at noon on Tuesday. ``That's pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was attending two fund-raisers Saturday night for the
Democratic National Committee. He raised $250,000 at a fund-raiser
sponsored by Scott Bessent, a hedge-fund manager, and Will Trinkle,
a real estate developer, from about 100 people, many of them
homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   At a later dinner, he raised $1 million from about 100 people at
the home of Craig Hatkoff, a real estate developer, and Jane
Rosenthal, a film producer who, with the actor Robert De Niro,
founded the Tribeca Film Center. Entertainment was provided by the
Bangles.
</P>
<P>
   Other guests at the events included Christie Brinkley, the
model; Andrew Tobias, the author; Charles Nolan, the designer; and
John Sykes, president of VH-1.
</P>
<P>
   Outside a fund-raiser here, Ed Rendell, chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, chatted with reporters about Gore's
vice-presidential selection. He said Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman of
Connecticut would be ``a bold and courageous choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendell also said William S. Cohen, the Republican who is
secretary of defense, would have been the candidate if he had not
announced that was voting for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   From Long Island, Gore heads to Nashville on Sunday afternoon to
prepare for the announcement of his vice presidential pick on
Tuesday. He will travel on Wednesday with his running mate to
Carthage, Tenn., Gore's hometown. They will hold a town hall
meeting at the Carthage elementary school with about 150 Tennessee
residents, many of whom will reminisce about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   From there, they will travel to the home state of the vice
presidential candidate. Speculation is narrowing to three
Democratic senators _ John Kerry of Massachusetts, John Edwards of
North Carolina, and Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gore and his running mate will go to Atlanta for a
meeting with Southern governors and a discussion on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, it is on to the Philadelphia suburbs for an event
with working women. On Saturday, they will travel to western
Pennsylvania and the girlhood home of the late Rachel Carson, the
environmental advocate and author of ``Silent Spring,'' a book that
Gore says strongly influenced him.
</P>
<P>
   Next Sunday, Gore plans to discuss children's health care at
University Hospital in Cleveland. On Monday, Aug. 14, the day the
Democratic convention opens, Gore will be in Independence, Mo.,
home of Harry S. Truman, where he will discuss issues involving
senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, will
speak at the convention. Gore will meet Clinton on Tuesday at an
as-yet-undesignated spot in Michigan, a crucial state, where they
will showcase the nation's economic expansion and try to highlight
Gore's role in the prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Gore will fly to Los Angeles, where his running
mate will be nominated. Thursday night, Gore gives his acceptance
speech and flies out that night to the Midwest, where he will begin
a four-day boat trip across the Great Lakes and down the
Mississippi River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
