<SLUG> BC-FORESTS-FORGOTTEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGOTTEN, OLD TREES GET ATTENTION FROM MODERN-DAY NATURE-LOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO, Kan. _ You say ``old-growth forest,'' and you think of
towering sequoias in the mists of West Coast mountains, right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, how about old-growth forests in Kansas?
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Southeastern Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas all have a
belt of virgin timber, some of it older than our nation.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? The trees _ cedars going back 500 years, post oak
and blackjack 300 years plus _ were deemed so marginal for use that
settlers initially largely ignored them.
</P>
<P>
   And they have been ignored until recently, because as far as
trees go, well, they're not pretty _ gnarled, twisted and short.
The weather and the rocky sandstone soil they grow in aren't
exactly hospitable.
</P>
<P>
   But the trees now have caught the eyes of nature lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Two fingers of the old trees extend into Kansas on the
Chautauqua Hills. By next spring a 1.5-mile walking trail will
snake along the north shore of Toronto Lake here so visitors can
see them and the land they inhabit, as pristine as before white men
came.
</P>
<P>
   The trail will be called the Ancient Trees of the Chautauqua
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to see the trees,'' said Doyle Niemeyer, a Kansas
Department of Wildlife and Parks manager. ``That's what the trail
will do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chautauqua Hills contain a small part of what once was a
35,000-square-mile belt of matted, tangled undergrowth and old
trees.
</P>
<P>
   The post oak and blackjack dominated, but there were cedars,
white and red oak, hickory and pecan, walnut and elm, shinnery
(dwarf oak) and hackberry. And, of course, the all-encompassing
briars. The trees and brush went from roughly where Dallas is now,
through Oklahoma and into Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The area was called the Cross Timbers, a physical barrier
between the woodland and plains Indian tribes that marked the
separation of the bluestem grasses to the east and the buffalo
prairie to the west, and caused Joblike tribulations for the first
whites trekking west.
</P>
<P>
   Once part of what now is Oklahoma was opened to white
settlement, settlers began to clear the Cross Timbers. By the start
of the 20th century, close to 80 percent of it had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of tie-cutters for the railroads in this part
of the country,'' said Niemeyer. ``But they left some, mainly on
the steep slopes above the rivers.''
</P>
<P>
   With civilization, the Cross Timbers area was largely forgotten.
The remaining trees didn't look old. They were rarely more than 30
feet tall. They didn't stand in groves. Their often-distorted
shapes could be passed off to lightning, ice storms or fires.
</P>
<P>
   How the Cross Timbers area came to modern-day attention starts
with, of all people, Sir Walter Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Raleigh _ courtier, adventurer, soldier and writer _ in the
1580s was also a sponsor of a colony in what would become North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   A relief expedition sent to resupply the colony discovered that
the settlers had vanished. Since then the Lost Colony of Roanoke
has been a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? In the early 1990s, David W. Stahle, a geoscience
professor at the University of Arkansas at Fayetteville, postulated
that the settlers might have died of drought-caused starvation.
</P>
<P>
   Stahle is a dendrochronologist, meaning he studies tree rings,
which are an accurate gauge of climatic conditions in a given year
because the thickness of the rings varies with soil moisture.
</P>
<P>
   By examining rings from old trees near Roanoke, Stahle found
that the worst drought in North America in the last 800 years
occurred around the time the colony was started. No rain meant no
crops, said Stahle, likely a fatal combination for the colonists.
</P>
<P>
   Being a scientist, Stahle had another question. Had the drought
occurred all over the country? To determine that he had to find old
trees, a difficult chore, because in the last 200 years settlers
had cut most of them down.
</P>
<P>
   The answer came on the wall of his office, on a map by A.W.
Kuchler, a professor of geography at the University of Kansas who
died in 1999 at age 91.
</P>
<P>
   From 1950 to 1977, Kuchler worked on various versions of the map
showing the vegetation of North America before Europeans came. The
largest hardwood forest, he found, extended southward from the
Missouri Bootheel to the Gulf of Mexico before being cut down.
</P>
<P>
   On the map, a small part was labeled ``Cross Timbers.'' A few
old trees might be on some of the slopes there, Stahle bet.
</P>
<P>
   Stahle and Matthew D. Therrell, a fellow dendrochronologist,
started taking test borings. They confirmed that the Roanoke
drought was confined to the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   They also were amazed at the number of old trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found 20-acre tracts, 40-acre tracts, even bigger,'' said
Stahle. ``Stuff that had never been touched and that had been
growing since well before the Revolutionary War and even farther
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Little by little, the word got out. In the middle of the country
were old-growth forests. And conservationists were determined to
keep them intact.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Chris Wilson, is conservation director for a Nature
Conservancy project called the Keystone Ancient Cross Timbers
Preserve, just west of Sand Springs, Okla. The preserve, which
should have its trails open by 2001, contains almost 1,400 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pristine,'' he said, the largest known intact remnant of
the Cross Timbers. ``It's never been touched except for some oil
exploration on top the bluffs. It's a whole forest ecosystem.''
</P>
<P>
   Saving the tract is akin to preserving the last vestiges of
unbroken prairie near Pawhuska, Okla., and near Cottonwood Falls,
said Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Stahle is upbeat about the Keystone preserve but worried about
the other old trees that have survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got chip mills on the Oklahoma-Arkansas border now,'' he
said. ``Those trees could be attractive to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can just see it _ chip mills turning those old post oaks
into paper and then some environmental magazine printed on that
paper wailing about chip mills and the loss of old-growth forest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
