<SLUG> BC-KIM-MUSIC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10-YEAR-OLD VIOLINIST IS ACCEPTED AT JUILLIARD PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HORSLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The first time you meet Miran Kim, she might
strike you as shy and a bit squirmy.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year-old can fall silent when asked about her goal as a
musician, but then suddenly exclaim: ``To become a spectacular
violinist.''
</P>
<P>
   But the complexity of Miran's personality is not obvious until
she picks up her three-quarter-sized Palliot fiddle from Paris. The
pensive girl with hair pulled back is instantly transformed into a
poised, determined young woman. With concentration focused
razor-sharp, she rips through concertos by Bruch and Mendelssohn.
</P>
<P>
   What strikes the ear is the expressive quality of her playing.
Although many would-be wunderkinder race through concertos as loud
and as fast as possible, Miran's music-making is earnest, restless,
striving.
</P>
<P>
   Lately her practice sessions have a new sense of purpose. Miran
is preparing to take a giant step: to New York, and the Pre-College
Division of the Juilliard School of Music there.
</P>
<P>
   Miran's selection to attend the world-renown school has thrilled
the family, but it has created apprehensions about how the
instruction will affect their future.
</P>
<P>
   Miran, who lives in Overland Park, Kan., with her parents and
3-year-old sister, Minna, says she is rarely ruffled by an
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Performing is just playing in front of people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But in May, when she auditioned for admittance to Juilliard, she
was terrified as she stood before a jury of some of the most astute
violin teachers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   These titans must have been impressed. Miran, who will be a
sixth-grader this fall at Barstow School, was one of 18 students
accepted into Juilliard's youth violin program from a field of
nearly 150.
</P>
<P>
   She has been placed in the class of Dorothy DeLay and her
associate, Hyo Kang. DeLay has taught many leading violinists,
including Itzhak Perlman, Nadja Salerno-Sonnenberg, Midori, Gil
Shaham and Sarah Chang.
</P>
<P>
   Rarefied air for a girl barely 4 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be wonderful exposure for her,'' said Paul
Kantor, Miran's summer teacher at the Aspen Music Festival and
School in Colorado. ``When you go to a place like Juilliard, you
really get a sense for what the world standard is.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this Juilliard euphoria stand two parents facing big
decisions. Should mother and daughter fly to New York every weekend
of the school year? Should the entire family move to New York?
Should the parents borrow money to pay for a future that is
anything but ensured?
</P>
<P>
   Despite financial help from relatives, last year the Kims sold
their Overland Park home and moved into a duplex nearby, which they
are renting until they determine how to orchestrate Miran's
education. Already the costs associated with the girl's violins,
her lessons (at $75 an hour) and the mother-daughter trips to Aspen
each summer (five weeks in June and July) are creating financial
stress.
</P>
<P>
   Juilliard's pre-college program takes place on 30 Saturdays from
late August through May. The annual tuition is $5,000, and airfare
for two and a weekend in a New York hotel could easily cost the
family $1,000 a week. And that's if they don't eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I got the good news, I got a big headache,'' said
Miran's father, Sung-Chul Kim.
</P>
<P>
   Kim is considering moving the family, or at least part of it, to
New York, which raises the biggest question of all: How much should
a parent sacrifice for the sake of a gifted child _ or, indeed, for
any child?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no limit,'' said Kim, 43, who owns a small discount
clothing store in Kansas City, Kan. ``If there's a limit, then
that's not a father's love.''
Film music
</P>
<P>
   Miran's musical ``career'' began simply enough: One evening the
Kims brought their 3-year-old daughter home from a movie and were
surprised when she went to the piano and pecked out the theme music
from the film.
</P>
<P>
   Dong-Yeong Kim, an artist herself (she recently completed a
degree at the Kansas City Art Institute), immediately recognized a
spark of talent. She enrolled Miran in the Suzuki Strings at Ottawa
(Kan.) University, where the girl quickly took to the
one-tenth-sized violin she received.
</P>
<P>
   By age 4, Miran was playing in concerts at the Suzuki school.
Seeing rapid progress, the family sought out former Kansas City
Symphony concertmaster Tiberius Klausner as her teacher and later
Elizabeth Suh, a former member of the London Symphony Orchestra who
now teaches in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very, very gifted,'' Klausner said of Miran, adding that
it had been awhile since he had heard her play.
</P>
<P>
   That can be remedied next Sunday when Miran performs her first
full-length recital. It will be at 3 p.m. in White Hall at the
University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you get to Carnegie Hall? Well, yes, you practice, as
the old saw suggests. Miran practices one to three hours every day
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Attending Juilliard helps you get to Carnegie Hall, too. One of
the best preparations for a music career is the school's
Pre-College Division.
</P>
<P>
   Miran is both excited and intimidated by the thought of being
thrown together with such talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of competitive spirit there,'' Miran said. ``But
it will just make me want to work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Miran is like a jewel, which must be shaped,'' said Klausner,
``and this is the time the jeweler can shape it into a diamond.''
`Into the music'
</P>
<P>
   Miran's technique is strong _ rapid passagework flows easily
through her short fingers _ though her teachers are working on
technical problems ranging from an awkward bow grip to a drooping
posture.
</P>
<P>
   Among the violinists she admires are Maxim Vengerov and Joshua
Bell, ``because they sound like they're really into the music and
not just into the notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Miran says she will not be content merely to become a member of
a major orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be a soloist,'' she said. ``You get more
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that classical music is her only focus. Her love of field
hockey, in-line roller-skating, bicycling and swimming is almost
matched by her devotion to Britney Spears and 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of kids who play music and don't have any
life,'' her mother said. ``We want to avoid that.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loves literature; she loves art; she loves school. I want
her to have a normal education.''
</P>
<P>
   At Juilliard, this might not be entirely possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like a regular school, with an important difference,''
said Andrew Thomas, director of the Pre-College Division since
1994. ``That the bell curve is askew. It's way up at the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had kids come into the office in tears because they got
an A in a class instead of an A-plus. They are driven by this
perfection. Of course, we try to give them some idea of what it's
like to be a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees with the Kim family's decision to send Miran
to Juilliard at this point. Benny Kim, who as Miran's teacher has
worked hard to remedy problems in her technique, fears it might be
premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very gifted girl,'' he said, ``who has some areas to
work on. It's very important that a 10-year-old child have a normal
upbringing, and that she not be completely consumed with music at
too early an age. Burnout can happen very easily....Maybe I'm a
little overly protective. She should try it for a year and see if
she likes it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kantor said Miran would do fine at Juilliard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miran is a very natural player, a very healthy player _ (that
is,) there's nothing compulsively driven about her playing, which
is not always the case with young talent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Miran goes to Juilliard this month, the rest of her family
will be with her, in spirit at least _ each contributing, with toil
and sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Dong-Yeong Kim, with her own career as a painter on hold,
wouldn't have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I barely have any time for me,'' she said, with no noticeable
regret. ``I took all my art supplies to Aspen this summer, and I
didn't even open the box. Maybe's that's the sacrifice. Miran is
young, and she has more potential. Maybe she can have a better
future than I've had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
