r p BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-KAN &LR;      08-05 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE HAS HIS WORK CUT OUT FOR HIM, OBSERVERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY and STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ When he played basketball as a congressman, Al
Gore didn't rebound much. He liked to launch three-point shots,
recalls Sen. Pat Roberts of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   That might be the Democratic presidential candidate's game after
a Republican convention that put a lot of points on the board for
nominee George W. Bush, said Roberts, a Republican who played ball
with Gore when they were in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be bombs away,'' Roberts predicted. ``There's no
question some attack dogs will be let off the chains.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans came out of last week's convention beaming over
their unity and their pronounced resolve to beat Gore. Now, many
wonder how Democrats will respond at their convention, which begins
Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Gore hopes his announcement Tuesday of a running mate will shift
the spotlight back to the Democrats. Last Thursday he released a
list of six contenders. He said he also was considering ``one wild
card.''
</P>
<P>
   The right pick could certainly put Gore on the road to recovery,
but the selection may not be enough to overcome Bush's double-digit
lead in the polls. That is why Roberts and others expect Gore to go
on the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Others urge Gore to use caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing Al Gore needs to do more than anything is reach down
into himself, find out what he believes in strongly and go out and
fight for that,'' said Paul Simon, a retired senator from Illinois
and former Democratic presidential candidate. ``Don't pay attention
to the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Buchanan, a political scientist at the University of
Texas, agreed that Gore should concentrate on himself, particularly
on closing a ``leadership gap'' he suffers in the minds of the
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's partly a question of style and image,'' Buchanan said.
``He can't fix it at one convention. An artfully constructed video
will help.'' So might an acceptance speech in which Gore comes off
as presidential, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said that so far Gore had not been effective in
attacking Bush. He might be better off letting someone else carry
the hatchet, much as GOP vice-presidential candidate Dick Cheney
did for Bush in his convention speech, Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore has a way of attacking that just seems petty,'' Buchanan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Cheney's speech and some lines in Bush's speech
Thursday, the Republican convention stuck mainly to image building.
</P>
<P>
   Given that approach, some Republicans think Democrats risk
public scorn if they decide to go into an attack mode at their
convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats do not agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that the Gore folks would miss an opportunity
to really draw some sharp contrasts,'' said Mike McCurry, a
political communications consultant and President Clinton's former
press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Republican volleys at Gore were actually aimed at
Clinton. Cheney made repeated indirect references to Clinton's
affair with Monica Lewinsky, which led to his impeachment in the
House and allegations of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has denounced Clinton's behavior but has staunchly defended
his record as president. At the convention and in the campaign,
Gore will have to juggle two different Clinton legacies, observers
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to decide if Bill Clinton was the greatest president in
American history or someone we have to get over collectively,''
said John Hancock, executive director of the Missouri Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   While the loudest cheers from the Republican convention floor
came when someone took a swipe at Clinton, he remained popular in
the polls, and the Lewinsky scandal did not affect Democrats in the
1998 congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats will play on the fact we've had eight years of a
great economy and that most people have seen some benefit from this
administration,'' said Henry Gueary, president of the Olathe branch
of the NAACP. ``As long as they seize on those things, they can
counter the Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the public knows that Gore is not Clinton from a
moral standpoint, said Jim Slattery, a former Democratic
congressman from Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have to be very careful they don't overplay the
attack on Clinton, because at some point in the election process
people will realize that Bill Clinton is history,'' Slattery said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore needs to say flat out that `I'm not Bill Clinton,'' '
Slattery said. He said Gore also should say: ``I've worked with
this president for things we agree on, and we've achieved a lot
together. Bill Clinton has made some personal mistakes, but they
are not my mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore has not been free of missteps of his own that
Republicans may choose to exploit, such as questionable fund
raising in 1996 at the White House and at a Buddhist temple in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the eight years with Bill and Hillary Clinton is bound to
link Gore with their era and so-called Clinton fatigue, especially
since both Clintons are expected to speak at the convention, said
Republican pollster Neil Newhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Another chore is to respond to the Republican effort to strike a
moderate tone at the convention by including speakers and
entertainers from minority groups traditionally in the Democratic
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Gore can ill-afford to lose votes from his own party, observers
noted. Polls show that Bush has the backing of about 90 percent of
Republicans but that Gore has 80 percent or fewer Democrats behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's best chance of winning over the electorate may come not
at the convention but in debates, said former Kansas City Mayor
Emanuel Cleaver, who is widely thought of as an effective public
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election will be won in the debates,'' said Cleaver.
``Nobody believes that George W. Bush can in any way handle Vice
President Al Gore in a debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, too, realize that elections are not won at
conventions, no matter how successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope we are not overconfident,'' said U.S. Sen. Kit
Bond, a Republican who is chairman of the Bush campaign in
Missouri. ``We have a lot of work to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
