r l BC-STOWERS-SMC-KAN &LR;      08-05 1507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOWERS-SMC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOWERS INSTITUTE FORMS ITS OWN VISION FROM DISTINGUISHED DALLAS
MODEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Long before this city's main medical center produced
Nobel Prize winners, and before it became a model for Kansas City,
there was a time when world renown was just a glimmering
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1972. The first research-only building was opening.
And top-notch scientists were being recruited to fill it. Folks
such as Bill Neaves. People who could sense that the University of
Texas Southwestern Medical Center would become something big.
</P>
<P>
   A few decades later Southwestern is as revered in medical
circles as Harvard or Johns Hopkins universities. It has nurtured
more Nobel winners, four, than any other medical institution. It
has built a six-block-long campus with 30-some buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Those who witnessed Southwestern's rise look back on 1972 as a
turning point. And today Kansas City's Stowers Institute for
Medical Research is at a similar point in its endeavor to establish
itself relatively quickly.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Neaves was at Southwestern then. And he is at Stowers
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the experience of Southwestern in the early 1970s in
bringing in all kinds of talented newcomers causes me to have
confidence that it can be reproduced here,'' said Neaves, who left
Southwestern this year to become Stowers' first president.
</P>
<P>
   Stowers' buildings will open this fall after a $200 million-plus
expansion and refurbishing of the old Menorah Medical Center near
the Country Club Plaza. It will attempt to answer some of the
fundamental questions of life sciences, such as how genes work
together to create and cleanse cancer and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   As such, Stowers represents something scarce in Kansas City, a
facility aiming for world renown. The city's civic community
promises to raise hundreds of millions of dollars to support the
institute and bankroll spinoff ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Stowers' model, the rise of Southwestern, is an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern's glory took only a couple of decades to attain,
not the generations it took Harvard or Johns Hopkins or even
Washington University in St. Louis. Southwestern did it in middle
America, not on the East or West coasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only place that's been successful in what we're
trying to do,'' said Jim Stowers Jr., the American Century mutual
fund magnate who is founding Kansas City's institute.
</P>
<P>
   A focused vision
</P>
<P>
   Edward Wakeland is, in his words, ``a Southern boy.'' But after
growing up in Texas and attending college there, he had ``had
enough of Texas.'' He went to medical school in Hawaii and took a
research position in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Kansas Medical Center in Kansas City, Kan.,
tried recruiting him a decade ago. He visited there but instead
decided to go home, to Southwestern, as the director of an
immunology center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They set the bar high and come up with the resources for the
very best people to achieve their goals,'' Wakeland said.
</P>
<P>
   The man who set that bar was one of Southwestern's pioneers,
Donald Seldin. When Seldin arrived in January 1951 from Yale
University, the center still occupied leftover Army barracks, the
same ones it had started with in World War II. The dean and various
top professors and department heads were fed up. They were leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Seldin found himself as the sole member of the medicine
department. He became chairman by default. He had no faculty. ``You
can look at that as a great liability. You can also look at it as a
great asset,'' he said. He chose the latter.
</P>
<P>
   For almost two decades his best resource was his own medical
students. He identified the top ones, recruited them for research
projects and then used his contacts to get them more prestigious
training, with the promise that they return to Southwestern. And
students like Joseph Goldstein did come back.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the mid-1960s, Texas' state government put a higher
priority on higher education. In the 1970s the federal government
did the same. Southwestern's state funding jumped from $2.5 million
in 1965 to $62.5 million two decades later. Meanwhile, Southwestern
received enough from the feds to go on a building boom, which would
eventually boost research space tenfold.
</P>
<P>
   As the first new building opened, Neaves arrived as a professor.
He became dean of the graduate school and then dean of the medical
school. His major responsibility was recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stood for high-level quality,'' Seldin said. ``He tried to
ensure the appointments were of the highest level.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the payoffs rolled in: Goldstein and colleague
Michael Brown won Southwestern's first Nobel in 1985 for
cholesterol research. Then research grants shot up from less than
$40 million to more than $180 million today. Southwestern
researchers found what's called the ``fountain of youth,'' an
enzyme that causes human cells to avoid the normal process of
aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``UT Southwestern has moved into the front rank of medical
schools ... and it's the only school to have done so in the last
decade,'' said H. Maxwell Cowan, who has been a distinguished
professor at the Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Southwestern officials about this success, and they
invariably stress two key themes.
</P>
<P>
   One is a narrowly focused vision, putting resources toward the
right areas of study. In the early 1980s, Southwestern's leaders
put their focus on molecular biology, believing genetics was where
scientific breakthroughs would come. They guessed right.
</P>
<P>
   The second theme is carefully choosing who gets the resources.
It's what Seldin calls ``taste,'' finding up-and-coming talent and
not blowing a hiring opportunity on mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to what Chris Newgard, a biochemistry professor,
calls a ``relentless, insatiable desire to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   A new start
</P>
<P>
   Back in Kansas City, Jim Stowers Jr. had his dream to cure
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Stanford University scientists came to visit him.
They wanted his money in California. He wanted to keep it in Kansas
City. Unable to change his mind, the scientists told him about
Southwestern. Intrigued, Stowers visited Neaves three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us what he had done, and that's what we wanted to
do,'' Stowers said.
</P>
<P>
   Stowers was so impressed that he made Neaves an adviser to his
fledgling organization. He didn't think about hiring him. Neaves
was too entrenched at Southwestern. He had become the executive
over all academics. But after one of their regular meetings last
February, Neaves called Stowers. He wanted to get back to building
gene-based science ``from the ground up,'' as he put it.
</P>
<P>
   He asked about becoming Stowers' chief executive. ``We about
fell over,'' Stowers said. ``We really believe in what Bill Neaves
believes in, and he's the one who built Southwestern. He's the one
who found the way to make it work in an unlikely place.''
</P>
<P>
   Neaves, at 56, started in Kansas City in June.
</P>
<P>
   Along a wall of books in his new office there is one white
binder _ Southwestern's operating handbook. Neaves intends to
follow Southwestern's formula, its two key themes.
</P>
<P>
   One already is in place: the narrowly focused vision. At Stowers
that's the genetic susceptibility to diseases. For the second,
choosing only the best up-and-coming talent, Neaves is setting his
bar high.
</P>
<P>
   He has stipulated that Stowers will select only those scientists
with enough credentials to be selected by the Hughes Medical
Institute, which funds the most promising research at medical
centers across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The imperative is to make no mistakes in the quality of the
individuals we recruit,'' Neaves said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither facilities nor money will likely limit Stowers'
potential. Jim and Virginia Stowers already have given one-third of
their $1.8 billion commitment to an endowment for operations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not everyone will come. Even Southwestern doesn't get
everyone it wants. ``Where we're hurt here, as in Kansas City, is
there are no mountains, there is no ocean, there's nothing,'' said
Southwestern's Wakeland.
</P>
<P>
   It will take time for Stowers to develop a reputation. It will
take 10 years, in Neaves' estimation, just to hire all 50 or 60
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City should not expect to have a Nobel Prize in three
years,'' said Kern Wildenthal, Southwestern's president.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Alpern, dean of Southwestern's medical school, added: ``Bill
will have it easier because he has the resources. But you need
patience to get the best people. You can't let impatience cause you
to accept lower quality. If you get mediocre researchers, it's all
over. You set a standard for the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who witnessed Southwestern's rise are encouraged about
Kansas City's chances _ because of Neaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't emphasize enough what a star you're getting,'' said
Newgard, the biochemistry professor. ``I know it's a big challenge,
but if anyone can do it, he can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
