<HEADLINE>
STARR SAYS HE DIDN'T HAVE VENDETTA AGAINST CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Before sitting down to talk, former
Whitewater special counsel Kenneth Starr stood to open the drapes
of a hotel conference room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a sunlight guy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who poured more sunlight on President Clinton than
anyone thought possible doesn't apologize for the work that led to
the impeachment, though not conviction, of a sitting president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task had to be done,'' Starr said in a Kansas City
interview Saturday. ``It was never a vendetta. It was never
anything but a professional investigation of facts. But its sheer
longevity and its expansion led to its vilification. That was
unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr was in Kansas City to address the National Lawyers
Association, a conservative lawyers group based here. In a
half-hour interview, he discussed the legacy of his work, which
ultimately led to the revelation of marital infidelity in the White
House, and how he coped, for a time, with being one of the most
reviled men in America.
</P>
<P>
   Television was a great escape when the acid opinions of former
presidential adviser James Carville became too vexing, Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched Monty Python reruns, that and John Cleese in `Fawlty
Towers,' '' Starr said. ``Manic British humor was helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said that in addition to the criminal convictions he
obtained against lesser Whitewater figures _ such as James and
Susan McDougal and former Arkansas Gov. Jim Guy Tucker _ the
important legacy of his investigation is on a personal level.
</P>
<P>
   ``By virtue of this horror we've gone through, we've seen some
shared values emerge,'' Starr told the lawyers in his address.
``Parents have been reminded to teach their children there is right
and there is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr declined to discuss his views on Hillary Rodham Clinton's
bid for a U.S. Senate seat from New York or say whether the media
should spend more time picking through Vice President Al Gore's
campaign finance issues. He suggested, however, that Attorney
General Janet Reno pay more attention to those asking her for a
more intense probe of campaign finance questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the highest regard for the integrity of (FBI Director)
Louis Freeh,'' Starr said. ``Judge Freeh called for an independent
counsel and urged the attorney general to do that. (Former Justice
Department campaign finance task force chief) Charles Labella
called for an independent counsel. Now we know his successor,
Robert Conrad, has called for an independent counsel. That suggests
to me that most attorneys general would have appointed an
independent counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's assessment of Clinton echoed that of Texas Gov. George
W. Bush in his acceptance speech at the Republican National
Convention last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Clinton is) a man of immense talent, first in his class,''
Starr said. ``But he was an individual who was willing to mock the
truth, even under oath. We want a remarkable president. We want our
president to be great. Very sadly, he squandered much of his moral
authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said those considering public office today should
scrutinize their motives and moral compass before deciding to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a hunger for plain speaking,'' Starr said. ``There are
too many poll-driven decisions now. A lot of people love power, the
trappings of power and the attention. I tend to be fearful of
those, in both parties. I tend to be skeptical of career
politicians.''
</P>
</TEXT>
