<HEADER>
A3681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0806-COX     08-05 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Bush anticipates debating Gore
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the GOP convention over, Republican presidential candidate
Gov. George W. Bush said Saturday that he's eager for one-on-one
debates with his opponent Al Gore. Bush, who has been criticized as
a poor orator, told The Associated Press that he could hold his
own, although he views Gore as ``a very good debater.'' ``The first
thing about a debate is to know what you believe. And I know what I
believe,'' he said. The bipartisan Commission on Presidential
Debates has tentatively set three presidential debates: Oct. 3 in
Boston, Oct. 11 in Winston-Salem, N.C., and Oct. 17 in St. Louis.
The vice presidential debate is set for Oct. 5 in Danville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH STILL HAS TWO DIGIT LEAD IN POLLS
</P>
<P>
   Bush leads Vice President Al Gore by more than 10 percentage
points, according to two new national polls taken after the
Republican National Convention. A Newsweek poll released Saturday
showed Republican Bush was ahead of Democrat Gore 49 percent to 38
percent while Green Party candidate Ralph Nader had 5 percent and
Pat Buchanan, a Reform Party hopeful, had 1 percent. The Newsweek
poll found Bush was viewed more favorably over Gore on the
following issues: upholding moral values (53-30), reducing crime
and violence (49-33), handling taxes (50-36), national defense (55
- 30), and foreign policy (48-37). Gore led on helping seniors pay
for prescription drugs (45-40), and protecting gay rights (47-30).
</P>
<P>
   A Voter.com-Battleground tracking poll of likely voters also
gave Bush an 8-point advantage at the start of the GOP convention
that grew by 10 points by the end of the week. In the tracking
poll, Bush led in every region of the country and among most
demographic groups. Overall, the convention gave 49 percent of
those surveyed a more favorable opinion of the Republican Party
while 22 percent said less favorable. Still, 41 percent said there
was not enough discussion of what actual policies the GOP would
pursue.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG LAWMAKER TO SPEAK IN L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Congressman Harold Ford Jr. will be a keynote speaker
at the Democratic National Convention to be held next week in Los
Angeles, Gore's campaign announced Friday. Ford, 30, the youngest
member of Congress, said Friday that an ``electric feeling'' went
through his body when Gore phoned to ask him to give a 15-minute
speech. ``He knows Al Gore. He's from Tennessee. He's an excellent
speaker,'' Gore campaign spokesman Jano Cabrera said.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS CHARGE HOUSTON IS `FILTHY'
</P>
<P>
   Democrats appear to have been caught criticizing one of their
own when party officials last week launched charges that Houston _
which is run by a Democratic mayor _ is filthy with pollution. In
Friday's Washington Times, Democrat spokeswoman Jennifer
Laszlo-Mizrahi said: ``We need to start letting people know, for
example, that Houston is a filthy, smoggy, disgusting city.''
Houston's mayor Lee Brown, however, is a Democrat. Democrats have
repeatedly criticized Bush's environmental record as governor of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jim Nicholson, Chairman of the Republican National
Committee: ``This is more `slaughterhouse' rhetoric from the Gore
campaign. It's hard to believe they are so desperate that they'd
level an attack that hurts one of their own party leaders.'' Brown
had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
