<HEADER>
A3682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-JIM-DANDY-NYT &LR;      08-05 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-JIM-DANDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAEME HALL'S VICTORY IS WORTH A SIGH OF RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ With a heartbreaking 24 hours behind
him and another harrowing 24 ahead, Todd Pletcher summoned a
comfortable truism he learned as a boy from his father, J.J., as
they knocked along the back stretches of the southwestern racing
circuit. One of three talented 3-year-olds in his barn, Graeme
Hall, had just galloped home a surprise winner in the Jim Dandy,
earning a relieved shake of the head from Pletcher, his 33-year-old
trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You eat chicken one day, feathers the next,'' he said. ``It's
just the way this game is. You have to enjoy the chicken when you
have it.''
</P>
<P>
   The trophy from the Grade II race represented the chicken he
could enjoy, the $240,000 first-place check could provide some
healthy feed for Graeme Hall's owners, Eugene and Laura Melnyk, and
the victory in this important prep for the Travers Stakes
catapulted Pletcher to the top of the trainers' standing here at
Saratoga Race Course.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, however, Pletcher's prospects were not nearly as
promising. His blazing sprinter, Trippi, was anything but in
finishing third as the odds-on favorite in the Amsterdam. A bruise
discovered on his left hoof explained part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   As Graeme Hall was preparing to run the best race of his young
career, Pletcher received more bad news. The jockey John Velazquez,
who was supposed to fly to the Jersey Shore and ride More Than
Ready, the morning-line favorite, for Pletcher in Sunday's $1
million Haskell Invitational at Monmouth Park, was involved in a
nasty spill in Saturday's fifth race and might have broken his left
collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   That tension was suspended for a startling 1:48.95 _ the time it
took Graeme Hall to dash 1[ miles and ruin the coronation of the
front-running Albert the Great _ as the slightly built son of
Dehere showed his victory in the Arkansas Derby was not a fluke
before an enthusiastic crowd of 64,979. Under Jerry Bailey, Graeme
Hall sat on the wing of the Nick Zito-trained Albert the Great as
the two clicked off a swift half-mile fraction of 46.11 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going too fast,'' Pletcher suspected from his perch in
the owner's box.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey was unruffled and believed he was just following the
trainer's instructions. ``He told me to let him find his rhythm,''
Bailey said. ``My horse was real aggressive around the turn. I
could have put Albert the Great away any time.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Bailey and Graeme Hall hit the top of the stretch,
they had, stopping Albert the Great's four-race winning streak and
leaving Zito sputtering for a reason. ``I'm at a loss for words,''
Zito said. ``I have no excuse. I thought we were just going to
gallop out to the lead and make the move, but we didn't. He cleared
to the lead, and the next thing I knew, he stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as he did in the Arkansas Derby, Graeme Hall continued to
dig down the middle of the lane determined to hold off the closing
charges of the late runners, Curule and Unshaded. That pair loped
along in sixth and seventh place until getting interested at the
bottom of the final turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stuck going into the final turn,'' said the rider of
second-place Curule, Mike Smith, a last-minute replacement for
Velazquez. ``He's not like a horse you ride every day. He's got a
quick trigger. Now I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Nafzger, the trainer for the 2-1 favorite, Unshaded, took
responsibility for his gelding's uneven race, but with a qualifier.
The trainer had said all along that his goal was to win the Aug. 26
Travers Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should have had him a little sharper,'' he said.
``This wasn't our main goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Nafzger's, Pletcher's sights are on winning the Travers and
making a case for one of his talented colts to be named 3-year-old
of the year. Besides More Than Ready, who will be ridden by Richard
Migliore on Sunday at Monmouth, the Kentucky Derby and the
Preakness' third-place finisher, Impeachment, will represent his
barn in the big race in Oceanport, N.J. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the racing future of the Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi
Pegasus clouded by an impending sale as a stallion and the
Preakness winner Red Bullet still recovering from a viral infection
and ulcers, the 3-year-old division is wide open. There was no
mistaking that one of Pletcher's horses had earned his way into the
Travers. Asked if he would run, the trainer responded: ``That's why
we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   If More Than Ready and Impeachment run well on Sunday, Graeme
Hall will have plenty of company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
