u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-MARINERS-     08-05 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS BEAT YANKEES, 6-5 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Cone tilted back his head, peered through
squinted eyes into a sunny, summer sky and seemed to say something
about the beautiful day to Mel Stottlemyre. The pitching coach
agreed with him, the only words spoken on their 150-yard walk from
the bullpen to the dugout before Cone's start Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The sun hung low by the time the organist Eddie Layton and the
highest rim of Yankee Stadium formed the shadow that covered the
third-base side stands and reached for the mound. Cone finished his
part of the game in the evening's darkness, departing after six
innings and 137 pitches _ the most he has thrown since generating
147 against Seattle in Game 5 of the 1995 division series.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 15th consecutive start made by Cone in which he was
not the winning pitcher, and although he was not charged with the
loss Saturday, the Seattle Mariners beat the Yankees, 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners took a 6-3 lead with three runs in the top of the
ninth inning against Dwight Gooden and Mariano Rivera, and in the
bottom of the ninth the Yankees' Jorge Posada hammered a two-run
homer, his second home run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden relieved Cone to start the seventh inning and shut out
the Mariners for two innings. But the Mariners put together a
couple of singles to begin the ninth, and with one out, Rivera
relieved Gooden, and Al Martin beat out a hit to the right side of
the Yankees' drawn-in infield to score Stan Javier with the
go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have not won any of Cone's last 13 starts, which is
why his plight to achieve his second victory of the season and
182nd of his career has become something of a mission.
</P>
<P>
   When Cone retired the Mariners in the top of the first inning,
some of the fans at Yankee Stadium stood and cheered, and there is
no telling how Cone would perceive a gesture like this. He has said
he appreciates the ample support offered to him; on the other hand,
he is a former Cy Young Award, a ruthless competitor and a
self-deprecating realist, and a small part of him might have found
it somewhat galling to be given such cheers for one scoreless
inning.
</P>
<P>
   But fans and Yankees Manager Joe Torre and Cone's teammates all
wanted the win for him, for his misery to end. The Yankees scored
twice in the bottom of the first, on a two-out, two-run single by
David Justice, and for only the fourth time since his last win
April 28, Cone was able to pitch with a two-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   During his week in Tampa, Fla., Cone made a handful of minor
adjustments, while under the counsel of former pitching coach Billy
Connors. Cone compacted his delivery, keeping his hands close to
his body, taking a short step back with his left foot at the outset
of his motion, drawing his right hand back and firing. Everything
he did was quicker: His hands, his feet, his pace. Cone allowed
back-to-back singles to start the second inning, before a ground
ball double-play killed the Seattle rally, but he threw 22 pitches
in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The shadows reached about 15 feet in front of home plate when
the top of the third inning began. Cone began the inning by walking
Mark McLemore, Seattle's No. 9 hitter; Cone was in the midst of a
stretch when he would reach three-ball counts to nine of 13
batters.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore stole second base, and with one out, Al Martin pulled a
slow roller through the hole between the second baseman Jose
Vizcaino and the first baseman Tino Martinez, scoring McLemore.
Alex Rodriguez, the Seattle shortstop, fell behind no balls and two
strikes, fouling off a couple of pitches, and Cone threw a fastball
and two breaking balls wide of the strike zone. The catcher Jorge
Posada signaled for a fastball, set his target just off the outside
corner, and when Cone's fastball drifted over the plate, Rodriguez
leaned forward and drove it into the right field stands. The
Mariners led, 3-2, and Cone's mouth turned down.
</P>
<P>
   The shade touched the base of the mound by the time Cone left
it, after 37 pitches. He had thrown 72 pitches in three innings,
and when he went out for the fourth inning, Gooden began to stretch
in the Yankees' bullpen, just in case he would be needed in short
order. Cone's shadow covered the back of the mound as the fourth
inning began; by the end of the fourth, sunshine touched only the
bill of his cap. Stottlemyre's fingers jabbed at the silver pitch
counter he held in his hand, and by the end of fourth, it read 92.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre was willing to wait, to give Cone every chance. The
right-hander allowed a hit and a walk with two outs in the fifth
and there was movement in the Yankees' bullpen. Cone pitched to
Mike Cameron, closed out the inning with a strikeout -- the 2,500th
strikeout of his career -- and again Cone walked off to a standing
ovation. When the milestone was announced to the fans, their cheers
grew, a call for Cone to come out of the dugout for a wave.
</P>
<P>
   He would not come out. He had thrown 113 pitches. Cone walked
out for the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Guillen walked leading off the sixth; now the Yankees'
bullpen was fully active, a left-hander and a right-hander. Cone
struck out Dan Wilson with his 126th pitch. Guillen was thrown out
at second on what appeared to be a botched hit and run, but
McLemore singled. One hundred thirty-two pitches. Cone appeared
exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   He summoned enough stuff to reach a 2-2 count on Rickey
Henderson, before throwing a fastball past the veteran. More
cheering. Cone's outing was over. He walked off in twilight and he
did not appear to be pleased.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
