<HEADER>
A3687 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-JENKINS-LADN-(SLA     08-05 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-JENKINS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-TROJAN JENKINS IMPROVES SKILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Geoff Jenkins realizes hitting is what draws the
publicity, the big contracts and is the easiest way to secure a
spot in the lineup. He's always considered it the most enjoyable
part of baseball and the part of the game at which he's excelled.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins entered this weekend's Milwaukee Brewers series against
the Dodgers with 19 home runs and the second-highest average on the
team at .300, but he takes just as much pride in his 11 outfield
assists, which rank second in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much is put on the offensive side that a lot of people
forget about defense,'' said Jenkins. ``I've always known that if I
just practice my hitting, it'll be there. But, defensively, that's
something they haven't always really thought I was good at.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've really worked hard at and I think I've
really become a good outfielder now just from listening to guys
like Marquis Grissom, Darrin Jackson and other veteran guys I've
played with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just listening to their advice and just studying the hitters,
where they hit the ball, it really helps you become a better
outfielder.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins' desire to become a more complete player started when
his older brother Brett played for USC and former Trojan Fred Lynn
was repeatedly mentioned as an example of an ideal outfielder. The
tales of Lynn continued when Geoff enrolled at USC, but the
numerous accolades Jenkins received during his three seasons there
were based on his hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, 26, left USC in 1995 as the Trojans' leader in career
RBI (175) and ranks among the school's top five in several other
career and season offensive categories.
</P>
<P>
   He capped his All-American career by leading USC to the 1995
College World Series final and playing well enough to earn a spot
on the College World Series All-Decade team even though the Trojans
lost the championship to Cal State Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a hitter,'' Jenkins said. ``I wasn't really
known for my fielding coming out of college, but I finally decided
I wanted to be more than just a hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   As a minor-leaguer in 1996, Jenkins did not make an error. His
14 outfield assists in 1999 _ his first full season in the major
leagues _ were fifth in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works on his defense a lot and he's definitely gotten
better,'' Brewers manager Davey Lopes said.
</P>
<P>
   Being more than a one-dimensional player is part of what Jenkins
hopes will make him a good example for teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm not one of the guys that has a ton of service
time like some of the other guys on our team, but I still feel like
when I go out there, how you perform out there and how you go about
your business on and off the field, can make you a leader,''
Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys around you see what you do. This year and years to
come, I definitely look forward to being one of the guys on the
team that everyone will want to turn to. It's just one more thing I
can contribute to the team.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !dlim!!dlim!JENKINS FILE!dlim!!tvspt2!Name: Geoff Jenkins &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !tvspt2!Team: Milwaukee Brewers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !tvspt2!Position: Outfield &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !tvspt2!Age: 26 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !tvspt2!Local tie: USC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !tvspt2!Career highlights: His nine home runs in April tied Rob
Deer for most homers in a month in franchise history. . . . Led the
Brewers in doubles in 1999. . . . Became the first player in
Brewers history to hit a home run in his major league debut when he
did so April 24, 1998. . . . Earned All-America honors in 1994 and
1995 and was the Pacific-10 Co-Player of the Year in 1995 when he
helped USC to the College World Series championship game. . . .
Milwaukee made him the ninth pick overall in the1995 draft.
</P>
