<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3889 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-JAMES-B     08-05 1932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-JAMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES-FALDO UPROAR A COMEDY OF ERRORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Truthfully, how can you not laugh at this entire Mark James
controversy? Good gracious, we are talking about an assistant
captain in the Ryder Cup. It's probably an important duty, like a
bullpen coach in baseball, but it cannot possibly be worth all
this.
</P>
<P>
   It's a serious matter in Europe, but from thousands of miles
away it is pure comedy. With such a madcap affair, it is difficult
to determine where to start, but let's begin with James's
appointment an assistant captain. Why? To reward him for some moves
that cost his team a victory last September at The Country Club in
Brookline? In case you forgot, let's recap his gaffes:
</P>
<P>
   --Choosing Andrew Coltart over Bernhard Langer or Nick Faldo
with the second of his picks. (Jesper Parnevik was the other.)
James had such faith in Coltart he didn't play him until the final
day. In 22 events since late last summer, Coltart has finished in
the top 10 just four times and broken 70 in only 18 of 74 rounds,
numbers that prove James was wise to keep him in the locker room
until Ryder Cup bylaws forced him to use all 12 guys. Anyone who
knows a 2-iron from a putter understands that Langer or Faldo could
have contributed more than Coltart.
</P>
<P>
   --Burning out his marquee guys, which was part of the fallout of
having Coltart on the team, in addition to Jean Van de Velde and
Jarmo Sandelin, players James didn't trust. In a coaching strategy
that only K.C. Jones could have liked, James rode his best players
hard, far too hard by the looks of things on Singles Sunday. And
before you defend James for giving his team its only chance,
remember this: If Jose Maria Olazabal had not asked out of the
foursomes, when he mysteriously forgot how to swing a driver, James
most likely would have stuck with him, and Padraig Harrington
wouldn't have played until Sunday. How shameful that would have
been, considering Harrington went 1-1-1 and has blossomed into a
wonderful player.
</P>
<P>
   --Tossing Sandelin, Van de Velde, and Coltart out 3-4-5. It was
a gamble _ and James lost big. Trailing, 10-6, the Americans were
going to load the front end of their singles lineup and everyone
knew it. James made it easier by tossing them three sacrificial
lambs as Phil Mickelson (4 and 3), Davis Love (6 and 5), and Tiger
Woods (3 and 2) cruised to help the US win the first six matches,
setting up the greatest comeback in Ryder Cup history.
</P>
<P>
   --Not playing Colin Montgomerie first or second. He was the best
player walking the hallowed grounds of TCC last September (Woods
included), his team needed an early point, and James rendered him
meaningless by batting him 10th.
</P>
<P>
   --Writing the book, ``Into the Bear Pit.'' We already knew he
didn't like Faldo and held Tom Lehman, Hal Sutton, and Ben Crenshaw
in contempt, but he had to tell us again. Ironically, for all the
harm the book has caused, every time Faldo opens his mouth or the
story is retold another sorry day, James rakes in the pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are sidekicks in any comedy. Faldo, arguably
the most self-centered player of his era, is acting as a team
spokesman in search of harmony, but he helped create this mess by
his ill-timed blast of Montgomerie just a few weeks before last
year's matches.
</P>
<P>
   Faldo said he apologized to Montgomerie and sent a letter of
encouragement to the European team. James tossed it in the circular
file without showing the team, according to Faldo.
</P>
<P>
   Faldo called James names. James called Faldo names.
</P>
<P>
   Faldo lined up veteran players on his side. James lined up
veteran players on his side.
</P>
<P>
   Faldo lined up British writers on his side. James lined up
British writers on his side.
</P>
<P>
   (We interrupt to remind you that these are grown men and
reportedly distinguished athletes.)
</P>
<P>
   Faldo got voted down at a tournament players' meeting. James got
voted out at a European Ryder Cup officials' meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, European events are being overshadowed by this petty
feud, and the best interest of the Ryder Cup has taken a back seat.
Of course, if you listen to James or Faldo, it's the other's fault.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Hill was never funnier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A British undressing
</P>
<P>
   There are few sports moments as rewarding as the winner's walk
up the 72d fairway, and when those victorious steps are as historic
as Woods's were at St. Andrews, the theater is special. So what
happened? Just as Woods takes off his hat to salute the fans, a
woman takes off every stitch of clothing and streaks onto the 18th
green. The same thing happened to Woods in Saturday's third round
and, in fact, it seemed to be a daily exercise. (A title for
James's next book: ``Into the Bare Pit.'') Harmless? Well, yes. But
the British press, which rightfully blasted fan behavior at The
Country Club, seems to accept naked fans prancing across golf
courses. (We won't even get into their soccer hooligans.) Too bad,
because the British Open at St. Andrews is the ultimate golf
experience, from the greatest fans (at least those who remain
clothed), to the most distinctive course, to the unmatched aura of
links golf . . . As for Woods, he'll tee it up at the Buick Open
this week, going against his stated strategy of playing the week
before a major. (The PGA Championship begins Aug. 17.) Obviously,
his endorsement deal with Buick has something to do with it, but
the commute (Grand Blanc, Mich., to Louisville, Ky.) isn't rough,
so he should be ready to make a bid at a third major championship
this year. Ben Hogan (1953) is the only man to win three majors in
a season in the modern era . . . Surely, Karrie Webb is used to it
by now, but the misfortune of being in Woods's shadow is a
disheartening reality. In 1999, she won six times, including her
first major; nice, but virtually unnoticed in light of Woods's
eight victories and second major. Now, as Webb chases her third
major of the season (the du Maurier, which begins Thursday), much
of the focus will move to the Buick Open _ an event that rarely
makes a blip on the radar screen _ simply because Woods is playing
. . . Woods has finished over par in just one event in 2000 _ his
own Williams World Challenge (an unofficial tournament), when he
was 10th at plus-2. In 12 PGA Tour medal events, Woods has done no
worse than 4 under (at the Masters) and he is an unthinkable 138
under par in 48 stroke-play rounds. That translates into an
adjusted scoring average of 67.77 and Woods is on his way to
breaking the mark of 68.43, which he set a year ago. When you
consider that Ernie Els is second in the Vardon Trophy race
(69.29), it's easy to see why Stuart Appleby said Woods enters each
round with a two-shot edge . . . Shame on me for a triple bogey
several weeks ago. The course used as a qualifier for the British
Open was Lundin Links, not London Links, and, of course, it is
within a short distance of St. Andrews, not outside of London.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Word from the wise
</P>
<P>
   On those days when Kevin Johnson wasn't hitting balls or playing
golf at North Hill in Duxbury, he was hitting balls or playing golf
at Halifax CC, where he got to know Ray Bump. ``He was always
telling me I needed to play the Publinx,'' said Johnson from Omaha,
where he was taking part in the BUY.com Tour event this weekend.
Johnson took Bump's advice and ended up winning the 1987 US Amateur
Public Links Championship at Glenview GC in Cincinnati. Johnson
remembers Bump flying out just to watch that championship match, a
10-and-9 rout. ``He was the guy behind the tournament. I remember
when (the Public Links Championship) came to Stow Acres, Ray was
talking about that for years, like it was his own little
tournament.'' Johnson, like many in the state's golfing circles,
was saddened by the death of Bump, 79, July 16. ``He was always
very good to me,'' said Johnson. ``He really helped me.'' . . .
Johnson returned to tournament action after three weeks off with
his wife, Christa, as they celebrated the birth of their daughter,
Jordan Paige, July 17 . . . Chip Drury, the 38-year-old former pro
from Atlanta who earned a US Amateur spot during a qualifier at
Salem CC in Peabody Tuesday, had a helping hand in one of golf's
most historic victories _ Jack Nicklaus's 1986 Masters triumph at
the age of 46. OK, maybe not a helping hand, but certainly some
inspirational assistance. As a US Amateur semifinalist the previous
summer, Drury had a spot in the Masters field in 1986, and got set
up with a Tuesday practice round with Nicklaus. That day, an
Atlanta columnist suggested Nicklaus should gracefully walk away
from the game and not return to Augusta as a ceremonial
participant. At one point, ``I turned to Nicklaus and said, `Mr.
Nicklaus, you have just struck it perfectly and putted beautifully.
You could win this tournament.' '' Drury said Nicklaus gave him a
sly grin, a memory he'll have forever. Drury shot 76-77 and missed
the cut; Nicklaus, of course, earned his 18th professional major.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clark's number is up
</P>
<P>
   Michael Clark played college golf with David Duval at Georgia
Tech. Michael who? Michael Clark, last week's John Deere Classic
winner. If you ever wonder why some guys keep plugging along on the
BUY.com Tour, the answer is Michael Clark. Before the John Deere
Classic, he played in 17 events this year, his rookie year on the
PGA Tour. He missed 11 cuts, finished in the top 20 just twice, and
broke 70 in just 12 of 47 rounds. If you found his name on the
money list it was only by accident. Now, thanks to the incredible
riches that throw things out of whack, Clark is 49th on the money
list, having earned $468,000 of his $588,994 at the John Deere. Not
bad for a guy who ranks 151st in scoring average, 134th in putts
per round, and 130th in greens in regulation . . . What's Clark
going to do with the bulk of his first-place check? Buy a
four-wheel drive tractor, of course, to help clear the 100 acres of
land he owns in Georgia . . . The John Deere also proved to be a
huge hit for Charles Howell III, who finished third and earned
$176,800 in just his third PGA Tour event since turning pro. With
$195,362, Howell would rank 132d on the money list, but he is not a
member of the PGA Tour yet. However, if at the end of the season he
has reached a figure equal to or greater than the 125th player
(last year that figure was $326,893), he would earn his card and
get to skip the hellish Q School . . . In case you are keeping
track, Fuzzy Zoeller made his first cut of the year at the Greater
Milwaukee Open, earning $4,550. That's all he has to show for 12
starts in 2000 . . . Don't look now, but Jumbo Ozaki has slipped to
54th in the world rankings. It has been a mere 28 years since his
victory in the New Zealand PGA Championship, his only win outside
of Japan. He should get points for having the guts to wear an
all-purple outfit . . . Defending champ Aree Wongluekiet was
stunned in the third round of the US Girls' Junior Championship at
Pumpkin Ridge in North Plains, Ore. Her twin sister, Naree, was a
second-round upset victim. Tears flowed and the shock factor
apparently was immense. Fortunately, at just 14 years old, they
have time to get over it. Suggested remedy: Head to the beach, the
game rooms, or water parks for a few weeks and be kids. Most likely
course of action: more practice for a dozen or so national
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews and wire service reports was
used in compiling this report.
</P>
