<HEADLINE>
NEW RULES MAY NOT BE ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As one Winston Cup driver put it, it was ``just smart thinking''
when NASCAR announced rule changes last week, requiring engines to
be outfitted with a throttle stop assembly and an auxiliary
shut-off switch on the steering wheel within reach of the driver's
thumb.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the changes, effective for Saturday's
Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis Motor Speedway, would have prevented
the deaths of Busch Series driver Adam Petty May 12 and Winston Cup
driver Kenny Irwin Jr. July 7 at New Hampshire International
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Both drivers were killed under similar circumstances when their
cars hit the wall in Turn 3 at NHIS. In both instances it was
speculated a stuck throttle was the cause, but NASCAR officials
have yet to find conclusive evidence to support that theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're running these things at around 200 miles per hour,
there's no way you're going to make them totally safe,'' said
driver Jeremy Mayfield, 31, of Owensboro, Ky., who discovered that
firsthand Friday morning when he crashed and sustained a concussion
during practice for the Brickyard. Mayfield, who was fourth fastest
during pole qualifications Thursday afternoon, suffered the injury
when his No. 12 Mobil Oil Ford Taurus spun as it entered Turn 3 at
Indy and slammed into the concrete wall on the driver's side.
</P>
<P>
   It took rescue workers 10 minutes to extricate Mayfield. He was
taken to Methodist Hospital, where he was examined and reported to
be alert.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Petty, Adam's father, who failed to qualify his own car,
drove Mayfield's backup Ford for the Penske-Kranefuss Racing team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that makes the cars safer,'' Mayfield said before his
accident, ``especially something that doesn't affect the racing,
and something that doesn't open up a can of worms for other stuff,
it's just smart thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   But how smart was it to wait so long before making those rule
changes?
</P>
<P>
   Were the safety measures overdue? Why did it take two tragedies
before NASCAR finally acted? And what of the timing of the
announcement? Winston Cup teams would have been better served if
NASCAR allowed for more time _ say, last weekend's open date _ for
the changes to be implemented. Instead, NASCAR announced the
changes two days before Winston Cup teams were scheduled to arrive
in Indy for the Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the ideas are still coming,'' said Gary Nelson,
NASCAR's Winston Cup Series director. ``As long as we never rest
and continue to look for ways to make the sport safer, ideas will
develop from that. If you look at a NASCAR stock car from 1949 and
you look at one from 2000, you will see there has been a lot done.
The fact that we did things this week tells me there will probably
be a lot more done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of evolution. It's a work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Petty and Irwin tragedies gave rise to talk about the
implementation of a foam barrier along the retaining walls, it has
resulted in nothing more than that, talk.
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers have taken steps to prevent serious head injuries
and the whiplash effect of violent wall crashes by using a head and
neck safety (HANS) device. The HANS device is nothing more than a
pair of straps at the back of a helmet anchored to the shoulder
harness. Its function is to stabilize the head and neck in the
event of a crash, but NASCAR has not yet made the device mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if NASCAR might be inclined to solicit help from crash
experts and engineers in developing other safety measures, Nelson
said: ``The specialized engineers are the guys in this garage who
build these cars every day and understand them. I don't think
there's anybody better who understands what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brotherly love
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Waltrip and Brett Bodine were treated to a pair of
uplifting experiences (courtesy of their brothers, Michael Waltrip
and Geoffrey Bodine) during the first and second rounds of
qualifying for the Brickyard 400, which was won Saturday by Bobby
Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the 53-year-old Waltrip, who is retiring at the end
of the season, surprised everyone when he set a track record with
his lap of 180.923 miles per hour, good enough for a spot on the
provisional pole.
</P>
<P>
   When ol' D.W. pulled down pit road, where Michael was awaiting
him, he was greeted by a rousing ovation. When he climbed out of
his car, Darrell jumped into Michael's arms and was carried around
the pits to the delight of the cheering crowd. Ricky Rudd knocked
Waltrip off the pole with a record-shattering lap of 181.068
m.p.h., but it didn't seem to diminish D.W.'s day. ``That doesn't
bother me,'' said Darrell Waltrip. ``I told y'all, and I mean it, I
don't have to win and I don't have to be on the pole. As long as
you can leave here this weekend and say, `Ol' D.W. was up there,'
that's all that matters to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, a similar scene played out between the Bodines, when
Brett erased Rudd's track record with a lap of 181.072 during the
second day of qualifications. Brett, who had failed to qualify for
last year's Brickyard race, wrested the honor of fastest second-day
qualifier away from Geoffrey, who had gone 179.037. The Bodines
started Saturday's race side by side in Row 13. As he was being
interviewed on pit road by an ESPN reporter, Brett was joined by
Geoffrey, who threw a bear hug on his younger brother and
triumphantly lifted him off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   It was an emotional scene that vastly differed from their first
trip to Indy for the inaugural Brickyard 400 in 1994, when Brett
bumped Geoffrey from behind on Lap 101, causing him to fall out of
the lead when he spun and hit the wall in Turn 4. Geoffrey caused a
family feud when he left the track that day claiming Brett had
``taken him out.'' If anything, Friday proved the Brothers Bodine
had mended their fences, finally.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   End of the road
</P>
<P>
   The streak is over.
</P>
<P>
   Despite overcoming injuries the past few weeks to continue
racing, Terry Labonte, Bobby's older brother, was not in the
Brickyard 400 lineup, thus ending his incredible string of 655
consecutive Winston Cup starts.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Labonte hobbled into the Jack Ratta Media Center at
NHIS, still smarting from the non-displaced fracture he suffered in
his right tibia after a wall crash at Daytona the week before.
Asked if he felt his Ripkenesque streak, which at the time numbered
653 races, was in any peril, Labonte replied, ``It's got to come to
an end some day, but you'd hate to see it come to an end like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old ironman expressed every hope of being healthy
enough to start not only the New England 300 (which he did) but
also the Brickyard 400. But his chances to race in Indianapolis
were further imperiled by his crash at NHIS, where he aggravated
his injuries when he had to climb out of his flaming wreck without
assistance and hop on one leg to the nearby retaining wall on the
frontstretch. When he arrived at Indy, Labonte could not get back
into the car and was forced to return to North Carolina for a
doctor's visit.
</P>
<P>
   He came back to Indianapolis intending to race Saturday. But,
after practicing in his No. 5 Chevy on Friday, Labonte made his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt much better today, but I just didn't feel 100
percent,'' he said. ``We talked with Dr. (Jerry) Petty (in
Charlotte) and he said I could run one lap in the race, if I wanted
to, and then come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident it's not a lingering problem, but I decided
I'm going to sit out (the Brickyard) and then Watkins Glen (next
Sunday), then pick up where we left off. We'll try to start another
streak.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It runs in the family
</P>
<P>
   Todd Bodine, Geoffrey and Brett's baby brother, climbed into the
No. 5 Kellogg's Corn Flakes Chevrolet and barely cracked the top 25
with a lap of 178.770 m.p.h. in the first round of pole
qualifications Thursday. He started 25th ahead of his brothers, who
started alongside each other on Row 13 in the 26th and 27th
positions . . . Brazilian-born drivers Cristiano da Matta and
Rubens Barrichello recorded their first victories last Sunday. Da
Matta, a seven-time winner on the Indy Lights circuit, won on the
CART FedEx Championship circuit at Chicago, surging to the lead
late in the race when Juan Montoya's gallop came to an halt because
of an electrical problem. Barrichello piloted his Ferrari to a
triumph in a Formula One race in Germany, where he sobbed as he
stood atop the podium. ``It was incredible,'' da Matta said. ``I've
won some races in other series, but this was just a different
emotion. And I'm so happy for Rubens. Both of us knew our day would
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from interviews, wire services, track publicity
departments, various race sanctioning bodies, teams, and sponsors
was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
