</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-AYALA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AYALA'S GAMBLE WAS RISKY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time you wonder why nobody fights anybody anymore, if
it can be avoided, think of Tony Ayala with tears in his eyes,
slumped in his corner, apologizing to his father for breaking his
hand and having to quit against Yory Boy Campas last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala's comeback, after a 16-year layoff in a New Jersey prison
after a rape conviction, was going well until that fight in San
Antonio. He had won five straight over powder puff opponents, was
pulling in about $200,000 a fight, and was selling tickets in his
hometown and haven, and slowly building new interest in an old
story.
</P>
<P>
   It was just a matter of time, if he kept winning, before the
37-year-old Ayala got the title shot he missed out on in 1982 or,
failing that, a least a chance for a big-money fight; his story and
his criminal record were too hard for the public and pay television
to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   But finally El Torito wanted to test himself. He wanted to get
in with some iron, although the belief was that Campas's iron had
been well pounded in his recent fights, several of which ended with
his early resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, veteran trainer and broadcaster Teddy Atlas was surprised
when Ayala agreed to the fight because ``Campas is not as shot as
people think. It's a dangerous fight for Ayala at a time when he
doesn't have to take the risk. He could just keep fighting anyone
down in San Antonio for $200,000 a fight until he gets into
position for what they want _ a big-money fight. It's an unusual
decision for a guy to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala's handlers probably were buoyed by the sight of Campas
being stopped by Oba Carr in March, but they also knew Campas could
punch with power. What they didn't know was that his head would be
hard enough to break Ayala's hand in the second round and his
punches would land often enough to nearly close Ayala's eyes by the
end of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Six rounds Ayala fought with a broken left hand, alternately
trying to widen a cut over Campas's eye and then trying to protect
his own swollen eyes and hand. In the end, Ayala's hand gave out
before Campas's heart and Ayala's father stopped the fight as Ayala
sat on his stool crying softly.
</P>
<P>
   From the fourth round, Ayala's father urged him to quit but he
refused. Ayala never quit. Not in that fight and not on himself.
</P>
<P>
   He is now an old fighter who must start over because he picked
the wrong guy on the wrong night. He must start over because he
took a chance, a chance that will keep him out of the ring until
December.
</P>
<P>
   He says he'll begin again because this setback was ``petty''
compared with what he faced in prison. That's true.
</P>
<P>
   Just like it's true most fighters won't gamble on themselves the
way Tony Ayala did.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Mayweather Sr. is having better luck than his son. He was
just hired as lead trainer of talented Erik Morales, the undefeated
World Boxing Council super bantamweight champion. Morales, coming
off a stirring battle with Marco Antonio Barrera, will challenge
Guty Espadas Sept. 2 for the WBC featherweight title. Mayweather
replaces Morales's father, Jose, because Mayweather is considered a
defensive genius. One thing he taught his son, Floyd Jr., before
their split was how not to get hit. If there is one skill Morales
does not possess, that's it, but Mayweather believes he has the
athletic ability to learn defense. If Morales can master defense to
complement his firepower, he'll win a lot of title belts before
he's through . . . Young Floyd is having problems of his own
making. The most talented 130-pound fighter in the world is
learning a harsh lesson. He's learning boxing doesn't need him.
Mayweather created a storm by calling a $12 million long-term offer
from HBO ``a slave contract,'' dumped his father-manager-trainer in
favor of ex-rap impressario James Prince, and irritated his
promoter to the point Top Rank refused to allow him to fight on the
Roy Jones Jr.-Eric Harding card Sept. 9 in New Orleans.
Mayweather's only appearance since last September was March 18,
when he defeated Goyo Vargas. Nobody noticed his presence then or
his absence now. He could not understand why his promoters did so
much more for Oscar De La Hoya, forgetting that De La Hoya earned
more income in one pay-per-view fight than Mayweather's produced in
his entire career. Mayweather learned what all this means when he
attended a press conference a week ago in New York announcing his
participation on the Jones card. A day later, Bob Arum, who still
holds Mayweather's promotional rights, could not reach a settlement
with Jones's promoter, Murad Muhammad. So Floyd Mayweather Jr. sits
some more. Muhammad acknowledged he never spoke to Arum about
getting a release to use Mayweather, dealing directly with Prince
and the fighter, apparently under the mistaken impression he could
work it out with Arum later. But things get worked out in boxing
only when all sides want them worked out, and at the moment few
people care about the problems Mayweather has created for himself.
Proof of that is everywhere, including on the Jones card, where
another Arum fighter, World Boxing Association featherweight
champion Freddie Norwood, will fight for Muhammad against Smoke
Gainer, a close friend of Jones. Arum had no trouble making a deal
there. Although Muhammad claimed he felt bad for Mayweather and
felt Arum was not acting in his fighter's best interest, he also
made clear he wasn't ready to go to war over Mayweather's services.
``We don't want trouble,'' Muhammad said. So a talented young man
sits for nearly a year and no one notices but his creditors. He has
no trainer since firing his father, no big-time TV contract and no
one rushing to give him one since he turned down that $12 million
deal. Don't feel sorry for Floyd Mayweather Jr. When all this
began, he listened to no one but the sound of his own voice . . .
Once again, boxing's TV players seem hellbent on hurting the sport.
Jones finishes up his contract with HBO Sept. 9 on a pay-per-view
card against Harding that seems likely to end up with Jones
fighting for nothing. TVKO, HBO's pay-per-view arm, wouldn't give
Jones a guarantee because he wouldn't extend his contract and since
he's the promoter, he must foot about a $900,000 bill. To make
money, the fight has to sell to around 60,000 homes. It would be
lucky if 60,000 homes that have HBO tuned in for this fight, as
great as Jones is. But give Jones some credit, too. Part of the
reason he could lose his shirt is that he told a fighter he
manages, David Izon, to sign to fight Mike Tyson Sept. 8 on HBO
rival Showtime. Izon stands to make $650,000 if it comes off. Tyson
has yet to agree and he always pulls out of every fight at least
once, so maybe there won't be a conflict, but Jones is ready to
take the fall if there is. That says he's a loyal friend, good
manager, and lousy businessman . . . Izon, by the way, seems to be
the perfect foil for Tyson. He's been knocked out by David Tua and
Michael Grant and was getting blasted by Derrick Jefferson before
suddenly knocking Jefferson stiff . . . Speaking of Tyson, there is
already talk of a showdown with Andrew Golota Nov. 4 in Hong Kong,
which would be Tyson's first pay-per-view appearance since
returning to boxing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits
</P>
<P>
   The planned Nov. 11 fight between Lennox Lewis and Tua in
Toronto is headed to purse bids because the sides cannot agree. Tua
has been offered $3.25 million but has demanded $4 million. A
Thursday deadline passed without Tua accepting the terms. If it
goes to purse bid, Tua will get 25 percent of the total with Lewis
receiving the rest . . . Fernando Vargas is set to fight Ross
Thompson Aug. 26 but says it is difficult to focus on defense of
his International Boxing Federation junior middleweight title
knowing he has a Dec. 2 date with Felix Trinidad for big money.
``It's hard to get up for a fight like this but I have to because I
know after this I get Trinidad.'' Only, of course, if he gets by
Thompson (24-3-1), who doesn't seem to pose much of a problem.
Although a deal has not been finalized, both fighters have
basically agreed to the significant terms, so all Vargas (19-0, 17
KO's) has to do is win . . . Evander Holyfield was asked last week
if he thought he won a rematch with Lewis. ``It's not what I
thought because I did win,'' Holyfield said. ``If you look at the
fight and judge it, you'll see that I controlled the fight.'' He
did? Holyfield fights John Ruiz Saturday for the vacant WBA title.
The winner may get a shot with Tyson . . . Anybody still think
Julio Cesar Chavez belonged in the same ring with Kostya Tszyu?
Shame on the WBC and its president, Jose Sulaiman. If Chavez needed
money that bad, why didn't Sulaiman give him some phony job with
the organization rather than a No. 1 ranking?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
