</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE GIVES TRADE THUMBS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has been gone for five months but it still seems strange to
think of Ray Bourque with the Colorado Avalanche. However, as much
of an icon as Bourque is in Boston, the move to the Rocky Mountains
very much agrees with the veteran defenseman. He has found renewed
life in his new home. Had he remained with the Bruins, it's
extremely likely he'd be retired now rather than gearing up for his
22d professional season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about what could've been, but the facts are, if I
would've finished here last year, I don't know if I would've played
another year,'' said Bourque. ``It just couldn't end like that for
me. It would've just ended with that sour feeling, just nothing
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of waiting for that inevitable bitter end, Bourque asked
to be traded to a Stanley Cup contender and the Bruins complied in
March. He wanted a chance to win what has eluded him as well as the
opportunity to find out how much he had left.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a major decision, going out, trying to compete to win
something and (revitalize) my career,'' said Bourque. ``And those
things happened. That's what I was looking for. That's how I want
to end my career, not with my head down and not feeling good about
the way I was playing or how the team was doing. I had to get into
a situation which was a positive one for me. Last year (in Boston)
just wasn't positive here with the club and the injuries and all
that.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as he looked forward to a new challenge, he did head
west with a heavy heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to leave, I didn't want to go anywhere,'' he
said. ``But for my best interests and my game and just the feeling
I've always played with and how I love playing the game, it wasn't
going to happen here. I went (to the Avalanche) and everything I
was looking for happened. I'm excited about the game and next year,
and that's how it should be. I still feel bad about leaving. I've
had so many great memories here and a great relationship with the
fans and it was a fun organization to play for, for the most part,
because we've been competitive and we've had some fun and some good
years, but I can't say that was the case last year. For me, I
needed a change and it was a tough one to make, but looking back,
it was a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque had the opportunity to become an unrestricted free agent
July 1 but rather than test the market, he came to terms on a deal
with the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked my situation there and I knew going back there, there
was some kind of unfinished business,'' said Bourque, referring to
Colorado's loss to Dallas in the Western Conference finals. ``I
thought we could've gotten to the (Stanley Cup) finals and came
close. Next year, I think we'll be there again. I was really liking
the situation I was in there.''
</P>
<P>
   As happy as he was at the end, Bourque acknowledged that after
more than 20 years with one team, it took some time to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the ice, it happened pretty quick, but off the ice, it was
very tough,'' he said. ``It took me probably three or four weeks to
feel comfortable with myself, the change and the move and that
whole thing. You go through a lot of emotions and a lot of
different thoughts come through your mind. Not having my family and
all that was hard. It took about three or four weeks and then
everything fell into place.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Bruins signed free agent defenseman Paul Coffey,
president/general manager Harry Sinden said he had been interested
in making an offer to Bourque. He said he didn't have the chance,
however, because Bourque never became a free agent. Bourque said he
didn't have any knowledge of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think there was any openings there,'' he said.
``I never really heard anything, not the slightest comment or
whatever in terms of them possibly offering me a contract, not that
they were allowed to talk to me until July 1. But I would've been
surprised. I kind of had my mind set with Colorado, that if it
could work out there then I probably wouldn't get to free agency. I
really didn't think all that much about it. Their GM (Pierre
Lacroix) said he'd get back to me within a week and he did.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Coffey signing, Bourque said he was surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little bit, like a lot of people,'' he said. ``The
power play, they don't really have anybody back there and I think
he'll help out in that situation. I hope it works out for him and
for them. He's been a great player, so we'll have to wait and see.
People can look at it in two ways, but if Paul Coffey plays the way
he's capable of, he's going to help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bourque certainly will help the Avalanche. The way
everything has worked out, he has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look back,'' he said. ``I'm just looking forward. It
would've been perfect and nice to finish here, but it wasn't meant
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Homeward bound?
</P>
<P>
   Word around the league is that injured center Eric Lindros will
land in his native Toronto. Lindros effectively cut his ties to the
Flyers by rejecting an $8.5 million qualifying offer that included
an $85,000 minor league clause, and he remains a restricted free
agent. Lindros, who suffered four concussions in a five-month span
last season and six in the last 28 months, is probably out of any
lineup until December or January, and most likely will change teams
via a trade rather than an offer sheet that would cost a team five
first-round draft picks. Others reportedly bidding for Lindros's
services are the Rangers, Kings, and Lightning. Maple Leafs
assistant to the president Bill Watters indicated much would have
to happen for Lindros to end up there. ``You're talking about what
would be a very complex deal, which would include the risk
factor,'' said Watters. ``We're one of the teams Philly targeted
and we're flattered. But first you have to satisfy the Flyers with
a package of draft picks and/or players. Then you have to work with
the Lindros people on a contract.'' . . . The Canucks hired former
Blackhawks GM Bob Murray as a pro scout. Murray, 45, had spent more
than 25 years with the Blackhawks _ as a player, scout, director of
player personnel, assistant GM, and, finally, as GM after Bob
Pulford resigned in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No big deal
</P>
<P>
   As talented as he is, right wing Alexsey Morozov had to settle
for a minimum raise from Pittsburgh after three so-so seasons.
Morozov was the Penguins' No. 1 pick in 1995. ``We were told by the
Penguins that they want him to be stronger,'' said Morozov's agent,
Jay Grossman. ``They want him to be able to win the battles you
need to win on the ice and fight through checks.'' Certainly sounds
reasonable . . . The Kings re-upped free agent center Ian
Laperriere, avoiding an arbitration hearing . . . No word yet on
what center Alexei Yashin is going to do. He sat out last season
rather than honor the final year of his contract with the Senators
that would have paid him $3.6 million. An arbitrator ruled that
Yashin still owes that final year until he can become a free agent.
But the bratty Yashin doesn't seem to care what the team thinks or
what the arbitrator rules. Unfortunately, Yashin's talent is such
an asset that it would make sense for the Senators to trade him in
order to get something back, but it would be great if he were
forced to sit out for the rest of his life. That might wake him up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rekindling an old Flame
</P>
<P>
   The Calgary Flames finally settled on a coach last week, hiring
46-year-old Don Hay, a former Flames assistant. Hay, who coached
the Coyotes during the 1996-97 season, replaces former Bruins coach
Brian Sutter and promises a more uptempo approach. ``Every team in
the NHL plays such a strong defensive game now,'' said Hay, who
spent the last two years in junior hockey as GM/head coach of the
Western League's Tri-City Americans. ``In the last 10 years, the
emphasis has been placed on defense, so every coach and every
player has really done a good job with the defensive part of the
game. Now we have to do a good job with the offensive part of the
game. We have to make the offense more of a factor in our game.''
New Flames GM Craig Button said he wanted to take his time
choosing, and considered retaining Sutter. He also talked to
Avalanche assistant coach Bryan Trottier. Nashville assistant Brent
Peterson also was in the mix until he pulled himself out . . . Nice
to see Roger Neilson back in the NHL. The 66-year-old Neilson, who
was let go by the Flyers, has accepted an assistant coaching
position with Ottawa under Jacques Martin. Neilson underwent
treatment for cancer last year and said the illness is in
remission. ``We had great doctors in Philadelphia and they tell me
I'm in good shape,'' he said. ``I'm off all medications and I'm
working out regularly. I'm probably in better shape than I was
before this whole thing started.'' . . . 32 days to training camp.
Think Anson Carter, Joe Thornton, or Sergei Samsonov will be there
at the start? Me neither.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
