<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-PROSPASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREND IS TO PASS THE TORCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, the Olympics are right after the US Open. And yes, they're
halfway around the world. And, yes, it's a long year. Still, the
refusal of several of the world's top tennis players (e.g. Pete
Sampras, Martina Hingis, Anna Kournikova) to play for their
countries points to a growing trend among professional athletes to
turn up their noses at the Games. It isn't just the tennis players.
Kobe Bryant said he wasn't interested in what would have been a
virtually certain gold medal with the US men's basketball team and
Shaquille O'Neal turned down a return trip. And Vlade Divac and
Aleksandar Djordjevic don't want to play for Yugoslavia, which is
expected to meet the US in the final. Too much of a time
commitment, they said.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude is mind-boggling to rowers, archers,
weightlifters, and the thousands of other amateur athletes who
scrimp and sweat for a quadrennium to make a team. The pros not
only make millions a year, they also get free passes to Olympus. No
trials. Just say yes. Those pros who do, like Andre Agassi, realize
that the Games offer an incalculable payoff. ``To me, the Olympics
represent the core of what sports are all about _ human challenge
and triumph,'' said Agassi, who is returning to defend the title he
won in Atlanta. ``The reward is pride, not anything material.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Test hasn't passed yet
</P>
<P>
   That breakthrough test for banned EPO (erythropoietin) announced
last week by the International Olympic Committee isn't a done deal
for Sydney. The unprecedented urine-blood test still has to be
approved by the IOC's lawyers and by its executive board at the end
of the month. And questions abound: Is the test 100 percent
accurate? Will athletes in all sports be tested, or just from those
sports under suspicion (e.g. endurance sports such as cycling and
swimming)? Is the blood test too ``invasive,'' as many athletes
(especially Muslims) claim? ``The final victory against doping
needs to go in steps,'' conceded IOC president Juan Antonio
Samaranch. ``Many steps build stairs, and at the top of the stairs
is heaven.'' . . . There are nearly enough women requesting injury
waivers to next week's Olympic Gymnastics Trials at the FleetCenter
to fill the team _ Magnificent 7 veterans Shannon Miller and Jaycie
Phelps plus Jeannette Antolin, Amanda Stroud, and Stephanie Carter.
All of them will have to pass fitness tests at Bela Karolyi's
Houston ranch before getting an OK. Already approved for the men's
trials are Chris Young and Yewki Tomita.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to make splash
</P>
<P>
   It's redemption time for Jenny Thompson at this week's Olympic
Swimming Trials in Indianapolis. After failing to qualify in an
individual event in 1996, Thompson has a shot at four (50-100-200
freestyle and 100 butterfly) plus three relays. The most intriguing
story, though, is sprinter Dara Torres trying for her fourth team
at 33 after being out of the pool for seven (yes, seven) years.
Torres could well earn a spot in the 50 and should at least make a
relay. Back for another go are Atlanta gold medalists Amy Van
Dyken, Tom Dolan, Brooke Bennett, Brad Bridgewater, and Beth
Botsford . . . Back on track, if gingerly, are Maurice Greene and
Michael Johnson after pulling up lame in the 200 at the Olympic
trials two weekends ago. Greene, who says his hamstring injury was
a cramp and not a pull, plans to run the 100 next weekend in
Zurich. Johnson is back training, but is iffy for Zurich . . . Why
did the Chinese turn thumbs-down on race walker Chen Yueling
competing for the US in Sydney after they'd granted waivers to
American badminton and table tennis players? Because Chen, who won
a gold medal for China in 1992, is still a contender. Though the
IOC requires waivers for any athlete wanting to compete for a new
country less than three years after they receive citizenship,
they're usually (but not automatically) granted. Cuba this year
nixed kayaker Angel Perez, who also had made the US team. Replacing
Chen will be Joanne Dow of Bedford, N.H., who was fourth at the
trials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wakeup call?
</P>
<P>
   Warning bells are going off for the US Olympic women's soccer
team, which has lost three times this year to the Norwegians, who
will be its opening opponent Down Under. ``We lost to China at home
right before the World Cup and it was a great thing for us,'' mused
midfielder Julie Foudy after the Americans lost, 2-1, in Oslo last
weekend. Meanwhile, the banged-up US males salvaged a 1-0 victory
over the Bolton Wanderers last weekend with only nine players on
the field for the final half-hour. For 10 minutes, while injured
midfielder Joey DiGiamarino was being tended to, the Americans were
down to eight . . . Getting named to the US Olympic men's road
cycling team by the coaches last week made up for the travel
nightmare that kept Fred Rodriguez out of the May trials. After bad
weather stranded him in San Francisco for an entire day, Rodriguez
missed his connecting flight in Dallas by 15 minutes and couldn't
get off the standby list for the last flight to Jackson, Miss.,
that would have gotten him to the starting line. ``I begged the
airline and told them that I had to make the Olympics and this was
one of my only chances,'' Rodriguez said. ``But nothing worked.''
Happy ending, too, for Johnny Bairos, who was added to the track
cycling team after recuperating from a horrific crash in June in
which he broke his jaw in two places, fractured a kneecap, and
damaged both sinus cavities . . . Except for Monica Tranel-Michini
(who is rowing the single), odds are that the US Olympic women's
eight will feature the same faces who won the silver medal at last
year's World Rowing Championships _ Linda Miller, Amy Martin, Betsy
McCagg, Katie Maloney, Sarah Jones, Torrey Folk, Amy Fuller, and
coxswain Raj Shah. Lianne Nelson, who missed qualifying in the
pair, probably will replace Michini and may stroke. With the roster
deadline barely a week off, the men's lightweight four is still a
scramble. The incumbents (Tom Auth, Paul Teti, Marc Schneider, and
Bill Carlucci) are in the mix, as is Harvard grad Greg Ruckman . .
. The man who vowed four years ago that we could shoot him if we
ever saw him around a racing shell again is going back to Olympus
for a shot at a fifth gold. Great Britain's Steve Redgrave, who
will row in the ``Fab Four'' in Sydney at 38, would be only the
second athlete to do it in five straight Games. Hungarian fencer
Aladar Gerevich managed six in a row between 1932 and 1960 despite
an eight-year hiatus for World War II.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perfectly awesome
</P>
<P>
   Goose eggs are looming ad infinitum for US Olympic softball
pitcher Lisa Fernandez, who has hurled four consecutive perfect
games. Her teammates, meanwhile, are 90-0 since 1998 and have
outscored rivals, 300-2, on their current exhibition tour . . .
After pulling out of last year's world championships because they
claimed the judges were hosing them, the Cuban boxing team is
talking trash again. ``We are going to clean up,'' bragged eternal
coach Alcides Sagarra. ``What we want is the national hymn played
12 times and our flag raised 12 times.'' Slim chance of that. The
Cubans, whose program has sagged in recent years, won only four
golds and two silvers in Atlanta. Two of their champions are back _
flyweight Maikro Romero (now a light fly) and heavyweight Felix
Savon, who is going for his third gold . . . Though the US Olympic
women's volleyball team is ranked only 10th in the world and has
just two Atlanta veterans (Tara Cross-Battle and Danielle Scott) on
the roster, it has a decent shot at surviving the prelims in
Sydney. All it needs to do is beat weak sisters Australia and Kenya
to make the quarterfinals . . . Nearly half of the US women's
Alpine ski team has gone AWOL from the mandatory summer camp in
Utah, saying that a month of team-building and workouts is too
much. So Megan Gerety, Katie Monahan, Sarah Schleper, and Kirsten
Clark went home . . . While skeptics were fretting about whether
Sydney's train system could withstand the Olympic onslaught, they
should have been worrying about the planes. Even though the
government spent two years and $351 million improving the airport,
the facility has been shut down twice in a month with power outages
in the control tower.
</P>
<P>
   Material from wire services, international federations, the US
Olympic Committee, sports governing bodies and interviews was used
in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
