<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3894 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-BBNOTES-GARCIAPAR     08-05 2463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-GARCIAPARRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLERUD: NOMAR HAS WHAT IT TAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is one of the fringe benefits that comes with having been
the last player to be hitting .400 this deep into the season: You
get to be asked about the chances of the next guy.
</P>
<P>
   So John Olerud was hardly surprised when a visitor from Boston
strolled into the Mariners clubhouse last week to solicit his
opinion on Nomar Garciaparra and his run at .400.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Olerud said, he believes Garciaparra has a legitimate shot
at becoming the first player since Ted Williams hit .406 in 1941 to
crack the .400 barrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been hitting for four months now and he's right there,''
Olerud said. ``He has to stay hot for another two months. That's a
long time to stay hot, but he's already done it for four months, so
it's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud was hitting .400 as late as Aug. 2, 1993, before tailing
off to .363. The only player to have gone deeper into the season at
.400 was George Brett of the Royals, who was at .400 on Sept. 20,
1980, before finishing at .390.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, of course, doesn't want to discuss the subject, but
it's impossible to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always going to have people asking questions about
it,'' said Olerud. ``It's in the forefront of your mind, but you
just try to downplay it as much as you can. But if you're still
there the middle of September, then you talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud, a low-key, affable sort who left the Mets as a free
agent in order to return to his native Washington, wasn't the type
who was going to allow his hair to fall out because of his batting
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt any pressure to do it because I never felt like I
was the guy who was going to do it,'' he said. ``I was just having
a real good year. I just wanted the chance to swing the bat the way
I had been for as long as I could and so that's the way I went at
it. I was going to keep going and if it was meant to happen it will
happen, and if not, then it's not. Just try to take good swings and
see how it goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the approach you have to take. I'm sure that
Nomar doesn't feel like he has to be the guy to do it. He's just
going to try and have as good a year as he can. That's what I would
think.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud smiled when told that Williams, at his Hitters' Hall of
Fame last year, said he thought Garciaparra could become the best
player of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real big compliment,'' Olerud said. ``He's having a
great year, and hopefully he's able to enjoy it for what it is, a
great year. Yeah, I enjoyed (1993). There was a lot of talking to
the media, which was a downside, but the upside was that I was
having a great year. It was just fun coming to the ballpark knowing
you're going to take good swings and you're going to hit the ball
hard. That makes it a lot easier to go to the park.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud doesn't know Garciaparra, other than to say hello to him
when he's playing first base and Garciaparra reaches safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he's a very aggressive hitter,'' Olerud said. ``If
he gets a pitch in his zone, he's going to hit it. And he's got a
real big zone. He covers the plate real well, he handles off-speed
pitches well, and he recognizes the pitches well. He's not the type
of guy who is easy to pitch around, and if it's a decent pitch to
hit or he can get a bat on the ball, he's going to take a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're a little different in that I'm looking for a
good pitch to hit, and if the pitchers make good quality pitches
I'm going to fall behind in the count and I'll be fighting pitches
off. Nomar, he's ready from the moment he gets up there for a pitch
in his zone. I like that approach. I like being aggressive and
being ready for your pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will it happen again?
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett, who bumped an umpire during a July 15 tirade and
was suspended, got into a shouting match with his manager Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious question today is: Will he go off again?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the traits that make him a great player have led to
trouble for him from time to time,'' said Houston Astros general
manager Gerry Hunsicker, who as an executive with the New York Mets
was instrumental in the 1994 trade that brought Everett to the Mets
from the Florida Marlins. Hunsicker then acquired him for the
Astros in 1997 and last December traded Everett to the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mainly his competitiveness and his lack of fear of anyone
or anything. At times, he can lose control. As he has matured and
grown up, those times have become fewer and fewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's just somebody who has the ability to lose control of
his emotions. His background shows that there are times when he
loses control and it's gotten him in trouble. It's just one aspect
of his personality. Some aspects of his personality get him in
trouble. They can also make him a great competitor. I still
maintain Carl is a good person. He needs a support system and an
environment that allows him to perform without a lot of stress and
distractions.''
</P>
<P>
   After all the controversy Everett endured in New York in '97,
few teams were willing to take a chance on him. An exception was
Houston. ``I felt with myself and (hitting coach) Tommy McCraw, we
had a support system in place,'' Hunsicker said. ``And this is a
much less scrutinized environment we have here in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of the fact this organization really helped
Carl get over the hump and helped to lay the foundation for the
player Carl became.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Astros players, including star first baseman Jeff
Bagwell, said Everett was their most valuable player last season,
although in Houston players took notice of Everett's penchant for
tardiness, which surfaced again this year in Boston. But Astros
manager Larry Dierker chose not to make an issue of it, just as
Jimy Williams has said it is not an issue with the Red Sox, even
though Everett did something here he never did in Houston, arriving
so late he was not on the field when his group took batting
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Until Everett dropped the appeal of his 10-game suspension for
his July tirade, the players' union was prepared to seek a
reduction in the penalty by arguing that in a previous incident,
Vince Coleman was suspended seven games after drawing blood from an
umpire's face when his batting helmet struck the umpire during an
argument.
</P>
<P>
   But Everett decided to drop the appeal for reasons he has not
made public. ``We want to let this thing die out,'' said Larry
Reynolds, his agent.
</P>
<P>
   Everett hurt his right hand when he punched the bat rack in the
Red Sox dugout during his explosion and did not play in two games
before beginning to serve his suspension. But both he and Red Sox
officials, including manager Williams, have insisted the wrist was
not a factor in his decision to drop his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Carl's position and the team's position that it made
sense to serve it at this point in the schedule, instead of later
when the team is deeper in the playoff race,'' said one baseball
official with knowledge of the case. ``And from Carl's personal
perspective, he wants this thing to go away. He didn't want to
prolong it, which would only exacerbate the rehabilitation of his
reputation, and a lot of that already has been undone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker was asked if it was possible that Everett may have
other incidents in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recent incident reinforces that there's part of his
personality that from time to time will surface,'' Hunsicker said.
``He needs somebody to be there in his corner, to give him a
support system. If there's not a support system in place, the
potential is there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Case closed: He's a keeper
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette's greatest find this season, hands down, has been
Hipolito Pichardo, who has come back from elbow surgery that caused
him to miss all of the '99 season to become an indispensable member
of the Sox bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me he was a two-pitch pitcher,'' said pitching coach
Joe Kerrigan. ``Fastball and a splitter. But he throws a slider
that is just as good as his splitter.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question, Kerrigan said, that Pichardo has closer's
stuff. ``And the control, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have been cautious about pitching Pichardo on
back-to-back days, but his workload of late, which includes
pitching in three of Boston's last four games entering Saturday,
suggests that concern is waning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws a 92-94-mile-an-hour with nasty sink, straight-down
sink that you don't see too often,'' Kerrigan said. ``And he throws
a heavy ball, the kind of ball that pitchers use to break bats when
guys swing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox may be perfectly content to leave Pichardo in a setup
role, but if his arm is sound and he continues to pitch as well as
he has, the Sox might have reason to think about converting Derek
Lowe back to a starter next season. Lowe was an All-Star this
season as a closer, but he recently admitted he hasn't abandoned
the idea of starting again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd still like to get a shot someday,'' Lowe said. ``It would
be hard to leave a position in the bullpen where I've had success
the last two years to go back to doing something where I didn't
have success (0-7 as a starter for the Sox), but I'd like to think
I'd do better this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe things will change in a year or two if (Rod) Beck and
Flash (Gordon) come back. It may be easier to find a guy who
pitches an inning than another starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to go by whatever they say _ setup, close, start. My
goal is just to spend a long time here while they use me however
they want. That's one of the advantages of having a long-term deal,
you don't care how you're used as long as we do whatever needs to
be done to get us to the playoffs. I've really enjoyed being the
closer the last two years, but I'm never going to say never (about
starting).''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Lowe would like to do, he said, is be an All-Star
again. ``I wish all players could go through it and see what it's
like, what a great feeling it is to be there,'' he said. ``It
really is one of my goals to get back because it was such a special
feeling. I've got to thank Joe Torre for picking me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt to ask
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Giants general manager Brian Sabean said, he did ask
Phillies GM Ed Wade whether Curt Schilling would add the Giants to
his list of teams to which he'd accept a trade. ``That was our aim
before the break, during the break, and after the break, but it
wasn't going to happen. We weren't the only team to ask. There's
nothing we could have done because we tried.'' On how Schilling
winding up in Arizona will impact the race in the NL West, Sabean
said: ``We can't worry about that. We're thankful we've got the
roster we've got. They're going to have to make do with what
they've got. It's all going to be settled on the field. Obviously,
they've got two starters who can cause some problems. But we've got
eight games left against them at the end of the season, and three
with LA. I'm sure LA will duke it out to the end and make it a
three-team race. Sabean on Giants closer Robb Nen, who set a record
for saves in a month with 14 in July: ``He's throwing better than
he ever has, including his time here.'' . . . How durable is Craig
Biggio, the Astros' gritty second baseman who went on the disabled
list for the first time in 13 seasons after tearing the medial
collateral and anterior cruciate ligaments in his left knee last
week? He had played with a muscle tear in his shoulder and a torn
ligament in his right ankle . . . David Segui, who has been playing
in the outfield since his trade from Texas to Cleveland, admits he
tried to come back too quickly after he had a metal plate
surgically implanted in his left foot last winter. The plate has
since snapped, Segui said, and he can hear it clicking when he runs
. . . Los Angeles Times columnist Bill Plaschke laments the passing
of another tradition at Dodger Stadium, where the ushers have given
up their boaters and uniforms for designer golf shirts and sweater
vests. The clothing company's name is visible, Plaschke said,
making it just another form of in-stadium advertising . . . Expos
catcher Chris Widger criticized the team for trading standout
outfielder Rondell White, who was sent to the Cubs, opening up a
spot for Milton Bradley. ``Vladimir Guerrero is our superstar, Jose
Vidro is our All-Star, but the person who makes this team go is
Rondell,'' Widger said. ``Everybody in this locker room knows it.
It's gone now. Our biggest building block is gone.'' . . . Mike
Lansing, the Sox' new second baseman, on the sudden collapse of his
former team, the Rockies, who went from first to fourth in a span
of about three weeks last month: ``I still don't have any
explanation for it,'' he said. ``We went into San Francisco and
lost a doubleheader and it seems like panic set in. I don't know
who panicked, if it was the players or the coaches. I don't think
it was the manager. Obviously, when you lose 12 in a row you're
going to try different things. But we got to the point where guys
were saying, `How can we not lose?' And they started playing not to
lose. I'm not going to say anything bad about the Rockies or Buddy
(Bell, the manager). He helped me have a great deal after I had
back surgery and missed last year.'' . . . Hunsicker on Adam
Everett, the shortstop who went to Houston in the Carl Everett
deal: ``We expected to get a polished defensive player and we did.
He has great instincts, and we believe in time he may become a
solid all-around shortstop.'' But Hunsicker concedes it may take
more time than originally anticipated. He believes the Red Sox may
have rushed Adam Everett offensively when they had him play at
Double A last season, and then the Astros had him start the year in
Triple A, where he was overmatched offensively. ``He's probably at
least a year away from having a chance to compete on the major
league level.'' And Moises Alou, Hunsicker said, was never
available, not at the price teams were willing to pay. ``So much
was written at the outset, but we were never trying aggressively to
move Alou as was reported,'' he said. ``A number of teams thought
we were going to dump him. But we made it very clear that he was an
All-Star-caliber player and we needed something pretty good back.''
. . . A law enforcement official said Friday that there are no new
developments involving Manny Alexander in connection with the
illegal steroids found in the glove compartment of his Mercedes
after he loaned it to a bat boy.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
