<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3895 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-MCCARTYMU     08-05 2157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-MCCARTYMUSIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCARTY HAS ROOM TO GROW WITH MUSIC CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM _ A single, low-watt bulb keeps most of the voice room
and its padded walls in shadow. The lone shaft of light shines on a
towering microphone just tall enough to fit 6-foot-10-inch Walter
McCarty. Lyrics scribbled over Celtics stationery rest on a nearby
music stand. In a basement recording studio at his home, McCarty
works on finishing his debut CD titled ``Situations.'' Rhythm and
blues music fills the control room. Dance beats and rap give the
tracks a hip-hop feel and, hopefully, popular appeal.
</P>
<P>
   With their chorus of doubts about an NBA player producing a
successful album, the skeptics can drown out the smooth tenor of
the Celtic forward. But not for long. Given a few minutes to
showcase his vocal talents, McCarty dispels any notion that he
might be a music dilettante. Wearing headphones and standing at the
microphone, McCarty sings with his eyes closed. He nods approvingly
with each down beat. He takes his music seriously, sometimes
spending 13 hours at a time in the studio refining a cut.
</P>
<P>
   During the last year and a half, McCarty pieced together
``Situations,'' drawing on his experiences in the NBA for some
subject matter and working around the Celtics' schedule. The lyrics
contain references to the league's fast-paced lifestyle, wealthy
players, and the price of sports celebrity. But McCarty believes
his audience will relate to the overriding music discussions of
relationships, dating, and partying.
</P>
<P>
   McCarty claims his NBA career and budding music career
complement each other. Without his lucrative contract and a day job
that leaves lots of down time, McCarty could not fund his music
company, IceStorm Productions, or afford a private studio. The
music gives McCarty a way to relax and gain perspective on
basketball. The CD gives McCarty a creative outlet outside
basketball and provides a rare insight into the life of an NBA
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``My music side brings out more of me than basketball does,''
said McCarty. ``People don't really get to know Walter McCarty the
Celtic. You can only get so close to NBA basketball players,
whether it's on the court or off the court. Shaking hands and
signing autographs, that's pretty much all the interaction you'll
get.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm doing this music thing, for me, it's more personal.
People get to know me better. I get to express myself. After a
game, you only talk about basketball. A lot of people know I like
to sing, but they don't know what's behind the big curtain. This
album opens up the curtain and says, `This is Walter.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heroic efforts
</P>
<P>
   With two different sides of his personality playing on different
stages, McCarty envisions himself ``being Superman and Clark
Kent.'' Not that the 3.8 points per game and 1.8 rebounds he
averaged last season in just over 14 minutes a contest were
Superman-like numbers. Not that he bumbles and stutters his way
through life off the court with an endearing nerdiness.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison to the comic book superhero works on a very basic
level. In a Celtics uniform, the aggressive, physical side takes
over. In the studio, the sensitive, emotional side of McCarty shows
up, hesitating to ask a girl to dance in one song and worrying
about the poor judgment of a female friend in another. Still,
parallels between the player and musician remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in the studio, time goes by so fast, especially
when you're doing something that you love,'' said McCarty. ``It's
like if you're out there having a good game and you know your shots
are going in, you don't want the game to end. It's the same way
with time in the studio. I'll just come in after games and put in
five or six hours in the studio. Basketball is my priority, but
sometimes I (sacrifice my basketball for my music). I could easily
be in the gym every day, instead of being in the studio.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowded with high-tech equipment and tangles of power cords, the
10-by-12-foot studio control room is much more than Superman's
telephone booth. And the transformation from McCarty the basketball
player to McCarty the musician is much less dramatic. Wearing a
Celtics T-shirt, sweatpants, and black cap turned backward, he
ducks his head under a door frame and moves quickly down a flight
of stairs to the home of IceStorm Productions.
</P>
<P>
   McCarty sits at a keyboard and fools around with a few chords,
playing by ear without any formal training. (He also has taught
himself guitar and bass.) An enviable collection of recording and
mixing equipment extends to his right. Five sound modules that help
layer the tracks for each song. Two drum machines. Two CD players.
Two tape decks. A microphone voice compressor. Two external effects
machines for reverbs and choruses. Three digital recorders. Five
large speakers. One digital mixing board. One closed-circuit
television monitor to watch the recording artist, since a bathroom
separates the control room from the voice room.
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple but impressive setup for an independent production
company that employs four people and competes in a billion-dollar
industry against other independent labels with million-dollar
budgets. ``It's a business, not a hobby for anybody in the house,''
said Frank Williams, a college friend of McCarty who serves as vice
president of operations of IceStorm and co-owner of the company.
When production intensifies, Williams lives in the McCarty
townhouse along with other contributing employees (occasionally six
or seven at one time). It's a music fraternity, with McCarty the
majority owner of IceStorm.
</P>
<P>
   The production company, whose name comes partly from McCarty's
college nickname, ``Ice,'' emphasizes collaborative efforts. The
creative minds in the house feed off each other. ``Situations'' is
the first major undertaking for IceStorm and, in an unusual step,
McCarty and crew will not only produce the CD, but also handle
promotion and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure I come in and let everybody know this is
something I'm serious about and put a lot of effort into,'' said
McCarty. ``I went about it the same way as somebody else trying to
make it in the music business would go about it. I tried to get the
best producers, struggled trying to come up with songs or stuff
that people will listen to.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Melodies, messages
</P>
<P>
   The debut CD begins with a two-minute interlude, a melodic
message to the listeners that sets the tone for the songs that
follow. The situation is McCarty ``talking to a girl, all girls''
about the pressures of being 26 with money and fame. He doesn't
want the people he meets to go out of their way to impress him or
act differently in his presence.
</P>
<P>
   How many times do I have to break it down to you?
</P>
<P>
   Living two lives in this world is some crazy stuff to do . . .
</P>
<P>
   Who are you trying to test?
</P>
<P>
   Please don't make me flex
</P>
<P>
   I sure don't need your stress
</P>
<P>
   In my situation
</P>
<P>
   As with the opening lines, most of the NBA-related content
remains veiled. From heartbreak and one-night stands to pulsing
club scenes, McCarty and his collaborators at IceStorm strived to
write about experiences common to everyone. Each song is a
self-contained story, some derived from real life experiences
traveling in the NBA and some fed by imagination.
</P>
<P>
   In every song and interlude, McCarty adopts the voice of the
narrator. At times, he sounds apologetic and kindhearted. At times,
he can come across as flaunting an extravagant lifestyle. (``If
it's on tonight, jump in the Benz,'' he sings at one particularly
raucous party moment. ``Let's ride, if the feeling's right. If the
Benz is too small or too tight, I've got a Navigator. The Navi's
just right.'')
</P>
<P>
   Before its yet unnamed early fall release date, ``Situations''
should grow to a compilation of 10 or 11 full songs with three or
four short interludes that announce thematic changes. McCarty
currently is finishing the last few tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The CD) is kind of what his lifestyle is,'' said Marc
Silverburg, co-executive producer of ``Situations'' and co-owner of
IceStorm. ``Naturally, he is an NBA guy. He's a bachelor, so it's
got a bachelor's feel. It's also got a searching feel. He's a
bachelor and he's searching, but during his search, he's having a
lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial interlude also addresses the skeptics and music
purists who might be offended by yet another athlete financing his
way into a music career. The recorded reply by McCarty to critics:
Listen first, then judge. In recent years there have been some
notable, rather than ignominious, contributions from NBA players.
``Shaq Diesel,'' the debut CD of Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal,
went platinum in 1993. Former player and talented jazz bassist
Waymon Tisdale signed a seven-year contract with MoJazz records in
1995. McCarty dreams of going gold or platinum, but would be
content selling 100,000 copies of his CD.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Serious business
</P>
<P>
   The thoughtful r &AMP; b style of McCarty's debut album and
influences of Boyz II Men and Brian McKnight should help
distinguish it from the less-serious efforts of other athletes, the
hastily compiled rap collections and ill-advised stage romps.
Unwilling to parlay friendships made through the NBA (especially
during his rookie year in New York) with such music business
magnates as Sean ``Puffy'' Combs into musical contributions,
McCarty drew from lesser-known talents (Ed O.G. and Iayadonna) and
artists signed on with IceStorm (Black Coffey and Kymyra Moore).
Still, producer Dave ``Jam'' Hall, who has worked with Mariah
Carey, Mary J. Blige, and Madonna, saw enough promise in McCarty to
help produce ``Situations.''
</P>
<P>
   But the best evidence of McCarty's commitment to the project is
his life-long interest in music. Following his great-great-aunt, he
started singing in church choirs as a child and in a family group
with his cousin, brother, and sister. When he reached high school,
he performed in concert choir, receiving his share of solos and
attending Indiana state music competitions. Although he missed high
school concerts because of All-Star games and tournaments, his
interest in music continued at Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to listen to him for six years,'' said Celtics coach
Rick Pitino, who also coached McCarty in college. ``(He sings) at
parties, when we go on the road. Any time there was a piano in
college, he would play and sing. He always had talent. I remember
him singing the national anthem in high school and he did it in
college. We've been in some restaurants where he's taken over the
piano (in college). I knew he was a talented young man to the point
of an amateur, then the players told me his (debut) CD was
outstanding. Paul Pierce was telling me and Antoine Walker. And
they would go the opposite way, razz him a little bit and say it
wasn't good.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, he turned his college dorm room into a small studio
with a keyboard given to him by his mother and equipment rented
from the Doo Wop Shop in Lexington. At Kentucky, he learned the
basics of music production by experimentation, recording teammates
rapping and allowing recruits to sit down and sing. As word of the
dorm room studio spread, the roots of IceStorm Productions formed.
Years of friendship and partnership are behind ``Situations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I like to take my time and put out the nicest project,
the hottest project,'' said McCarty. ``That's what I've been trying
to do. When you start making records and if you've never done
records before, it is foreign. You have to go the extra mile to
make sure it's done the proper way, especially when you're doing it
independently. By doing our own research, we're doing it the way we
think it should be done. Right now, we think we're doing a heck of
a job.''
</P>
<P>
   With the NBA season fast approaching, McCarty and the creative
minds at IceStorm are putting in long studio hours to finish most
of the project before training camp. McCarty figures he has six
weeks to work through the kinks, polish the existing tracks, and
select the last few songs for the debut. A yet-to-be-chosen single
will be released in early September. A video shoot and promotional
tour will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-September, the focus for McCarty will shift to the Celtics.
More shooting and weightlifting. Less writing and recording. But
considering McCarty's serious interest in basketball and music,
there still will be a lot of mixing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we're professional basketball players, it doesn't
mean it's all we want to do with our lives,'' said McCarty. ``We do
have other lives, other loves. Some people get caught up in doing
just one thing. But I don't think you should look at yourself, your
life, as meant to do just one thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
