<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3896 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     08-05 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUD RETURN INCLUDES SHOUTING MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The day was practically gift-wrapped for him. The only thing
missing was a skywriter's calligraphy _ ``Welcome Back, Carl!''
hovering above Fenway Park. If Carl Everett simply had accepted
this gift of an afternoon, a lot of the overhyped madness
surrounding him would have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't accept, and so the madness continues. When will it
end? Well, no matter what spin you hear from the Red Sox, the truth
is that only one man (Everett) holds the answer to the question.
Jimy Williams doesn't know. Dan Duquette doesn't know. Everett's
teammates don't know. And the man who does know chose to leave the
park Saturday afternoon without saying much.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad he didn't show such verbal restraint earlier in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Everett came off a 10-game suspension and immediately walked
into the middle of a ruckus. At about 10:30 a.m., 15 minutes before
the Red Sox held batting practice, Everett got into a loud, profane
argument with Williams. Both men are known for their unique
phraseology, but they weren't quite as original during their
confrontation in the manager's office. They were cussing each other
out with language that we've all heard before.
</P>
<P>
   After the brief eruption, Everett left the office cursing and
headed to the trainer's room. He returned and began watching
television. It would have been fitting if a WWF performance had
been on the screen, because that's exactly what this organization
is beginning to resemble. At least the wrestlers' act is scripted;
what excuse do Everett and his enablers (Williams and Duquette)
have?
</P>
<P>
   Following BP, Williams said that he would keep all information
``in house.'' He said that families sometimes have disagreements in
which the participants raise their voices. He gave a lot of vague
answers and nonanswers, but the most revealing one came when
someone asked if his beef with Everett was resolved. He did an
old-school lindyhop around a straight answer. Here's why: He
probably knows there will be no resolution this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Duquette regime has displayed a consistent distaste for
players who can't be controlled. Even if the players aren't out of
control, they are frowned upon if they can't be controlled. Nomar
Garciaparra may slam the team occasionally, but he shows up for
work on time and frustrates pitchers, making his attack on
management's decisions (Lou Merloni, Mike Stanley, the value of Dr.
Arthur Pappas) more palatable. Everett is the anti-Duquette player:
forever opinionated and fearless of any man . . . even the man who
gave him his sizable contract.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way Duquette and Williams can discipline him this
year and they know it. If they suspend him, they will hurt
themselves. If they don't suspend him, they will take such
nonaction before a group of judging clubhouse eyes, eyes that will
see that a double standard exists.
</P>
<P>
   None of that would have mattered if Everett had simply gone to
the office, taken the field, and played his brilliant game.
Everett, justifiably, complained that he was being skewered by the
media in the aftermath of his July 15 showdown with umpire Ronald
Kulpa. He said people were trying to portray him as a monster.
Obviously he is not a monster. Saturday, he was also not very
smart.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not he began the dispute with Williams is irrelevant.
What he should be asking is why he allowed himself to be put in
this position. More than 31,000 people were at the park Saturday,
ready to file away the events of July 15. Some of those folks have
deep philosophical problems with Everett's actions that day, but
they also have a deep attachment to the Sox. They were prepared to
ignore personal philosophy and instead pursue pennant philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Everett wouldn't let them do it. Instead, he gave critics _ some
of whom surely lurk in his own clubhouse _ more ammunition to use
against him. Boston wanted to throw Everett a party Saturday.
Rather than enjoy it, he walked into the party and began cursing at
one of his biggest supporters. Williams is similar to some of those
fans in that he sees some things with which he doesn't agree, but
lets some of them slide because he wants to win.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is that Williams mentioned Everett's frequent
tardiness (that was a problem in Houston, too) and that angered the
outfielder. Even if Williams had said, ``Carl, you look like a sumo
wrestler when you wear those pants,'' Saturday was the day not to
respond publicly. Not only is it unprofessional, but this ragged
team already has enough to worry about without another Everett
incident.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that has Pedro Martinez, Tim Wakefield, and a
bunch of pitchers who are going through an I'm-a-reliever identity
crisis. When starters such as Ramon Martinez and Jeff Fassero can't
go more than six innings (combined) in the same week, it's a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that doesn't need the center fielder yelling at
the manager, even though those arguments happen often in baseball.
Everett may not need anger management classes, but he does need to
learn the arts of Timing and Knowing When To Fight With The Boss.
There are thousands of employees in North America who rip their
managers. Most often, they do it away from the office and away from
nosy media members. After reflecting on their rage, they usually
decide that it wasn't as serious as they originally thought.
</P>
<P>
   Everett should consider this.
</P>
<P>
   He talked with Tommy Harper, Wendell Kim, and Jose Offerman
after his blowup. There were whispers and closed-door meetings in
the clubhouse, up until game time. Harper, an extremely wise man,
was asked if he has become a liaison between Everett and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, and began to explain that he was talking to
Everett about hitting. After a while, he seemed to grow annoyed and
said, ``I don't want to talk about Carl anymore. If he doesn't want
to talk to (the media), then that's your problem. I'm not going to
speak for him.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the game began, Everett went 3 for 5 and smacked a
ninth-inning homer. The only redeeming element of the day was that
it reminded us of our contradictions. If the self-righteous Sox fan
finds Everett's summer behavior loathsome, will that same fan
continue to applaud his brilliant play?
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a good day,'' Williams said. ``He hit the ball good.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no Jimy. Everett didn't have a good day. He had a day of
wasted energy. He also hit the ball very well. Maybe it was a good
day for Everett because he now knows that he has the organization
by its, ahem, tail. That must trouble the souls of Duquette and
Williams because there is nothing they can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
