<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ROYALS-BOS     08-05 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ROYALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDSOX FALL IN FIELD OF SCREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Confining his anger to the clubhouse, Carl Everett Saturday
thundered back to Fenway Park and proved how much the Red Sox
missed his bat, if not his temper.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who began the day with a high-decibel shouting match
behind closed doors with manager Jimy Williams, capped his return
from a 10-game suspension with a ninth-inning home run that nearly
propelled the Sox to their second straight come-from-behind victory
against the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   But the rally died with the potential winning run at the plate,
as the Royals spoiled Everett's release from baseball's penalty
box, 7-5, before 31,441 in the Fens. He was suspended July 20 for a
July 15 tirade at Fenway involving plate umpire Ron Kulpa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big boost to the offense to have him back,'' said Rico
Brogna, the team's new first baseman. ``He can strike at any
time.''
</P>
<P>
   As Everett showed with his double off the Green Monster that
fell 2 feet short of the screen in the seventh inning, his 409-foot
homer in the ninth, and his verbal scrimmage with his boss. He made
his return in a nationally televised game three weeks after he
erupted on national TV in Kulpa's face.
</P>
<P>
   Everett refused to speak with reporters Saturday about his
doings on or off the field. And Williams would not discuss details
of their disagreement, which he described as ``a family feud.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a family that ran smoothly every day,''
Williams said. ``Sometimes you have a little argument. Voices get
raised. You move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox tried to move on Saturday. But no one needed the
National Security Agency to crack the secret of their defeat.
Mediocre pitching, errant fielding, and missed scoring
opportunities can flummox even the happiest baseball family.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: Rolando Arrojo, making his Fenway debut for the Sox,
provided a textbook lesson in pitching's pitfalls. In remaining
winless in his last seven starts for the Sox and the Colorado
Rockies, Arrojo allowed the leadoff batter to reach base in four of
the five innings he started, and all four scored.
</P>
<P>
   He threw more balls (44) than strikes (39), and before Bryce
Florie took over with two out and two on in the fifth, Arrojo
yielded four runs (one unearned) on seven hits, two walks, and a
wild pitch. The unearned run was the product of an uncharacteristic
fielding error by Brogna.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched bad,'' Arrojo said through a translator, reliever
Rich Garces. ``I didn't have any command of my pitches. I just
pitched bad today.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the Sox bullpen, which has excelled most of the season,
muster a masterful outing.
</P>
<P>
   Florie was on the mound when the Sox, trailing, 4-3, snuffed
Kansas City's fifth-inning rally. But the credit went to left
fielder Troy O'Leary, who gunned out Jermaine Dye as he tried to
score from second on a single by Mark Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   And with the score tied, 4-4, in the eighth, the game was in
Rheal Cormier's left hand when he allowed back-to-back singles that
set up Kansas City's game-winning rally.
</P>
<P>
   Cormier knew the fans had better expectations of the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're not going to do it every day,'' he said. ``There
are times when you're going to have a bump in the road. You just
try to limit the damage as much as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Rod Beck couldn't, though. Summoned to rescue Cormier, Beck
yielded a double to Quinn that scored one run, a single to Gregg
Zaun that scored a second run, and a groundout to Dave McCarty that
scored a third, making it 7-4, more than Everett &AMP; Co. could
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your job is to come into the ballgame and make something
happen, good or bad,'' Beck said. ``Unfortunately, it wasn't too
good today.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Red Sox took only what was handed to
them. And Royals starter Chad Durbin was their biggest benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   Before he departed for a late brunch with one out in the second,
the rookie allowed three runs on three walks and single by Mike
Lansing. He only made it once through the order and averaged four
pitches to every batter.
</P>
<P>
   Everett did almost all the rest for the Sox. After he doubled in
the seventh, he scored on Nomar Garciaparra's two-out single on a
1-2 count to tie the score at 4. It was a huge hit in the clutch
for Garciaparra, who is batting a remarkable .350 with two strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra went hitless in his first three at-bats and finished
the game at .392.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's 27th home run, off Royals closer Ricky Bottalico,
accounted for Boston's only other run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have a guy like that in the middle of your lineup
who can add some offensive punch,'' Lansing said. ``It's a nice
bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicer if the others chip in, too. But the Sox stranded 10
runners, including four in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   The last opportunity dissolved in the bottom of the ninth, when
Garciaparra and O'Leary each drew walks after Everett's homer. But
Jason Varitek, who had been left stranded after reaching on doubles
in the sixth and eighth, struck out to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bottalico survived the ninth for his 10th save, the
Royals owed their victory in large measure to Brian Meadows, a new
arrival from the San Diego Padres who pitched 6 2/3 innings of
one-run relief after Durbin's debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a super job of holding us down,'' said Brogna, who was
0 for 2 with two walks. ``We weren't able to get anyting going
against him.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Everett.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
