<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3898 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-05 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME HAS COME TO THINK MODERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only Mr. Mayor himself knows why he didn't make nice a long time
ago with Jimmy Kelly and the Debating Society, known as the Boston
City Council, on the subject of a new ballpark, but he didn't. Now
all of us will temporarily be held hostage by a group of people
who, being unaccustomed to spotlights of any kind, will play this
thing out until every last newspaper reporter, newspaper
photographer, radio reporter, television reporter, and television
cameraperson pleads for mercy.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the deal will be struck.
</P>
<P>
   That said, we can only hope that someone in the John Harrington
entourage has brought something extremely important to his
attention _ a prescient article in the July 30 Globe by Robert
Campbell, our esteemed architecture critic, who called attention to
a sadly under-discussed aspect of this entire affair. ``I'm
wondering why everyone is talking about politics and money,'' he
wrote, ``and nobody is talking about the fact that this is a
terrible design for a ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how completely correct he is.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that Harrington and Co. do come up with the requisite
financing, what they are prepared to do is kowtow to the dewy-eyed
preservationists while attempting to address their business needs.
Operating on the apparent theory that no one really wants to leave
Fenway, and the Fenway Experience, behind, they are circulating a
ballpark design that would perpetuate the nonsense of the
left-field wall, a freak of real estate that has skewed performance
evaluation for 66 years and, whether the Sentimental Set wishes to
admit it, has had as much to do with the team's inability to
construct a championship team as any other single factor.
</P>
<P>
   No, no, a trillion times, no!
</P>
<P>
   The new ballpark, (and, by the way, let's agree that we shall
never, ever refer to it as the ``New Fenway,'' because that's not
gonna happen), has simply got to be a truly new ballpark, not a
mindless derivative of the old. Warns Campbell, ``Once you
replicate the Monster on a different site, you've transformed it
from reality to stage set. Instead of being a real place with a
real game, the park will feel like a planned amusement park ride.''
</P>
<P>
   It's very possible you can do something about it. I know for a
fact that the design we have seen is a first draft. Harrington and
friends authorized it on the assumption that to submit a design
that failed to look like Son of Fenway would be politically
disastrous. But I am counting on the good sense of intelligent
baseball fans to let him know that they most definitely do not want
to make any attempt to transport the history and memories they
cherish to a phony-baloney, Las Vegas-style Fenway re-creation,
that to do so would not merely be flat-out stupid, but borderline
sacrilegious.
</P>
<P>
   I say this because people are already weighing in, and here are
a few e-mail samples I have received:
</P>
<P>
   ``Why anyone in their right mind would want to build a ballpark
that retains the stupid left-field wall, the ladder, the
center-field triangle, etc. is beyond understanding.'' _ Bob Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd only ditch the idea of re-creating the wall in the
new park! _ Charles G. Ruberto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preserving the current Fenway is akin to the Amish not wanting
to progress with the rest of society.'' _ Jim O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   So I know you're out there, and I suspect you're out there in
far greater numbers than the Harringtonians realize.
</P>
<P>
   It is imperative to do the right thing with this new ballpark.
Lord knows there are enough models out there. Camden Yards in
Baltimore basically works, although the left-field fence should
definitely be higher. Cleveland's Jacobs Field comes very close to
being the answer, except for the hideous sight of three-tiered
luxury boxes that extend the length of the left-field line and
which, when lit, look like the Titanic an hour or so prior to its
encounter with the iceberg. Comiskey Park (Chicago) is an outdoor
FleetCenter. The Ballpark (Arlington, Texas) is contrived. Coors
Field (Denver) and Enron Field (Houston) are too skewed toward
offense. I have not been to either Comerica Park (Detroit) or
Safeco Field (Seattle), but the word is that the former has
regrettable sight lines, while the latter isn't bad at all. Nor
have I been to Pacific Bell Park (San Francisco), but it has
received staggeringly positive reviews on every level. Of course,
we've already blown our chance for a waterfront setting, but that's
the price we pay for allowing demagogues like Kelly to have too
much say in civic affairs. The other park worth studying is Turner
Field (Atlanta), which, while lacking landmarks, is very
comfortable and brings everyone reasonably close to the action.
</P>
<P>
   Many people here are skeptical that a new ballpark will turn out
all right because of the aforementioned disaster known as the
FleetCenter, otherwise known as the Wal-Mart of indoor arenas. But
the FleetCenter's sterility and lack of imagination at least serves
as a definitive ``How Not To.'' And an arena is not a ballpark. In
all the world, there is only one truly breathtaking, goose-bumpy
and charming, large-sized venue for professional basketball, and
that is Conseco Fieldhouse in downtown Indianapolis. That is a
unique situation. But there are many examples of new baseball parks
that enhance the experience.
</P>
<P>
   With a price tag approaching $700 million, there is going to be
only one chance in our lifetime for the Red Sox to construct a 21st
century ballpark with heart. Fenway Park remains a joy. I look
forward to each game there. But it is, as Campbell points out, a
joy because it is real. It was not designed to be a baseball
heirloom; it just turned out that way. And let me remind you that
as recently as 1966, when the Red Sox drew 811,172, no one was
rhapsodizing about Fenway, least of all Thomas A. Yawkey (trust me;
I've looked it up).
</P>
<P>
   Here's how silly this can get: The Red Sox have seriously
discussed painting one of the bleacher seats in the new park red,
to commemorate the 1946 Ted Williams home run that hit a man on the
head and broke his new straw hat. How sick is that? What's next?
Will they paint a big white X on the spot that approximates where
Rico Petrocelli caught Rich Rollins's pop fly that ended the 1967
season? It's all so absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Fenway is Fenway, and when it goes we won't forget about it. The
Red Sox are moving out for many reasons. They should be interested
in creating new experiences, new memories, new history. So write,
phone, e-mail, and otherwise contact John Harrington to let him
know you want an all-new ballpark, with good sight lines for all.
Tell him to let Fenway rest in appropriate peace. Remind him that
one Williamsburg is enough.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
