u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-TRADES-B     08-05 2226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-TRADES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOT OF TALK, LITTLE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've been through a month of rumors and romancing. Free agents
were wined and dined in Orlando, Chicago, and, yes, even in Boston.
(Ever try to get on Charles River Country Club?)
</P>
<P>
   Almost every day, sports Web sites breathlessly tracked the
comings and goings of free agents. NBA executives called the
process way too protracted and far too exhausting. They also could
have added futile.
</P>
<P>
   After all the offers, counteroffers, proposals, threats,
promises, and winks, one may wonder if there has been any notable
change in the NBA balance of power. True, there's still time left,
but most of the major free agents have committed and all we really
have is a reconfigured and possibly better team in Orlando and
something in Detroit that looks a lot like Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest winner in free agency, by far, is San Antonio
because it kept Tim Duncan. Anything else is gravy. The second
biggest winner, Indiana, also managed to keep its key people.
(We're assuming Reggie Miller stays.) The Magic made some big
changes; the Bulls tried to make some big changes; Miami and
Charlotte made a big trade. Everyone else talked, talked, talked,
and did nothing, unless you count Randy Brown, Tony Delk, and John
Starks as major additions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remember the phrase `short-sheet' from your camp days?
That's what the NBA has done to its teams,'' says player agent
Keith Glass. ``You kicked and you kicked and you couldn't break
through that sheet. That's what is happening now to teams. They
can't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is the way the NBA wants it. (One rumor was
that the league denied the Nets both injury exceptions for that
very reason.) The less movement for players, the better. But the
less movement for players means the less movement for teams. It's
positively Newtonian.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA encourages and invites teams to re-sign their players,
which takes them over the salary cap. Thus, the teams are unable to
compete for somebody else's players. The players, therefore, have
few options, even though the money is slightly above the league's
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the summer started, only five teams were going to be
possible players in free agency. Two, Orlando and Chicago, had
planned it that way. A third, the Clippers, were among them because
they're the Clippers. Indiana and Houston had trade exceptions in
excess of $4 million. (Detroit and Toronto subsequently got into
it, but only after losing free agents they wanted to re-sign.)
</P>
<P>
   That left 24 teams to work out sign-and-trades if they wanted a
free agent. If that could not be done, and only Miami has been able
to seriously pull it off (forget the Orlando deals, those were not
the same thing). Teams had no room and free agents were left to
hope, like Danny Fortson, that something could be done to make them
not settle for the mid-level exception.
</P>
<P>
   Executives spent all of July on the phone. Atlanta GM Pete
Babcock spent last week in Rhode Island, where it rained every day,
and said he noticed only that it was cooler than it would have been
had he stayed in hot 'Lanta. He had two phones going at his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I wouldn't have been doing the same thing in
Atlanta,'' he said. ``I'm just doing it in a different place.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can only talk so much. The marketplace is what it is,
the rules are what they are, and, well, you have a lot of square
pegs trying to fit into round holes. Everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stagnant now,'' contends Glass. ``The league is stifling
its teams. The teams just can't get any better. I'm hearing more
complaints from teams, from general managers, than I am from the
players.''
</P>
<P>
   And it could be even worse the next two summers.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with this class. What would it have been without
Duncan, Tracy McGrady, Austin Croshere, Tim Thomas, and Ron Mercer?
Can you spell Y-A-W-N? Had they fallen into the new rookie scale,
they'd all still be with their current teams. Grant Hill might well
have stayed put without the prospect of joining Duncan, and Orlando
might not have done anything without the possibility of signing
Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Houston, Dallas, Miami, and perhaps Atlanta and San
Antonio will have cap room. Who will be out there? None of the
third-year rookies who, under the last agreement, would be looking
ahead to big paydays, even if, as was the case with Croshere,
Thomas, and McGrady, they played perhaps one decent season among
them.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter, Mike Bibby, Paul Pierce, and Larry Hughes not only
won't be free next summer, they won't be free in the summer of
2002, either. All their respective teams have to do is push a
button by Halloween and those players are under lock and key for
two more years. Teams also have a right of first refusal for year
five, so, in essence, if those players seriously want to test the
market, they will have to wait until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how many guys are going to want to do that (wait
five years),'' says Celtics GM Chris Wallace. ``I just think it's
so overwhelming in favor of the home team.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber will be the Big Kahuna next summer. He will have
been in the league eight years at that point. (Geez, wasn't it just
yesterday that he and Nellie were dueling at 20 paces?) After that,
you have players such as Jamal Mashburn, Anthony Mason, Jim
Jackson, and Christian Laettner. Cedric Ceballos will be there.
Excited yet? How about the Hall of Fame center list: Patrick Ewing,
Dikembe Mutombo, Hakeem Olajuwon, David Robinson, and Arvydas
Sabonis? No? How about if we added Shawn Bradley? Still no?
</P>
<P>
   What's missing are young players about to hit their prime who
can spell H-O-P-E. Of all the players we just listed, Mashburn is
the youngest. He's 27. And this season will be his seventh. Of the
early list of next summer's free agents, around 80 or so including
Adrian Griffin, almost half of them will have had at least eight
years in the league. By then, most players are already established.
You won't hear the words ``upside'' or ``potential'' or ``growth''
mentioned with any of them in the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   So prepare yourself. You're going to have to wait until 2003 at
the earliest for the next possible Free Agent Frenzy, and that's
only if Carter et al don't re-sign before then.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, enjoy it while it lasts.
</P>
<P>
   In the free agency update, the undisputed winner is San Antonio.
As noted, Spurs kept Duncan. End of story. Derek Anderson, if he
comes, will help. As of now, the Spurs and Trail Blazers remain the
most viable alternative in the West to the Lakers, with Phoenix
closing in on the rail. Portland's pursuit of Shawn Kemp has to be
part of its ``closing window'' mentality, as in, ``We've got two
more years left before we have to blow it all up.'' The Kemp
situation is interesting. Only two weeks ago, a Western Conference
coach said this about Kemp: ``Untradeable. He's a walking luxury
tax.'' But Paul Allen doesn't care about such trivial things and
Portland must feel it somehow can work both Kemp and Rasheed
Wallace together, even though they play the same position. Kemp
also hates playing center and he'd have to play against real
centers in the West. But he'd also be doing it for a title
contender, not for Cleveland. If you look back at Portland's Game 7
collapse against the Lakers, it would have been nice to have Kemp
around when Sabonis picked up his fifth foul (and the game turned).
But isn't that when guys like Steve Smith and Scottie Pippen also
are supposed to step up? Orlando failed to land Duncan, who would
have altered the landscape in the East. The Magic added Hill and
McGrady (and, don't forget, rookie Mike Miller) both of whom, you
would think, would want the ball. Darrell Armstrong needs the ball.
Hmmm. Meanwhile, you have John Amaechi at center and a power
forward-in-waiting (Fortson would fit here). They also lost some of
their valuable ``dirty-work'' guys in Ben Wallace and Chucky Atkins
(who signed for $24 million over six years with Detroit).
</P>
<P>
   Does that make you wonder if Hill and McGrady might have taken a
starting salary of, oh, a paltry $7 million so Orlando could have
kept its team intact? It continues to amaze me why teams feel they
have to ``max out'' players when the money is so staggering anyway
and when there might actually be a benefit in taking slightly less
for the overall betterment of the team. Isn't that why they went
where they did? To win? The Lakers needed four years and Phil
Jackson to recover from Shaq's signing in 1996. He later said he
would have taken less had he known it would have meant that the
Lakers could have retained some of their players. Then again, the
next player who does that will be the first. Still, you'd like
Orlando's chances a lot better if at least Wallace stuck around.
He's tough and he rebounds and blocks shots. The Magic right now
look like about a 45-50 win team, but we were all wrong about them
last year. Doc Rivers is now officially on notice.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the NBA sent out a directive last week, informing
teams of several figures, the most prominent of which is the early
estimate for next year's salary cap. As of now, it is projected to
rise to $42.7 million next season, an increase of almost 20
percent. (The Celtics will still be over.) The maximum starting
salary for players in years 1-6 rose from $9 million to $9.658
million and for players at the second level from $11 million to
$11.589 million. The maximum starting salary for players with 10 or
more years remains at $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bulls get the horns
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls and GM Jerry Krause, meanwhile, are taking a serious
beating in the press for their inability to land a big-name free
agent. One reason being offered: players don't want to go to
Chicago because of Michael Jordan's legacy. That seems to be a
reach. A more plausible explanation is that the Bulls are a
horrible team, will continue to be a horrible team, and that the
only player who might have made a difference _ Duncan _ did not
want to go there.
</P>
<P>
   We've heard that players are upset over the way Chicago forced
out Jordan and Pippen. The last time I looked, Jordan chose to
retire because the only coach he'd play for decided not to return.
He also pocketed $60 million-plus in salary over his last two
seasons. We'd all like to be forced out like that. The Bulls could
have stood up to Pippen. Instead, they re-signed him to a maximum
deal and traded him to Houston for Roy Rogers and a draft pick.
They kept Rogers for nine days and the pick was a second-rounder.
Never mind that most of this ``mistreatment'' was in the minds of
MJ and Pippen, who simply don't like Krause. It stuck. Sure, Krause
could work on his people skills. Sure, he made some ridiculous
statements. Sure, he hired Tim Floyd, who is a good guy and
probably a good coach, but who knows after what he's been through?
But why would a free agent coming out of a bad or mediocre
situation, as was the case with Hill and McGrady, not try to go to
a better one? Why go through the same thing, or something even
worse, in a different city for the same money?
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls have been 30-102 over the last two seasons and may be
lucky to win 30 games this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe some free agents look at the way Michael left, and the
way Scottie left, but I think most of them are looking at the
talent that's there,'' said Brown, an ex-Bull. ``These guys want to
win and they want to win now. The Bulls are just not a very good
situation right now.'' Don't rule out the Bulls from still being a
player, provided they keep some cap space. Come this fall, when
rosters start getting squeezed, and again at the trading deadline,
they may be in position to take on someone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rocket launcher
</P>
<P>
   Another team that could be in an interesting position is
Houston, which has a trade exception that expires in early October,
courtesy of the Pippen deal. The Rockets could get $8 million to
$12 million under the cap next summer depending on what they do
with Olajuwon. Their thinking is that they will use the exception
only if they can acquire a legit keeper. Otherwise, they'll do what
Indiana did, which is let the exception expire. The Pacers had to
use theirs by midnight Tuesday, but after shelling out all the
money to Jalen Rose and Croshere, and with Miller still out there,
they probably figured they'd spent enough. Or, as we noted above,
they might have looked around and simply decided there was no point
spending any more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The good news
</P>
<P>
   While it's still way too early to project anything for the
upcoming season, a quick glance at the Celtics schedule is
revealing. Seventeen of their first 25 games are at the FleetCenter
and here are some of the opponents: Detroit, Toronto, Washington,
Atlanta, Houston, Vancouver, LA Clippers, Denver, and Chicago. They
have a decent shot to go no worse than 10-5 in November, and one
might suggest they have to go no worse than 10-5 given what lies
ahead. In other words, we might know by mid-December what sort of
season they are going to have.
</P>
<P>
   Material from wire services, personal interviews, other beat
writers and team and league sources was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
