</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-ALLNFLTEAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALL WAS DROPPED ON SOME PICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 36 Hall of Fame voters did a dangerous thing last week. They
selected an all-time NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they made mistakes, but that is a given when anyone
tries to do such a thing because it is impossible to take the
thousands of men who have played in the National Football League
and select the best 27 and think you can get away without an
argument.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, fueling arguments is probably the idea.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the selectors did an admirable job with the
exception of picking the wrong quarterback, wrong tackle (in one
case), wrong center (twice over), wrong outside linebacker, wrong
cornerback, and wrong safety.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start at quarterback, where Johnny Unitas was chosen over
Joe Montana. One could argue that Unitas helped create the modern
frenzy that is pro football by his play in the historic 1958 NFL
championship game. And there is no arguing his greatness. It is
just that Montana was greater.
</P>
<P>
   He won more frequently, which is the measuring stick of a
quarterback. He also made more plays in the final moments. In fact,
Unitas was not as great a thrower as Dan Marino (neither was
Montana) nor as great an athlete as John Elway, who may really have
been the greatest quarterback of all time.
</P>
<P>
   But for me, it is Montana because every time he got his team to
the biggest game _ the Super Bowl _ he won. Unitas cannot make such
a claim.
</P>
<P>
   The tackles selected were Anthony Munoz of the Bengals and
Roosevelt Brown of the New York Giants. I am old enough to remember
Brown, faintly. I remember he was big, fast, athletic and got out
in front of Frank Gifford and Alex Webster to name two.
</P>
<P>
   But has everyone forgotten how dominant a tackle Art Shell was
for nearly his entire career with the Raiders and how overpowering
Forrest Gregg was when he anchored the Packers offense of the
1960s?
</P>
<P>
   I watched Shell play throughout his career, so I can assure you
this: He may not be better than Brown, but he wasn't any worse. And
neither was Gregg.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that the selectors opted for Mike Webster
at center. He was a force for those great Steelers teams of the
1970s, but I would argue Miami's Dwight Stephenson was more than
his athletic equal and the Raiders' Jim Otto was as good as anyone
who ever played the position. Given those three, I would select
Stephenson, even though his career was cut short by knee injuries.
He was the best athlete and tough as nails.
</P>
<P>
   Let's move to defense. It is impossible to quarrel with the
selections of ends Deacon Jones and Reggie White, but I will
anyway. How do you keep Willie Davis of the Packers off any
all-time team? That is especially true when you consider not a
single player from those superb Green Bay squads made the list
despite the fact the Packers won five NFL titles under Vince
Lombardi.
</P>
<P>
   At outside linebacker, Jack Ham and Lawrence Taylor were the
selections. No one can quarrel with Taylor, but I'd take Dave
Robinson over Ham and I'd take Jack Lambert over both, even though
he was a career middle linebacker. For my money, a linebacking
corps of Dick Butkus, Taylor, and Lambert playing out of position
would be as good as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   In the secondary, I would replace Mel Blount with Mike Haynes or
Jimmy Johnson, the old 49er cornerback of the 1950s and '60s.
Blount was a great player and an intimidating force, but Haynes
covered people to death and also was a great return man.
</P>
<P>
   If you talk to old-timers, they'll tell you Dick ``Night Train''
Lane (the other selection) and Johnson were the best. So, forced to
choose, I'd go with Lane and Haynes on the corners.
</P>
<P>
   As for the safeties, the selectors went with Ronnie Lott and
Larry Wilson. I'm OK with Lott, but although Wilson revolutionized
the position (and hence may deserve the selection), I think
Minnesota's Paul Krause and Houston's Ken Houston were better.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at the Hall of Fame last week Krause and Houston said
Wilson was their idol but Krause conceded Houston was the best
safety ever. Nothing against Wilson, but I'll go with Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, the selections of Jim Brown, Walter Payton, Don
Hutson, Jerry Rice, John Mackey, Munoz, John Hannah, and Jim Parker
on offense, and Joe Greene, Bob Lilly, Butkus, Taylor, Lane, and
Lott seem right. Same is true of specialists Jan Stenerud, Ray Guy,
Gale Sayers, and Deion Sanders, and Steve Tasker on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the selectors did a good job, but my computer tells me
my team wins, 28-24, with Montana making a spectacular throw for
the winning score.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over before it started
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback competition ended early in Miami after
Dartmouth's Jay Fiedler injured his hip last week and will miss
most, if not all, of camp. That leaves the job of replacing Marino
to Damon Huard, although Fiedler is still hoping to get back in
time for the final week of camp. However, what difference does it
make? . . . Old friend Al Groh showed how relaxed a guy can be
replacing a legend last week when he spent part of one of his press
conferences suggesting the top seven storylines for writers
covering the team. To his credit, Groh put the return of
quarterback Vinny Testeverde from his Achilles' injury ahead of his
own first appearance Sept. 3 as Bill Parcells's replacement . . .
Life would appear tough on the surface for the Buffalo Bills after
losing Doug Flutie until next month and nine defensive players to
free agency or salary cap complications, including four starters.
They lost their best cornerback (Thomas Smith), best safety (Kurt
Schulz) and all-time greatest pass rusher (Bruce Smith) before
Smith's replacement, Marcellus Wiley, went down with a back injury.
But general manager John Butler has done a superlative job drafting
over the years and so the Bills' brass believes it can reload while
remaining competitive in the AFC East with people like Wiley, Sam
Cowart, Pat Williams, and Shawn Price. Price, in particular, is on
the hot seat because his playing time is expected to increase after
four years as a backup. Top draft pick Erik Flowers was considered
for Smith's right defensive end job after Wiley's injury but coach
Wade Phillips has decided to allow the rookie to focus on rushing
the passer from the left side. This leaves Price, a career backup,
to start in Smith's old spot. The only problem with that scenario
is Price lacks the speed to be a consistently effective outside
rusher, and the Bills know it. But until Wiley is healthy, Price
will have to hold the fort. ``A lot of people are saying we're a
second-rate defense now because of the players we lost, but we
believe we can be just as good as last year,'' Cowart said. ``We'll
be a little younger, but with youth I think we're faster than last
year.'' The Bills allowed the fewest total yards per game last year
and have been in the top 10 in fewest yards allowed for four
straight years . . . The injury to Flutie all but assures part of
the Bills' salary cap plans are out the window. With two
high-priced quarterbacks in Flutie and Rob Johnson, Buffalo planned
to have a third quarterback signed for the rookie minimum of
$193,000. The best they can hope for now is paying a veteran backup
the league minimum of $440,000, a difference of $247,000 in cap
money . . . What does the schedule maker have against the AFC East?
Five of the six teams facing the toughest schedules are in the AFC
East with the Bills' opponents having a .586 winning percentage a
year ago. Next is Miami, whose opponents have a .570 winning
percentage, Indianapolis at .563, the Jets at .559, and the Vikings
at .555. Right behind them comes the Patriots, whose opponents'
winning percentage was .539 last season. But the Patriots play the
most 1999 playoff teams, nine. The defending Super Bowl champion
St. Louis Rams have the second-easiest schedule with their
opponents having a 1999 winning percentage of .430. They face only
four 1999 playoff teams. Part of the reason is because their
division, the NFC West, is weak with San Francisco, New Orleans,
and Atlanta among the league's worst teams. AFC Super Bowl
representative Tennessee also caught a break. Its strength of
schedule is 24th . . . Rookies need to learn their place and
Dolphins offensive tackle Todd Wade was informed of his last week
after he criticized the antics of Tampa Bay's Warren Sapp for
taunting Dolphins players and a ball boy during joint practices.
``That would be like me talking about Reggie White the week before
Wade had to face Reggie,'' said left guard Mark Dixon, who faces
Sapp when the teams meet. When Sapp heard of Wade's criticisms, he
snapped, ``That kid has no idea who I am and what I'm all about.''
Chances are Sapp will find a way to let him know this season . . .
Indianapolis Colts running back Edgerrin James has lost none of his
edge. After a remarkable rookie season that earned him nearly $15
million in salary and bonuses, James had Reebok print him up
T-shirts that read ``Back to the Grind.'' Unfortunately, it's a
term James says one of his uncles used to use when referring to
returning to the streets to sell drugs. ``He was always saying,
`You've got to get back out there grindin' and hustlin' to make
your money,' '' James said. ``Now you know I'm not saying anything
about drugs, but you've got to have that mentality. Every year
you've got to be hungry.'' After rushing for 1,533 yards as a
rookie and earning $9.85 million in incentives and other bonuses,
James may still be hungry but he won't be missing any meals . . .
You can't blame Clay Matthews if he hopes brother Bruce sprains an
ankle this season. The retired Cleveland Browns linebacker played
in 278 NFL games over 19 years, the third-highest total in league
history. Bruce, the perennial All-Pro offensive lineman with the
Titans, can pass him if he starts 15 games this season. The younger
Matthews has played in 264 NFL games. The league record is held by
former quarterback/kicker George Blanda, who played 340 games . . .
Guard Will Shields got a break and a big raise when he signed a
one-year tender offer from the Chiefs last week worth more than $4
million. The five-time Pro Bowl performer carried the team's
franchise designation, which meant he had to be paid the average of
the top five salaries at his position. But fortunately for Shields,
offensive linemen are put in one pot, so the fact that the top five
salaries all belong to left tackles didn't affect him. In fact,
that quirk meant about a 20 percent raise over what Shields would
have made if paid the average of the top five guards . . . Of the
nine franchise players designated in February, five have signed
one-year tender offers, one (Joey Galloway) was traded, one (San
Diego defensive tackle Norman Hand) had the designation rescinded
and moved on to New Orleans, and two (Jacksonville's Tony Brackens
and Arizona's Simeon Rice) are holding out . . . Colts linebacker
Cornelius Bennett faces a big test Monday when his surgically
repaired knee will again be evaluated. Bennett failed to pass his
training camp physical and has been on the physically unable to
perform list since. The Colts hope he can begin limited work this
week . . . Some guys will do anything for a chance to play in the
NFL, including pass up a $7,000 work week. Wide receiver Ben
Clampitt already has been cut this year by the B.C. Lions of the
Canadian League and the Cincinnati Bengals, but he signed a
contract with the Seattle Seahawks last week rather than accept a
position on his father's fishing boat out of Edmonds, Wash., that
would have earned him $7,000 for a week's work . . . Rookie wide
receiver JaJuan Dawson continued to impress the Browns so much last
week that he was named a starter ahead of veteran Darrin
Chiaverini. Dawson was a third-round pick but he has sprinted ahead
of holdout second-round choice Dennis Northcutt and made life
miserable for Chiaverini, who caught 44 passes, including four for
touchdowns, last year. Coach Chris Palmer apparently is not
sympathetic to Chiaverini's claim that he hasn't had enough passes
thrown in his direction. ``Some receivers say, `I'm not getting the
ball enough,' '' Palmer said. ``Hey, I don't care if you get the
ball or not. All I have to do is turn on the film. Are you open?
The coach knows if you're open or not.'' . . . Veteran Browns
running back Terry Kirby was informed last week he would play some
backup fullback. That was after he came to camp 11 pounds lighter
because he was told they wanted him to be quicker. ``We're not
going to ask Kirby to isolate on (Steelers linebacker Levon)
Kirkland or one of those guys,'' Palmer said. ``That doesn't make
much sense. He'd come out faster than when he came in. What I'm
looking for is as many options as we can have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bargaining chip
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of Darnay Scott (broken leg) for the season, the
Bengals' hard line on holdout running back Corey Dillon has to
change. For now, the Bengals are without their three leading
rushers of a year ago, their four most productive receivers, and 75
percent of their total offense. If that isn't negotiating leverage
for Dillon, then Bengals owner Mike Brown doesn't know the meaning
of the term. If Dillon isn't given an extension, the Bengals will
have a roster that does not have a single back or receiver who
amassed as many as 350 yards last year. And that's of total offense
. . . Scott was not only a deep threat but also a big target for
young quarterback Akili Smith, who will have to look hard for
Scott's replacement. Scott's spot will be taken by Craig Yeast, who
stands 5 feet 7 inches and weighs 165 pounds. Scott is 6-1 and
weighs 204, which is becoming the prototype for an NFL receiver . .
. Bengals running back Michael Basnight can do more than move with
the football. His first volume of poetry, entitled ``Deeper Than
The Game,'' will be published Sept. 9 . . . Some holdouts know how
to make friends in a hurry. Nine days and 15 practices after his
new teammates in Baltimore had gone to work, Ravens No. 1 pick
Travis Taylor agreed to a five-year, $7.67 million contract. After
scoring a touchdown on his first practice reception, Taylor then
improved his status by announcing he would take all 84 players out
to dinner. The only caveat was that they be restricted to $100 per
man. With a new $5 million signing bonus, Taylor's bank account can
handle the $8,400 charge . . . Here's how set the $100 million
Washington Redskins lineup is: The only real competition for a
position is between Adrian Murrell and Skip Hicks to back up
Stephen Davis at running back. That's unless anyone really believes
No. 1 pick LaVar Arrington is going to be beaten out by Greg Jones
. . . Minnesota Vikings linebacker Bryce Paup took some shots at
his old coach, blaming Jacksonville's Tom Coughlin for his lack of
production as a pass rusher while with the Jaguars. Paup said he
``hated'' playing in Jacksonville, where he went from being the
NFL's defensive MVP in 1995 to a guy who had 7 1/2 sacks in two
seasons with the Jaguars. Why the drop off? According to Paup, he
was misued by Coughlin and grew so bitter he nearly retired this
past offseason after becoming a free agent . . . Carolina Panthers
linebacker Lee Woodall was eating dinner recently in Las Vegas with
his wife and father-in-law when a woman approached and asked if he
was Evander Holyfield. Woodall, who is frequently mistaken for
Holyfield, insisted he was not but the woman persisted in her
search for an autograph so Woodall turned to his father-in-law for
support. He responded, ``Come on Evander, just give her your
autography, will you?'' It was not until Woodall produced his NFLPA
union card that she believed him. But now she wanted the two-time
Pro Bowler's autograph instead. He complied . . . The Vikings are
sticking with the move of former tight end Jim Kleinsasser to
fullback. He gives them a 278-pound blocking back in front of
Robert Smith. But word is Dennis Green also plans to give
Kleinsasser some carries and use him in the short-passing game even
though the shift was originally made after Kleinsasser fumbled
twice last year in a 2-point loss to the Bears . . . Robert McNair,
owner of the new Houston franchise, said last week he hopes to see
his team included in the AFC Central to rekindle some of the old
rivalries the Oilers had with the Steelers and Browns. Talk is the
Tennessee Titans will move to a new Southern Division, which could
open a spot for Houston, although Houston is also a good bet for
the Southern Division . . . After last week's loss to the Patriots,
San Francisco 49ers quarterback Jeff Garcia bemoaned the lack of
help he received last year from Steve Young, the man he replaced.
Although Garcia claimed to understand that Young ``was dealing with
a very difficult decision (to retire),'' he felt he should have
been given more support. ``I would have liked to have seen more of
the coach come out in him,'' Garcia said. ``If I was in his shoes,
I would have approached it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from wire services, personal interviews, other beat
writers and team and league sources was used in this report.
</P>
