<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3901 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-ONFOOTBALL-WEIS-B     08-05 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ONFOOTBALL-WEIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIS DECIDES NOT TO SHOW HIS HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the intention of Patriots offensive coordinator Charlie Weis
has been not to reveal any of his secrets, he's in the wrong
business. He should be the head of the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   After two exhibition games, the Patriots have shown nothing.
They have revealed no secrets except that they are willing to run
the option with backup quarterback Michael Bishop. Other than that,
Weis's answer to the questions defenses have asked has been simply,
``I know nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   If Weis were a prisoner of war, all the enemy would have gotten
out of him would have been name, rank, and serial number.
</P>
<P>
   Troop movement plans? I have no idea.
</P>
<P>
   Secrets of the Patriots' attack? Beats me.
</P>
<P>
   Design of their offense? Wouldn't know a thing about that, sir.
</P>
<P>
   After two games, the Patriots have shown few signs of even
possessing an offense, although obviously they must because every
time someone gives them the football 11 men keep running onto the
field to play with it for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, against a fair and physical Detroit defense, they
didn't stay out there very long, very often. That was especially
(and alarmingly) true when the first offense was in place in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They did make cameo appearances a couple of minutes at a time,
though, so one has to assume the Patriots will have an offense to
go with their players before much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Or will they?
</P>
<P>
   Considering how poorly that offense produced in the dismal
second half of last season, one has to wonder. Certainly Weis must
be, although quiet counsel is his approach to these matters.
</P>
<P>
   One always needs to remember, of course, that this time of year
nothing you see really means anything when the ``games'' are being
played. That's why they're called exhibitions, although it is fair
to think a team would exhibit some offense eventually, just by
accident. That time may come Friday against the Washington Redskins
if it's going to come at all because one would have to assume the
Patriots are not going to show much in the fourth exhibition game
against Tampa Bay since they open the season against the Buccaneers
two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, it is the next-to-last exhibition game where
teams really try to play the way they will during the regular
season because by the final game they just want to keep their
players in one piece. But with the odd placement of the Tampa Bay
exhibition on the schedule, those plans may well be altered,
meaning if the Patriots have an offense you'd better hope to see it
against the Redskins. If you do, it will be saying something
because Washington has a highly paid and vastly improved defense
that includes Bruce Smith, Deion Sanders, and No. 1 draft choice
LaVar Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Patriots have the firepower to match up with the
Redskins is still difficult to tell, but each time the first
offense goes on the field and produces 9 yards in the first
quarter, as it did against the Lions, it is cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   Not panic, mind you, but concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be hard to make judgments until we have all our guys
back,'' insisted quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who calmly was alluding
to missing tackles Grant Williams and Bruce Armstrong, guard Todd
Rucci, and rookie running back J.R. Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Bledsoe has a point. Having 60 percent of your
offensive line missing in action affects what you can do, but
Friday night against the type of physical defensive front that has
bothered them in the past, the Patriots' offense wasn't merely
limited, it was nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Of New England's 261 total yards, 111 came in the two-minute
offense. The offense, if it can be called that, failed to score a
touchdown, and even worse failed to score one after the defense
gave it the ball at the Lions' 9-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds familiar it should because that's the way it's
gone all too often for Bledsoe and Co. the past two years. Given
the ball in most situations, nothing has happened, especially on
third down when forward motion is most necessary. Given the ball
with time running out, a track meet breaks out.
</P>
<P>
   Just before halftime, the Patriots' second-team offense traveled
52 yards before Adam Vinatieri hit on a 50-yard field goal for a
10-3 lead. After nearly two more quarters of stasis on offense, in
the game's final 49 seconds the third-team offense marched 59 yards
to set up Vinatieri's winning 28-yard kick with two seconds on the
clock.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, real estate in California probably moved as
much as the Patriots' offense did Friday night, which is to say a
little bit but not noticeably.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a lot of consistency with any phase of our
offense,'' coach Bill Belichick said. ``Now we have to go back and
evaluate what to do (offensively) the next couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to step back, take a deep breath, and reevaluate what
we have to do to get going. But overall there has been a lack of
consistency and third down is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   If that last point also sounds familiar it should. In the first
two games of the summer season, the Patriots' offense has converted
on 7 of 25 third-down tries, a success ratio of 28 percent. Friday
night it was 3 of 14, a pathetic 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you recall, third down killed the Patriots last season, when
drive after drive would stall because of an inability to convert in
those situations. Perhaps Weis has an improved way to handle this
and is simply keeping it to himself until Sept. 3, when the
Buccaneers' manhandling defense arrives in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Then again . . . well don't think about ``then again'' quite yet
because it's too early for negativity. Rather try this instead.
</P>
<P>
   Remain faithful to the cause for now, residents of Patriot Land.
Remain as loyal to that cause as Mel Gibson, the cinematic Patriot.
</P>
<P>
   Remain steadfast in the belief that Friday when the Patriots
have the ball they'll do something more with it than give it back
to the Redskins. If they don't, continue to believe this is just an
effort to keep all matters offensive secret until the real B Day
(Bucs Day) invasion Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Like Charlie Weis, what other choice do you have?
</P>
</TEXT>
