<HEADLINE>
STORY ON ARROYO IS LACK OF COMMAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This time it was Rich Garces instead of Pedro Martinez who got
the nod as Rolando Arrojo's interpreter after Saturday's 7-5 loss
to the Kansas City Royals at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez was late coming out of the shower, Garces, the
Venezuelan reliever, was called upon in a pinch to help translate
questions for the Cuban righthander from reporters. But given
Arrojo's lackluster performance in his Fenway debut, there wasn't
much need for Garces to translate.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish, Swahili, Greek, or German, it didn't matter. The
disappointment on Arrojo's face spoke volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``How did you think you pitched today?''
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo: ``Yo piche mal. Mi control no era como (yo) queria.''
</P>
<P>
   Garces: ``He pitched bad today. He just didn't have any command
of his pitches. He just threw bad today.''
</P>
<P>
   That was evident from the outset when Arrojo _ acquired July 27
in a trade with the Colorado Rockies along with infielder Mike
Lansing and reliever Rick Croushore in exhange for Jeff Frye, John
Wasdin, and Brian Rose _ struggled in the first inning, spotting
the Royals a 1-0 lead on three hits.
</P>
<P>
   He wound up leaving after 4 2/3 innings in which he gave up four
runs on seven hits and had two walks, one strikeout, and a wild
pitch in the third that allowed Johnny Damon to score from third,
making it 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuff-wise, he was good,'' said manager Jimy Williams.
``Control-wise, he was a little erratic. But stuff-wise, he's good.
We just need him to harness it a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Was it a matter of mechanics?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being honest with you, yeah,'' Williams said. ``Maybe he
needs a consistent release slot. He throws from different angles,
but he's trying hard. He's a great kid, he works hard, and he wants
to be successful. He's trying really hard out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stuff is good. Dang, his stuff is good and it's movin'.
But maybe too much, or out of the strike zone instead of into the
strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo faced similar problems in his Red Sox debut July 30 at
Oakland, Calif., where he walked the bases full and then served up
a two-out grand slam to Sal Fasano in the second inning that lifted
the A's to a 5-2 victory. Arrojo lasted 6 1/3 innings in that
start, overcoming his early shakiness and retiring 13 of the next
16 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only seen him pitch twice, so I have to come in and look
at the tape tomorrow before I can try to evaluate him,'' said
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. ``I mean, I know he doesn't throw that
first-pitch strike, it's evident in the two games here, because
he's always working from behind in the count. So we've got to do
something that will promote him throwing first-pitch strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``How are your mechanics? Is it a mechanical thing
right now?''
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo: ``Es bastante bien. Mas mejor que la otra vez.''
</P>
<P>
   Garces: ``He said his mechanics were better than the first
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not quite good enough to help Arrojo win his second
start with the Sox. He recorded his sixth no-decision of the season
and matched a season low with his solitary strikeout. And so,
Arrojo's evaluation period continues as he tries to help fill a
growing void in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a new pitcher, you have to see for yourself,''
Kerrigan said. ``It takes you sometimes three, four, or five starts
before you get locked in on a guy. You have to study a lot of film
and try to find some key checkpoints in his delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Everyone will just have to be patient as Arrojo and
the Red Sox get through their adjustment period.
</P>
</TEXT>
