</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BELICHICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT DECISION ON COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What makes Bill Belichick such a good coach is the
unpredictability of his defense. And that unpredictability carries
over into other areas.
</P>
<P>
   His reactions, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   While quite concerned about his team following a 20-0 blowout of
the San Francisco 49ers Monday, Belichick seemed more understanding
in the aftermath of the Patriots' 13-10 win over the Detroit Lions
Friday, when there were big problems in the running game, passing
game, and offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   So understanding that after watching game film, Belichick
concluded it was time to give his players and coaching staff a
break Sunday. The players watched and analyzed their performances
Saturday, and will resume practice Monday with a light workout in
the morning and a tougher one in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a tough stretch,'' said Belichick during a media
teleconference. ``We've been going at it pretty hard both
physically and mentally. From a coaching standpoint we need a
chance to see what's going on in the last 10 days since some things
have been installed.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Belichick, who also acts as the defensive coordinator,
has to be pleased with his unit. He was slightly critical of his
safeties being perhaps ``overly aggressive'', probably referring to
a 61-yard pass on which safety Larry Whigham got burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think hard-hitting safeties are an important element of
defense,'' said Belichick. ``You want to control the middle of the
field. When (the receivers and backs) come in you want them
thinking about what happens after the pass and have to worry about
the bobbles and holding the ball. We have a problem with our
safeties maybe playing too aggressive. I told them if you guys want
to play linebacker, I'll switch you over, but don't expect Chad
Eaton or Bobby Hamilton to cover post-patterns; that's not their
job. There's a balance between knowing their coverages and being
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the licking Lawyer Milloy put on Lions quaterback Mike
Tomczak was the aggressive nature Belichick likes. Milloy forced a
fumble and gave the offense great field position, which it
squandered.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said he didn't blame all of the offensive lapses on
the players, though they also took their share of the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be some things . . . as we went through our
films that you see something and you say `this isn't really your
fault. We haven't covered this situation or it was different the
way we covered it.' OK. But when you have covered some things and
those mistakes occur, those are not acceptable. We had both. We had
a blitz that came a little differently than what we had prepared
for, but there are other times they brought people in and it was
our fault,'' said Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   The coach didn't seem overly concerned about quarterback Drew
Bledsoe, feeling he has three more exhibition games to get into a
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   He said of quarterback Michael Bishop's performance, ``He played
OK. He did a nice job with the 2-minute drive (at the end of the
first half) and got 3 points. He threw one pass he'd like to have
back (an interception by Corwin Brown). He did some good things but
overall offensively we didn't have a lot of consistency. He
contributed to that and so did a lot of people. The 2-minute drill
was a positive point.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach gave rookie signal-caller Tom Brady credit for his
poise, but also found room for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems in the San Francisco game is it was 20-0 and
Brady was handing the ball off when he was in there,'' said
Belichick. ``This is a much more realistic situation to evaluate.
Tom did some good things and some not so good. He handled himself
well. The more he sees the better he's going to get. He's had a lot
thrown at him. He's the type of guy that once he sees it, he either
gets it the first time or he reacts to it a lot quicker the second
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady led the Patriots to the go-ahead score late in the fourth
quarter, hitting Marshfield's Sean Morey in the middle of the field
for a 47-yard gain to set up Adam Vinatieri's 28-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick applauded Morey for his special teams play and the
long pass play, but added ``I think he needs to find a more
consistent performance. Some of it's good, but he still has a ways
to go toward being a good, consistent, polished receiver. You want
your quarterbacks to have confidence in those receiver routes.''
</P>
<P>
   What bothered Belichick most about the offense were the five
negative-yardage running plays. He said those led to the Patriots
having to rely more on the pass.
</P>
<P>
   He also thought his young coaching staff performed better than
in the last game. ``We did OK. I think there's a lot of newness and
there are some things we have to iron out. On the offensive side
there's more years of experience than the defensive side. In New
York I worked with Al (Groh) and Romeo (Crennel) and Eric (Mangini)
for years. Part of it is working our way through it for the first
time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belichick hopes to have rookie running back J.R. Redmond ready
to play Friday against Washington. Belichick said Redmond is
``close'' and thinks the first step was to have him practice Monday
. . . Belichick said there were only a few ``bumps and bruises''
from the game but nothing major. Linebacker Ted Johnson and
defensive end Brandon Mitchell should see action against
Washington. Bruce Armstrong is expected to begin practicing
sometime this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
