<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-future-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MLS to Houston no longer priority
<TEXT>
<P>
   City won't get team until at least 2004
</P>
<P>
   By BRIAN McTAGGART
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicl
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The checkered history of professional soccer in
Houston has seen teams and leagues blow through town like
tumbleweeds, leaving thousands of area soccer fans confused in the
aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   From the Houston Stars of the 1960s to the present-day Houston
Hotshots indoor team, there has usually been an outlet for soccer
fans to show their support for the game. Unfortunately, the teams
or the leagues historically haven't lasted long enough to develop a
strong following.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotshots, who play in the World Indoor Soccer League, have
fielded a team for all but one season since 1994, and the
minor-league Houston Hurricanes of the outdoor United Soccer League
have filled a niche for some.
</P>
<P>
   But for diehard fans of the outdoor game, living in Houston in
recent years hasn't provided many opportunities to see the world's
most popular sport played at the highest level, and it might be
some time before it happens again.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, once thought to be a front-runner during the next wave
of Major League Soccer expansion partly because of its large
Hispanic population, won't get a team until 2004 at the earliest,
according to recent statements by MLS commissioner Don Garber.
</P>
<P>
   In his state-of-the-league address July 28, Garber said a second
team in the New York tri-state area and a team in Philadelphia or
Atlanta likely would land the 2002 expansion franchises. Garber
said Houston, Seattle, Rochester and Sacramento are potential
expansion cities in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   MLS chief executive officer Mark Abbott didn't want to handicap
Houston's chances of eventually landing an expansion franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't rate (Houston's) chances, other than it's a market
we care a lot about and we have an interest in and would like to
find a way to get there,'' he said. ``We've had on-and-off
discussions with (investors) who would have an interest, but
there's nobody imminent. We need to find an ownership group, but a
lot of things line up well.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Houston no longer being a priority to the MLS,
declining attendance and reported annual losses of $50 million have
forced local investors to back off their efforts to bring a team to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in limbo,'' said John Cape, president of Houston Soccer
Ventures, which was organized in 1996 by a local group of investors
in an effort to bring a team to Houston. ``We're still a factor in
the market and we could ultimately do this if it makes sense, but
the real burden is on Major League Soccer. They've got to deliver
in terms of increasing attendance or television ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   When the MLS was formed after the World Cup in the United States
in 1994, Houston was bypassed by the league because it lacked a
qualified facility and had no lead investor.
</P>
<P>
   Even though MLS is trying to move away from playing in large
football stadiums like the Cotton Bowl in Dallas and Rose Bowl in
Los Angeles, Abbott said MLS is interested in becoming a tenant in
the new NFL stadium under construction adjacent to the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, any kind of new facility is an exciting thing to be
a part of, and we're very excited about the facility that's being
built down there,'' he said. ``We are still taking a look at the
stadium situation. I would certainly say the NFL stadium could work
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous talk of an MLS team coming to Houston had the team
possibly playing at the University of Houston's Robertson Stadium,
which was last year expanded to an MLS-friendly 33,000 seats.
</P>
<P>
   MLS officials visited the stadium last year and were concerned
about needed improvements to concession stands, locker rooms and
broadcast booths _ worries that have since been addressed.
</P>
<P>
   An MLS team might not be on the immediate horizon, but Houston
also is in the running for an expansion team in the Women's United
Soccer Association _ a new league that will kick off in April.
</P>
<P>
   The league, which has a cooperation agreement with the MLS, will
start with franchises in Tampa/Orlando, Fla.; New York; Boston; San
Francisco; Atlanta; San Diego; Philadelphia, and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The WUSA, would like to add two teams by 2002 and another two by
2004. Houston, along with Los Angeles, Chicago and Miami, have been
tabbed by the league's board of directors as possible expansion
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expansion will happen,'' said Lee Berke, the acting president
of the WUSA. ``We've been blessed by the fact we have even more
potential owners than we have teams right now. There's strong
interest from a number of groups in various markets around the
country to have the WUSA play there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cape said Houston Soccer Ventures also has an interest in
getting a WUSA expansion team, but Berke wouldn't identify which
local investors have shown an interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``But suffice it to say there is interest, there are
opportunities and things we'd like to pursue further,'' he said.
``From a marketing standpoint, there's interest and I know there's
potentially some facilities being developed (in Houston).
Obviously, if things progress over the next six months we'll take a
look at what's being developed.''
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary plans call for the country's top female players to
be assigned to cities in which they have a regional connection,
much like basketball's WNBA did when it began in 1997. The MLS and
WUSA will cross-market and promote each other and work to build
soccer-only stadiums in cities throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get our first eight markets going, which will take
place in April 2001, but very quickly beyond that we will
methodically begin to expand this league,'' Berke said.
</P>
<P>
   If and when Houston secures an MLS franchise, it wouldn't be the
first time the city took a shot at major pro soccer.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Stars called the Astrodome their home when they
played one season in the United Soccer Association in 1967 and one
season in the North American Soccer League in 1968. The city
returned to the NASL from 1978-80 with the Houston Hurricane, which
also played in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   After the Hurricane came the Dynamos, who from 1984-86 competed
in the United Soccer League and played most of their home matches
at Delmar and Butler stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, poor attendance and league financial trouble spelled
doom for soccer teams in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But the MLS is hoping the city can become the professional
soccer hotbed that many think it can. Recent matches at Robertson
Stadium involving teams from Mexican leagues have drawn crowds as
large as 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It obviously has a large population segment that's come from
countries where soccer is a primary sport,'' Abbott said. ``The
television ratings, even though they don't have an MLS team, they
seem to be following the MLS. There are a lot of good things about
Houston that would argue for an MLS team to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for history.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
