<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BASECOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HART MADE RIGHT MOVES FOR INDIANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Cleveland Indians have new life.
</P>
<P>
   Decimated by injuries, particularly to the pitching staff, the
Indians found themselves 10 games behind the surging White Sox in
the American League Central race before they knew what hit them.
But after a flurry of deals leading up to the trading deadline, the
Indians feel invigorated.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Charlie Manuel asked for another starting pitcher,
bullpen help and another bat. General manager John Hart filled
those needs, trading for starters Jason Bere and Steve Woodard and
closer Bob Wickman from the Brewers, outfielder Wil Cordero from
the Pirates and first baseman David Segui from the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Bere has already paid dividends. In his first two starts, he's
2-0 with a 2.40 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 10 years, I've seen him pitch about 20 times,''
Manuel said. ``The last two games are the best I have ever seen him
throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when times were tough, the Indians never fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is a very professional team,'' pitcher Chuck Finley
said. ``It's so even-keeled around here, it's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians won the AL Central five consecutive years under
manager Mike Hargrove, so Manuel could be on the hot seat if the
Indians miss the playoffs this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the focus is more on me, that's the way it's supposed to
be,'' Manuel said. ``That's how I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new faces did not come without a cost. The Indians
traded away outfielder-first baseman Richie Sexon and pitchers Paul
Rigdon and Kane Davis to Milwaukee, infielder Enrique Wilson and
outfielder Alex Ramirez to Pittsburgh, and outfielder Ricky Ledee
to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   __ Cleaning house: It stood to reason, with the Orioles out of
the race, going nowhere and having the third-largest payroll ($83.1
million) in the big leagues, that there would be some changes.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the trading deadline passed, the Orioles' roster was
without more than half the players that began the season with the
team on opening day. Gone are B.J. Surhoff, Will Clark, Mike
Bordick, Mike Timlin, Harold Baines, Rich Amaral and Charles
Johnson, all traded during a 72-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   The club will save more than $10 million in payroll because of
the trades.
</P>
<P>
   All the dealing means only five players _ Brady Anderson, Scott
Erickson, Alan Mills, Mike Mussina and Cal Ripken _ remain from the
1997 Orioles, who reached the American League Championship Series.
They haven't had a winning season since.
</P>
<P>
   __ Doesn't stink anymore: When Tim Salmon homered for the Angels
on opening night against the Yankees, it put him on a pace for 162
home runs this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous? Of course.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is a game of numbers, but we can get carried away when
it comes to figuring out what a player is ``on pace for.'' But now
here it is August, more than two-thirds of the way through the
season, the ``on pace for'' statistics carry a little more weight.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' Darin Erstad is having an incredible season and the
projected numbers reflect that.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable record Erstad is chasing is George Sisler's
mark of 257 hits set in 1920 with the St. Louis Browns. It's a
record older than many single-season marks.
</P>
<P>
   Including Saturday's game, Erstad is on pace for 255 hits. With
175 hits in 111 games, Erstad needs 82 hits in the Angels' final 51
games _ or 1.61 hits per game _ to tie the mark.
</P>
<P>
   The other records he is chasing are not as glamorous but still
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   No leadoff hitter in baseball history has driven in 100 runs in
a season. Nomar Garciaparra of the Red Sox set the record in 1997
with 98 RBI. Erstad has 79 RBI, a pace for 115.
</P>
<P>
   The home run record for a leadoff hitter is Brady Anderson's 35
for the Orioles in 1996. Erstad is short of record-pace, on track
for 27.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad is also looking to become only the third player ever to
get 700 at-bats in a season. Erstad's pace is 699. The all-time
record is 705, set by Willie Wilson of the Royals in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Erstad became the fastest player to reach
100 hits since Hall of Famer Heinie Manush did it in 1934 for the
Washington Senators. Manush got there in 60 games, Erstad in 61.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad's reaction when informed of his achievement?
</P>
<P>
   ``So? . . . People can talk all you want about what you're doing
now. But at the end of the season is when it really counts. Every
day's important, but you have to keep it in perspective. There's a
lot of baseball left.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Erstad the meaning of a particular record, and he'll look at
you like you have a third eye in the middle of your forehead.
What's the big deal? After all, he hit .253 last season and he
won't let himself forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't stink anymore,'' he explained. ``I stunk for a
year- and-a-half, it's as simple as that. I wasn't any good.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad says he isn't superstitious, but he is maniacal about
maintaining his daily routine. He's at the park early every day. He
studies videotape of opposing pitchers. He plays cards with
teammates Troy Percival and Kent Merkcer. He stretches. He hits off
the tee. He hits in the cage. He's on a very tight schedule. If
anything is thrown off schedule, Erstad is not comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I battle to get myself in position to get ready to
play,'' he said. ``It's not like it's easy. You try to put a good
swing on the ball. Sometimes they fall, sometimes they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   About 37 percent of the time, they fall. He's hitting .365. To
understand how drastic Erstad's turnaround from last year to this
year is, figure this: If Erstad gets an average of four at-bats per
game the rest of the season and doesn't get another hit (0 for
204), he'll finish with an average of .256, three points higher
than his average last season.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad's reaction? Go ahead, you ask him. __ Short hops: What's
behind the A's recent surge? Starting pitching. Their starters put
together a streak of seven consecutive games in which they went at
least seven innings. It is the longest streak by an A's staff in 10
years. During the streak, the starters' ERA was 1.90 and opposing
batters hit .161 off them. . . . Outfielder Dave Martinez tied a
major-league record by playing with four teams in one season. He
began the season with the Devil Rays, then was traded, in order, to
the Cubs, Rangers and Blue Jays. . . . Blue Jays assistant GM Dave
Stewart is back on the field as the club's pitching coach. Stewart
is continuing with his front-office duties, but the club felt its
younger pitchers weren't progressing under pitching coach Rick
Langford, who was reassigned to its Triple-A club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 2306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
