<DOCNO> NYT20000805.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-POLLUTION-POLICE-2TAK     08-05 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLUTION-POLICE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUT FISHERMEN SERVE AS POLLUTION POLICE, FIGHTING TO PROTECT THE
WATERSHED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Wis.)   (For use with POLLUTION-POLICE-CREEK)  
 By ROBERT WORTH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a cloudless Saturday recently, George Nikitovich stood
shin-deep in the Cross River, surrounded by overhanging maple
branches. As he stroked his fly rod back and forth in the air with
a gentle whipping motion, his eyes were glued to the stream, where
his fly -- a size 14 Caddis made of elk hair and rooster feather --
floated gently down the gin-clear water.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know how to read the water, to find out where the
trout will naturally hide,'' Nikitovich said.
</P>
<P>
   And watching the water alerts you to anything that may be wrong
with it.
</P>
<P>
   New York state's Westchester County still has some of the best
trout fishing in the state. Wild brown and brook trout swim in the
rivers and reservoirs that supply New York City with its drinking
water, luring scores of fishermen on summer days like this one.
</P>
<P>
   But a continuing development boom has threatened the city's
watershed as never before. Since trout, more than most other fish
species, require clean water to thrive, Nikitovich and other
fishermen have become some of the region's most alert and
aggressive environmental advocates.
</P>
<P>
   These fishermen are now leading a new offensive in the struggle
to protect the watershed. Focusing on stormwater runoff, which the
federal Environmental Protection Agency has called the greatest
threat to drinking water across the country, members of the group
Trout Unlimited have documented dozens of storm drains that are
channeling polluted water into the area's reservoirs and streams.
They are also planning to sue the owners of those storm drains, in
concert with Riverkeeper, the environmental watchdog group based in
Garrison, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Nikitovich, 50, a somber-looking stock broker from Cross River,
doesn't exactly fit the profile of a tree-hugging activist. ``I
sometimes wonder -- why am I the one doing this?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, he added, is that no one else is out in the streams
all day. When there is a threat to the city's water, fishermen are
usually the first to know about it.
</P>
<P>
   Robert F. Kennedy Jr., the lead lawyer for Riverkeeper, agreed.
``You can talk to state biologists all day, but the people who
really know what's going on in the watershed are the fishermen,''
he said. ``They have always been the mainstay of our
evidence-gathering capacity and our clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen have played a role in the watershed since its
creation. When the city began building a network of reservoirs for
its water supply in the 19th century, it created the ideal
environment for trout. Trout thrive in very cold water, and the
bottom water from the reservoirs, feeding into the shallow
tailwater streams below, is so cold that on summer days mist rises
from it.
</P>
<P>
   In return, fishermen helped to police the city's waters and
limit development in the forests that surrounded them.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Gordon, William Harris, and other founders of modern
fly-fishing also helped start the conservationist movement in the
Catskills at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, Robert Boyle founded the Hudson River Fishermen's
Association, now known as Riverkeeper, one of the watershed's most
aggressive legal advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the water's purity was not in doubt. The city's
daisy chain of upstate streams and reservoirs acted as a vast
filter, cleansing the water as it flowed through forests and
tributaries into the aqueducts that supply what a succession of
mayors have called ``the champagne of city water.''
</P>
<P>
   But the city owns only 4 percent of the land that drains into
the watershed, and some of the city officials charged with
protecting the water supply had moonlighting jobs as consultants to
developers. As Westchester and Putnam Counties grew in the 1960s,
'70s, and '80s, pollution seeped into the water from septic fields,
sewage treatment plants, roads, and lawns.
</P>
<P>
   As threats to the water mounted, fishermen became some of most
active reporters of water violations, helping to fill the gaps in
the city's understaffed police unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had a real impact,'' said Tony Bonavist, an Ossining,
N.Y., native who worked for the state's Fisheries Department for 26
years until he retired in 1992. ``We didn't have people in the
field. If there was a problem in the streams, I'd get a call.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most serious concerns for trout fishermen has been
the more than 100 sewage treatment plants in the watershed. In
October, John Keane and several other members of Trout Unlimited
tested the water in Hallock's Mill Brook, a trout stream that
receives wastewater from the largest of the plants, in Yorktown,
N.Y. They used methods they had been taught by the state's Stream
Biomonitoring Unit in upstate Troy. Above the plant, 75 percent of
the aquatic insects they found were Caddis flies -- an indicator of
high water quality. Below the outlet, the figure was 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In April, Bonavist went to the stream in hopes of catching
trout. Instead, he saw foaming bubbles floating on it, not far from
the sewage plant outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Pierce, a senior aquatic biologist for the state, said an
official had tested the water in the stream in response to
Bonavist's complaint and had not found any evidence of serious
pollution. But the Yorktown plant has chronically violated its
permit in years past, and let raw sewage overflow at least four
times in 1999, said James Tierney, the inspector general for the
city's watershed.
</P>
<P>
   City and county authorities are now looking into ways to pipe
the Yorktown plant's waste to a site out of the watershed.
</P>
<P>
   But it is impossible to remove the largest threat to the city's
water, which comes from the countless miscellaneous pollutants that
collect on roads and fields and flow into rivers and reservoirs.
This kind of pollution tends to grow in direct proportion to the
amount of paved surface in a given area, as the land's natural
ability to filter out pollutants is diminished.
</P>
<P>
   Such diffuse or ``nonpoint'' pollution is hard to measure or
police, because its sources are so various. The federal government
has only begun to regulate it, and states and counties tend to
follow the federal lead.
</P>
<P>
   For fishermen, however, it is often impossible to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   When a storm drain from a housing development in the town of
Carmel began shooting muddy water onto the west branch of the
Croton River seven years ago, Nikitovich noticed immediately. The
West Branch is one of the most beautiful streams in the watershed.
Every fall, brown trout as large as 10 pounds swim up the river to
spawn from the Croton Falls reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   The storm drain was a threat to those spawning grounds because
newborn trout live in streambeds; when the beds become silted up,
the trout cannot survive.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Keane and other Trout Unlimited members became
involved. They realized that the silt pouring into the river wasn't
just a threat to trout. Silt or mud -- turbidity is the the
technical term -- is a serious threat to drinking water, because
the mud can carry with it bacteria, heavy metals, and other
dangerous pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   Already, 10 of the city's 19 reservoirs are overloaded with
phosphorus, an unwanted nutrient carried in runoff, which can cause
algae blooms and elevate toxic elements in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential pollutants could be deadly. In 1993, an
intestinal parasite called cryptosporidium, which is carried in
animal and human waste, entered Milwaukee's water supply, killing
more than 100 people and making 400,000 ill.
</P>
<P>
   Even if pollution never causes similar disasters in New York, it
could cost the city a considerable amount of money. Because of
pollution in the Croton watershed, the city has already committed
itself to building a $1-billion filtration plant for the 10 percent
of its water that comes from east of the Hudson River. If the
pollution gets worse, the federal government has made clear that
the city will have to build what would be the world's largest
filtration plant for the 90 percent of the water that comes from
the Catskills and the Delaware River Valley. That plant would cost
at least $6 billion to build and more than $300 million a year to
operate, sending city water and sewer rates up even more than the
annual rise of 7 percent to 9 percent in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid these costs, the city reached an agreement in 1997 with
federal, state, and local governments and environmental groups to
spend $1 billion over 10 years on watershed protection. That
agreement includes a commitment to buy more land as a buffer
against development, as well as modernizing septic fields and
sewage-treatment plants and carrying out new rules and restrictions
on development.
</P>
<P>
   But there are gaps in the current laws, and fishermen have been
among the most active in pointing them out.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Nikitovich and other trout fishermen have led a
campaign to bolster the laws protecting watershed streams. All
reservoirs in the watershed are rated AA -- the highest class of
protection -- but many of the streams that flow into them are rated
C or D, a rating that could allow developers to reroute them with a
backhoe. Under federal law, the state is supposed to review streams
for possible reclassification every three years. But that has not
happened in the watershed for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Post, a spokeswoman for the state, said
reclassification was a complicated and expensive process, and other
states had also taken decades to complete it. She also said that
hearings on the watershed's streams are expected to begin before
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen have also been among the most vocal opponents of new
development projects in the watershed, like the current proposal to
broaden Route 120, which runs along the Kensico Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the fishermen have focused on finding effective ways
to combat stormwater runoff, which has the most direct impact on
trout streams.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most effective methods, they say, can be seen on the
west branch of the Croton River, where runoff from a pipe once
threatened the brown trout's spawning grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Today, that runoff flows into a shallow bog known as a detention
basin, about 180 feet long and 75 feet wide, which the town of
Carmel built last year. The water accumulates in the basin, where
the sediment slowly settles out, and plants on the bottom help to
filter out toxic elements. At the basin's far end is a stone weir,
which regulates a slow flow of water through a pipe and into a
stone culvert, where it trickles gently and harmlessly into the
stream.
</P>
<P>
   That detention basin is a model for controlling stormwater
runoff, Keane said. But it took years of complaints and letter
writing by Trout Unlimited before city officials finally visited
the site and forced the town to build the basin.
</P>
<P>
   Although the city tried to combat the problem by mandating
stormwater controls for all new development in 1997, it has done
little to fix runoff problems caused by buildings constructed
before that time.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Keane organized a team to document other runoff
problems throughout the portion of the watershed east of the Hudson
River. They photographed each site from several angles. They took
samples of water before and after it rained. They did toxicological
tests. In a third of the sites, they found toxic elements in the
water.
</P>
<P>
   Their final report, recently released, includes a novel legal
threat. Instead of giving way to the conventional wisdom that
runoff is everybody's and nobody's fault, the report claims that
storm drains are ``point sources'' of pollution and their owners
can therefore be sued under the Clean Water Act. Already, Kennedy
has announced that Riverkeeper plans to sue the owner of every
storm drain listed in the report.
</P>
<P>
   It is an unusual strategy, and it is too early to tell whether
it will work. Some of the storm drains are owned by the state, some
by the city, some by the towns, some by private individuals, and it
is not always clear who is responsible for the pollution that flows
through them.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, one thing is certain: Keane and his fellow
fishermen have made clear that trout play a role in safeguarding
the city's water supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitude is that trout are like canaries in the mine,''
Keane said. ``If trout can't live in the water, you've got to be
concerned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
