<HEADLINE>
PITCHING COSTS RANGERS IN DEFEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates usually keeps meticulous
count of the number of pitches his pitchers throw in a game.
Yesterday, he couldn't keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost count I got so frustrated,'' Oates said. ``I kept track
of \RDavid\S Wells. He was much more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates, seething in his SkyDome office, looked at his pitching
chart, shook his head and said, ``Way too many pitches. I hope some
of our guys were watching David pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   If they did, they would have seen Wells outmatch Rangers rookie
Doug Davis and pitch the Blue Jays to an 8-5 victory yesterday.
Davis gave up three runs in the first inning and the Rangers never
really recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Wells cruised through six innings as his teammates gave him a
7-1 lead off Davis and reliever Jonathan Johnson. Rusty Greer's
three-run double made it 7-4 in the seventh, but the Rangers got no
closer, falling to their sixth loss in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, in his first start since replacing Darren Oliver in the
rotation, allowed six runs on nine hits and a walk in five innings.
He is 1-2 with a 10.07 earned-run average in four starts this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had trouble throwing my fastball where I wanted it and I
didn't have my changeup at any point in the game,'' Davis said.
``Every time I did throw a good pitch over the plate, they seemed
to bloop it in or find a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   But Oates, his frustration reaching the boiling point, made it
clear he wants to see more good pitches over the plate. Many more.
Not only from Davis, but from all his young pitchers. Oates was
still fuming yesterday about Matt Perisho, who walked Brad Fullmer
to start the seventh inning in Friday's game when he had a 5-3
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for improvement,'' Oates said. ``It's time. It's
time. You've got to throw strikes. Make them swing the bat.
Stuff-wise, you're telling me David Wells' stuff is better than the
guys we've got? His command, though, was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates watches pitch counts closely. Davis threw 43 pitches in
the first inning. Wells threw 42 pitches in the first four innings.
Oates believes his pitchers should average 15 pitches an inning and
throw less than 140 a game. He's getting tired of seeing pitchers
throwing more than 20 pitches an inning and 150 a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't keep throwing 20 pitches an inning,'' Oates said.
``Your arm can't keep doing that. We're trying to impress on them,
throw the ball over the plate and let them hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, when told of Oates' comment, said he totally agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get ahead in the count and challenge hitters,'' Wells said.
``That's what I tell our young guys, don't nitpick. That's the way
I've been my whole career. Go out and challenge hitters, that's
where I get my energy and success. Even on days when you don't have
your good stuff, you've got to do things differently, but you've
still got to challenge hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, 17-3 with a 3.85 ERA, threw 100 pitches in seven innings,
65 for strikes. Davis threw 107 pitches in five innings. Another
instructive statistic: Wells threw as many as five pitches to only
two of the first 24 batters he faced. He threw seven pitches in the
second inning and six pitches in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you keep the ball down and throw strikes, you're going to
have success,'' Wells said. ``Believe in your defense. Give them a
chance to make the plays. If you get ahead of hitters and throw
strikes, it sets the tone for the entire game.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Oates is looking for from the Rangers' young
starters. His impatience is growing.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
