<HEADLINE>
WHEN CREEK WATERS GROW MUDDY, THE TROUT DISAPPEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Ga.)   (For use with POLLUTION-POLICE)  
 By ROBERT WORTH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Local fishermen in New York state call it Yoohoo Creek for the
orange-brown clay that has muddied its waters for four years and
driven away trout. But Esopus Creek used to be one of the best
trout-fishing streams in the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the mud comes from the Shandaken Tunnel, an 18-mile
tube, which is operated by New York City and flows into the Esopus
from the Schoharie Reservoir to help maintain the city's water
supply.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Catskill chapter of Trout Unlimited, and several
other groups, teamed up with Riverkeeper, the environmental group,
to take their concerns to the city's Department of Environmental
Protection.
</P>
<P>
   They hired experts to help make their case: the muddy water
flowing into the Esopus was damaging the trout habitat and killing
the aquatic insects they feed on. Since the city owned the
reservoir that was creating the problem, it had a responsibility to
do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   The state's attorney general's office helped mediate discussions
between the fly-fishermen and the city. But after almost a year and
a half, the city refused to budge, and the fishermen filed suit in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of the case is that under the Clean Water Act you
cannot discharge a pollutant from a point source without a
permit,'' said Karl Coplan, the Riverkeeper's lawyer, who is
representing the fishermen. ``It's clear under the law that
suspended solids are a pollutant.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has moved to dismiss the suit. Geoffrey Ryan, a
spokesman for the city, said: ``The allegations in the complaint
are without basis in law or fact.''
</P>
<P>
   But William W. Buzbee, a professor of environmental law at Emory
University, in Atlanta, said that some legal precedents suggest
that the law may be on the fishermen's side. In several earlier
cases, polluted water being channeled from one body of water to
another was found to be a violation of the Clean Water Act.
</P>
<P>
   The Shandaken Tunnel was built by the city early in the 1900s to
take water from the Schoharie Reservoir to the Esopus, where it
flows southward to the Ashokan Reservoir and on through aqueducts
to faucets in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Water first began flowing through it in 1924, and muddy water,
known as turbidity, has been an occasional problem in the Esopus
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But it only became a serious threat to trout in 1996, when a
major storm damaged the clay stream banks in the Schoharie and the
streams that feed it, turning the water reddish brown for months on
end.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Esopus has often been crystal clear above the
Shandaken Tunnel outlet and reddish brown below it, said Burt
Darrow, who runs a fly-fishing guide service and has lived in the
area all his life.
</P>
<P>
   If it gets bad enough, the mud can be a threat to the city water
supply, because turbidity carries with it bacteria, metals, and
other dangerous pollutants and can interfere with the effectiveness
of chlorination.
</P>
<P>
   The water, however, is generally cleaner in the Catskill
watershed than east of the Hudson River. And if turbidity becomes a
serious problem, the city can use chemical treatments to help
clarify the water.
</P>
<P>
   But that is no comfort to the fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stream is literally dying,'' Darrow said. ``This used to
be the center of fishing in the Catskills. Now there are weekends
when you don't see a single fisherman on the river.'' His own
business as a guide has dropped significantly since the mud became
a problem, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Urban, the president of the Catskill chapter of Trout
Unlimited, a party to the suit, said: ``It's had a real impact on
the guides and on bed and breakfasts and motels up here.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several things the city could do to remedy the
situation, Coplan said. The intake of the Shandaken Tunnel is on
the bottom of the Schoharie Reservoir, where it is muddiest. The
city could build a multilevel intake, which would minimize the mud
flowing into the tunnel. It could also dredge the reservoir. And it
could restore stream banks in the Schoharie basin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
