<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3920 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-OLY-VAN-DYKEN-SWIMMIN     08-05 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VAN-DYKEN-SWIMMING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN DYKEN SWIMMING TOWARD GOAL OF A PORSCHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was 27, and after her second shoulder surgery in 19 months,
Amy Van Dyken sat there, unable to brush her teeth or dress
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Her swimming career, she had decided, was done.
</P>
<P>
   That was January. Beginning this week in Indianapolis, Van Dyken
will attempt to again make the U.S. Olympic team in the 50- and
100-meter freestyles.
</P>
<P>
   Another inspiring saga of a great athlete willing herself to
overcome adversity, yes?
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting there, my arm in a sling,'' Van Dyken recalled,
``and I'm telling my friends and family that I think I'm through.
No more swimming. And my fiance, Tom, says, ``That's too bad,
because if you had made the Olympic team, I was going to buy you a
Porsche Boxster.''
</P>
<P>
   The sling was off, and Van Dyken was back in the pool the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect this great story,'' Van Dyken said. ``But there
is none. I want that car.''
</P>
<P>
   If Van Dyken is embarrassed at the confession, she doesn't show
it. For one thing, her fiance is Tom Rouen, veteran punter for the
Denver Broncos, and he can afford the Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   For the other thing, it's time for the Olympics, and Van Dyken
has her ``attitude'' again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm still cocky and arrogant,'' said Van Dyken, who won
four gold medals at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics. ``And the reason I
am that way is because you have to be. You're out there by
yourself. You don't have a team behind you, where if you screw up,
they're there to back you up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who's out there swimming wants to be the best. The
way I carry myself is that I deserve to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Van Dyken said, her friends will attest that it's a
good front.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not that cocky in real life,'' she added. ``I
completely change when I get to the pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyken's track record attests to the other side. Back in
Littleton, Colo., she works for both United Way and the Make-A-Wish
Foundation. She learned sign language for the hearing impaired and
says she wants to teach high school and work with deaf children.
</P>
<P>
   This was even before the tragedy that struck close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Columbine kids are very special to me,'' Van Dyken said.
``To hear the stories from these kids ... to hear from one kid, who
felt it was his fault that one of his friends was dead and another
friend was in a wheelchair. He said it was because he had told them
he wanted them to stay in the cafeteria instead of going outside
that day. These are things these kids have to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is another young boy, who works with my mom, who was in
the choir room when the shootings began. He was running out when he
tripped over one of his good friends' bodies. Another friend of
his, a basketball player, recently committed suicide. The boy said
it's hard to go on every day. He just doesn't see why this is
happening to him and his school. To look in his eyes, there's such
a sadness that comes over him.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyken has volunteered a lot of her spare time to help the
teen-agers at Columbine High. On her swimsuit, she wears a ribbon
in honor of the 13 students and teachers who died. Her swim cap
bears the letters ``CHS.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kind of adopted the school,'' she said. ``I will continue
to wear the `CHS' and the ribbon until I'm done swimming. And,
hopefully, if I make the team, the Olympic Committee will allow me
to wear that on my Olympic suit, because it's something I feel very
strongly about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who lost their lives and the lives that were
changed forever can't be forgotten. Once you forget, that's when
things like this happen again.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
