<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-VALDES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPLE-A OUTFIELDER EARNS PROMOTION TO RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Outfielder Pedro Valdes joined the Rangers yesterday.
Ruben Sierra remained at Triple-A Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin said the Rangers considered calling
up Sierra when they traded Dave Martinez to the Toronto Blue Jays
for a player to be named later. But he said his staff, including
farm director Reid Nichols, felt Valdes deserved the promotion
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reid said Valdes has done the better job and has been
consistent all year,'' Melvin said. ``There's a loyalty factor
involved too. Valdes has been with us all year. We felt he deserved
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who was with the Rangers in spring training, was hitting
.333 with 16 home runs and 78 runs batted in for 91 games with the
RedHawks. Sierra, a former major-league All-Star who signed a
minor-league contract with the Rangers on May 1, is hitting .325
with 14 home runs and 80 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it yesterday,'' Valdes said. ``We've been
talking about it all season, whether one of us would get called up.
He wasn't disappointed. He understands. He's a nice guy, everybody
likes him down there. He's playing great and he's really helping
the young players.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said Sierra, 34, might be called up in September when the
rosters are expanded to 40 players, but ``I don't see where he'll
get at-bats. You can't have too many \Rdesignated hitters\S. He's
more of a pinch-hitter type. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes is likely to play a similar role with the Rangers for
now. He could be a candidate to be the team's DH next year, but it
is doubtful he will get a lot of playing time this season. His
defensive abilities are considered limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may get some at-bats that way; he has been a pretty
productive player the last couple of years,'' Melvin said. ``But he
probably won't get the same opportunities as the other guys. It's
up to Johnny \ROates\S to play him where he wants. We look at him
as an older player. He's not someone I told Johnny he has to play.
He'll probably play the same role David \RMartinez\S was playing, a
bat off the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes is a left-handed hitter. Right now, Oates is committed to
Frank Catalanotto as his left-handed designated hitter.
Catalanotto, who was benched yesterday with left-hander David Wells
on the mound for Toronto, is hitting .355.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cat deserves to play,'' Oates said. ``Very few players are
going to play every day. We'll see how it works out.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes played in 23 games with the Chicago Cubs in 1997-98. He
signed with the Boston Red Sox as a minor-league free agent in
1999. The Rangers signed him just after the '99 season started, and
he hit .327 at Oklahoma with 21 home runs and 72 RBI. That earned
him a nonroster invitation to spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good chance to show what I can do,'' Valdes said.
``I've got to be ready any time I get a chance to play, whether
it's coming off the bench or whenever I get into a game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
