r s BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COLUMN-B     08-05 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COLUMN-BODYSUITS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODYSUITS DEBATE OVERSHADOWS OTHER STORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1972, Mark Spitz stepped out of the Olympic swimming pool in
Munich, West Germany, wearing a star-spangled swimsuit that wasn't
much larger than his moustache.
</P>
<P>
   Women swooned. The ensuing poster made Spitz, bound for dental
school, a lot of lunch money.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, it seems, the Olympic motto for swimsuits has
remained the same: ``modicus, stringius, citius,'' or something
like that.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller, tighter, faster.
</P>
<P>
   But wait until you see what they're wearing this time _
bodysuits. Neck-to-ankle suits made of space-age materials that are
alleged to knife through water in the same way a shark's skin does.
</P>
<P>
   Human sausage casings. Australian butterfly queen Susie O'Neill
reported that it took 15 minutes just to squeeze into hers.
</P>
<P>
   To bodysuit, or not to bodysuit? That will be the overshadowing
question this week as the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials begin in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the human melodramas, like Amy Van Dyken's comeback
attempt after two shoulder surgeries and 33-year-old Dara Torres
trying to become the first American to swim in four Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Ignore, if you will, the saga of backstroker Lenny Krayzelburg,
born in Ukraine and taken to the United States by his parents
because they wanted him to grow up in the land of the free.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind it all, because in these trials, the race may not go
to the swift, but to who has the best Speedo tailor.
</P>
<P>
   To get the best fit for one of the new bodysuits, the swimmer
has to undergo a 3-D scan of his or her entire body.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy has gurgled ever since the first neck-to-ankle
bodysuit was worn in international competition at a July 1999, meet
in Istanbul, Turkey. The world governing body for swimming, FINA,
soon approved use of the suit for the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments ensued, not the least of which was who was going to
get the new suits in time to make their respective Olympic teams.
At an estimated $250 per suit, clearly it isn't for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   But does it matter?
</P>
<P>
   FINA rules specifically outlaw any device that aids in ``speed,
buoyancy and endurance during a competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Speed enhancement is exactly one of the manufacturer claims of
the new suits.
</P>
<P>
   At the Short Course World Championships in Athens, Greece, in
March, 15 world records were broken, most of them by swimmers
wearing the bodysuits. At the Australian Olympic trials in May, the
bodysuit-clad O'Neill shattered Mary T. Meagher's 19-year-old
record in the 200-meter butterfly, even though head coach Don
Talbot had urged his swimmers not to wear the new suits.
</P>
<P>
   Olympian Rowdy Gaines has said that he thinks the bodysuits can
improve a swimmer's time by a half-second per 100 meters. The coach
of Dutch sensaton Inge DeBruijn, Paul Berger, estimates the
improvement as more like 1.5 seconds. Which is huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the new suit a lot,'' said Krayzelburg, who has assumed
the role of world's best backstroker. ``You can tell the
difference. It helps you swim with more proper technique. By
holding you in, it makes your body more compact. And that's the
whole idea when you swim, to be as efficient as possible to move
through the water.''
</P>
<P>
   After a June announcement banning use of the bodysuits at the
Olympic Trials, USA Swimming relented one month later and announced
July 18 that swimmers could wear the suits. The manufacturers _
Speedo, adidas, Tyr and Nike _ have promised to make enough suits
available.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, one suspects, is sponsor-driven. Imagine the
number of bodysuits that Speedo will sell if the world sees them
breaking records on the Olympic TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   As the saga of Spitz, his Speedo and his seven gold medals
remind us, swimsuits have always been a part of the Olympic story.
Once upon a time, the magic cloth was said to be Lycra. Four years
ago in Atlanta, 77 percent of the swim medalists wore Speedo's
Aquablade suits.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen and ladies, start your sausage casings. We have
another Olympic team to pick.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
