<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3931 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-TCU-RANKING-TEX     08-05 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-RANKING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESEASON RANKING FIRST FOR TCU IN 40 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU football fans had been waiting for
yesterday since Jan. 5, the day The Associated Press poll anointed
Florida State the 1999 national champions.
</P>
<P>
   TCU free safety Curtis Fuller, however, had other things on his
mind. Working on a couple of summer-school papers, this graduate
student was stunned to hear the Frogs' standing at No. 20 in AP's
2000 preseason poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you serious?
</P>
<P>
   ``The AP poll?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, that is very shocking to me,'' Fuller said on the phone
during a study break. ``I don't know what to say. I don't know if
that will give us more confidence or more pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgive Fuller for being uncertain about how to handle the news.
It has been 40 years since TCU was ranked in AP's preseason poll,
checking in at No. 11 in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   And nearly as rare as having three college graduates still
eligible _ Fuller, Jeff Millican and Stuart Ashley are each in
graduate school _ are TCU appearances in the AP poll since 1960.
Only twice since then _ 1984 and '90 _ have the Frogs been ranked
during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But with consecutive bowl victories the past two years, 18
starters returning, a Heisman Trophy contender in LaDainian
Tomlinson and now a national ranking, the stage appears set for
TCU's greatest season in a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased that there's a gesture of respect in being
acknowledged as a Top 25 team,'' Horned Frogs coach Dennis
Franchione said. ``We had hoped to get into the Top 25 after
\Rbeating\S East Carolina in the \RMobile Alabama Bowl.\S
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're flattered by that, but we also know that the 2000
team hasn't done anything yet. It's based on how your team finished
in '99 and how many returning starters you have in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs won their last five games in '99, including an upset
of No. 20 East Carolina in the Mobile Alabama Bowl, to finish 8-4.
Franchione hoped TCU would squeeze into the final Top 25, but the
Frogs found themselves four teams deep in the ``others receiving
votes'' category.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's previous preseason ranking also followed the last time the
Frogs played in consecutive bowl games. TCU limped to a 4-4-2
record in 1960 and would post only seven winning years until
Franchione took over in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Inheriting a 1-10 team from Pat Sullivan, Franchione led TCU to
a 7-5 record in 1998 and a stunning victory against Southern
Californa in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being ranked gets us started on something Coach Fran set out
to do when he came here two years ago, make us a Top 25 program,''
said Fuller, a Fort Worth Christian graduate who transferred to TCU
from Tyler Junior College before the '98 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that note, when we look down the road at this 2000 team, we
want to make sure we left our mark. We may have started at 20, but
finished at 10. We want to keep building this for others to keep
going.''
</P>
<P>
   A large part of the 2000 legacy will be based on whether the
Frogs reach a third consecutive bowl _ that has never been done in
school history _ and which bowl that is. Winning the Western
Athletic Conference championship would ensure a return trip to the
Mobile Alabama Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little bit more of a target, but I don't know how much
more of a target we can be,'' Franchione said referring to TCU's
final season in the WAC. ``The only pitfall of being ranked is not
living up to expectations, which keep growing by each day.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, talk of a TCU berth in the Bowl Championship Series
has begun. Should the Frogs finish the season ranked among the top
six in the BCS standings, a berth in one of the four BCS games is
guaranteed. Franchione and Fuller realize starting at No. 20 makes
that climb a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, it's attainable,'' Fuller said of a BCS game. ``But
for that to happen we would have to have a great season. No
injuries and we have to be flawless game in and game out, which we
can be if we set our minds to it. We don't hang our hats on that
goal, but we know it's in our grasp.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
