<HEADER>
A3932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PHONE-TALKS-NYT &LR;      08-05 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEPHONE STRIKE LOOMS AS TALKS FALTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Verizon Communications had failed to reach a contract agreement
with its unions late Saturday night, setting the stage for a
walkout by more than 86,000 telephone workers on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   A walkout affecting about 25 million households and businesses
in an area stretching from Maine to Virginia might create delays
for Verizon customers who need telephone repairs, telephone
installation or directory assistance from service representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Basic dial tone and automated services would remain functional,
and emergency services like 911 would also operate normally. A
strike would not affect Verizon's wireless service, which has 26
million subscribers. Verizon did not establish any hot lines or
special numbers for customers having difficulties in soliciting
services.
</P>
<P>
   Because the walkout would start Sunday, it was not expected to
have as great an impact as it would have had if it were to begin on
a weekday, when the volume of calls would be greater. Both sides
appeared ready to continue talks Sunday in effort to reach an
agreement before the start of the work week.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon, the company created when Bell Atlantic acquired GTE and
formed an alliance with Britain's Vodafone AirTouch for wireless
services, is the nation's largest provider of local telephone and
wireless services, with 260,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the dispute involves fairly ordinary labor
issues, including wages, benefits, stress levels on the job and
outside contracting of certain work.
</P>
<P>
   But, perhaps more important, Verizon and officials from the
Communications Workers of America and the International Brotherhood
of Electrical Workers also failed to agree on how the union should
be allowed to organize workers in Verizon's fast-growing wireless
division. The union had sought to make it easier for wireless
workers to join a union.
</P>
<P>
   According to people close to the talks, Verizon submitted a new
proposal late Saturday altering an earlier proposal. The new
three-year contract proposal would raise wages 10.5 percent over
three years, compared with 17.5 percent over five years, and would
lower the percentage of the company's workforce which could be
affected by the migration of jobs as the result of the merger, from
6 percent to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate negotiations were initiated Saturday over
the unions' request that organizing wireless employees be made
easier. But both sides were not optimistic of reaching an agreement
by 12:01 a.m. Sunday, the unions' deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect we'll get to midnight without an agreement, but we're
ready to continue talking past the deadline and throughout Sunday
to reach common ground,'' said Eric Rabe, Verizon's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at the company's old wireline operations, providing
local and long-distance service, worry that the wireless arm will
soon eclipse the rest of the company in importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about the stress level of my job, with things like
random monitoring of my calls by a supervisor or forced overtime,''
said Stephanie Harrison, 47, a customer service representative in
Westchester County. ``I'm worried that in five years I won't have a
job because wireless will be dominant and plain old telephone
service will be very small.''
</P>
<P>
   The communications workers have predicted that revenue for the
wireless division will grow by 86 percent between 1998 and 2003,
compared with a 25 percent increase in revenue for local services.
But while nearly 80 percent of the 120,000 employees in the
company's local telephone division are unionized, fewer than 50
percent of the 32,000 workers in its wireless unit are.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a strike could have broad implications for many
high-technology industries, which, in general, have not been
unionized.
</P>
<P>
   The wireless communications industry as a whole already has more
than 90 million subscribers and is adding 30,000 more a day. The
unions hope that if they win concessions that make it easier for
them to organize Verizon's wireless workers, and if they then
persuade the workers to join, workers at other wireless companies
will become more enthusiastic about unionization efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But Verizon officials say that the wireless industry is so
competitive that increased union representation of its wireless
workers would put it at a critical disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way unionization wouldn't be a competitive
disadvantage to Verizon would be if all their competitors were
unionized, too,'' said Jeff Kagan, an independent
telecommunications analyst. ``If only one or two of the companies
are unionized and the rest are not, it will be like a ball and
chain around the ankles of the ones that are.''
</P>
<P>
   One way the company has limited union influence even in its
unionized local and long-distance divisions has been to contract
out work to nonunionized companies for services like the
installation of high-speed Internet lines. The unions strongly
object to this practice, and they are arguing for limits on
Verizon's ability to contract out certain tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The natural pressures of the market can be fierce, but a
fearful, non-union workforce does not necessarily enhance
competitiveness, said Harley Shaiken, a professor of labor issues
at the University of California at Berkeley. At the core of this
issue is whether our companies will be able to compete in a human
way.
</P>
<P>
   The walkout comes at a delicate time for Verizon. The company is
in the midst of establishing an identity for its new brand name
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   And it was unclear late Saturday how long the strike might last.
In 1998, the two unions struck Bell Atlantic for only two days,
with little effect on customer service, winning a no-layoff clause
and improved pension benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1989, workers struck for 17 weeks against Nynex, which
later merged with Bell Atlantic. Thousands of union members
picketed, dozens of strikers were arrested and a backlog of nearly
250,000 installation orders built up. The unions succeeded in
reversing a company demand that workers pay monthly health
insurance premiums.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-00 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
