<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3938 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     08-05 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE NAKED AND THE DEAD &LR;  By Norman Mailer. (Picador USA, $16.)
Norman Mailer was a young World War II veteran with a story to tell
in 1948 when this hefty novel, his first, was published. In The New
York Times Book Review, David Dempsey found it ``the most ambitious
novel to be written about the recent conflict'' and ``the most
ruthlessly honest.'' ```The Naked and the Dead' is not a great
book,'' this early evaluation concluded, ``but indisputably it
bears witness to a new and significant talent among American
novelists.'' The novel has been reissued in a 50th anniversary
edition with a new introduction by Mailer.
</P>
<P>
   Picador has also reissued  &UR; WHY ARE WE IN VIETNAM? &LR;  ($13), a
Mailer novel from 1967, when he was well established as a celebrity
writer. Vietnam itself is not mentioned until the last page of the
novel, which chronicles the Alaska hunting trip of two
soldiers-to-be, who set out to prove their virility in various
ways. Anatole Broyard said that it ``may be a third-rate work of
art, but it's a first-rate outrage to our sensibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ISAAC'S STORM &LR;  By Erik Larson. (Vintage, $13.) More than 6,000
people died in the hurricane that struck Galveston, Texas, in 1900;
the Isaac in question was Isaac M. Cline, chief of the U.S. Weather
Bureau's Galveston station. He ``survived his colossal misreading
of the situation on an impromptu raft,'' W. Jeffrey Bolster wrote
last year, adding that ``Larson never personifies nature, but he
sees poetry in weather.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALICE SPRINGS &LR;  By Nikki Gemmell. (Penguin, $12.95.) A footloose
young artist journeys into the Australian outback to find her
mysterious father. The novel ``offers a whittled-down portrait of
external and internal landscapes under pressure,'' Elizabeth Graver
wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE VIEW FROM ALGER'S WINDOW: A Son's Memoir &LR;  By Tony Hiss.
(Vintage, $13.) The author was 7 years old when his father, Alger
Hiss, was accused of passing secrets to the Russians. By drawing on
hundreds of letters Alger Hiss sent from prison, the son takes up
his father's cause in what Ann Douglas last year called ``a
poignant, wonderfully written and deeply troubling memoir.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THOSE DAMN YANKEES: The Secret Life of America's Greatest
Franchise &LR;  By Dean Chadwin. (Verso, $15.) The author, a New York
lawyer, sees baseball's perennial overdogs as a malign influence on
the sport. He ``tackles his topic with a zealotry worthy of any
Kennedy conspiracy theorist,'' Allen St. John wrote last year. But
St. John finds the author's larger point ``muddled by his
anti-Yankee animus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' championship season of two years ago, along with
the Mark McGwire-Sammy Sosa home-run derby, is celebrated in
 &UR; SUMMER OF '98 &LR;  by Mike Lupica (Contemporary Books, $14.95). The
book ``finds fresh ways of telling us history we have already lived
through,'' George Robinson wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RIVER OF DARKNESS &LR;  By Rennie Airth. (Penguin, $6.99.) Surviving
the carnage of the third Battle of Ypres in World War I, a sergeant
major returns to Surrey's green and pleasant land as a psychopathic
killer. The Scotland Yard inspector on his trail is himself a
battle-scarred veteran. The novel ``has balanced savagery and
civilization neatly, and given civilization just the barest edge,''
Christopher Dickey wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ACCIDENTAL BRIDE &LR;  By Janice Harayda. (St. Martin's Griffin,
$13.95.) In this comedy of contemporary manners, Lily Blair, a
newspaper reporter, is about to marry the third-richest man in the
second-largest city in Ohio when she is torn between the security
of married suburban life and following her career dreams to New
York. This first novel is ``devoid of the delicious tension that
infuses books like `Pride and Prejudice,''' Maggie Galehouse wrote
last year. But she praised the author as ``an astute social
commentator.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATER AUDEN &LR;  By Edward Mendelson. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$17.) The work of W.H. Auden rather than the life dominates this
second of two biographical volumes by his literary executor and the
editor of his collected works. The author ``makes Auden dull, a
mere clerk of the emotions,'' William Logan wrote last year, though
he found that ``Mendelson's readings fathom the poem phrase by
phrase, and even the footnotes are lively with criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has also released  &UR; EARLY AUDEN &LR;  ($16),
covering the poet's life until he left England for New York in
1939. ``Mendelson is informative on the early influences,'' Denis
Donoghue wrote in 1981.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
